var QUESTIONS=[{"id":"7764","category":"Cancer and palliative care and haematology","stem":"A 70-year-old woman with advanced metastatic breast cancer presents with clinical deterioration, including vomiting and dehydration. Investigations reveal calcium of 4.1 mmol/L. She is treated with IV normal saline rehydration followed by intravenous pamidronate.\n\nConcerning this patient's vomiting, which of the following would be the most appropriate antiemetic to use in this case?\n\nThe most appropriate first-line antiemetic in this patient with severe hypercalcaemia would be haloperidol. It is a dopamine D2 antagonist and useful in opioid-induced nausea and vomiting, too. Haloperidol is usually given orally, once or twice a day, to treat chemically or metabolically induced vomiting. This is an off-label indication for haloperidol tablets and an oral solution. Metoclopramide is useful where there is gastric stasis, cyclizine is useful in raised intracranial pressure or motion sickness and ondansetron in the treatment of chemotherapy-induced emesis.","options":["Leach, C. Nausea and vomiting in palliative care, Clinical Medicine 2019 Vol 19, No 4: 299–301.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"The most appropriate first-line antiemetic in this patient with severe hypercalcaemia would be haloperidol. It is a dopamine D2 antagonist and useful in opioid-induced nausea and vomiting, too. Haloperidol is usually given orally, once or twice a day, to treat chemically or metabolically induced vomiting. This is an off-label indication for haloperidol tablets and an oral solution. Metoclopramide is useful where there is gastric stasis, cyclizine is useful in raised intracranial pressure or motion sickness and ondansetron in the treatment of chemotherapy-induced emesis."},{"id":"3383","category":"Cancer and palliative care and haematology","stem":"You are reviewing a patient in the clinic with a 12-month history of cholangiocarcinoma. He has had a biliary stent in situ for three months with good symptomatic relief of jaundice and pruritus. He has felt unwell for 24 hours with nausea, sweats and malaise.\n\nOn examination, he has a temperature of 38.6oC, a pulse of 82 bpm regular, and a blood pressure of 136/80 mmHg. Examination of the abdomen reveals tenderness over his right upper quadrant.\n\nWhich of the following would be the most appropriate approach to the management of this patient?","options":["Patients who present with sepsis should be managed using an ABCDE approach. The sepsis 6 bundle should be started as soon as possible, with antibiotics administered within an hour of presentation.","It is likely that this patient has a blocked stent and will require ERCP when stable.","Please read the difference between biliary colic (only RUQ pain with no fever or jaundice), cholecystitis (RUQ pain with fever but no jaundice), and cholangitis (RUQ pain with fever and jaundice).","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"Ascending cholangitis (also called acute cholecystitis) may occur in patients with a partially obstructed or stented common bile duct. It often causes severe systemic upset and should be promptly treated with antibiotics."},{"id":"3392","category":"Cancer and palliative care and haematology","stem":"A 65-year-old man, known to have non-small cell lung cancer with metastases to the bones and liver, is admitted to the acute medical take with confusion, constipation and a history of falls at home.\n\nHis biochemistry results on admission are:\n\nWhat is the recommended initial course of action?","options":["Rehydration should initially precede the use of a bisphosphonate in acute presentations.","Corticosteroids are no longer recommended in the management of the hypercalcaemia of malignancy because of poor response rate, but may occasionally be used as an adjunct to calcitonin.","There are case reports supporting the use of octreotide in the treatment of hypercalcaemia associated with neuroendocrine tumours.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"Rehydration should initially precede the use of a bisphosphonate in acute presentations.","explanation":"Rehydration should initially precede the use of a bisphosphonate in acute presentations."},{"id":"18468","category":"Cancer and palliative care and haematology","stem":"A 68-year-old man presented to the medicine department with vertigo, recurrent dizzy spells, generalised body aches, severe back pain, and weakness in both lower limbs. On examination, the patient was confused, severely dehydrated, moderately anaemic, and 1+ pedal oedema was present.\n\nInvestigations reveal the following findings:\n\nWhat should be the immediate management for this patient?","options":["Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"This is a case of multiple myeloma with cord compression with severe hypercalcaemia with renal impairment. Among them, severe hypercalcaemia is a medical emergency and should be treated with IV hydration with normal saline; otherwise, it may cause cardiac arrest. The other options are also relevant and can be given subsequently rather than immediately."},{"id":"3395","category":"Uncategorised","stem":"You are reviewing a 69-year-old man on the ward who has had potentially curative surgery for colorectal carcinoma. The patient is two days post-op and feeling very nauseous. Whilst the patient is on the commode, he becomes pale and breathless. On examination, he is distressed and cyanosed with a heart rate of 110/min, blood pressure of 80/40 mmHg, a respiratory rate of 30/min and his neck veins are engorged. His saturations are 86% (previously 98% on air). He already has an IVI in situ.\n\nWhich would be the most appropriate initial course of action for this patient?","options":["My Details","Login and Security","Preferences","Order History","Sign out","Consider giving alteplase","Get an urgent bedside ECHO","Get further IV access","Give a stat dose of unfractionated heparin followed by LMWH","Give high flow oxygen","British Thoracic Society guidelines for the management of suspected acute pulmonary embolism."],"correct":"","explanation":""},{"id":"3401","category":"Cancer and palliative care and haematology","stem":"You see a patient on the ward who has recently undergone potentially curative surgery for colorectal carcinoma. The patient is two days post-op and has been doing quite well. However, you have been asked to see the patient as he has become acutely unwell.\n\nWhat is the likely diagnosis?\n\nThe features of sudden collapse associated with shock and reduced saturations in the post-operative period would suggest a diagnosis of large pulmonary embolism. The fact that the chest is clear would argue against a diagnosis of acute pulmonary oedema. Similarly, fast AF is a sequelae of PE. Treatment for this needs to be considered in the context of his previous surgery, but thrombolysis may be required if the PE is considered life-threatening.","options":["What is the likely diagnosis?","BTS guidelines. British Thoracic Society guidelines for the management of suspected acute pulmonary embolism.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"What is the likely diagnosis?","explanation":"The features of sudden collapse associated with shock and reduced saturations in the post-operative period would suggest a diagnosis of large pulmonary embolism. The fact that the chest is clear would argue against a diagnosis of acute pulmonary oedema. Similarly, fast AF is a sequelae of PE. Treatment for this needs to be considered in the context of his previous surgery, but thrombolysis may be required if the PE is considered life-threatening."},{"id":"6423","category":"Cancer and palliative care and haematology","stem":"A 65-year-old woman presented to the unit with a two-day history of left leg pain and swelling. She had a background history of metastatic non-small cell lung cancer with cerebral metastases for which she had received cranial irradiation and was also receiving chemotherapy plus dexamethasone. The cerebral metastases were stable, and she was otherwise living an independent life. On examination, general observations were fine, and she was generally well. She was slightly Cushingoid and had a swollen and tender left leg. Doppler studies revealed that she had a proximal deep vein thrombosis.\n\nWhich of the following would be the most appropriate treatment for this patient’s DVT?\n\nThe patient has a DVT, and this should be treated. The complication of cerebral metastases may prompt some to consider the risk of intracerebral haemorrhage too high with anticoagulation and therefore to prefer an IVC filter. However, evidence indicates that whilst there is a risk of cerebral haemorrhage with cerebral metastases, this risk is similar whether the patient is receiving anticoagulation or not. Thus, the most appropriate approach to the management of this patient’s thromboembolism is Apixaban. Filters are problematic without concomitant anticoagulation with obstruction and thrombotic problems.","options":["Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"to prefer an IVC filter","explanation":"The patient has a DVT, and this should be treated. The complication of cerebral metastases may prompt some to consider the risk of intracerebral haemorrhage too high with anticoagulation and therefore to prefer an IVC filter. However, evidence indicates that whilst there is a risk of cerebral haemorrhage with cerebral metastases, this risk is similar whether the patient is receiving anticoagulation or not. Thus, the most appropriate approach to the management of this patient’s thromboembolism is Apixaban. Filters are problematic without concomitant anticoagulation with obstruction and thrombotic problems."},{"id":"11645","category":"Cancer and palliative care and haematology","stem":"A 50-year-old woman presented to the gastroenterology clinic with jaundice. She has no pain or itching, but friends have commented on her change in skin colour. She has poorly controlled diabetes and is currently on insulin. She was a heavy drinker in the past, but has recently been abstinent from alcohol due to poor diabetic control. She was widowed four months ago and has been mostly housebound due to severe depression. She has a decreased appetite and reports a 2-stone weight loss over the last few months.\n\nInvestigations show the following results:\n\nWhat is the most likely diagnosis?","options":["Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"This patient has painless obstructive jaundice as demonstrated by her raised alkaline phosphatase and bilirubin. Her ALT is normal. Patients with cirrhosis can have normal ALT as they have few hepatocytes to generate ALT, but these patients have very low albumin and fairly normal ALP."},{"id":"8372","category":"Cancer and palliative care and haematology","stem":"A 35-year-old patient presents with a three-month history of weight loss and chest infection and has one dark purple raised lesion on his abdomen of 2.5 cm in diameter. He is an IV drug abuser and HIV positive with a new diagnosis of Kaposi’s sarcoma presenting as an AIDS-defining illness. He commences treatment with highly active antiretroviral combination treatment (HAART).\n\nWhat is the most appropriate approach to the management of his associated Kaposi’s sarcoma?\n\nKaposi’s sarcoma is caused by human herpesvirus-8. The majority of cases of Kaposi’s sarcoma associated with HIV infection respond to HAART. In the minority that does not respond to HAART, treatment with chemotherapy or radiotherapy can be offered. HIV-associated KS typically occurs in patients who have high HIV viral loads (10,000 copies/mL).","options":["Mayo Clinic Staff (2018). Kaposi's sarcoma. Mayo Clinic.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"Kaposi’s sarcoma is caused by human herpesvirus-8. The majority of cases of Kaposi’s sarcoma associated with HIV infection respond to HAART. In the minority that does not respond to HAART, treatment with chemotherapy or radiotherapy can be offered. HIV-associated KS typically occurs in patients who have high HIV viral loads (10,000 copies/mL)."},{"id":"8120","category":"Cancer and palliative care and haematology","stem":"A 37-year-old woman with advanced carcinoma of the cervix is admitted with a temperature of 38 oC orally. She is hypotensive and has a regular pulse of 106 beats per minute. You suspect infection and start broad-spectrum antibiotics. The nurse tells you she is vomiting.\n\nWhich of the following is the most appropriate antiemetic to use in this case?\n\nIn this context of complex metabolic derangement (sepsis) with advanced cancer, an antiemetic that works directly on the chemotactic trigger zone is the most appropriate agent. The SIGN guidance (below) gives a good overview of the appropriate agents, which include a D2 antagonist like Metoclopramide, Haloperidol or Levopromazine.","options":["Scottish Palliative Care Guidelines – Nausea and Vomiting","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"In this context of complex metabolic derangement (sepsis) with advanced cancer, an antiemetic that works directly on the chemotactic trigger zone is the most appropriate agent. The SIGN guidance (below) gives a good overview of the appropriate agents, which include a D2 antagonist like Metoclopramide, Haloperidol or Levopromazine."},{"id":"3421","category":"Cancer and palliative care and haematology","stem":"A 65-year-old man was diagnosed with T-cell promyelocytic leukaemia a year ago and was successfully treated with subcutaneous alemtuzumab at the time. However, the patient returned to the outpatient clinic recently with the following blood count: haemoglobin was 121 g/L (120-155), white blood cell count 147.8 x 109/L (3.7-11), platelets 120 x109/L (140-400). His serum biochemistry was normal with the following results:\n\nIn his past medical history, he has been diagnosed with angina for which he is receiving bisoprolol 2.5 mg daily and simvastatin 40 mg daily. His physicians decided to treat him with pentostatin 4 mg/m2 intravenously for one dose.\n\n24 hours after the administration of the chemotherapy, the following results are obtained:","options":["If the serum potassium continues to rise, the patient needs to have cardiac monitoring to observe any changes in his ECG, and there may be a need for haemodialysis.","Reflection: As the hyperkalaemia is caused by tumour lysis syndrome, consider how to manage the syndrome to prevent further deterioration with this patient.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"If the serum potassium continues to rise, the patient needs to have cardiac monitoring to observe any changes in his ECG, and there may be a need for haemodialysis.","explanation":"Hyperkalaemia is a life-threatening complication of tumour lysis syndrome and needs to be treated by the use of intravenous dextrose and insulin; this will enable the potassium in the bloodstream to be shifted back into the cells. The onset of the hypokalaemic action occurs within 15 minutes and may last at least 60 minutes; however, the patient may require further administration of dextrose and insulin depending on the serum potassium. The reduction in potassium observed ranges from 0.6 to 1.0 mmol/L. This patient will also need intravenous calcium chloride or calcium gluconate for cardiac membrane stability, along with cardiac monitoring due to ECG changes. The new drug called sodium zirconium has been approved as an alternative to calcium resonium to remove potassium from the body."},{"id":"7921","category":"Cancer and palliative care and haematology","stem":"A 45-year-old woman attends MAU with acute severe pain in the mid-thoracic region. She had a 2-year history of metastatic breast cancer.\n\nOn examination, she was found to have tenderness over the mid-thoracic region and a sensory level at T8 with some weakness (4/5) of the lower limbs. An urgent MRI revealed spinal cord compression at level T7/8. She was commenced on dexamethasone 16 mg daily.\n\nWhich of the following is the most appropriate approach to the further management of this patient?","options":["Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"This patient has spinal cord compression associated with metastatic breast cancer and requires urgent referral to the spinal/oncology team for a decision on potential surgical decompression followed by fractionated radiotherapy. NICE guidance, as detailed below, advocates this approach."},{"id":"3397","category":"Cancer and palliative care and haematology","stem":"You are asked to review an 18-year-old university student who is refusing to have a blood test. He has been admitted with pyrexia and vomiting. He had his first cycle of chemotherapy seven days ago for a germ cell tumour. He is disoriented to time, place and person.\n\nWhich of the following is the most appropriate approach to this patient?\n\nAlthough not ideal, this patient currently lacks capacity (the clinical history is one of probable neutropenic sepsis and confusion). Although he will require IV antibiotics, he may also have other biochemical abnormalities which will need to be investigated and, if abnormal, corrected. Waiting for an IMCA may result in his death. His next of kin, although guiding on the likelihood of an acute loss of capacity, do not have any legal status in prescribing what we should or should not do.","options":["Patients above 16 years of age are presumed to have mental capacity until shown otherwise.","Capacity decisions are time and decision-specific. An evaluation of capacity will normally involve discussion with the patient's family, friends, carers or an IMCA.","Loss of capacity may be temporary (as in the case above).","The Two-Stage Test for Capacity involves:","Diagnostic:","Does the patient have an impairment of the mind or brain, which means that they are unable to decide for themselves?","Functional: the patient is unable to:","Deprivation of Liberty Safeguards (DoLS) at a glance | SCIE.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"Although not ideal, this patient currently lacks capacity (the clinical history is one of probable neutropenic sepsis and confusion). Although he will require IV antibiotics, he may also have other biochemical abnormalities which will need to be investigated and, if abnormal, corrected. Waiting for an IMCA may result in his death. His next of kin, although guiding on the likelihood of an acute loss of capacity, do not have any legal status in prescribing what we should or should not do."},{"id":"3389","category":"Cancer and palliative care and haematology","stem":"You are called to see a 58-year-old man who was transferred from the hospice. He has a diagnosis of metastatic pancreatic carcinoma. He was admitted from home for control of liver capsule pain the previous day. He is currently in favour of resuscitation, and when the team discussed this with him, he was very clear he would want to be resuscitated and have ‘everything done’. He has become increasingly breathless overnight.\n\nClinical examination of the respiratory system finds bilateral air entry with clear lung fields. CXR is normal.\n\nWhich of the following would be the most appropriate treatment for this patient?","options":["Observations:","Blood pressure\t110/72 mmHg","Heart rate\t106/min regular","Respiratory rate\t25/min","Oxygen sats","Temperature\t37.0°C","Which of the following would be the most appropriate treatment for this patient?","Venous thromboembolism in adults.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"Respiratory rate\t25/min","explanation":"Acute onset of shortness of breath in the middle of the night in a patient with cancer (in particular brain, pancreas, ovary, lung, bladder, stomach, uterus) is likely to be a pulmonary embolism, especially with raised respiratory rate, tachycardia and oxygen saturations on the cusp of the desaturation curve. The biggest mistake is not to consider it as a possibility and to diagnose panic attacks instead, whereas panic attacks need to be a diagnosis of exclusion. LMWH in this scenario can also be palliative in its effect. Similarly, the patient should be counselled regarding future care and the decision on resuscitation further discussed."},{"id":"9134","category":"Cancer and palliative care and haematology","stem":"A 72-year-old man presents with shortness of breath and left-sided chest pain. He has metastatic colonic carcinoma and was diagnosed with a pulmonary embolism six months ago, for which he was treated with low molecular weight heparin. He has been on enoxaparin since then at the treatment dose, and this has been administered religiously by his wife.\n\nFBC is normal with a platelet count of 250 (140-400).\n\nA CTPA is requested, and this is reported as showing evidence of bilateral moderate pulmonary emboli. Ultrasound of the legs reveals no evidence of a clot.","options":["FBC is normal with a platelet count of 250 (140-400).","A CTPA is requested, and this is reported as showing evidence of bilateral moderate pulmonary emboli. Ultrasound of the legs reveals no evidence of a clot.","Which of the following is the most appropriate approach to the management of this patient?","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"Which of the following is the most appropriate approach to the management of this patient?","explanation":"The patient illustrates a rather unusual event of recurrent venous thromboembolism despite a treatment dose of LMWH. Roughly 20% of patients with cancer-related thromboembolism will have recurrent thromboembolism despite anticoagulation. In the case of patients who are treated with warfarin or DOACs, the switch should be made to LMWH. The most appropriate approach to the management of this patient who has developed venous thromboembolism despite the LMWH is to increase the dose of the LMWH by around 25-33%. Others suggest a switch to a different LMWH, although this has less evidence related to it."},{"id":"7917","category":"Cancer and palliative care and haematology","stem":"An 80-year-old man was referred to MAU with a swollen left leg. In his background history, he had previously been treated with palliative chemotherapy for metastatic lung cancer. On examination, he had a swollen and tender left calf.\n\nInvestigations revealed:\n\nDoppler scans confirmed the presence of a proximal left deep vein thrombosis.","options":["Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"This patient has a DVT associated with moderate thrombocytopaenia and moderate renal impairment. These pose no contraindications to anticoagulation with low molecular weight heparin (LMWH), and this should be instituted in the usual dose. Dose alteration only needs adjustment when the estimated glomerular filtration rate (eGFRr) falls below 20-30. Similarly, one can administer full-dose LMWH in the context of a platelet count above 50. However, NICE guidance suggests that NOAC should be preferentially used in place of LMWH as it has been found to be more cost-effective. See the NICE guidance below concerning cancer and DVT."},{"id":"3384","category":"Cancer and palliative care and haematology","stem":"You are reviewing a 70-year-old patient in the ward with severe chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD) who is recovering from community-acquired pneumonia (CAP), having just completed a course of antibiotics. He is experiencing diarrhoea. On further questioning, he tells you it is green/brown, and he is opening his bowels up to seven times a day. The FY1 has sent a stool sample to the lab. His observations are stable. Investigations reveal normal U+Es, White cell count 14x109/L (3-10) with a neutrophil count of 10x109/L. Abdominal examination is unremarkable.\n\nWhat should you advise in this case?\n\nThe patient has recently completed antibiotics for a CAP, is elderly, and is at risk of C.difficile.","options":["The patient has recently completed antibiotics for a CAP, is elderly, and is at risk of C.difficile.","Vancomycin must be administered orally because intravenous administration does not achieve the gut lumen's minimum therapeutic concentration.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"The patient has recently completed antibiotics for a CAP, is elderly, and is at risk of C.difficile.","explanation":"The patient has recently completed antibiotics for a CAP, is elderly, and is at risk of C.difficile."},{"id":"11968","category":"Cancer and palliative care and haematology","stem":"A 52-year-old man presents to the clinic for his follow-up appointment. He has been on rivaroxaban 20 mg following two unprovoked deep venous thrombosis (DVT) and has now completed six months of anticoagulation. He has no significant past medical history and has not been on any other regular medicine. The patient is asymptomatic with no symptoms or signs to suggest cancer. His recent full blood count, liver function test, urea and electrolytes are normal. He has no side effects related to rivaroxaban. However, he was concerned about continuing any anticoagulation for more than six months, and after you explained the expected benefits and risks, the patient decided he did not want to continue anticoagulation.\n\nHow should you proceed with this patient?\n\nThis patient had two unprovoked DVT and should be on anticoagulation for life, which he does not agree to. As recommended by NICE guidelines, offering aspirin 75 to 150 mg once daily is recommended, which is an off-label use. The patient has no contraindication to aspirin. Clopidogrel has no known benefit in this case. There is no benefit in asking for a Doppler scan as he is asymptomatic and has been on anticoagulation. He does not have any symptoms or laboratory findings to suggest cancer, and as advised by NICE guidelines, he does not need more investigations to check for cancer.","options":["Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"This patient had two unprovoked DVT and should be on anticoagulation for life, which he does not agree to. As recommended by NICE guidelines, offering aspirin 75 to 150 mg once daily is recommended, which is an off-label use. The patient has no contraindication to aspirin. Clopidogrel has no known benefit in this case. There is no benefit in asking for a Doppler scan as he is asymptomatic and has been on anticoagulation. He does not have any symptoms or laboratory findings to suggest cancer, and as advised by NICE guidelines, he does not need more investigations to check for cancer."},{"id":"3402","category":"Cancer and palliative care and haematology","stem":"A 56-year-old woman with metastatic renal cell carcinoma is admitted with symptoms of general malaise and nausea and is noted to have corrected calcium 3.45 mmol/L (2.2 - 2.6). You prescribe an intravenous bisphosphonate infusion after rehydration.\n\nWhich of the following best describes the mode of action of bisphosphonates?\n\nThese drugs are pyrophosphate analogues that bind to hydroxyapatite crystals in bone matrix and inhibit osteoclastic bone resorption. They do not affect parathyroid hormone or parathyroid-related protein.","options":["Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"These drugs are pyrophosphate analogues that bind to hydroxyapatite crystals in bone matrix and inhibit osteoclastic bone resorption. They do not affect parathyroid hormone or parathyroid-related protein."},{"id":"3416","category":"Cancer and palliative care and haematology","stem":"A 55-year-old man with locally advanced non-small-cell lung cancer (NSCLC) is admitted to the hospice with a one-week history of progressive arm and facial swelling, facial plethora and shortness of breath. A chest x-ray is done, which shows a large superior mediastinal mass in the right lung. Symptoms and signs are suggestive of the diagnosis of superior vena caval obstruction secondary to mediastinal compression by the tumour, and you commence the patient on high-dose dexamethasone and symptomatic treatment.\n\nWhat is the next best active treatment option?","options":["Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"NICE guidance advises stenting as the 1st line option for patients with NSCLC as it gives faster relief of symptoms (95% in 48 hours) and is better tolerated than other treatments. After stenting, patients may be referred for radiotherapy or chemotherapy if appropriate."},{"id":"3414","category":"Cancer and palliative care and haematology","stem":"A 76-year-old man is being treated for renal cell carcinoma and has just received trimethoprim for a urine infection. You are called to see him as, within minutes of receiving the drug, he developed facial swelling, light-headedness, and difficulty breathing. On immediate assessment, you note that he has swelling of the lips and eyes with a widespread red blotchy rash. He is particularly wheezy, with a respiratory rate of 28/min, a pulse of 110 bpm and a supine blood pressure of 100/70 mmHg.\n\nWhich of the following would be the most appropriate immediate treatment for this patient?\n\nThis patient is likely to have developed a severe allergic reaction, as evidenced by the swelling and rash, but more worryingly, there are also features of anaphylaxis, as evidenced by the difficulty breathing and wheezing. He requires urgent treatment, and the acknowledged first-line treatment for anaphylaxis is IM adrenaline, which is typically administered via an adrenaline autoinjector. In case of no response, IM adrenaline can be repeated after 5 minutes.","options":["Resuscitation Council UK - Emergency treatment of anaphylactic reactions: Guidelines for healthcare providers.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"This patient is likely to have developed a severe allergic reaction, as evidenced by the swelling and rash, but more worryingly, there are also features of anaphylaxis, as evidenced by the difficulty breathing and wheezing. He requires urgent treatment, and the acknowledged first-line treatment for anaphylaxis is IM adrenaline, which is typically administered via an adrenaline autoinjector. In case of no response, IM adrenaline can be repeated after 5 minutes."},{"id":"3405","category":"Cancer and palliative care and haematology","stem":"You review a 76-year-old man who has cancer of the prostate and widespread bony metastases. His back pain is much worse this morning, and his legs feel weak and “wobbly”. He is unable to pass urine.\n\nOn examination, he has weakness in both legs with reduced tone and brisk reflexes of the lower limbs with upgoing plantar responses. The sensation is difficult to assess but seems impaired in the lower limbs up to the waist.\n\nWhat is the most appropriate immediate course of action for this patient?","options":["Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"The history suggests spinal cord compression, and with neurological symptoms and signs, spinal instability cannot be excluded. The patient should, therefore, be nursed flat in bed and log-rolled as necessary until spinal stability is known. The urgent request for an MRI and commencement of steroids is also urgent, but whilst these are being organised, preventing further neurological deterioration should be the first action."},{"id":"8121","category":"Cancer and palliative care and haematology","stem":"A 55-year-old man, who has a history of metastatic prostate cancer which has been well-controlled with LHRH analogues plus radiotherapy, is reviewed in admissions. He has a background of type 2 diabetes, currently treated with tablets. He informs you that he has developed muscle aches and pains over the last two months. He currently takes metformin, ramipril, aspirin, simvastatin and recently amlodipine. On examination, there are pains to palpation of his thighs and shoulders with no weakness in his proximal muscles, but his blood pressure and temperature are normal.\n\nInvestigation results reveal:\n\nWhich of the following is the likely diagnosis?","options":["Severe statin-induced autoimmune myopathy successfully treated with intravenous immunoglobulin Cansu Güngör,1 Udo Carl Wieshmann,2.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"This is typical of a statin-induced myopathy with mild elevation of the CPK and typical of generalised muscle aches. Polymyositis would seem improbable with this mild elevation of CPK. Drugs that inhibit cytochrome P450 and hence the metabolism of statins may precipitate myopathy and include fibrates, amiodarone, calcium channel blockers, and thiazolidinediones."},{"id":"7924","category":"Cancer and palliative care and haematology","stem":"A 72-year-old man presented to MAU with a one-day history of intermittent, mild abdominal pain and five episodes of diarrhoea. He had a history of bowel cancer for which he had received adjuvant chemotherapy with 5-fluorouracil nine days ago.\n\nOn examination, the patient’s pulse was 80 beats per minute, regular, temperature was 37oC and blood pressure was 132/88 mmHg. There was mild abdominal tenderness, but no masses palpable.\n\nInvestigations revealed:","options":["Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"This patient has symptoms of abdominal discomfort and diarrhoea as a side effect of 5-FU chemotherapy and should be treated with loperamide and reassured, along with advice to maintain adequate oral hydration. Diarrhoea is a very common side effect of 5-FU and generally settles after 2-3 days. The low neutrophil count is also a component of chemotherapy, but in the absence of overt infection, it does not require intervention. If they do not settle, then the patient should be informed to return."},{"id":"3393","category":"Cancer and palliative care and haematology","stem":"A 42-year-old man with a known mid-oesophageal squamous cell carcinoma had a metal stent inserted three weeks ago to relieve dysphagia. He had been feeling much better since the insertion and eating a semi-soft diet. He presents to the accident and emergency department on a Sunday evening with acute-onset dysphagia over the previous 8 hours. He had been out for a meal with his family earlier that day.\n\nYou are called by the A&E doctor for advice. What would you advise?","options":["BSIR.ORG - Oesophageal Stents - Complications.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"A warm or fizzy drink is most likely to unblock a blocked metal stent. It is also recommended that the patient stand and walk around if able to, rather than lying down.\nIf a stent is suspected of being blocked, the patient should not be encouraged to eat any food until unblocked.\nAvoid ice/cold drinks, which can alter the shape of a metal stent and cause it to move out of place.\nThere is nothing in the history to suggest that the patient is choking and requires the Heimlich manoeuvre."},{"id":"3396","category":"Cancer and palliative care and haematology","stem":"You are reviewing a 45-year-old woman with acute dyspnoea. She has a swollen leg and is currently in the hospital being treated for neutropenic sepsis following chemotherapy for adrenal carcinoma. You suspect acute DVT and possible pulmonary embolism.\n\nRegarding investigating venous thromboembolism, which of the following is true?\n\nA negative D-dimer assay reliably excludes PE in patients with a low or intermediate probability, and such patients do not require imaging for VTE. However, in patients with high clinical probability (i.e., high Wells score), diagnostic investigation like CT pulmonary angiogram or ventilation-perfusion scan should be done, and D-dimers are not indicated.","options":["CTPA is now the recommended initial lung imaging modality for pulmonary embolism, where possible, as this will show other possible diagnoses too.","Thrombolysis is the first-line treatment for massive PE and may be instituted on clinical grounds alone if cardiac arrest is imminent (BTS Guidelines; may not be appropriate in our patient subgroup).","Heparin should be given to patients with an intermediate or high probability of PE before imaging. LMWH is considered preferable to unfractionated heparin.","British Thoracic Society guidelines for the management of suspected acute pulmonary embolism.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"A negative D-dimer assay reliably excludes PE in patients with a low or intermediate probability, and such patients do not require imaging for VTE. However, in patients with high clinical probability (i.e., high Wells score), diagnostic investigation like CT pulmonary angiogram or ventilation-perfusion scan should be done, and D-dimers are not indicated."},{"id":"7926","category":"Cancer and palliative care and haematology","stem":"A 60-year-old woman was admitted with a two-day history of deteriorating headaches. She is known to have breast cancer with lung and liver metastases, which had proven responsive to palliative chemotherapy.\n\nThere was nothing of note on physical examination. A CT head scan revealed an isolated left frontal mass with surrounding oedema.\n\nWhich of the following is the most appropriate approach to the management of this patient?","options":["Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"to treat with high-dose steroids (dexamethasone 16 mg daily)","explanation":"This patient presents with a likely case of isolated frontal cortex metastasis, and the most appropriate approach would be to treat with high-dose steroids (dexamethasone 16 mg daily), particularly as the scan suggests oedema. The patient should also receive an MRI to confirm if there is more than one metastasis. If there is a single metastasis, the neurosurgeons may consider surgery based on the evidence of improved survival with the removal of a single metastasis. Lumbar puncture (LP) is contraindicated with a space-occupying lesion (SOL) and evidence of raised pressure. Stereotactic radiotherapy will be suitable for a single brain metastasis with a diameter of up to a maximum of 3cm to 4cm."},{"id":"3413","category":"Cancer and palliative care and haematology","stem":"A 55-year-old man treated for bowel carcinoma develops anaphylaxis on the ward and is successfully treated. The precipitant is unknown. He is observed overnight, and his discharge is planned for the following morning.\n\nWhich of the following should the patient be provided with before discharge from the hospital?\n\nIt is recommended that all patients who are admitted with diagnosed anaphylaxis should be provided with an adrenaline auto-injector and trained on its use before discharge. The patient should be advised to keep the auto-injector with them at all times and should also be referred to a specialist allergy clinic for follow-up, where this is available. The patient should also be supplied with a written emergency management plan, where possible.","options":["Emergency treatment of anaphylactic reactions: Guidelines for healthcare providers.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"It is recommended that all patients who are admitted with diagnosed anaphylaxis should be provided with an adrenaline auto-injector and trained on its use before discharge. The patient should be advised to keep the auto-injector with them at all times and should also be referred to a specialist allergy clinic for follow-up, where this is available. The patient should also be supplied with a written emergency management plan, where possible."},{"id":"3388","category":"Cancer and palliative care and haematology","stem":"You see a patient who is very unwell in the hospice on a Saturday whilst you are on call. He has a known diagnosis of lung cancer with liver, adrenal and contralateral lung metastases. He was commenced on antibiotics for a lower respiratory tract infection yesterday, and today is very lethargic, dizzy and clammy. You ask the staff nurse to check his observations, and she’s very worried when his heart rate is recorded at 123/min and blood pressure as 77/52 mmHg.\n\nWhat would be your first course of action?\n\nThe history and clinical features are suggestive of an Addisonian crisis. You would expect a high potassium, lowered sodium, and raised urea (secondary to hypovolaemia). A short synacthen test will confirm adrenal insufficiency, but this takes time, and the results would not be back in time to influence management in this patient over the weekend. The initial treatment should consist of rapid IV rehydration and IV steroids. Oral hydrocortisone may be given to manage adrenal insufficiency, but not in crisis. Atenolol would only lower BP further.","options":["Rathbun, K. M., Nguyen, M., Singhal, M. Addisonian Crisis. StatPearls, 2021.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"The history and clinical features are suggestive of an Addisonian crisis. You would expect a high potassium, lowered sodium, and raised urea (secondary to hypovolaemia). A short synacthen test will confirm adrenal insufficiency, but this takes time, and the results would not be back in time to influence management in this patient over the weekend. The initial treatment should consist of rapid IV rehydration and IV steroids. Oral hydrocortisone may be given to manage adrenal insufficiency, but not in crisis. Atenolol would only lower BP further."},{"id":"3404","category":"Cancer and palliative care and haematology","stem":"You review a 39-year-old woman with a primary brain tumour who has become pancytopenic due to temozolomide chemotherapy. She has left lower leg swelling and redness. A venous Doppler confirms a femoral deep vein thrombosis. Due to her brain tumour (grade 2 astrocytoma), she had limited mobility.\n\nWhich of the following is the most appropriate immediate management of her DVT?\n\nAs the patient is well enough to receive chemotherapy, we must assume that she is also well enough to receive treatment for DVT. However, her platelet count is < 40 (due to chemotherapy, so this is likely temporary), and the most appropriate management would be the insertion of a temporary IVC filter. Once her platelet count is > 40-50, then it would be reasonable for her to receive newer anticoagulant therapy, which is effective and safe for cancer-associated VTE and is now included in national guidelines. A local haematologist should be consulted.","options":["Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"the insertion of a temporary IVC filter","explanation":"As the patient is well enough to receive chemotherapy, we must assume that she is also well enough to receive treatment for DVT. However, her platelet count is < 40 (due to chemotherapy, so this is likely temporary), and the most appropriate management would be the insertion of a temporary IVC filter. Once her platelet count is > 40-50, then it would be reasonable for her to receive newer anticoagulant therapy, which is effective and safe for cancer-associated VTE and is now included in national guidelines. A local haematologist should be consulted."},{"id":"3415","category":"Cancer and palliative care and haematology","stem":"A 50-year-old woman with a diagnosis of metastatic ovarian carcinoma is reviewed, and she reports being unwell for the past day with a chest infection. She has had a cough and slight fever and was given some antibiotics by her GP. She also has a diagnosis of hypoadrenalism for which she has been receiving hydrocortisone 10 mg twice daily.\n\nOn examination, she has a temperature of 37.5oC, a couple of crackles at the left base, a blood pressure of 122/72 mmHg with a pulse of 84 bpm, and a respiratory rate of 14 breaths per minute.\n\nWhich of the following is the most appropriate approach regarding her steroid therapy?","options":["Department of Diabetes and Endocrinology. Sick day rules for patients taking long-term replacement steroid therapy (Hydrocortisone or Prednisolone).","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"This patient has hypoadrenalism for which she is receiving a replacement dose of hydrocortisone, which is typically 10mg bd. To avoid acute hypoadrenalism, the patient should be informed of sick day rules and should at least have their dose of steroids doubled for the duration of the illness. There is no evidence of acute hypoadrenalism here that would merit IV hydrocortisone."},{"id":"3386","category":"Cancer and palliative care and haematology","stem":"A 78-year-old man has a history of hypertension and two previous myocardial infarctions, and he was diagnosed with metastatic small-cell lung cancer a month ago. His community nurse specialist has referred him to be admitted to the hospice for symptom control of his chest wall pain, but she also suspects he may be dying. You note on admission that he has an implantable device under his skin, and following a review of his hospital case notes and discussion with the patient, you confirm this is an implantable cardioverter-defibrillator (ICD).\n\nWhat would be the best management plan?\n\nThe best approach would be for the management plan to be multidisciplinary and to involve the cardiologists. Given the concerns that this patient may be entering the terminal phase, this should not be a routine referral, although it does seem appropriate that a DNACPR order be discussed with the patient and completed. Also, many cardiologists have remote monitoring systems in place for their ICD patients, and if you were to inactivate a device with a magnet without informing them, the device downloads could be very confusing.","options":["Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"for the management plan to be multidisciplinary and to involve the cardiologists","explanation":"The best approach would be for the management plan to be multidisciplinary and to involve the cardiologists. Given the concerns that this patient may be entering the terminal phase, this should not be a routine referral, although it does seem appropriate that a DNACPR order be discussed with the patient and completed. Also, many cardiologists have remote monitoring systems in place for their ICD patients, and if you were to inactivate a device with a magnet without informing them, the device downloads could be very confusing."},{"id":"3423","category":"Cancer and palliative care and haematology","stem":"(Normal ranges: phosphate 0.8-1.45 mmol/L, Potassium 3.4 - 5.0 mmol/L, Urea 2.5-7.5 mmol/L, Calcium 2.2-2.6 mmol/L, Urate <0.42 mmol/L)\n\nWhich of the following investigation results would support this diagnosis?\n\nThe condition is classified using the Cairo-Bishop (2004) definition. This consists of two categories: Laboratory Tumour Lysis Syndrome (LTS) and Clinical Tumour Lysis Syndrome (CTLS).","options":["(Normal ranges: phosphate 0.8-1.45 mmol/L, Potassium 3.4 - 5.0 mmol/L, Urea 2.5-7.5 mmol/L, Calcium 2.2-2.6 mmol/L, Urate <0.42 mmol/L)","Which of the following investigation results would support this diagnosis?","The condition is classified using the Cairo-Bishop (2004) definition. This consists of two categories: Laboratory Tumour Lysis Syndrome (LTS) and Clinical Tumour Lysis Syndrome (CTLS).","Laboratory Tumour Lysis syndrome (LTS) is when any two or more of the following occur within 3 days of receiving chemotherapy:","Clinical Tumour Lysis Syndrome (CTLS) develops when there is a significant rise in serum creatinine, cardiac arrhythmia, seizure and death.","Reflection: It is important to consider that each establishment may interpret its results differently, and this needs to be considered when analysing the blood values of patients.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"The condition is classified using the Cairo-Bishop (2004) definition. This consists of two categories: Laboratory Tumour Lysis Syndrome (LTS) and Clinical Tumour Lysis Syndrome (CTLS).","explanation":"The condition is classified using the Cairo-Bishop (2004) definition. This consists of two categories: Laboratory Tumour Lysis Syndrome (LTS) and Clinical Tumour Lysis Syndrome (CTLS)."},{"id":"3412","category":"Cancer and palliative care and haematology","stem":"A 65-year-old woman develops acute facial swelling and dyspnoea following a second dose of opiates for cancer-related pain. On examination, she is breathless and has angioedema of the face, eyes, and lips.\n\nWhich of the following is the most appropriate initial treatment for this patient?","options":["Resuscitation Council (UK) Guidelines","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"Resuscitation Council (UK) Guidelines","explanation":"All healthcare professionals should be aware of how to treat anaphylaxis as displayed by this patient's presentation. The MRC has developed formal guidelines on treating anaphylaxis, and the most important initial therapy is IM adrenaline, often given by an autoinjector. Full guidelines on the Resuscitation Council (UK) website and more specifically on page 20 of the PDF (see reference). IV adrenaline should not be administered unless by a specialist with expertise in the delivery of adrenaline IV."},{"id":"10142","category":"Cancer and palliative care and haematology","stem":"A 39-year-old woman presents with a 7-day history of progressive swelling of the entire left leg. She has recently returned from a holiday in Mexico. She has no past medical history. On examination, her entire left leg is swollen with tenderness along with the deep venous system. A Doppler confirms a left Iliofemoral deep vein thrombosis (DVT). You admit her for anticoagulation.\n\nWhat other management strategy should you consider?\n\nCatheter-directed thrombolytic therapy should be considered in those patients who have symptomatic iliofemoral DVT if they have had symptoms for <14 days, have good functional status, >1 year to live, and low bleeding risk. An IVC filter would be considered if the patient was unable to be anticoagulated (e.g. recent intracranial bleed) or if they had recurrent VTEs despite adequate anticoagulation therapy.","options":["Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"Catheter-directed thrombolytic therapy should be considered in those patients who have symptomatic iliofemoral DVT if they have had symptoms for <14 days, have good functional status, >1 year to live, and low bleeding risk. An IVC filter would be considered if the patient was unable to be anticoagulated (e.g. recent intracranial bleed) or if they had recurrent VTEs despite adequate anticoagulation therapy."},{"id":"3631","category":"Cancer and palliative care and haematology","stem":"A 72-year-old man is sent to emergency admissions after his GP found that his INR was 10 a day ago. The patient has been taking warfarin for atrial fibrillation for the last three years and has had no problems. His INR is maintained between 2-2.5 in general. Recently, he took some antibiotics for a chest infection, but has otherwise been well.\n\nHis INR on this occasion is 10.1.\n\nWhich of the following is the most appropriate approach to the management of this patient?","options":["Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"This patient has an elevated INR but no sign of haemorrhage. Guidelines suggest that the patient can be managed with a dose of oral vitamin K 1-5 mg and by stopping the warfarin. In patients who do not have bleeding, oral vitamin K is preferred as equal correction is achieved at 24 hours, as compared to intravenous, which produces the effects in 6-8 hours when required for rapid correction in bleeding patients."},{"id":"7860","category":"Cancer and palliative care and haematology","stem":"A 65-year-old man presents to MAU with diarrhoea and central abdominal pain. These symptoms have evolved over the last three days. His diarrhoea was loose, with no evidence of blood and yellowish-green in colour, up to 10 times per day. In his past medical history, he had a recent diagnosis of T3 N2 rectal carcinoma for which he had just finished chemotherapy with capecitabine along with radiotherapy.\n\nOn examination, he had a pulse of 100 bpm, a temperature of 37oC and a blood pressure of 110/74 mmHg. Abdominal examination revealed tenderness over the epigastrium and central abdomen, and loud bowel sounds. His abdominal plain film demonstrated distended small bowel loops.\n\nWhich of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","options":["Stacey, R. and Green, J.T., 2014. Radiation-induced small bowel disease: latest developments and clinical guidance. Therapeutic advances in chronic disease, 5(1), pp.15-29.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"The differential here includes infection, yet the temperature is low, and the proximity of symptoms to the chemo-radiation needs to be appreciated. Campylobacter jejuni infection may be expected to cause pain, fever and bloody diarrhoea. Enterocolitis and ischaemic colitis are uncommon in association with capecitabine and would be a less credible explanation than radiation-induced small bowel enteropathy. The symptoms include bloating, profuse diarrhoea and nausea/vomiting. It is particularly common in patients receiving abdominal or pelvic radiotherapy."},{"id":"3390","category":"Cancer and palliative care and haematology","stem":"A 45-year-old man with known lung cancer presents to A&E with leg weakness and urinary retention. He was assessed and commenced on dexamethasone, and an urgent MRI whole spine was requested.\n\nWhich of the following features would favour surgical decompression over radiotherapy in the management of this likely metastatic spinal cord compression?\n\nThe prime purpose of spinal surgery is to preserve or recover neurological function in the hope of maintaining functional independence and the highest possible quality of remaining life. This may include either separately or in combination: spinal cord decompression to avert or treat MSCC, spinal column stabilisation to treat mechanical pain or bony instability, and resection/reconstruction of the spinal column in the hope of a durable surgical result providing good quality long-term survival. Simple decompression of the spinal cord is the least demanding for the patient and may be sufficient to optimise the neurological outcome, but stabilisation of the involved levels is usually required to maximise spinal stability and duration of effect.","options":["Indications for radiotherapy: radiosensitive tumour, several levels of compression, unfit for major surgery, and patient choice.","The real extra benefit of surgical decompression would seem to be for the non-ambulant patient with a single site of cord compression and a prognosis of >3 months.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"The prime purpose of spinal surgery is to preserve or recover neurological function in the hope of maintaining functional independence and the highest possible quality of remaining life. This may include either separately or in combination: spinal cord decompression to avert or treat MSCC, spinal column stabilisation to treat mechanical pain or bony instability, and resection/reconstruction of the spinal column in the hope of a durable surgical result providing good quality long-term survival. Simple decompression of the spinal cord is the least demanding for the patient and may be sufficient to optimise the neurological outcome, but stabilisation of the involved levels is usually required to maximise spinal stability and duration of effect."},{"id":"8063","category":"Cardiovascular medicine","stem":"An 80-year-old man is admitted to medical emergency admissions with a 10-hour history of slurred speech and right arm weakness.\n\nClinical assessment and investigations confirm an acute stroke. The patient is not a suitable candidate for thrombolysis.\n\nWhich of the following should be the standard of care for this patient?","options":["RCP guideline calls for suspected stroke patients to be scanned within 1 hour of hospital admission.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"According to the NICE and RCP guidance, patients with proven stroke should be transferred to a dedicated stroke unit where a multidisciplinary team is available to provide management during the acute phase, monitor for any complications like seizures or progression of stroke and also can provide rehabilitation once the acute phase is over."},{"id":"5095","category":"Cardiovascular medicine","stem":"A 54-year-old man presents with chest pain. Four hours ago, he developed central chest pain, which he describes as heavy and left-sided. There was some radiation to the jaw. It settled down within about 30 minutes, but he decided to seek advice. The A&E department has referred him to you.\n\nHe has no past medical history of note but has a family history of ischaemic heart disease (IHD), with his father having had a myocardial infarction (MI) at the age of 62. He is a smoker of 10 cigarettes daily.\n\nThere is little to find on examination, and he is pain-free now. His ECG is normal. Relevant results include a high sensitivity troponin T taken at admission (4 hours after onset of pain) 12 ng/L (<14).\n\nWhat is the most appropriate management strategy for this patient?","options":["Troponin testing in the primary care setting. Manuela S Mauro, Adam J Nelson, Michael B Stokes.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"the patient should have a repeat troponin arranged as the initial step and","explanation":"The high-sensitivity troponin T-test has revolutionised the management of patients with suspected IHD. Two measurements are required if the patient presents within 6 hours and the value is <14 to exclude acute coronary syndrome (ACS). In this case, the patient presented 4 hours later and had a pretty good story for IHD. Therefore, the patient should have a repeat troponin arranged as the initial step and, if ACS is excluded, the patient should be referred for assessment, such as ETT."},{"id":"16833","category":"Cardiovascular medicine","stem":"A 79-year-old woman was assessed at the acute medicine follow-up clinic. She was previously hospitalised due to episodes of tachycardia; however, upon admission, a 12-lead electrocardiogram (ECG) revealed a normal sinus rhythm. The patient reported prior instances of similar symptoms that resolved on their own. She does not have a significant past medical history. Subsequently, an outpatient 24-hour ECG was performed and revealed a 10-minute episode of atrial fibrillation (AF). She reported no symptoms of palpitations during the examination.\n\nWhat is the first line of management for this patient?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Paroxysmal AF","Paroxysmal AF begins suddenly and ends spontaneously within seven days. It is the most common form of intermittent AF, typically terminating within 48 hours.","Persistent AF","On the other hand, persistent AF requires pharmacologic or electrical intervention to return to a normal sinus rhythm.","Permanent AF","When the normal rhythm cannot be restored for a substantial period, AF is deemed permanent.","It is crucial to mention that this patient requires anticoagulation therapy as her CHA2DS2VASC score is equal to or greater than 2.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"Paroxysmal AF","explanation":"This patient's precise diagnosis has yet to be confirmed due to an absence of correlation between the symptoms and rhythm. However, the patient is likely experiencing intermittent episodes of atrial fibrillation (AF), called paroxysmal AF, that is causing her symptoms."},{"id":"12260","category":"Cardiovascular medicine","stem":"A 50-year-old man presents to the acute medicine unit with acute-onset right hemiparesis, and his CT brain shows an acute left middle cerebral artery infarct. He undergoes successful thrombolytic therapy. He describes a history of a recent injury to his left leg with a fracture of his patellar bone. Following this, he remained immobile for two weeks. A Doppler ultrasound of his left leg shows a proximal deep venous thrombosis.\n\nHis ECG is shown below:\n\n[Author’s own image].\n\nWhat further investigation should be done as a workup for the cause of this patient’s ischaemic stroke?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"This patient has a paradoxical embolism causing the acute stroke from the deep venous thrombus (DVT) in the leg from his immobility. The ECG shows a right bundle branch block suggestive of elevated right heart pressure/volume and likely congenital heart disease (atrial/ventricular septal defects). The next appropriate investigation to determine the cause of the stroke would be to perform trans-thoracic echocardiography."},{"id":"16832","category":"Cardiovascular medicine","stem":"A 66-year-old woman was admitted to the local district general hospital with an anterior ST-segment elevation myocardial infarction (STEMI). She complained of severe chest pain before her husband called for help. The husband also noted that she was clammy and sweaty. About five minutes after being transferred to the emergency department, a student nurse pointed out that the patient looked unwell and appeared grey. The cardiac monitor showed a broad-complex tachycardia. Her femoral pulse was palpable, and his blood pressure was 79/40 mmHg.\n\nWhat should be your next approach?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","There is no role for CPR or adrenaline as this is not a cardiac arrest situation.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"The patient has unstable tachycardia, and the answer, according to European Resuscitation Guidelines and Resuscitation Council UK guidelines, is immediate DC cardioversion, given that the patient is haemodynamically compromised and presenting with presumed ventricular tachycardia until proven otherwise."},{"id":"17406","category":"Cardiovascular medicine","stem":"A 60-year-old woman is a known case of heart failure with a reduced ejection fraction (EF) of 30 per cent. The patient’s current medications include metformin 1000 mg in the morning and evening, bisoprolol 5 mg at night, lisinopril 10 mg in the morning, spironolactone 50 mg and furosemide 40 mg in the morning. She has been admitted to the hospital for acute pulmonary oedema, which has now resolved after intravenous furosemide and nitrates. Her current haemoglobin A1c (HbA1c) is 7.1% (normal range: < 5.7 %)\n\nWhich medication, if added to the treatment regime, will help improve glycaemic control, have positive mortality benefits for this patient, and reduce the risk of hospitalisations due to heart failure?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"dapagliflozin","explanation":"The correct answer is dapagliflozin. All of the medications can be considered as step-up therapy in addition to metformin for normalisation and better control of HbA1c; however, in this particular case, the patient is suffering from heart failure with reduced ejection fraction. Dapagliflozin, which is a sodium-glucose cotransporter-2 (SGLT-2) inhibitor, is the preferred option as it has a mortality benefit in heart failure with reduced ejection fraction and has been shown in randomised controlled trials to reduce the incidence of hospitalisations due to heart failure. Empagliflozin, which is another drug of the same class, has also been found to have the same benefit."},{"id":"13639","category":"Cardiovascular medicine","stem":"A 25-year-old man attends the emergency department after he suffers a sudden onset of palpitations, nausea, light-headedness, and dizziness with central chest pain, which lasted for about 10 minutes while he was sitting at his desk and working. He says the symptoms abruptly stopped on their own. He says this is his second episode in two months, but this episode lasted considerably longer, which makes him very worried. He drinks beer about twice a week but admits to having three pints of beer the previous night, and also smokes about a pack of cigarettes per day. Otherwise, he denies any other medical history and has an unremarkable family history.\n\nOn examination, he is alert and oriented. He has a pulse rate of 75 beats per minute, a blood pressure of 120/80 mmHg, a respiratory rate of 12 breaths per minute, and oxygen saturation on air of 100%. His temperature is 37 oC. Capillary refill time is 1 second, and his jugular venous pressure is not elevated. No leg oedema is noted. A respiratory system examination shows normal breath sounds on both sides. A cardiovascular system examination reveals normal heart sounds. His abdomen is soft with no tenderness, and there are active bowel sounds.\n\nHis ECG is shown below:\n\nImage source: Author’s own.\n\nWhat is the most likely diagnosis?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","His ECG is shown below:","Image source: Author’s own.","What is the most likely diagnosis?","The ECG shows WPW pattern (pre-excitation) changes: shortened PR interval (<0.12 seconds) with a widened QRS complex due to a delta wave (slurred upstroke in the QRS).","(Green: shortened PR interval. Orange: Delta wave)","The patient has had two episodes of palpitations with associated symptoms suggestive of tachyarrhythmias; therefore, he likely has WPW syndrome.","Thyroid storm is characterised by tachycardia, hyperpyrexia, and anxiety states, and it is unlikely in this patient as the symptoms are paroxysmal and self-terminating.","Alcohol withdrawal is unlikely given the patient’s history of insignificant consumption.","Panic attacks should be diagnosed only if no other physical cause is found.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"The ECG shows WPW pattern (pre-excitation) changes: shortened PR interval (<0.12 seconds) with a widened QRS complex due to a delta wave (slurred upstroke in the QRS).","explanation":"The ECG shows WPW pattern (pre-excitation) changes: shortened PR interval (<0.12 seconds) with a widened QRS complex due to a delta wave (slurred upstroke in the QRS)."},{"id":"8073","category":"Cardiovascular medicine","stem":"An 80-year-old man is admitted to the stroke unit following admission with left-sided weakness. He has a history of atrial fibrillation and is being treated with bisoprolol and warfarin. A CT scan is suggestive of an ischaemic stroke.\n\nWhich of the following assessments should be undertaken initially on this patient?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"This patient should undergo an assessment of swallow to determine if it is safe for him to take nutrition orally or not. This is a vital component of stroke rehabilitation that is sometimes overlooked."},{"id":"12399","category":"Cardiovascular medicine","stem":"A 76-year-old man presented to the emergency department with symptoms suggestive of a urinary tract infection over the last weekend. He felt well in himself with no sepsis features. He had been started on oral antibiotics by the A&E doctor who was planning to discharge him; however, upon review of the patient’s ECG, the doctor became concerned.\n\nThe patient was known to have benign prostatic hypertrophy and moderate to severe aortic stenosis, for which he was having 6-9 monthly surveillance echocardiograms. He denied any chest pain or shortness of breath but confirmed a two-year history of episodes of palpitation, which were self-limiting. He had not informed his doctor of these episodes.\n\nThe patient’s ECG can be seen below:\n\nThe ED doctor contacts you to ask about possible anticoagulation strategies suitable for this patient's situation. What should you advise?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","The patient has atrial flutter with variable block, and the anticoagulation rules for atrial fibrillation (AF) are the same for atrial flutter.","The patient's age puts him at risk with a CHADS2 Vasc score of 2, suggesting high thromboembolic risk and the need for anticoagulation.","Warfarin can be used as an anticoagulation option, but not because of AF with VHD reasons. Aspirin has no role unless the patient refuses anticoagulation.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"The patient has atrial flutter with variable block, and the anticoagulation rules for atrial fibrillation (AF) are the same for atrial flutter.","explanation":"The patient has atrial flutter with variable block, and the anticoagulation rules for atrial fibrillation (AF) are the same for atrial flutter."},{"id":"17506","category":"Cardiovascular medicine","stem":"A 28-year-old woman was brought to the emergency department after collapsing in the bathroom one hour ago. The patient provided a history of consuming salt fish two hours before the collapse. She also complained of generalised itching and giddiness. She has consumed salt fish in the past and never had any allergic reactions. The patient reports no history of food allergy or any drug use. She is not suffering from any other medical conditions. On examination, the patient had a generalised erythematous reaction with a pulse rate of 94 per minute, a blood pressure of 64/42 mmHg, and oxygen saturation of 98% on room air.\n\nThe patient was immediately connected to the monitor, which showed sinus tachycardia. She was given an IV bolus of normal saline 500 ml and intramuscular 0.5 ml of 1:1000 adrenaline stat. There was no improvement in her blood pressure. The dose of adrenaline was repeated, but there was no change in the blood pressure.\n\nWhat is the most important next step in the management of this patient?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","What is the most important next step in the management of this patient?","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"What is the most important next step in the management of this patient?","explanation":"Refractory anaphylactic shock is a rare life-threatening condition where there is no improvement in blood pressure even after two doses of adrenaline. The next important step in the management is to start a low-dose adrenaline infusion in the appropriate healthcare settings under supervision. There is no proven role for hydrocortisone in the management of anaphylactic shock. Antihistamines are useful only for the management of skin reactions, not for circulatory failure. Intramuscular adrenaline can be given every five minutes."},{"id":"3589","category":"Cardiovascular medicine","stem":"A 56-year-old man is admitted with an episode of palpitations. He is known to suffer from paroxysmal atrial fibrillation and is being treated with bisoprolol 5mg daily. He finds that the bisoprolol does ‘slow him down physically’, but he has been compliant with treatment. This is the second occasion over the last year that he has been admitted with palpitations. The ECG confirms atrial fibrillation at a rate of 96 bpm. He knows when the AF happens as he feels strange, gets a little breathless and can feel an irregular pulse. Usually, it settles after a couple of hours of rest, but on this occasion, it persisted for about 3 hours, so he came to the hospital. He previously had an ECHO, which was normal.\n\nWhich of the following would you suggest for the management of this man’s atrial fibrillation?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"This man has recurrent paroxysmal atrial fibrillation, and the patient should be switched to an alternative agent with guidelines recommending flecainide, provided there is no evidence of IHD, and the objective is the maintenance of sinus rhythm. This patient will not qualify for anticoagulation as his CHA2DS2-VASc score is 0."},{"id":"11964","category":"Cardiovascular medicine","stem":"You have been asked to review a 64-year-old man in the emergency department who is known to be hypertensive. He presented with central chest pain that started 30 minutes ago. The pain has improved little with glyceryl trinitrate (GTN) given by the ambulance team.\n\nHis ECG is shown below:\n\n[Image: author’s own]\n\nThe A&E doctor asks for your opinion on this patient’s ECG and how to best proceed with management.\n\nHow should you respond?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"The ECG shows V7, V8 and V9 that was done due to ST Depression in V2& V3 suspecting posterior myocardial infarction (MI). The posterior leads show ST Elevation, confirming posterior MI. The best way forward is to refer him for primary PCI (PPCI) in the nearest tertiary hospital if expected to be performed within 120 minutes."},{"id":"16834","category":"Cardiovascular medicine","stem":"A 37-year-old veterinary surgeon was admitted to the acute medical unit with a fever and malaise. He had a patent ductus arteriosus closed as a child.\n\nOn examination, the patient looked flushed. His temperature was 38.1oC, his pulse was 96 beats per minute and regular, and his blood pressure was 109/60 mmHg. He had generalised muscle tenderness, red, painless spots on his palms and soles, and signs of recent weight loss. No cardiac murmurs were heard.\n\nInvestigations reveal serum C-reactive protein of 238 mg/L (<10), and blood culture reveals coxiella burnetii.\n\nWhat is the most appropriate next step in management?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Treatment for infective endocarditis should be started immediately as the diagnostic criteria have been met.","The Modified Duke criteria for the diagnosis of infective endocarditis (IE) necessitate:","A definite diagnosis of Infective endocarditis (IE) requires:","Pathological criteria satisfaction, or\nTwo major criteria, or\nOne major and two minor criteria, or\nFive minor criteria.","A possible diagnosis of Infective endocarditis (IE) is established with:","One major and one minor criterion, or\nThree minor criteria.","A rejected diagnosis of infective endocarditis (IE) is established in the presence of:","The major criteria for Infective endocarditis (IE) encompass:","The minor criteria for Infective endocarditis (IE) include:","Blood culture-negative IE refers to infectious endocarditis in which no causative microbe can be isolated using conventional blood culture methods.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"Treatment for infective endocarditis should be started immediately as the diagnostic criteria have been met.","explanation":"Treatment for infective endocarditis should be started immediately as the diagnostic criteria have been met."},{"id":"3977","category":"Cardiovascular medicine","stem":"You are part of the crash team at a local district general hospital. You are called to a 78-year-old patient with ventricular tachycardia, who still has a cardiac output.\n\nWhich of the following scenarios would you deliver urgent electrical cardioversion?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","ALS guidelines recommend immediate DC cardioversion for all decompensated tachycardias. Life-threatening features in an unstable patient include:","Resus: 2021 Resuscitation Guidelines.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"ALS guidelines recommend immediate DC cardioversion for all decompensated tachycardias. Life-threatening features in an unstable patient include:","explanation":"ALS guidelines recommend immediate DC cardioversion for all decompensated tachycardias. Life-threatening features in an unstable patient include:"},{"id":"7110","category":"Cardiovascular medicine","stem":"A 17-year-old boy presents to A&E with a minor sporting injury. However, he is noted to have a blood pressure reading of 180/110 mmHg. He is admitted, and his blood pressure does not settle below 160/90 mmHg. His dad says there is a family history of high blood pressure and strokes on his father’s side.\n\nClinical examination is unremarkable.\n\nInvestigations reveal:\n\nWhat is the most likely diagnosis?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Cobb, A. and Aeddula, N.R., 2021. Primary hyperaldosteronism. In StatPearls [Internet]. StatPearls Publishing.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"In primary aldosteronism (PA), there is excess aldosterone production, which is autonomous, causing excessive sodium reabsorption within the distal nephron. It leads to hypertension and suppression of the renin-angiotensin II system, which means patients will have high aldosterone and low renin levels. Plasma aldosterone/plasma renin activity ratio is a useful screening test."},{"id":"7988","category":"Cardiovascular medicine","stem":"A 52-year-old man presented with a 4-hour history of central heavy chest pain, sweating and sickness. His ECG shows the following:\n\nWhich artery is most likely to be occluded?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","A 52-year-old man presented with a 4-hour history of central heavy chest pain, sweating and sickness. His ECG shows the following:\n\nWhich artery is most likely to be occluded?","The ECG shows an inferior myocardial infarction with ST elevation in leads II, III and aVF. There is also reciprocal anterior ST-segment depression and T-wave inversion in the anterior chest leads.","Burns, E. (updated 2019). Inferior STEMI. Life in the Fast Lane.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"The ECG shows an inferior myocardial infarction with ST elevation in leads II, III and aVF. There is also reciprocal anterior ST-segment depression and T-wave inversion in the anterior chest leads.","explanation":"The ECG shows an inferior myocardial infarction with ST elevation in leads II, III and aVF. There is also reciprocal anterior ST-segment depression and T-wave inversion in the anterior chest leads."},{"id":"11502","category":"Cardiovascular medicine","stem":"A 55-year-old woman is admitted to the Acute Medical Unit of a tertiary hospital with cardiac catheterisation facilities on-site, after complaining of retrosternal burning sensation and palpitations 3 hours ago. Since then, her condition has progressively worsened with profuse diaphoresis and vomiting.\n\nHer past medical history is remarkable for systemic lupus erythematosus, and she has taken daily hydroxychloroquine 400 mg for the past 5 years.\n\nOn examination, she is alert and oriented with a pulse rate of 130/min, regular. Her blood pressure is 170/90 mmHg, respiratory rate is 15/min, and oxygen saturation on air is 100%.\n\nA respiratory system examination reveals normal bilateral breath sounds. A cardiovascular system examination reveals normal heart sounds; tachycardic.\n\nHer ECG is shown below:\n\nWhat is the most appropriate management?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Her past medical history is remarkable for systemic lupus erythematosus, and she has taken daily hydroxychloroquine 400 mg for the past 5 years.","Her ECG is shown below:","[Image: authors own]","What is the most appropriate management?","Fibrinolytic therapy should be offered if the patient presents within 12 hours of symptoms and PCI is not possible within 120 minutes.","This patient has sinus tachycardia, and adenosine or amiodarone is not indicated.","DC cardioversion is for the management of tachyarrhythmias only.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"Fibrinolytic therapy should be offered if the patient presents within 12 hours of symptoms and PCI is not possible within 120 minutes.","explanation":"This patient’s ECG shows an acute, inferolateral ST-elevation myocardial infarction (STEMI), which is around three hours in duration, and the NICE guidelines advise that primary percutaneous coronary intervention (PCI) should be offered to patients presenting within 12 hours of symptoms and if PCI can be delivered in 120 mins."},{"id":"8079","category":"Cardiovascular medicine","stem":"A 72-year-old man with a mechanical mitral valve prosthesis is admitted with right-sided limb weakness. He takes warfarin, and his INR is 2.8. Examination reveals a right-sided hemiparesis, pulse is 90 bpm regular, and his blood pressure is 122/88 mmHg. He undergoes an urgent CT scan of the brain, which reveals a left thalamic haematoma.\n\nWhich of the following is the most appropriate approach to the management of this patient’s anticoagulation?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"In this scenario of intracerebral haemorrhage in a patient with a mechanical heart valve, the patient needs to stabilise the haematoma by achieving an INR of 1.3 or less as quickly as possible. This should be undertaken through the use of prothrombin complex concentrates. However, the correction of coagulopathy means that the patient is subjected to an increased risk of thromboembolism, so early resumption of anticoagulation is then mandated."},{"id":"17490","category":"Cardiovascular medicine","stem":"A 45-year-old Asian man who is a chronic smoker with abdominal obesity and a history of type-2 diabetes mellitus and hypertension comes to the emergency department with on-and-off chest pain radiating to the upper abdomen and jaw for one month. An ECG and cardiac enzyme test were done in the emergency department, and were normal.\n\nWhat is the recommended next line of management for this patient?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","If these tests are positive or inconclusive, invasive tests like a coronary angiogram should be offered.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"Chest pain is one of the most important symptoms dealt with in the emergency department. Chest pain can be cardiac or non-cardiac chest pain. Cardiac chest pain can be typical or atypical anginal pain. Anginal pain can be stable angina, unstable angina, or acute myocardial infarction. The cardiac risk factors for atherosclerotic vascular disease are type 2 diabetes mellitus, hypertension, hyperlipidaemia, family history of coronary artery disease, smoking, age, and sex. A patient presenting with chest pain should be risk-stratified based on the history, clinical presentation and laboratory abnormalities."},{"id":"3697","category":"Cardiovascular medicine","stem":"You are called to the arrest of a 68-year-old woman who was admitted with chest pain about 2 hours previously. She was being treated for an acute coronary event when she suddenly collapsed and became pulseless. The arrest call went out, and on arrival, the team resuscitated at a rate of 30:2, and the anaesthetist intubated the patient. She has a peripheral patent IV line in place. The rhythm tracing is as shown.\n\nWhich of the following is the most appropriate approach to the management of this patient?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Resuscitation Council (UK) Guidelines - Adult Advanced Life Support.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"The rhythm strip reveals asystole – non-shockable rhythm. The initial treatment is adrenaline 1 mg IV as soon as possible. Resuscitation in pulseless electrical activity and asystolic arrest is unlikely to be successful unless a reversible cause can be found – e.g. electrolyte disturbance (hyperkalaemia), tamponade, hypoxia, PE."},{"id":"7984","category":"Cardiovascular medicine","stem":"A 66-year-old man is admitted to the medical emergency department with a 4-hour history of central chest pain associated with nausea and sweating. There is no prior history of exercise-related pain, although he does have a family history of coronary disease, with his father having died of a heart attack at the age of 54; however, his father was a smoker. The patient does not smoke and drinks little alcohol.\n\nOn examination, he has a heart rate of 78 bpm and blood pressure of 148/80 mmHg. His ECG is shown below:\n\nWhat is the likely diagnosis?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Extending the ECG to include posterior leads would reveal ST-elevation as shown below:","LITFL: Ecg library diagnosis posterior myocardial infarction.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"LITFL: Ecg library diagnosis posterior myocardial infarction.","explanation":"The patient has a history suggestive of myocardial infarction, and there is significant ST depression in the anterior facing leads V2-3 with T-wave inversion in leads V5-6 and in the inferior leads of II, III, and aVF. These features suggest a true posterior MI, and percutaneous coronary intervention with possible stenting would be the treatment of choice."},{"id":"3588","category":"Cardiovascular medicine","stem":"A 46-year-old man is admitted complaining of an acute onset of palpitations. He has no other history of note and takes no medication. He denies the use of illicit drugs but drinks about 20 units of alcohol weekly. He does not smoke. He was playing golf this morning when he became slightly short of breath upon climbing a hill and was aware of palpitations. He denies being aware of palpitations before. He finished playing, but the fast heart rate persisted, and he has been aware of this for roughly 2-3 hours.\n\nOn examination, he appears well with a pulse of 140 bpm irregular, blood pressure 116/76 mmHg. His BMI is 27.3 kg/m2, clinically he is euthyroid. CVS examination is otherwise normal. His ECG reveals him to be in atrial fibrillation, and his chest x-ray is normal.\n\nWhich of the following is the most appropriate initial approach to managing this patient?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"As this is an acute onset AF, a rhythm control strategy should be adopted. The patient is stable and does not require an immediate DCCV. According to NICE guidelines, if pharmacological cardioversion has been agreed on clinical and resource grounds for new-onset atrial fibrillation, offer a choice of flecainide or amiodarone to people with no evidence of structural or ischaemic heart disease or amiodarone to people with evidence of structural heart disease."},{"id":"8069","category":"Cardiovascular medicine","stem":"A 75-year-old woman is seen at home with weakness and is suspected of having had a stroke.\n\nWhich of the following is recommended as a screening tool for stroke in the community?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","A 75-year-old woman is seen at home with weakness and is suspected of having had a stroke.\n\nWhich of the following is recommended as a screening tool for stroke in the community?","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"A 75-year-old woman is seen at home with weakness and is suspected of having had a stroke.\n\nWhich of the following is recommended as a screening tool for stroke in the community?","explanation":"NICE guidelines recommend using the FAST score as a screening tool to identify any patient with a new neurological deficit suspected of having a stroke."},{"id":"3698","category":"Cardiovascular medicine","stem":"A 72-year-old man with coronary artery disease is being resuscitated following a cardiac arrest. He has had a VF arrest and received 3 escalating shocks over the last 5 minutes. The patient has also received adrenaline 1 mg IV following the second shock. He remains pulseless in VF and continues on CPR.\n\nWhich of the following is the next step in the management of the patient?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Following the third attempted defibrillation, guidelines recommend the use of 300 mg IV amiodarone and a further 150 mg IV dose should be considered after a total of 5 shocks.","Resuscitation Council (UK) Guidelines - Adult Advanced Life Support.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"Following the third attempted defibrillation, guidelines recommend the use of 300 mg IV amiodarone and a further 150 mg IV dose should be considered after a total of 5 shocks.","explanation":"Following the third attempted defibrillation, guidelines recommend the use of 300 mg IV amiodarone and a further 150 mg IV dose should be considered after a total of 5 shocks."},{"id":"11499","category":"Cardiovascular medicine","stem":"A 55-year-old woman is admitted to the Acute Medical Unit for worsening breathlessness. Her past medical history includes chronic heart failure secondary to ischaemic cardiomyopathy, type 2 diabetes mellitus, hypertension, and hypercholesterolaemia.\n\nShe has been experiencing progressive breathing difficulty, intermittent chest pains and palpitations in the last 24 hours and has had difficulty lying down in bed, which prompted her to come to the hospital.\n\nOn examination, she is alert and oriented but distressed. Her pulse rate is 160/minute irregularly irregular, blood pressure is 80/50 mmHg, respiratory rate is 25/minute, oxygen saturation on air is 92%, temperature is 36 oC. Capillary refill time is 5 seconds, and jugular venous pressure is 2 cm elevation above the sternal notch. There is bilateral pitting leg oedema.\n\nA respiratory system examination reveals bilateral crepitations in both lung bases. A cardiovascular system examination reveals normal heart sounds, irregularly irregular.\n\nHer abdomen is soft, no tenderness is noted, and there are active bowel sounds.\n\nAn ECG reveals atrial fibrillation with rapid ventricular response; heart rate is around 170/min.\n\nWhat is the most important urgent intervention now?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Her abdomen is soft, no tenderness is noted, and there are active bowel sounds.","An ECG reveals atrial fibrillation with rapid ventricular response; heart rate is around 170/min.","What is the most important urgent intervention now?","This patient has atrial fibrillation (AF) with rapid ventricular response, and this has decompensated her chronic heart failure. She is also haemodynamically unstable (Blood pressure 80/50 mmHg).","Intravenous furosemide would be required for the decompensated heart failure, but the priority is cardioversion.","Intravenous metoprolol is useful for rate control but is likely to make the hypotension and the acute heart failure worse in this patient.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"This patient has atrial fibrillation (AF) with rapid ventricular response, and this has decompensated her chronic heart failure. She is also haemodynamically unstable (Blood pressure 80/50 mmHg).","explanation":"This patient has atrial fibrillation (AF) with rapid ventricular response, and this has decompensated her chronic heart failure. She is also haemodynamically unstable (Blood pressure 80/50 mmHg)."},{"id":"8051","category":"Cardiovascular medicine","stem":"A 55-year-old woman presented with an acute onset of weakness in the left arm, which resolved after 2 hours. She was diagnosed with a stroke mimic.\n\nWhich of the following is true regarding stroke mimics?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"Stroke mimic is where other conditions are the cause of stroke-like presentations. It may account for up to 30% of all presentations potentially considered to be stroke. The commonest of these is seizures, with studies revealing it to account for around 21%. The next most common mimics are hypoglycaemia and sepsis. A low NIHSS score (<5) together with a blood pressure <140 mmHg systolic, a history of diabetes or a lack of history of arrhythmia are predictors of stroke mimic."},{"id":"17405","category":"Cardiovascular medicine","stem":"A 65-year-old man presents to the emergency department with progressive shortness of breath, orthopnea and dyspnoea. He has a previous history of ischaemic heart disease and had undergone a coronary artery bypass graft five years ago. He also has chronic atrial fibrillation for which he takes apixaban tablets 5 mg once daily and bisoprolol tablets 5 mg at night. He is also taking ramipril 5 mg daily and aspirin 75 mg in the morning. The patient was started on furosemide 40 mg daily three months ago. On auscultation of the chest, he has extensive expiratory wheezing along with bilateral pedal oedema and bilateral fine crackles at the lung bases. His jugular venous pulse (JVP) is raised. An electrocardiogram (ECG) shows rate-controlled atrial fibrillation. A diagnosis of decompensated heart failure with adult-onset asthma is made. Pulmonary function tests show obstructive pathology, and the echocardiogram shows an ejection fraction of 30 per cent.\n\nWhich one of the following medications should be added to the treatment regimen in place of bisoprolol?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"The correct answer is digoxin as it has a positive inotropic effect on the heart and improves the cardiac output in addition to controlling the rate of atrial fibrillation. Bisoprolol is stopped owing to the diagnosis of new-onset asthma. Verapamil and diltiazem are calcium channel blockers which are contraindicated in heart failure with reduced ejection. Flecainide is contraindicated in patients with structural heart disease, and amiodarone can be used, but will not be a favourable option in the presence of digoxin."},{"id":"11500","category":"Cardiovascular medicine","stem":"A 57-year-old woman is admitted to the Acute Medical Unit with a three-day history of palpitations and mild central chest pain with breathlessness. Her medical history includes hypothyroidism, type 2 diabetes mellitus, and gastro-oesophageal reflux disease. She explains that three days ago, she woke up in the middle of the night with a sudden onset of palpitations.\n\nOn examination, she is alert and oriented, with a pulse rate of 170/minute (irregularly irregular), and her blood pressure is 140/100 mmHg. Respiratory rate is 15/minute, she is speaking full sentences without pause, and she is not noted to be using any accessory breathing muscles. Oxygen saturation on air is 100%.\n\nHer temperature is 36oC, capillary refill time is two seconds. Jugular venous pressure is not elevated. There is no leg oedema.\n\nRespiratory system examination reveals normal breath sounds, and cardiovascular system examination reveals normal heart sounds but is irregularly irregular.\n\nHer abdomen is soft, no tenderness noted, and there are active bowel sounds.\n\nAn ECG reveals atrial fibrillation (AF) with rapid ventricular response; her heart rate is around 180/min.\n\nWhat would be the most appropriate management of the symptoms of atrial fibrillation in this patient?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Her temperature is 36oC, capillary refill time is two seconds. Jugular venous pressure is not elevated. There is no leg oedema.","Her abdomen is soft, no tenderness noted, and there are active bowel sounds.","An ECG reveals atrial fibrillation (AF) with rapid ventricular response; her heart rate is around 180/min.","What would be the most appropriate management of the symptoms of atrial fibrillation in this patient?","Adenosine is used for supraventricular tachycardia management and is not suitable for use in this patient.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"What would be the most appropriate management of the symptoms of atrial fibrillation in this patient?","explanation":"This patient has a clear history of new-onset atrial fibrillation, which is of more than 48 hours duration, is haemodynamically stable and has no evidence of cardiac decompensation. The most appropriate intervention would be rate control rather than electrical (DC cardioversion) or pharmacological cardioversion (using amiodarone or flecainide)."},{"id":"3983","category":"Cardiovascular medicine","stem":"A 55-year-old man with a history of ischaemic heart disease was found collapsed at home. He has an implantable cardioverter-defibrillator (ICD) and has received several shocks from the device in the ambulance, for recurrent ventricular tachycardia. On arrival in Resus, he is in pulseless ventricular tachycardia and cardiopulmonary resuscitation (CPR) is ongoing.\n\nWhich of the following is the most appropriate management?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Advanced Life Support. 7th Edition. (2016) Resuscitation Council (UK)[book].\nResus: 2021 Resuscitation Guidelines","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"External defibrillation should be used where an ICD has failed to terminate a shockable rhythm or the rhythm is recurrent. Pads should be placed on the chest at least 10-15 cm away from the device, or the anterior-posterior positions used. Placing a magnet over an ICD will disable the defibrillation function, but it will continue to pace for bradycardia. Placing a magnet over a standard bradycardia pacemaker will trigger a short burst of ventricular pacing at a rate of approximately 100 bpm, after which normal function resumes. There is no significant risk to a CPR provider in contact with a patient during an ICD shock."},{"id":"8074","category":"Cardiovascular medicine","stem":"An 80-year-old man is admitted with left-sided weakness. He has a history of atrial fibrillation and is being treated with bisoprolol and warfarin. A CT scan is suggestive of an ischaemic stroke.\n\nWhich of the following best describes the optimal patient care pathway following acute stroke?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"Guidance reveals that the patient requires admission to an acute stroke unit with subsequent patient planning and secondary prevention, even if the patient does not require thrombolysis or thrombectomy, as dedicated stroke units are associated with improved outcomes. Following this, the patient could then be transferred to a stroke rehab unit for appropriate supportive rehabilitative intervention."},{"id":"11965","category":"Cardiovascular medicine","stem":"An 83-year-old man has been referred to ambulatory emergency care (AEC) by his GP following a routine check. His ECG was done in the practice, and the GP was concerned about the ECG findings, which suggest that the patient may need a permanent pacemaker (PPM). His recent blood results have been unremarkable besides mild hypercholesterolaemia. The patient is known to have hypertension and is on amlodipine 5 mg and ramipril 10 mg. He is also known to have benign prostatic hypertrophy and is on tamsulosin 400 mcg once daily. On examination, he is asymptomatic with a normal general examination and normal findings on cardiac auscultation. The patient denied any history of dizziness or loss of consciousness.\n\nHis BP was 145/84 mmHg, and his ECG is shown below:\n\n[Image: author’s own]\n\nWhat is the best management plan for this patient?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Kashou, A.H., Goyal, A., Nguyen, T. and Chhabra, L., 2017. Atrioventricular block.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"The ECG shows a second-degree atrioventricular block Type-I (Mobitz I/ Wenckebach). Each QRS complex is preceded by a P wave, and the PR duration is increasing until a non-conducted P wave (every third P wave is not conducted in this ECG). As the patient is asymptomatic, no interventions are needed. In case the patient is symptomatic, ECG monitoring would be needed, and PPM may be considered. The case would be different if it were Type II/ Mobitz II, when PPM is usually needed, as progression to complete heart block is common, in contrast to Mobitz I. A 24-hour ECG monitor is not needed in this patient as he is asymptomatic."},{"id":"12261","category":"Cardiovascular medicine","stem":"A 77-year-old woman is admitted following a collapse when shopping in a supermarket. She says she does not remember how it happened and denies feeling unwell before the collapse. Her past medical history includes type 2 diabetes, hypertension, and mild asthma. This is the patient’s second collapse in a week. The patient also says that, in the past few months, she has had spells in which she has ‘felt off’ and dizzy for a few seconds, which would resolve on their own. She is not currently taking any medications.\n\nHer electrocardiogram rhythm strip revealed the following in the emergency department on arrival:\n\nShe is currently asymptomatic, her pulse rate is 100 beats per minute, and her blood pressure is 150/90 mmHg.\n\nA transthoracic echocardiogram is done, which shows normal LV systolic function, type-1 diastolic dysfunction, normal chamber sizes, valves, and flows.\n\nWhat would be the most appropriate management for this patient?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Tilt table testing is useful for the evaluation of syncope and is not needed in this patient, as the cause is now evident.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"for early pacemaker implantation rather than further investigations","explanation":"This patient has a significant pause (of around 2.24 seconds) without a ventricular beat in the recorded ECG due to sinus node dysfunction, and she has had multiple symptomatic episodes in the recent past. The most appropriate management would be for early pacemaker implantation rather than further investigations, and she is unlikely to improve from conservative management."},{"id":"3591","category":"Cardiovascular medicine","stem":"A 50-year-old man is admitted with an episode of palpitations. He is known to suffer from paroxysmal atrial fibrillation and is being treated with bisoprolol 5 mg daily. This is the second occasion over the last 6 months that he has been admitted with palpitations. The ECG confirms atrial fibrillation at a rate of 96 bpm. He has a three-year history of hypertension and diabetes for which he is treated with metformin and amlodipine. His blood pressure is 124/80 mmHg. Previous investigations reported on the clinical portal reveal a normal echo. Within an hour, he reverts to sinus rhythm.\n\nWhich of the following approaches would you take regarding long-term anticoagulation/antiplatelet therapy?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"This man has a CHADS-VASC score of 2 based on his age<65 (0) plus diabetes and hypertension (1 each). This, in conjunction with paroxysmal atrial fibrillation, puts him at risk of stroke/TIA and therefore anticoagulation is the most appropriate approach – either with warfarin or the newer antithrombotics – dabigatran, apixaban and rivaroxaban."},{"id":"3989","category":"Cardiovascular medicine","stem":"A 45-year-old man with no past medical history of note presents to A&E feeling generally unwell with palpitations that started earlier in the day. The patient's examination is unremarkable. He consumed a large quantity of alcohol during a stag party the previous day. His ECG confirms atrial fibrillation with a rate of 145 bpm. His blood pressure is stable at 110/60 mmHg, and his bedside echo is reported as normal.\n\nWhat is the most appropriate treatment for this patient?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Atrial Fibrillation.\nAlcohol and atrial fibrillation - how well do they mix? | BCS (britishcardiovascularsociety.org)","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"His AF has likely been precipitated by alcohol. Given his relatively young age, structurally normal heart on echo, and as the duration is less than 48 hours, Flecainide would be the most appropriate choice here."},{"id":"17092","category":"Cardiovascular medicine","stem":"A 71-year-old man with a background history of hypertension and type 2 diabetes mellitus is admitted with a syncopal episode on a background of frequent pre-syncopal symptoms. He was found to have a complete heart block for which a dual-chamber pacemaker was inserted, and he was discharged. After two weeks, he presents with a temperature, generalised lethargy, stiffness, and joint pain.\n\nThe patient’s examination was grossly unremarkable with a low-grade temperature of 37.9oC, and the pacemaker site seemed to be healing well.\n\nInitial investigations showed the following results:\n\nHe was managed for hospital-acquired pneumonia with intravenous tazocin 4.5g three times a day. On the second day, the blood culture came back positive for Staphylococcus aureus. Repeat blood tests after 48 hours showed a CRP of 201 mmol/L, a white cell count of 17.9 x 109/L, and neutrophils of 15.7 x 109/L, and a repeat chest X-ray showed increased consolidation. A CT scan of the thorax was done afterwards, which showed cavitating consolidation in both lungs, and a transthoracic echocardiogram (TTE) showed no evidence of endocarditis.\n\nWhat investigation should be done next?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"This is a case of cardiac device-related infective endocarditis (CDRIE) until proven otherwise. Renal failure, heart failure, corticosteroid use, diabetes mellitus, haematoma formation, and anticoagulation use have been identified as risk factors. Staphylococci account for the majority of cases (60-80%). Clinical presentation can vary predominantly involving respiratory and rheumatological symptoms along with local signs of infection. Echocardiography is the key to diagnosis and, if TTE is normal, TOE should be considered but a normal echocardiographic examination does not rule out CDRIE. In cases with a high index of suspicion, other modalities, such as radiolabelled leucocyte scintigraphy and F-FDG PET/CT scanning, have been described as investigation modalities to aid in the diagnosis of CDRIE and associated complications, including pulmonary septic embolism (which was present in this case). The Duke criteria have lower sensitivity in these cases, and modified Duke criteria have been suggested, which include local infective signs and pulmonary embolism as major criteria."},{"id":"3696","category":"Cardiovascular medicine","stem":"You are called to the arrest of a 76-year-old male who was admitted with a chest infection and sepsis. The arrest call went out, and on arrival, the team resuscitated at a rate of 30:2, and the anaesthetist intubated the patient. He has a peripheral patent IV line in place. During a brief pause in resuscitation, you confirm that the patient has no pulse and the rhythm is as below:\n\nWhich of the following is the most appropriate initial approach to the management of this patient?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Resuscitation Council (UK) (2015) Guidelines - Adult Advanced Life Support.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"The rhythm strip reveals ventricular fibrillation, and the initial treatment according to guidance is to give a shock from a biphasic defibrillator. A range of defibrillation energy levels has been recommended by manufacturers and previous guidelines, ranging from 120-360 J. In the absence of any clear evidence for the optimal initial and subsequent energy levels, any energy level within this range is acceptable for the initial shock, followed by a fixed or escalating strategy up to the maximum output of the defibrillator. For the SCE exam, one needs to be very familiar with the latest guidance on resuscitation procedures."},{"id":"14147","category":"Cardiovascular medicine","stem":"A 26-year-old man, who is an intravenous drug user and is HIV positive with CD4 counts > 500, was admitted with palpitations, feeling breathless, with a low-grade temperature. On examination, he had a temperature of 37.9 oC, a respiratory rate of 19 breaths per minute, a heart rate of 107 beats per minute, SaO2 98% on room air, and a blood pressure of 121/67 mmHg. Chest examination revealed a few crackles in the right base, and cardiovascular examination revealed a possible soft systolic murmur. Abdominal and neurological examinations were unremarkable.\n\nHis last injection, heroin administration, occurred two days ago before admission, and there were obvious injection marks on both arms and legs with no infection. His blood test showed raised inflammatory markers, his chest X-ray was clear, and his ECG showed sinus tachycardia. He was managed for a lower respiratory tract infection with oral co-amoxiclav 625 mg three times a day. On the third day of his admission, his temperature started to spike up to 40oC. An urgent transthoracic echocardiogram was organised, which showed tricuspid and pulmonary regurgitation.\n\nWhat is the recommended management option at this point?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","What is the recommended management option at this point?","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"This patient is at high risk of right-sided infective endocarditis, considering his history of intravenous drug use and should be managed in the same manner until proven otherwise. The findings of pulmonary and tricuspid regurgitation can point towards the diagnosis, but a transesophageal echocardiogram is the gold standard to look for any vegetation and the severity of valvular involvement. The most common organism is Staphylococcus aureus, but other possibilities should be considered. Pneumocystis carinii infection is less likely, considering his CD4 count is more than 500. Raised creatinine kinase levels can be seen in acute opioid withdrawal syndrome, but as this patient has no typical signs or symptoms such as myalgias, insomnia, agitation, delirium, hallucination, sweating, diarrhoea, lacrimation, piloerection, and/or dilated pupils, then checking the creatinine kinase level is not indicated."},{"id":"19865","category":"Cardiovascular medicine","stem":"A 72-year old man presents to the acute medical unit with a 4-hour history of central crushing chest pain and feeling light-headed. There is no history of syncope. He has a past medical history of hypertension and hyperlipidaemia for which he takes amlodipine 10mg OD and atorvastatin 20mg OD.\n\nOn examination, his temperature is 36.8 oC, blood pressure is 105/68mmHg, his pulse is 38bpm, and his oxygen saturations are 98% in air. Immediate ECG shows acute ST-elevation in leads II, III and aVF with a narrow QRS escape rhythm and complete heart block. He has been given aspirin 300 mg, ticagrelor 180 mg, and is awaiting urgent transfer for primary percutaneous coronary intervention (PCI). Transcutaneous pacing pads have been applied as a precaution.\n\nWhich single factor most strongly indicates the need for temporary transvenous pacing wire insertion before transfer for primary PCI?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Which single factor most strongly indicates the need for temporary transvenous pacing wire insertion before transfer for primary PCI?","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"Which single factor most strongly indicates the need for temporary transvenous pacing wire insertion before transfer for primary PCI?","explanation":"Haemodynamic compromise (hypotension, symptoms of hypoperfusion) is the primary indication for temporary pacing in complete heart block complicating MI. ESC guidelines state that temporary pacing should be considered when there are symptoms related to bradycardia or haemodynamic instability. Light-headedness with borderline low blood pressure (105/68 mmHg) suggests inadequate cerebral perfusion. This represents haemodynamic instability requiring intervention BEFORE transfer. Transcutaneous pacing may be unreliable during transport, making transvenous pacing safer. The combination of symptoms and borderline BP indicates the escape rhythm is insufficient to maintain adequate perfusion. Temporary transvenous pacing provides stable pacing during transfer and PCI."},{"id":"17094","category":"Cardiovascular medicine","stem":"A 71-year-old woman with a background of hypertension, type-2 diabetes mellitus, and chronic kidney disease stage 3, presents with palpitations for three days and is found to be in atrial fibrillation (AF) with a rapid ventricular response. The rest of the examination was unremarkable. Her home medications include ramipril 2.5 mg once daily, amlodipine 5 mg once daily, gliclazide 60 mg twice daily, along with over-the-counter aspirin 75 mg once daily. She was given bisoprolol 2.5 mg once daily, and she reverted to sinus rhythm with 75 beats per minute after six hours.\n\nInvestigations showed the following results:\n\nWhat is the best decision for this patient regarding anticoagulation/antiplatelet therapy?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"can be stopped after starting anticoagulation","explanation":"NICE recommends the CHA2DS2-VASc score to assess stroke risk and the ORBIT score to assess bleeding risk. The CHA2DS2-VASc score here is 4 (female, age 71 years, hypertension, diabetes mellitus), which means a 4.8% per year stroke risk in more than 90,000 patients (Swedish Atrial Fibrillation Cohort Study) and a 6.7% risk of stroke/TIA/systemic embolism. ORBIT score here is 3 (female, haemoglobin < 12g/dl, eGFR < 60ml/min/1.73m2), which means a bleeding risk of 4.7 bleeds per 100 patient-years. ORBIT score also includes 1 point for antiplatelet therapy, and this patient is on aspirin, but it is not counted in the score as there is no indication of aspirin and, therefore, can be stopped after starting anticoagulation. Although this was paroxysmal AF, the recommendation is not to stop anticoagulation even if AF is no longer detectable."},{"id":"11967","category":"Cardiovascular medicine","stem":"A 74-year-old man was brought by ambulance to the accident and emergency department due to cardiac-sounding chest pain. He was seen by the A&E team, who diagnosed acute coronary syndrome (ACS) and referred him to you. The patient mentioned that he started to have chest pain roughly one hour before you saw him, which was a central, severe chest pain that referred to both arms. His chest pain slightly improved after having (GTN), which was given twice by the ambulance team. He is known to be hypertensive, diabetic, and an ex-smoker. Chest and cardiac examinations were unremarkable, and his blood pressure was 160/90 mmHg. He reports that his chest pain is now 7/10 down from 9/10.\n\nHis ECG is shown below:\n\n[Image: author’s own]\n\nWhat is the best next step in his management?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"Primary PCI and not thrombolytic therapy","explanation":"The patient has high lateral STEMI with ST elevations in leads I and aVL. The ECG changes could be subtle due to widespread ST depressions, in this case. However, careful ECG reading is important to properly decide on the best next step. There is no point in waiting for the cardiac Tn, as the symptoms are typical of cardiac chest pain and the ECG findings are diagnostic. The best treatment would be Primary PCI and not thrombolytic therapy, as he is still within a few hours of the start of symptoms."},{"id":"8116","category":"Cardiovascular medicine","stem":"A 43-year-old man is admitted to the hospital with painful swelling of the left calf. He has a history of chronic pain for which he has received several analgesics, including opioids. Ultrasonography of the leg confirms the clinical suspicion of a distal, below-knee, deep vein thrombosis.\n\nWhich of the following concerning longer-term anticoagulation is appropriate for this man?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"3 months of anticoagulation","explanation":"It is a common misconception that below-knee DVTs are benign and do not require anticoagulation, yet 30% extend and may embolize. Hence, it is important to provide anticoagulation for between 6 weeks to 3 months. In this patient, the most appropriate approach would be 3 months of anticoagulation."},{"id":"14148","category":"Cardiovascular medicine","stem":"A 47-year-old woman who has a background of diabetes mellitus type 2 and hypertension is admitted with palpitations and breathlessness. On examination, she was overtly breathless with a respiratory rate of 31 breaths per minute, a heart rate of 160-180 beats per minute, irregular, blood pressure of 117/67 mmHg, and a temperature of 36.7 oC and SaO2 91% on room air. Chest examination revealed bibasal fine crackles, precordium examination was unremarkable, jugular venous pulse (JVP) was not raised, and there was no pitting oedema in the legs. The patient’s blood tests were unremarkable. A chest X-ray revealed pulmonary oedema, and an ECG showed atrial fibrillation with a ventricular rate of 167 beats per minute. She was given intravenous digoxin 500 mcg along with furosemide 40 mg. On re-assessment, her blood pressure dropped to 76/45 mmHg with no improvement in heart rate, and she started feeling faint.\n\nWhat is the most recommended action at this point?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","What is the most recommended action at this point?","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"Haemodynamic instability, pulmonary oedema, syncope/presyncope symptoms, and chest pain are indications for DC cardioversion in the management of tachyarrhythmias. Giving metoprolol, in this case, will cause more hypotension and worsening of pulmonary oedema because of negative inotropic and chronotropic effects. Amiodarone can be considered intravenously, but it will take longer to have any effect in this case, and the safest option would be DC cardioversion. Flecainide should not be used unless structural heart disease is ruled out. In emergency cases like this, DC cardioversion should not be delayed to exclude atrial thrombus on echocardiogram, and the patient, in this case, is too unstable to have a transoesophageal echocardiogram."},{"id":"13106","category":"Cardiovascular medicine","stem":"A 74-year-old man with uncontrolled type-2 diabetes, diabetic autonomic neuropathy, systemic hypertension, stage 2 chronic kidney disease, and hypercholesterolaemia is brought to the acute medical unit with general deterioration and progressive exertional breathlessness of 1-2 months duration. For the past two days, he has been feeling worse, has been unable to lie flat on his bed, and has been waking from sleep to get his breath back. He says he has never had any breathing problems in the past, and he has also never smoked.\n\nOn examination, the patient is alert and oriented with a pulse rate of 100 beats per minute and blood pressure of 90/70 mmHg. His respiratory rate is 22 breaths per minute, oxygen saturation on air is 94%, and he has a temperature of 37 oC.\n\nJugular venous pressure is elevated 2cm above the sternal edge. Bilateral pitting ankle oedema is present.\n\nHis respiratory system shows extensive crackles in both lung bases, and his cardiovascular system reveals normal heart sounds. The patient’s abdomen is soft with no tenderness, and there are active bowel sounds.\n\nHis ECG is shown below:\n\nImage source: author.\n\nHis chest X-ray is shown below:\n\nImage source: author.\n\nHis investigations are shown below:\n\nWhat is the most likely cause of his breathlessness?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Jugular venous pressure is elevated 2cm above the sternal edge. Bilateral pitting ankle oedema is present.","His ECG is shown below:","Image source: author.","His chest X-ray is shown below:","His investigations are shown below:","What is the most likely cause of his breathlessness?","Acute myocardial infarction is unlikely with no acute ST-T changes and normal troponin.","Asthma does not fit the auscultation signs, the ECG, or the chest x-ray.","Pneumonia is unlikely given the normal leucocyte count, ESR, and CRP.","Acute pericarditis usually manifests as global ST-elevation in the ECG, and the clinical picture here is consistent with congestive cardiac failure and pulmonary oedema.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"Asthma does not fit the auscultation signs, the ECG, or the chest x-ray.","explanation":"This patient has all the typical clinical symptoms and signs of congestive cardiac failure; the ECG shows features of old or established anterior wall myocardial infarction (pathologic Q waves in V1-4), and the chest x-ray shows cardiomegaly and features of pulmonary oedema."},{"id":"20208","category":"Cardiovascular medicine","stem":"A 58-year-old man presents to the acute medical unit with a 6-hour history of palpitations and mild dyspnoea. He has a history of paroxysmal atrial fibrillation but no structural heart disease. Recent echocardiography showed normal left ventricular systolic function with no valvular abnormalities.\n\nOn examination, he is alert with a heart rate of 142 beats per minute, irregularly irregular, blood pressure of 128/82 mmHg, and oxygen saturation 97% on room air. An ECG confirms atrial fibrillation with a rapid ventricular response. Blood tests, including renal function and electrolytes, are normal. He has been anticoagulated with apixaban 5mg twice daily for 8 months. Rate control has been achieved with 5mg of intravenous metoprolol, and his heart rate is now 88 beats per minute.\n\nWhat is the most appropriate pharmacological cardioversion option for this patient?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","What is the most appropriate pharmacological cardioversion option for this patient?","The recommended intravenous flecainide dose for rapid cardioversion is 2 mg/kg over 10–20 minutes, maximum 150 mg.","Digoxin provides rate control but does not cardiovert atrial fibrillation; It has no significant effect on restoring sinus rhythm.","Vernakalant is an effective and rapid-acting agent for pharmacological cardioversion of atrial fibrillation, but it is not as widely available as flecainide in UK practice.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"What is the most appropriate pharmacological cardioversion option for this patient?","explanation":"Flecainide is a highly effective class Ic antiarrhythmic agent for pharmacological cardioversion of recent-onset atrial fibrillation in patients without structural heart disease. Cardioversion rates of 70–90% within 2-4 hours are reported in clinical trials."},{"id":"5097","category":"Cardiovascular medicine","stem":"A 62-year-old man presents with chest pain on Friday. Eight hours ago, at 3 a.m., the patient developed left chest heaviness that radiated to his left arm. He felt rather sweaty with this pain. The pain lasted an hour or so and subsided. He was concerned and visited the GP for an emergency appointment in the morning, and the GP immediately sent him to you to query acute coronary syndrome.\n\nHe has no medical history of note, but he has a family history of ischaemic heart disease (IHD), with his father having died of myocardial infarction (MI) at the age of 62. The patient is a smoker of 10 cigarettes daily.\n\nThere is little to find on examination, and he is now pain-free. His ECG is normal. High sensitivity troponin T was taken at admission and 8 hours after the pain stopped, revealing a result of 12 ng/L (<14).\n\nWhat is the most appropriate management strategy for this patient?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"In this case, the history is highly suggestive of unstable angina and because of several risk factors, smoking history and strong family history, he should be commended on a dual antiplatelet, beta-blocker (if no contraindication) and a statin and admitted for cardiology review as he will need further investigations, like coronary CT etc., to decide if he needs an inpatient angiogram. Scores like the GRACE score can also help with risk stratification."},{"id":"17265","category":"Cardiovascular medicine","stem":"A 68-year-old patient has been progressively breathless for the past two weeks. He denies any history of cough and temperature. On examination, he had raised JVP, and the auscultation of his lungs revealed an asymmetric reduced expansion, stony dull percussion, reduced breath sounds, and absent tactile vocal fremitus; regular heart sounds but with a heart rate of 95 beats per minute, and he also presented with bilateral peripheral oedema. The patient had no previous medical history.\n\nWhat is the most likely cause for this presentation?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Saguil A, Wyrick K, Hallgren J. Diagnostic approach to pleural effusion. Am Fam Physician. 2014 Jul 15;90(2):99-104. PMID: 25077579.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"Pleural effusions are characterised by reduced air expansion of the affected side, reduced or absent tactile vocal fremitus, reduced breath sounds and a \"stony\" dull percussion. The progressive breathlessness with raised JVP (jugular venous pressure) and peripheral oedema indicates raised right arterial pressure and makes the diagnosis of congestive cardiac failure more likely. For a patient with chronic liver disease to present with pleural effusion, they need to have an advanced disease, which means liver disease stigmata, and this is not a feature of this patient’s presentation, ruling out chronic liver disease. Similarly, in chronic renal disease, pleural effusion is present in the advanced stages of the disease. The patient had a two-week history of symptoms and did not present with fever or crackles on auscultation, making pneumonia unlikely. Cancer is a possibility; however, a history of weight loss, smoking, breast cancer (a common cause of pleural effusion), lymphadenopathy, clubbing, etc, would be relevant for this diagnosis."},{"id":"11503","category":"Cardiovascular medicine","stem":"A 40-year-old woman is admitted to the Acute Medical Unit with a sudden onset of palpitations associated with sweating. Her past medical history includes type 2 diabetes mellitus, obesity and hypertension. Her current medications are metformin 1g BD, empagliflozin 10mg OD, amlodipine 5mg OD and ramipril 10mg OD.\n\nOn examination, she is alert and oriented, her pulse rate is 220/min, her blood pressure is 130/90 mmHg, and her respiratory rate is 20/min.\n\nA respiratory system examination reveals normal breath sounds bilaterally.\n\nA cardiovascular system examination reveals tachycardia. There are no murmurs or added sounds.\n\nHer ECG on arrival is shown below:\n\nWhat would be the most appropriate initial treatment?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Amiodarone is used for ventricular tachycardia (broad complex tachycardia) and is not indicated here.","DC cardioversion (up to 3 shocks) should be used if life-threatening features are present.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"Amiodarone is used for ventricular tachycardia (broad complex tachycardia) and is not indicated here.","explanation":"This patient’s ECG shows regular narrow complex tachycardia (supraventricular tachycardia (SVT)) without any life-threatening features. As per the Resuscitation Council’s adult tachycardia algorithm, the initial treatment should be vagal manoeuvres; if that is ineffective, then intravenous adenosine should be tried."},{"id":"16835","category":"Cardiovascular medicine","stem":"A 44-year-old man was referred to the acute medical unit by his ophthalmologist. He had gone to have his eyes tested due to recurring headaches. The ophthalmologist had found bilateral papilloedema.\n\nOn examination, his pulse rate was 80 beats per minute and his blood pressure was 240/130 mmHg. His heart sounds were normal, and he had bilateral crepitations on chest examination. Abdominal examination was normal.\n\nInvestigations revealed the following results:\n\nAn ECG is done and reveals left ventricular hypertrophy. Chest X-ray reveals mild pulmonary oedema.\n\nWhat is the recommended management option for this patient?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Intravenous nitroprusside is most commonly used due to its rapid onset of action and predictable effect, but other intravenous medications such as labetalol can be used.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"This patient has a hypertensive emergency, which is a severe increase in blood pressure (>180 mmHg systolic or >110 mmHg diastolic) associated with acute impairment of one or more target organs. He has renal impairment and left ventricular failure as well as papilloedema."},{"id":"7986","category":"Cardiovascular medicine","stem":"A 52-year-old man presented with a 4-hour history of central heavy chest pain, sweating and sickness. His ECG shows the following:\n\nWhich artery is likely to be affected?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","A 52-year-old man presented with a 4-hour history of central heavy chest pain, sweating and sickness. His ECG shows the following:\n\nWhich artery is likely to be affected?","Lome, S. Top 5 MI ECG patterns you must know. Healio Learn the Heart.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"This ECG reveals so-called tombstoning, with greatly raised ST segments of all the anterior chest leads, suggesting proximal occlusion of the left anterior descending artery before both septal and diagonal branches. This means that both the anterior leads overlying the septum and the lateral leads are also involved."},{"id":"3979","category":"Cardiovascular medicine","stem":"A 43-year-old woman presents with crushing chest and back pain for one hour. She is 20 weeks pregnant after having received IVF treatment. Thus far, the pregnancy has progressed well, and she has no other past history of note.\n\nOn examination, heart rate is 110 bpm, blood pressure 95/60 mmHg, and oxygen saturation is 92% on room air. She is pale and clammy, and there are bibasal crepitations on auscultation of the lungs, and the JVP is raised +3cm. The ECG shows 2 mm ST-elevation in leads II, III and aVF.\n\nWhich of the following is the most appropriate management?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Which of the following is the most appropriate management?","Guidelines on Management of Cardiovascular Disease during Pregnancy. European Heart Journal (2011) 32, 3147-3197.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"This patient has had an inferior myocardial infarction, and the Gold standard treatment is PPCI, ideally within 120 minutes of presentation. Pregnancy does not preclude coronary intervention (with tailored drug treatment). Bare metal stents are preferred to minimise the duration of dual antiplatelet therapy post-intervention. Thrombolysis can be used if PPCI is not available and the patient’s condition is life-threatening. Spontaneous coronary dissection occurs more commonly in pregnancy and can be identified and treated during PPCI. The risk of aortic dissection is also increased during pregnancy and should always be considered in the differential diagnosis of chest pain. Aortic dissection involving the coronary arteries will cause ST elevation in the relevant territory on ECG."},{"id":"11963","category":"Cardiovascular medicine","stem":"You are the night registrar on call in a district general hospital with no on-site 24-hour cardiology service. The Critical Care Unit (CCU) calls you regarding a 71-year-old man who was admitted a few hours ago with non-ST-elevation myocardial infarction (NSTEMI) and who has ongoing chest pain. The nursing staff are concerned about the patient’s condition. He has diabetes mellitus and hypertension, and is an ex-smoker. The patient presented with chest pain with ECG changes and rising Troponin I.\n\nThe patient received aspirin 300 mg, ticagrelor 180 mg, and atorvastatin 80 mg and has been on GTN infusion because of the chest pain with little response. His ECG is shown below:\n\n[Image: author’s own]\n\nHis blood pressure is currently 90/60 mmHg, heart rate is 110/min, and SO2 is 98% on room air. There was no murmur detected when listening to the heart, and he had bilateral fine basal crepitations on listening to the chest. The patient is fully awake and reports chest pain of 6/10 compared to 8/10 on admission. His blood results were normal besides the rising Tn.\n\nWhat is the best next step in management?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","The patient received aspirin 300 mg, ticagrelor 180 mg, and atorvastatin 80 mg and has been on GTN infusion because of the chest pain with little response. His ECG is shown below:","[Image: author’s own]","What is the best next step in management?","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"What is the best next step in management?","explanation":"This patient with NSTEMI has become unstable, and an immediate coronary angiogram is the best plan according to NICE guidance. Signs of instability are persistent chest pain despite initial management, signs of left ventricular dysfunction, persistent arrhythmia, and shock."},{"id":"11108","category":"Cardiovascular medicine","stem":"You have been asked to review a 24-year-old man to evaluate his left-sided chest pain that radiates to the back, which he reports started six hours ago and was associated with nausea and a single episode of vomiting. The patient denies dyspnoea, palpitation, and cough. He underwent an appendectomy last night for acute appendicitis and was recovering well. He was also treated for an upper respiratory tract infection five days before admission and given loratadine and aminophylline cough syrup. He has no past medical history and is non-alcoholic.\n\nOn examination, his blood pressure was 108/60 mmHg, pulse rate was 56 beats per minute, regular, temperature was 37.8 oC, and O2 saturations were 94% on room air. His cardiovascular and chest examinations were unremarkable.\n\nHis blood test showed:\n\nWhat should be the subsequent management plan?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","His blood test showed:","What should be the subsequent management plan?","Diagnosis requires the presence of two out of four findings:","The third-line therapeutic options include azathioprine, intravenous immunoglobulin, and anakinra (an interleukin-1ß antagonist). A surgical pericardiectomy is the last treatment modality.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"This patient’s symptoms and ECG changes are reflective of acute viral pericarditis after suffering from an upper respiratory tract infection. In the UK, most cases are either idiopathic or viral in aetiology. However, tuberculosis and autoimmune diseases are important conditions to exclude."},{"id":"7868","category":"Cardiovascular medicine","stem":"A 40-year-old woman of Afro-Caribbean origin presented with breathlessness a day after the delivery of her second child. She had an uncomplicated vaginal delivery, and her son was well and weighed 2.7 kg. The following day, she developed gradual breathlessness and was unable to lie flat. She was previously fit and well.\n\nOn examination, she is breathless, has a temperature of 36.8 oC, a pulse of 96 bpm regular and a blood pressure of 110/68 mmHg. Auscultation of the heart revealed no specific abnormalities, but she had bibasilar crackles on examination of the chest. A chest X-ray reveals bilateral pulmonary congestion. Transthoracic echo shows a left ventricular ejection fraction of 35%.\n\nWhat is the most likely diagnosis?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","What is the most likely diagnosis?","Anthony, J. and Sliwa, K., (2016). Decompensated heart failure in pregnancy. Cardiac failure review, 2(1), p.20.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"This patient has peripartum cardiomyopathy as evidenced by the development of features of heart failure post-delivery. Peripartum cardiomyopathy is well-recognised in the puerperium and is associated with an ejection fraction of 45% or below. It is an idiopathic cardiomyopathy, yet associated factors include women of Afro-Caribbean origin, multiparous and hypertensive."},{"id":"18707","category":"Cardiovascular medicine","stem":"A 20-year-old man presented to the emergency department with a gradual onset of left-sided chest pain, which started 10 hours prior and progressively worsened until it became unbearable 2 hours before presentation. Pain radiates to his shoulder tip, is associated with vomiting, and is relieved by sitting upright/leaning forward. He had the flu last week.\n\nThe patient has no significant past medical history. He has no known drug allergies. He works as a carpenter and lives with his parents. He smokes 1-2 sticks of cigarettes per day and drinks alcohol occasionally (<5 units per week). He has not travelled out of the county for over a year.\n\nOn observation, he has a respiratory rate of 21 breaths per minute, oxygen saturation of 99%, and blood pressure of 127/72 mmHg with a heart rate of 98 beats per minute.\n\nAn ECG showed global ST-elevation on all leads.\n\nWhat is the most likely diagnosis?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","An ECG showed global ST-elevation on all leads.","What is the most likely diagnosis?","Chest pain radiating to the shoulder tip is suggestive of radiation via the phrenic nerve, which supplies the pericardium. The pain relief on leaning forward supports this diagnosis.","He also had a viral infection the previous week. A viral infection is the most common cause of pericarditis. Furthermore, global ST-elevation is a pathognomic feature of pericarditis.","Acute myocardial infarction is a good differential diagnosis, but the patient’s age and lack of convincing risk factors make it highly unlikely.","Costochondritis would not explain the ECG changes or the nature of the pain.","Heart failure would present with other features, such as shortness of breath and crackles, and there would be an obvious cause.","Pulmonary embolism is a good differential diagnosis, but once again, there are no risk factors from the information provided. His PERC (Pulmonary embolism rule-out criteria) score was zero.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"Chest pain radiating to the shoulder tip is suggestive of radiation via the phrenic nerve, which supplies the pericardium. The pain relief on leaning forward supports this diagnosis.","explanation":"Chest pain radiating to the shoulder tip is suggestive of radiation via the phrenic nerve, which supplies the pericardium. The pain relief on leaning forward supports this diagnosis."},{"id":"11501","category":"Cardiovascular medicine","stem":"A 55-year-old woman is admitted to the Acute Medical Unit with worsening breathing difficulty. She has experienced difficulty in exertion due to breathlessness for the past month, with fatigue. For the past two days, she has had difficulty lying down flat in her bed. She has also had a couple of episodes of breathing difficulty at night when sleeping, when she had to sit or stand up to improve her breathing.\n\nHer past medical history includes refractory hypertension, type-2 diabetes mellitus, obesity, obstructive sleep apnoea, chronic kidney disease stage II, and chronic obstructive pulmonary disease.\n\nOn examination, she is alert and oriented, with a body mass index of 40 kg/m2, a pulse rate of 100/minute regular, blood pressure is 150/96 mmHg, respiratory rate is 21/minute, oxygen saturation on air is 94%; 99% on 28% FiO2, Temperature is 37oC.\n\nJugular venous pressure is 2 cm elevated, capillary refill time is 2 seconds. Mild bilateral pitting ankle oedema is present.\n\nA respiratory system examination reveals bilateral basal crepitations; scattered wheezing is also heard bilaterally. A cardiovascular system examination reveals normal heart sounds; tachycardic.\n\nHer abdomen is soft, and no tenderness is noted. There are active bowel sounds.\n\nInvestigations reveal:\n\nArterial blood gas on air\n\nWhat is the likely cause of her current admission?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Her past medical history includes refractory hypertension, type-2 diabetes mellitus, obesity, obstructive sleep apnoea, chronic kidney disease stage II, and chronic obstructive pulmonary disease.","Jugular venous pressure is 2 cm elevated, capillary refill time is 2 seconds. Mild bilateral pitting ankle oedema is present.","Her abdomen is soft, and no tenderness is noted. There are active bowel sounds.","Investigations reveal:","Arterial blood gas on air","Investigation\tResult","Electrocardiogram (ECG)\tSinus rhythm; left ventricular hypertrophy with secondary repolarization change","Chest X -ray\tHyperinflated lung fields; small bilateral pleural effusion noted","Echocardiography","What is the likely cause of her current admission?","Heart failure with reduced ejection fraction would require an echocardiographic finding of low ejection fraction, which is not the case here.","The patient has wheeze, multiple features of heart failure and normal PCO2 in ABG, which are all against a diagnosis of COPD exacerbation.","The total WBC count, CRP, and ESR are all normal, and there is also no history of fever, making pneumonia unlikely as the diagnosis.","The patient has features of uncontrolled hypertension in an ECG and ECHO, but her current blood pressure is not in the malignant or accelerated levels; malignant hypertension is not the case here.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"Heart failure with reduced ejection fraction would require an echocardiographic finding of low ejection fraction, which is not the case here.","explanation":"This patient has classic symptoms and signs of congestive heart failure, pleural effusions and raised BNP, but the echocardiogram shows normal systolic ejection fraction with diastolic dysfunction, and this is consistent with a diagnosis of heart failure with preserved ejection fraction. Her risk factors for the diagnosis include obesity, sleep apnoea, and metabolic syndrome."},{"id":"17093","category":"Cardiovascular medicine","stem":"A 77-year-old man with a background history of ischaemic heart disease, heart failure (left ventricular ejection fraction of 25%), and hypertension, presented with worsening breathlessness and increased leg swelling over a few months. His home medications include bisoprolol 2.5 mg once daily, ramipril 5 mg once daily, aspirin 75 mg once daily, atorvastatin 40 mg once daily, and furosemide 40 mg once daily. Examination revealed that he was haemodynamically stable, had bibasal fine crackles on chest auscultation, mild pitting oedema, and his jugular venous pulse was not raised. Blood tests were unremarkable and chest X-ray confirmed pulmonary oedema. His furosemide was increased to 40 mg twice daily and he was started on spironolactone 25 mg once daily.\n\nThe addition of which medication will help improve this patient’s symptoms and reduce cardiovascular mortality and morbidity?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","The addition of which medication will help improve this patient’s symptoms and reduce cardiovascular mortality and morbidity?","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"The addition of which medication will help improve this patient’s symptoms and reduce cardiovascular mortality and morbidity?","explanation":"Dapagliflozin (SGLT2 inhibitor) was initially licensed as an anti-diabetic medication. The DAPA-HF trial investigated its long-term effects on morbidity and mortality in patients with heart failure with reduced ejection fraction (HFrEF) and found a 26% reduction in worsening heart failure (hospitalisation or hospital attendance requiring intravenous treatment for heart failure) or cardiovascular death. Therefore, in addition to optimal medical therapy for heart failure, dapagliflozin is recommended for patients with HFrEF irrespective of their diabetes status. The additional diuretic/natriuretic properties of dapagliflozin help by reducing congestion, allowing a reduction in loop diuretic requirements."},{"id":"17261","category":"Cardiovascular medicine","stem":"A 65-year-old woman visited the ambulatory care service complaining of breathlessness. She reported a six-month history of progressively worsening breathing and swollen legs, which started around the same time. She denied any chest pain. On examination, she was speaking in full sentences with no breathing difficulty; however, her respiratory rate was slightly raised to 22 beats per minute at rest. The patient also had a raised jugular vein pressure (JVP) of 5 cm, with pulmonary crackles in both lung bases on auscultation; no abdominal swelling, but peripheral oedema was present with pitting oedema below the knee bilaterally.\n\nWhat is the most likely diagnosis for breathlessness in this patient?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Berliner, D., Schneider, N., Welte, T., & Bauersachs, J. (2016). The Differential Diagnosis of Dyspnea. Deutsches Arzteblatt international, 113(49), 834–845. https://doi.org/10.3238/arztebl.2016.0834","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"The differential diagnosis of breathlessness is vast and is a common symptom in general practice and secondary care. The history is important because it allows further classification with a focus on the temporal course, situational aspects, and causative factors; it is the history combined with the physical examination that will help us distinguish the underlying cause of dyspnoea. This patient has some chronicity of the symptoms (at least 6 months), and presents with distension of neck veins in addition to crackles on the lungs and peripheral oedema, with no previous lung pathology, which all point towards an acute decompensated heart failure diagnosis. In pulmonary embolism, the symptoms are more acute, with normal auscultatory findings, and there might be haemodynamic instability associated. Pneumonia also has an acute presentation, and patients can have lung crackles with associated chest pain, but no other signs. Lung cancer has an insidious course, and some patients present with haemoptysis as an acute presentation instead of the above signs. COPD can be present; however, without risk factors, it is unlikely, and patients do not have hepatojugular reflux or peripheral oedema."},{"id":"13715","category":"Cardiovascular medicine","stem":"A 55-year-old man was admitted to the acute medical unit after feeling unwell for 12 hours and complaining of palpitations. An ECG has confirmed atrial fibrillation (AF) with a rate of 135 beats per minute. His blood pressure was 115/70 mmHg. His cardiovascular and respiratory examinations were otherwise normal. He does not smoke and does not take any medications. On further questioning, he admitted to drinking an excessive amount of alcohol two nights ago at his wife’s 50th birthday party.\n\nWhat is the recommended first line of approach in this case?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","This man has new-onset AF that is probably related to excess alcohol intake (a reversible cause), which is known to precipitate AF.","Pharmacological cardioversion with flecainide seems reasonable given that this man was previously fit and well and likely to have a structurally normal heart.","Electrical DC cardioversion would be the choice if this patient were haemodynamically unstable or if the onset of AF was less than 48 hours in duration.","Long-term antiarrhythmic medication is usually not required, and AF does not recur if alcohol intake is reduced.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"This man has new-onset AF that is probably related to excess alcohol intake (a reversible cause), which is known to precipitate AF.","explanation":"This man has new-onset AF that is probably related to excess alcohol intake (a reversible cause), which is known to precipitate AF."},{"id":"3590","category":"Cardiovascular medicine","stem":"A 65-year-old man is admitted with an episode of palpitations. He is known to suffer from paroxysmal atrial fibrillation and is being treated with bisoprolol 7.5 mg daily. This is the second occasion over the last 6 months that he has been admitted with palpitations. The ECG confirms atrial fibrillation at a rate of 96 bpm. He knows when the AF happens as he feels strange, gets a little breathless and can feel an irregular pulse. Usually, it settles after a couple of hours’ rest, but on this occasion, it persisted for about 3 hours, so he came to the hospital. He previously had an ECHO, which was normal, and had an exercise test in the past, which was normal, too. Thyroid function tests were also normal. In his previous history, he is known to be hypertensive and overweight.\n\nWhich of the following characterises his annualised risk of stroke associated with his paroxysmal atrial fibrillation?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","The CHADS-VASC is used to determine the risk of stroke in AF and, therefore, the requirement for anticoagulation. In this man, the CHAD-VASC is: 2 - 1 each for hypertension and age.","VASc Score for Atrial Fibrillation Stroke Risk - MDCalc.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"The CHADS-VASC is used to determine the risk of stroke in AF and, therefore, the requirement for anticoagulation. In this man, the CHAD-VASC is: 2 - 1 each for hypertension and age.","explanation":"The CHADS-VASC is used to determine the risk of stroke in AF and, therefore, the requirement for anticoagulation. In this man, the CHAD-VASC is: 2 - 1 each for hypertension and age."},{"id":"7866","category":"Cardiovascular medicine","stem":"A 32-year-old woman was referred to MAU by her GP after presenting with chest discomfort. She is 20 weeks pregnant in her second pregnancy, and the pregnancy so far has been uneventful. She feels that the pain is 6/10 and feels that it is like indigestion.\n\nWhich of the following features on ECG would not be expected to be a normal variant in this patient?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Elliott, C., Sliwa, K. and Burton, R., (2014). Pregnancy and cardiac disease. South African Medical Journal, 104(9).","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"Normal variants on the ECG in pregnancy include T wave inversion in lead III, V1 and V2, left axis deviation, sinus tachycardia and atrial ectopic beats. ST elevation in the anterior leads would not be expected and suggests pathology."},{"id":"3581","category":"Medicine in the elderly","stem":"An 83-year-old man is admitted to the hospital following a fall at home. His wife died a year ago, and he has been living on his own since. His daughter found him at home after she went to visit him after work. He told her that he had fallen about an hour before she arrived and was unable to stand. She informs you that he has found looking after himself increasingly difficult and has had a recent history of falls. On this occasion, the patient explains that he has had increasing problems with his muscle strength, and he tripped over and cut his head. He did not lose consciousness but was unable to stand.\n\nCurrently, he takes amlodipine 10 mg/d, simvastatin 40 mg/d and omeprazole 10 mg/d.\n\nOn examination, he is frail and has a superficial laceration to the right temporal region, which has not required stitching. Observations are fine, but he has a BMI of 20.5kg/m2 and has obvious sarcopenia, particularly with proximal muscle weakness. His pulse is 80 beats per minute, regular, and his blood pressure is 142/78 mmHg lying and standing.\n\nWhich of the following is the most appropriate treatment for a fall prevention strategy for this man?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"This elderly male patient has had a fall at home, resulting in his admission to the hospital. This is a very common occurrence and, according to guidance, this patient should be treated with at least 800IU vitamin D3 as part of a fall prevention strategy. It is highly likely that the patient has vitamin D deficiency, and this may contribute to the sarcopenia and proximal muscle weakness. There is no evidence of postural hypotension, so there would be no requirement to stop the amlodipine."},{"id":"10275","category":"Medicine in the elderly","stem":"A 72-year-old woman is admitted with fever, suprapubic pain, haematuria, and nausea. She has a past medical history of stage 3 chronic kidney disease, type 2 diabetes, hypertension, and gallstones. Her regular medications include metformin 500 mg twice daily, losartan 50 mg once daily, and bendroflumethiazide 2.5 mg once daily.\n\nHer observations show:\n\nBlood pressure 110/80mmHg,\nHeart rate 90 bpm,\nTemperature 38.3oC,\nRespiratory rate 19/min,\nSats 100%RA.\n\nHer urine dipstick shows: erythrocytes ++, nitrates +++, leucocytes +++, protein+ and her inflammatory markers are raised: WBC 13x109/L(N:4-11) and serum C-reactive protein (CRP) 67mg/L (<10).\n\nShe was commenced on nitrofurantoin as per her previous urine culture sensitivities. She presented repeatedly over the last 12 months with a urinary tract infection (UTI), and she previously tried vaginal oestrogen and cranberry products. She enquired regarding antibiotic prophylaxis to prevent recurrent UTIs.\n\nHow many episodes of UTI should she have had recently to be diagnosed with recurrent UTIs?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Her observations show:","Her urine dipstick shows: erythrocytes ++, nitrates +++, leucocytes +++, protein+ and her inflammatory markers are raised: WBC 13x109/L(N:4-11) and serum C-reactive protein (CRP) 67mg/L (<10).","How many episodes of UTI should she have had recently to be diagnosed with recurrent UTIs?","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"Recurrent UTI is defined as 2 or more UTIs in the last 6 months or 3 or more UTIs in the last 12 months. It may happen due to relapse or reinfection. The diagnosis needs to be confirmed by the urine culture. Vaginal oestrogens can be considered for postmenopausal women when personal hygiene and behavioural changes have been ineffective."},{"id":"17507","category":"Medicine in the elderly","stem":"An 80-year-old man presents to the emergency department with complaints of fever, cough with yellowish-green mucopurulent sputum production, and breathing difficulty of three days' duration. The patient is a known case of type 2 diabetes mellitus, hypertension, and chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD). On examination, he was tachypnoeic. The patient has an O2 saturation of 89% on room air, a pulse rate of 112 beats per minute, blood pressure of 154/82 mmHg. Chest examinations showed bilateral extensive scattered wheeze. The patient was immediately connected to the monitor and started on O2 support at 4 litres per minute via nasal prong. His symptoms and oxygen saturation improved with oxygen support and nebulisation with bronchodilators, but the monitor showed features of atrial fibrillation.\n\nInvestigations showed the following results:\n\nWhat is the next important step in the management of atrial fibrillation?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Investigations showed the following results:","What is the next important step in the management of atrial fibrillation?","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"What is the next important step in the management of atrial fibrillation?","explanation":"Atrial fibrillation is the most common arrhythmia seen in our clinical practice. It can be paroxysmal, persistent or permanent. The treatment varies according to the duration, precipitating factors, and underlying cardiac structural abnormalities. All patients should be assessed for anti-coagulation therapy, CHAD2S2-VASc. Treatment options include cardioversion by electrical and pharmacological methods and rate control. If the patient is having acute life-threatening symptoms like chest pain, palpitation, dyspnoea, or syncope, then they might need immediate electrical cardioversion. If the patient does not have life-threatening symptoms, then either pharmacological cardioversion or rate control will depend on the duration of the symptoms and underlying cardiac structural abnormalities."},{"id":"10274","category":"Medicine in the elderly","stem":"A 75-year-old man was admitted with increased confusion and agitation, fever and cough. He had a past medical history of dementia, Parkinson’s disease, benign prostatic hyperplasia (BPH) and emphysema. His regular medications included tamsulosin 400 mcg once daily, finasteride 5 mg once daily and co-careldopa 125 (100/25) mg three times daily.\n\nOn admission, his observations were as follows:\n\nTemperature 38.7oC,\nRespiratory rate 25/min,\nBlood pressure 100/85 mmHg,\nHeart rate 110 bpm,\nSats 93%RA,\nGCS 13/15.\n\nHis chest X-ray showed right basal consolidation, and his blood results were:\n\nThe patient was diagnosed with right community-acquired pneumonia and acute kidney injury (AKI) and commenced on intravenous fluids and antibiotics.\n\nHe was found to be very agitated and refused oral medication. He was also found to have an unsafe swallow at the bedside swallow assessment. Nasogastric tube insertion was not successful despite repeated attempts; hence, he was commenced on rotigotine patch 8 mg/24 hours for his Parkinson’s disease.\n\nThe following day, he was more delirious with visual hallucinations. He was also vomiting frequently.\n\nHow should he be managed?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","On admission, his observations were as follows:","His chest X-ray showed right basal consolidation, and his blood results were:","The patient was diagnosed with right community-acquired pneumonia and acute kidney injury (AKI) and commenced on intravenous fluids and antibiotics.","The following day, he was more delirious with visual hallucinations. He was also vomiting frequently.","How should he be managed?","Patients with Parkinson’s disease can develop serious complications if their dopaminergic medication is missed.","Therefore, if they are NBM/unable to swallow, the following approach should be considered:","There are various online tools available for the calculation of equivalent doses, such as Optimal Calculator.","People with PD presenting with nausea and vomiting should not be managed with metoclopramide, prochlorperazine or haloperidol, as this may worsen their PD symptoms.","Domperidone PO or pr can be used, as well as cyclizine and ondansetron.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"Patients with Parkinson’s disease can develop serious complications if their dopaminergic medication is missed.","explanation":"Patients with Parkinson’s disease can develop serious complications if their dopaminergic medication is missed."},{"id":"10796","category":"Medicine in the elderly","stem":"A 65-year-old man presents in the emergency department with an acute onset of weakness in both legs. Examination reveals grade-2 power, hypotonia and areflexia of both lower limbs. He has no sensory loss or sensory level, and there is no bowel and bladder involvement. Babinski’s sign is absent. The rest of the systemic examination is normal. His previous history is unremarkable.\n\nHow should you manage this patient?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Alteplase is a thrombolytic used in acute ischemic stroke, while methylcobalamin is used in vitamin B12 deficiency. Methylprednisolone is used in acute attacks of multiple sclerosis.","Ocrelizumab is a humanised anti-CD20 monoclonal antibody used in multiple sclerosis.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"This patient presents with a case of Guillain-Barré syndrome (AIDP variant), and the treatment of choice is IV immunoglobulins and plasmapheresis. Intravenous immunoglobulins (IVIg) have been shown in a number of trials to be an effective and standard treatment for the Guillain-Barré syndrome (GBS) because of their ease of administration and better side effect profile. IVIg is thought to affect many immune system components, including B-cells, T-cells, macrophages, complement, cytokines, and cellular adhesion molecules, to exert its immunomodulatory impact."},{"id":"10803","category":"Medicine in the elderly","stem":"A 78-year-old woman with a history of depression is admitted after taking an overdose of atenolol. She had taken approximately 40 x 50mg tablets 2 hours earlier. On examination, she had a blood pressure of 86 mmHg systolic and a pulse of 48 beats per minute, regular. Her ECG revealed a sinus bradycardia without clear P waves. Her GCS was 13.\n\nShe is administered IV fluids, but which of the following should initially be given to this patient?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"This woman has taken a life-threatening overdose of beta-blockers and is critically ill. She requires immediate transfer to the ICU; the most appropriate initial treatment for a beta-blocker overdose would be IV glucagon. Other treatment approaches include dialysis in an atenolol overdose, as well as a High-Dose Insulin Infusion. Similarly, once the airway is secure, one could also use activated charcoal."},{"id":"17262","category":"Medicine in the elderly","stem":"An 85-year-old woman is admitted to the hospital for social admission as she is not coping at home. Her medical history is taken from a relative, who states that the patient deteriorated over the last week with confusion and reduced mobility, needing assistance to transfer and walk. The patient’s relative also reports that the patient fell out of bed one night and had urinary incontinence. She has a background of myocardial infarction, fracture of the right femur, and depression. The patient is deaf, uses hearing aids, is short-sighted and wears glasses. Her drug history is extensive, with 10 medications, and she lives alone with once-a-day carers.\n\nOn examination, she was slow to respond with a Glasgow Coma Scale of 14/15, a temperature spiking to 38.5oC, blood pressure of 112/70 mmHg lying and 90/68 mmHg standing, and there were crackles in the right lung base. She failed her bedside water swallow test.\n\nHer chest X-ray revealed right base consolidation, and the relevant blood tests showed:\n\nThe patient’s medications pre-admission are as follows: amlodipine 10 mg, aspirin 75 mg, bendroflumethiazide 2.5 mg. Vitamin D/calcium 600UI/1000 mg, fluoxetine 20 mg, furosemide 20 mg, ibuprofen 400 mg as required, lactulose, ramipril 5 mg, simvastatin 20 mg.\n\nWhat is the main management option for this patient?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"The patient's inability to swallow is one of the reasons to stop all her medications, but also to keep her nil by mouth and use intravenous hydration because of reduced GCS with risk of aspiration. The Na+ level does not vary with infection and needs further investigation for potential causes, although, in her case, it is likely hypovolaemia-related. The primary treatment for this patient would be to treat the infection and hydration, following which, if there is no improvement in her GCS, then brain imaging can be considered."},{"id":"11419","category":"Medicine in the elderly","stem":"An 87-year-old woman living in a nursing home is admitted to the Acute Medical Unit with general deterioration and fever.\n\nHer past medical history includes type-2 diabetes mellitus, chronic venous leg ulcer, Alzheimer’s disease, hypertension, and hypercholesterolemia. The general practitioner who had seen the patient 2 days ago has taken a wound swab of her ulcer, and the culture has grown methicillin-resistant Staphylococcus aureus (MRSA) as per provisional reports.\n\nOn examination, she is alert but pleasantly confused, with a pulse rate of 115/minute, blood pressure of 100/70 mmHg, respiratory rate is 21/minute, oxygen saturation on air is 99% and temperature is 39oC. Capillary refill time is 4 seconds, and jugular venous pressure is not elevated.\n\nA respiratory system exam reveals normal breath sounds on both sides, and a cardiovascular system exam reveals normal heart sounds.\n\nThe patient’s abdomen is soft, with no tenderness noted, and active bowel sounds are present.\n\nA large ulcer is noted on her right leg over the medial malleolus with surrounding cellulitis up to the level of the knees. Bilateral ankles were noted to be oedematous.\n\nYou have taken the necessary blood samples and blood culture on arrival, and an intravenous line is secured.\n\nWhich initial intravenous antibiotic would be the most appropriate for this patient?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","An 87-year-old woman living in a nursing home is admitted to the Acute Medical Unit with general deterioration and fever.","The patient’s abdomen is soft, with no tenderness noted, and active bowel sounds are present.","A large ulcer is noted on her right leg over the medial malleolus with surrounding cellulitis up to the level of the knees. Bilateral ankles were noted to be oedematous.","You have taken the necessary blood samples and blood culture on arrival, and an intravenous line is secured.","Which initial intravenous antibiotic would be the most appropriate for this patient?","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"This elderly patient likely has MRSA cellulitis with features of SIRS and sepsis. As per the NICE guidelines, either vancomycin, teicoplanin, or linezolid should be given, on suspicion of MRSA cellulitis/sepsis without delay."},{"id":"11415","category":"Medicine in the elderly","stem":"An 80-year-old man with a past medical history of type-2 diabetes mellitus, systemic hypertension, hypercholesterolemia, right-sided middle cerebral artery infarct with residual left-sided weakness, peripheral artery disease, and a 50-pack-year smoking history has been having epigastric pain within an hour of a meal for the past 3 months. He has subsequently lost 7 kg due to apprehension of meal-related pain. His general practitioner has noted that his abdomen has been soft and non-tender and has been treating him with Gaviscon (antacid) and omeprazole for the past week.\n\nHe is admitted with worsening abdominal pain to the Acute Medical Unit.\n\nOn examination, the patient is alert and oriented but in distress due to severe pain. His pulse rate is 120 beats per minute, blood pressure is 160/80 mmHg, respiratory rate is 25/minute, oxygen saturation on air is 97% and his temperature is 37oC.\n\nCapillary refill time is 2 seconds, jugular venous pressure is not elevated, and there is no leg oedema present.\n\nA respiratory system examination reveals normal breath sounds on both sides, and a cardiovascular system exam reveals normal heart sounds. His abdomen is soft, with mild epigastric tenderness.\n\nInvestigations reveal:\n\nArterial Blood Gas On Air:\n\nWhat is the likely diagnosis?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","He is admitted with worsening abdominal pain to the Acute Medical Unit.","Capillary refill time is 2 seconds, jugular venous pressure is not elevated, and there is no leg oedema present.","Investigations reveal:","Arterial Blood Gas On Air:","What is the likely diagnosis?","A Perforated duodenal ulcer does not explain the severe metabolic acidosis, the relatively mild abdominal palpation signs and absence of peritonitis, and the food apprehension with weight loss.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"What is the likely diagnosis?","explanation":"This elderly patient, with strong atherosclerotic risk factors, has a history of post-prandial pain which has led to a fear of eating and weight loss which is due to mesenteric angina; his acute abdominal pain is out-of-proportion to the abdominal tenderness and is associated with decompensated metabolic and lactic acidosis and the most important diagnosis to consider here would be mesenteric infarction which can be catastrophic, especially with delayed diagnosis. For an elderly patient with vascular risk factors who presents with acute abdominal pain (out of proportion to the tenderness) and severe metabolic acidosis, mesenteric ischaemia should be the most important diagnosis to be considered."},{"id":"10272","category":"Medicine in the elderly","stem":"An 81-year-old woman developed a sudden onset of left-sided weakness and slurred speech whilst eating dinner 2 hours earlier. She has a past medical history of hypertension, dyslipidaemia, GORD, type-2 diabetes and recurrent falls. She had a transient ischaemic attack (TIA) 2 months ago and was taking clopidogrel 75 mg once daily.\n\nOn arrival at the accident & emergency unit, her observations were:\n\nBlood pressure 200/100 mmHg\nHeart rate 105 bpm\nSats 100% room air (RA)\nTemperature 37oC\nRespiratory rate 22/min\n\nHer capillary glucose was 17 mmol/L. She was promptly assessed by the Stroke Team, and her NIHSS score was 12. The subsequent CT head confirmed developing ischaemic stroke in the right MCA territory, and thrombolysis with alteplase was being considered.\n\nWhat is the contraindication to thrombolysis in this patient’s case?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","On arrival at the accident & emergency unit, her observations were:","What is the contraindication to thrombolysis in this patient’s case?","The absolute contraindications to stroke thrombolysis include:","Advanced age (>75 years) is not considered a contraindication or exclusion.","Relative exclusion criteria include:","Major surgery or non-head trauma in the last 2 weeks\nGI, urinary or gynaecological haemorrhage in the last 21 days\nBrain tumour, cerebral aneurysm, arteriovenous malformation (AVM)","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"The absolute contraindications to stroke thrombolysis include:","explanation":"The absolute contraindications to stroke thrombolysis include:"},{"id":"11417","category":"Medicine in the elderly","stem":"An 83-year-old man was admitted to the Acute Medical Unit following a syncopal episode 8 hours ago. His past medical history includes type 2 diabetes mellitus, hypertension, osteoporosis, rheumatoid arthritis, and mild Alzheimer’s disease. Before this episode, he had been his usual self and denied any history of chest pain, breathlessness, leg swelling, dizziness, or fevers. His appetite has been unchanged, but he has lost about 1 kg of weight in the past year.\n\nHis current medications include galantamine, aspirin, simvastatin, amlodipine, methotrexate, alendronate, ramipril, and calcium supplements.\n\nOn examination, he is alert and oriented, with a pulse rate of 32/minute and supine blood pressure is 90/60 mmHg. His respiratory rate is 15/min, temperature is 36.4oC and oxygen saturation on air is 99%. The respiratory system reveals normal breath sounds. A cardiovascular system examination reveals normal heart sounds. There is a faint ejection systolic murmur in the aortic area.\n\nThe patient continues to be dizzy in bed during observation, and a temporary transvenous pacemaker is inserted. The patient’s pulse rate and blood pressure improved to 90/min and 130/80 mmHg, respectively, with complete symptomatic resolution.\n\nWhat is the most likely cause of this patient’s 3rd degree atrioventricular block?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","His current medications include galantamine, aspirin, simvastatin, amlodipine, methotrexate, alendronate, ramipril, and calcium supplements.","Investigations:","What is the most likely cause of this patient’s 3rd degree atrioventricular block?","It is unlikely this patient had a recent acute myocardial infarction, given no significant ST-T changes, no pathologic Q waves, and a normal troponin value.","Myocardial fibrosis can cause cardiac electrical conduction problems, but in this patient, there is an identifiable drug-induced cause for the atrioventricular block.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"What is the most likely cause of this patient’s 3rd degree atrioventricular block?","explanation":"This patient is on galantamine, which is a central acetylcholinesterase inhibitor. It is NICE-approved for use in Alzheimer’s disease; galantamine can have vagal effects, which may cause bradycardia and heart block in patients with or even without a history of heart disease."},{"id":"11966","category":"Medicine in the elderly","stem":"An 84-year-old has been admitted to the accident and emergency department after he had a loss of consciousness (LOC). He has been admitted three times over the last six months with the same presentation and was diagnosed with possible postural hypotension. He is known to be hypertensive and diabetic, and he had a stroke two years ago with no residual weakness. He has recently been diagnosed with Parkinson’s disease.\n\nOn examination, he is fully awake, and a scalp wound that has been sutured by the A&E team is noted. His BP was 130/70 mmHg. His CT head was normal. The patient gave a history that he lost consciousness while having his dinner, and he denied any warning symptoms. His wife called the ambulance, and he became fully conscious after one minute. He denied any chest pain or palpitation.\n\nThe patient’s ECG is shown below:\n\n[Image source: author]\n\nWhat is the best next step in his management?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"The ECG shows what is known as Trifascicular block with right bundle branch block (RBBB), first-degree heart block, and left axis deviation (suggesting LAHB), which suggests extensive conduction system disease. Given that the patient has a typical cardiac level of consciousness (LOC), a permanent pacemaker is indicated. Lying and standing BP is not mentioned here, but the patient lost consciousness while eating his dinner. An ECG monitor may or may not show pauses, and it will be risky to send the patient home given recurrent admission with LOC and head injury without having a permanent pacemaker fitted (PPM)."},{"id":"11413","category":"Medicine in the elderly","stem":"An 86-year-old man with a past medical history including vascular dementia, benign prostatic hyperplasia with transurethral resection of prostate done 12 months ago, chronic constipation, type-2 diabetes, recurrent transient ischaemic attacks, and hypertension, lives in a residential home. He is usually pleasantly confused and dependent on help for activities of daily life. His carers noted that he had been \"out of sorts\" the previous day, and noted that he had a low-grade fever for which they had given him paracetamol. However, he had become acutely confused and agitated and has since been admitted to the Acute Medical Unit.\n\nOn examination, he is alert but agitated and disoriented. His pulse rate is 97/min regular, and his blood pressure is 160/90 mmHg. He has a respiratory rate of 18/min, with an oxygen saturation on room air of 97%. His temperature is 37oC.\n\nA respiratory system exam reveals normal breath sounds on both sides, and a cardiovascular system exam reveals normal heart sounds.\n\nHis abdomen is soft, but he is noted to be in discomfort on palpation below the umbilicus and dullness on percussion is noted below the umbilicus. Bowel sounds are active on auscultation.\n\nA neurological exam was completed, with no focal neurological deficits apparent.\n\nThe patient’s capillary blood glucose is 7 mmol/L.\n\nInvestigations reveal:\n\nWhich one of the following interventions is likely to improve his confusion rapidly?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","His abdomen is soft, but he is noted to be in discomfort on palpation below the umbilicus and dullness on percussion is noted below the umbilicus. Bowel sounds are active on auscultation.","The patient’s capillary blood glucose is 7 mmol/L.","Investigations reveal:","Which one of the following interventions is likely to improve his confusion rapidly?","This patient likely has an acute urinary retention, and this is the most likely cause of the acute confusional state. Urinary catheterisation can significantly improve his confusion.","His urinary tract infection requires antibiotics, but his acute confusion is likely to improve significantly with catheterisation itself initially.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"This patient likely has an acute urinary retention, and this is the most likely cause of the acute confusional state. Urinary catheterisation can significantly improve his confusion.","explanation":"This patient likely has an acute urinary retention, and this is the most likely cause of the acute confusional state. Urinary catheterisation can significantly improve his confusion."},{"id":"10801","category":"Medicine in the elderly","stem":"A female patient was seen in the acute receiving unit out-of-hours, with a transient right facial and arm weakness lasting for 1 hour, which occurred yesterday. Her symptoms have completely resolved, and she is eager to get home. She is on Edoxaban.\n\nWhat is the preferred management for this patient?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","In this case, Edoxaban is an anticoagulant and haemorrhage should be excluded.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"In this case, Edoxaban is an anticoagulant and haemorrhage should be excluded.","explanation":"Patients with suspected TIA should be assessed by a specialist physician before a decision on brain imaging is made, except when haemorrhage requires exclusion in patients taking an anticoagulant or with a bleeding disorder, when unenhanced CT should be performed urgently."},{"id":"11416","category":"Medicine in the elderly","stem":"A 75-year-old man without any significant past medical history is admitted to the Acute Medical Unit following a fall and is undergoing assessment.\n\nHe explains that for the past 6 months, he has been having difficulty walking. He has also noted his hands to be clumsy and has difficulty buttoning his shirt. He says he cannot remember how it started, but it has been slowly getting worse. He has also been experiencing pain in his neck and upper shoulders, along with stiffness.\n\nOn examination, he is alert and oriented, with a pulse rate of 87 beats per minute and blood pressure of 140/80 mmHg.\n\nA respiratory system examination reveals normal breath sounds, and a cardiovascular system examination reveals normal heart sounds.\n\nA neurological examination reveals normal speech comprehension and articulation and normal cranial nerves. His mini-mental state examination (MMSE) score is 29/30.\n\nUpper limbs: Mild wasting of both shoulders and biceps is present; normal intrinsic muscles of both hands noted; muscle power of 3/5 proximally and 4/5 distally noted; Biceps and brachioradialis reflexes are absent on both sides with brisk triceps reflexes. Reduced sensation over the lateral arm bilaterally (C5).\n\nLower limbs: Mildly increased muscle tone bilaterally, 4/5 muscle power throughout; brisk knee and ankle reflexes bilaterally with extensor plantar reflexes; gait noted to be broad-based. No sensory deficit is noted.\n\nInvestigations reveal:\n\nWhat is the most likely diagnosis?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","This patient has classical features of cervical myelopathy at the C5-C6 level with C5 sensory loss, C5 level lower motor weakness (LMN), and upper motor neuron (UMN) signs caudally.","Vascular Parkinsonism is unlikely given the dermatomal sensory loss and a combined LMN + UMN feature seen here.","Motor neuron disease (MND) patients usually do not have objective sensory deficits as described here. The absence of any signs above the C5 level or bulbar signs is also against the diagnosis of MND.","A cerebral tumour is unlikely to produce quadriparesis as described and does not produce a dermatomal sensory loss.","Donnally III, C.J., Hanna, A. and Odom, C.K., 2021. Cervical myelopathy. StatPearls [Internet].","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"This patient has classical features of cervical myelopathy at the C5-C6 level with C5 sensory loss, C5 level lower motor weakness (LMN), and upper motor neuron (UMN) signs caudally.","explanation":"This patient has classical features of cervical myelopathy at the C5-C6 level with C5 sensory loss, C5 level lower motor weakness (LMN), and upper motor neuron (UMN) signs caudally."},{"id":"12024","category":"Medicine in the elderly","stem":"An 82-year-old man with metastatic prostate cancer has been admitted to a specialist palliative care inpatient unit. He lives alone, and the request had been for a 'social admission', as he had become acutely unable to look after himself. On admission, the nurse found him to be fully alert but restless and distracted. He was able to recall his date of birth and the current year, but he was not able to recall the place or his age. When asked to count the months of the year backwards, he was only able to state ‘December’ and then ‘November’, but nothing further beyond that. The nurse has therefore completed the ‘4AT’ (4 A’s Test) screening tool in light of the patient’s confusion.\n\nWhat would the ‘4AT’ score indicate for this patient?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","It is based on four factors: alertness, abbreviated mental test-4 (recall of age, date of birth, place/name of the building, year); attention; acute change or fluctuating course.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"The 4AT (4 A’s Test) is a screening tool for the initial assessment of cognitive impairment and delirium. It is one of the tools recommended by NICE (National Institute for Health and Care Excellence) and SIGN (Scottish Intercollegiate Guidelines Network) for screening for delirium."},{"id":"11422","category":"Medicine in the elderly","stem":"A 75-year-old elderly man is admitted to the Acute Medical Unit after a fall and is undergoing assessment.\n\nHis only past medical history is depression. According to his general practitioner’s (GP) clinical notes, the patient lost his wife to cancer about 8 months ago and has been having difficulty coping with the loss; he has been living on his own since then and has refused support from social services. The GP also adds that the patient has been drinking alcohol heavily since his wife’s death and says he has lost about 10 kgs of weight over 8 months.\n\nOn examination, the patient is alert and oriented but noted to be withdrawn and weak, with a body mass index of 17 kg/2 and an unkempt and dishevelled appearance. His pulse rate is 90/minute, blood pressure is 120/80 mmHg, respiratory rate is 14/minute, oxygen saturation on air is 99% and temperature is 36.6oC. Capillary refill time is 2 seconds, and jugular venous pressure is not elevated.\n\nMild pitting ankle oedema is noted. Perifollicular hyperkeratotic papules with surrounding haemorrhage and petechiae are noted over the chest wall and arms.\n\nHis gums are noted to be bleeding with dental caries/glossitis noted. Multiple ecchymotic lesions are noted over both legs. His left knee is swollen, but no warmth or overlying erythema is noted.\n\nA respiratory system examination reveals normal breath sounds on both sides, and a cardiovascular system exam reveals normal heart sounds.\n\nHis abdomen is soft with no tenderness, there are active bowel sounds, and there is no palpable hepatosplenomegaly.\n\nInvestigations reveal:\n\nWhat is the likely diagnosis?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","A 75-year-old elderly man is admitted to the Acute Medical Unit after a fall and is undergoing assessment.","Mild pitting ankle oedema is noted. Perifollicular hyperkeratotic papules with surrounding haemorrhage and petechiae are noted over the chest wall and arms.","His gums are noted to be bleeding with dental caries/glossitis noted. Multiple ecchymotic lesions are noted over both legs. His left knee is swollen, but no warmth or overlying erythema is noted.","His abdomen is soft with no tenderness, there are active bowel sounds, and there is no palpable hepatosplenomegaly.","Investigations reveal:","What is the likely diagnosis?","Scurvy is commonly misinterpreted as vasculitis, but the normal ESR and CRP are against the diagnosis here.","Decompensated chronic liver disease is not the cause of this presentation, as his PT is normal.","Scabies is unlikely, given the absence of itching.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"This patient has classical features of scurvy (vitamin C deficiency) with evidence of self-neglect and protein-energy malnutrition. Individuals can develop clinical manifestations of scurvy within 3 months of deficient intake."},{"id":"11418","category":"Medicine in the elderly","stem":"An 80-year-old man was brought to the Emergency Department after he developed a sudden onset of right eye blindness, which has now completely recovered within one hour. He has been experiencing left-sided headaches and jaw pains while chewing food for the past month. He has also had a low-grade fever for the past month and noted that he developed morning stiffness affecting both his shoulders lasting for one hour, along with pain for the past 3 months; he adds that this shoulder problem had started abruptly one morning.\n\nOtherwise, his past medical history is remarkable only for right knee osteoarthritis.\n\nOn examination, the patient is alert and oriented, with a pulse rate of 75/minute, regular, blood pressure of 150/80 mmHg, respiratory rate is 14/minute, oxygen saturation on air is 99% and temperature is 37.5oC. Capillary refill time is 2 seconds. Jugular venous pressure is not elevated, and no leg oedema is present.\n\nA respiratory system examination reveals normal breath sounds on both sides, and a cardiovascular system exam reveals normal heart sounds.\n\nThe patient's abdomen is soft, with no tenderness noted, and active bowel sounds are present. He has normal visual acuity in both eyes, and mild left temporal forehead tenderness is noted. No carotid bruits heard on auscultation.\n\nRecent investigations by his general practitioner from the electronic medical record reveal:\n\nWhat is the most important immediate treatment?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Otherwise, his past medical history is remarkable only for right knee osteoarthritis.","Recent investigations by his general practitioner from the electronic medical record reveal:","What is the most important immediate treatment?","Uncomplicated GCA (no jaw claudication or visual disturbance): 40–60 mg prednisolone daily.","Evolving visual loss or amaurosis fugax (complicated GCA): 500 mg to 1 g of i.v. methylprednisolone for 3 days before oral glucocorticosteroids.","Established visual loss: 60 mg prednisolone daily to protect the contralateral eye.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"This elderly patient has had a transient monocular visual loss (amaurosis fugax) and has a history of headaches, jaw claudication, and constitutional features along with raised ESR, which are all suggestive of giant cell arteritis (GCA). His morning shoulder stiffness and pain of 3 months duration is due to polymyalgia rheumatica (PMR), which is well known to be associated with GCA."},{"id":"12262","category":"Medicine in the elderly","stem":"A 76-year-old man is admitted to the acute medicine unit with progressive deterioration. His wife says that he has been behaving erratically and has been feeling disoriented, very thirsty, and constantly visiting the toilet to pass urine. He has not passed stools for several days. There has been no fever or other symptoms, but his wife has noted that he is short of breath with even mild exertion. His past medical history includes type-2 diabetes mellitus for which he takes metformin 1 gram a day; he also has a 50-pack-year smoking history.\n\nOn examination, he is alert but confused.\n\nA mini-mental state examination (MMSE) reveals a score of 10/30 (24-30 normal; 18-23 mild impairment; < 17 severe cognitive impairment).\n\nHis pulse rate is 105 beats per minute, blood pressure is 160/80 mmHg, respiratory rate is 19 breaths per minute, and oxygen saturation on air is 94%.\n\nHis temperature is 37 oC. Capillary refill time is 4 seconds. He has dry oral mucosa.\n\nJugular venous pressure is not elevated, and there is no leg oedema.\n\nA respiratory system examination reveals reduced air entry in the right base, with scattered wheezes bilaterally. A cardiovascular system examination reveals normal heart sounds.\n\nThe patient’s abdomen is soft, there is no tenderness, and active bowel sounds are present.\n\nHis investigations are as follows:\n\nArterial blood gas analysis – on room air\n\nHis chest X-ray is shown below:\n\n[Image source: Author]\n\nWhat would be the likely cause of the acute confusional state in this patient?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","His temperature is 37 oC. Capillary refill time is 4 seconds. He has dry oral mucosa.","Jugular venous pressure is not elevated, and there is no leg oedema.","The patient’s abdomen is soft, there is no tenderness, and active bowel sounds are present.","His investigations are as follows:","Urine Analysis","Arterial blood gas analysis – on room air","Investigation\tResult\tNormal range\npH\t7.38\t7.35-45\npCO2\t4.4 kpA\t4.5-6 kPa\npO2\t8.9 kpa\t10.6-13 kpA\nBicarbonate\t26\t24 - 28\nBase excess\t0\t-2 to +2","His chest X-ray is shown below:","[Image source: Author]","What would be the likely cause of the acute confusional state in this patient?","He has normal random plasma glucose, normal acid-base balance, and no evidence of ketosis; therefore, DKA is unlikely. HHS is unlikely given a plasma glucose of 4.44.","Urinary tract infection is unlikely given the normal urine analysis. The symptoms and chest X-ray are not consistent with congestive cardiac failure.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"This patient has right lung lower zone collapse-consolidation and multiple cannonball metastases and has symptoms consistent with hypercalcaemia (confusion, polyuria, polydipsia, constipation and dehydration)."},{"id":"13718","category":"Medicine in the elderly","stem":"An 86-year-old man was referred to the acute medical unit by his GP with increasing shortness of breath and a cough with green sputum. On further questioning, he complained of choking on his food for several months and having had double vision for even longer. On examination, he had left partial ptosis, but otherwise, his cranial nerve examination was normal. He was generally weak in all muscle groups; his reflexes were normal.\n\nWhich is the most important investigation for this patient?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","This man has symptoms correlating with myasthenia gravis.","It is also worth mentioning the bimodal distribution of myasthenia gravis, i.e. with a peak in the 2nd and 3rd decades for women and the 8th decade for men.","Anti-GQ1b ganglioside antibody is detected in most patients with Miller Fisher syndrome (a variant of Guillain-Barré syndrome).","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"This man has symptoms correlating with myasthenia gravis.","explanation":"This man has symptoms correlating with myasthenia gravis."},{"id":"4220","category":"Medicine in the elderly","stem":"A 95-year-old woman was admitted to the medical assessment unit from her residential home on account of increased difficulty mobilising secondary to left hip pain. She had recently suffered a minor viral upper respiratory tract infection.\n\nShe had a past medical history of type-2 diabetes, hypertension, and chronic renal impairment for which she took sitagliptin, bendrofluazide, and Ramipril. She also took combined calcium and vitamin D3 supplements 1g daily of calcium and 800iu D3.\n\nOther than hip pain that had progressed over 2 years, she denied feeling unwell. Specifically, she denied thirst or frequency and otherwise reported no health concerns. There was no history of weight loss.\n\nHer observations and examination were unremarkable except for mild hypertension, discomfort and stiffness of her left hip noted when internally rotated. She was observed mobilising on her tripod and was found to be functionally at her baseline.\n\nInvestigations revealed:\n\nFBC, LFT, and CRP were normal.\n\nHip x-ray revealed moderate-severe osteoarthritis in her left hip, with no fractures or other abnormalities.\n\nSimple analgesics were initiated, and an outpatient referral to the orthopaedic team was arranged. Her combined calcium and vitamin D3 supplements were stopped. Aside from this, how else would you manage her hypercalcaemia?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Wermers, R. A. Kearns, A. E. Jenkins, G. D. Melton, L. J. III. Incidence and Clinical Spectrum of Thiazide-associated Hypercalcemia. Am J Med. 2007 Oct; 120(10): 911.e9–911.15.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"In this elderly woman's case, the raised calcium is an incidental finding, and she is on two medications that can precipitate hypercalcaemia – bendrofluazide and oral calcium – she may well have been tipped over, causing this mild hypercalcaemia with her recent viral illness. She is mobilising reasonably well presented and admission will likely adversely affect her functional state."},{"id":"11962","category":"Medicine in the elderly","stem":"An 85-year-old man was referred by his GP for an opinion regarding recurrent falls over the last year. He had a history of hypertension and benign prostatic hypertrophy (BPH) and is currently on regular ramipril 10 mg, atenolol 50 mg, and tamsulosin 400 mcg. He was told that he probably had a mild cataract. The patient mentioned that he has had six falls over the last year, and he believed that his falls were secondary to tripping over something on his way, and he thought using a stick would be helpful. He reported no dizziness and no loss of consciousness related to the falls, and until that time, he had minor abrasions following each fall. On examination, his sitting BP was 145/75 mmHg and 135/70 mmHg on standing up, with a heart rate of 74/min; his chest was clear to auscultation, and he had no additional sounds on listening to the heart. His ECG showed a 1st-degree heart block with a PR interval of 220 msec.\n\nWhat is the best management plan for this patient?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"The exact cause of recurrent falls is not clear in this patient. He reported multiple falls over the last year and, as advised by NICE guidelines, should be referred for multifactorial falls risk assessment, preferably in a specialist falls service."},{"id":"13168","category":"Medicine in the elderly","stem":"An 81-year-old woman was referred by her GP due to a high international normalised ratio (INR). She is known to have hypertension and paroxysmal atrial fibrillation, and she had a tissue aortic valve replacement (AVR) 10 years ago for aortic stenosis. The patient had her routine INR check today in the GP surgery, and the result was 8. She is currently on amlodipine 5 mg, ramipril 5 mg, bisoprolol 2.5 mg, and warfarin 4 mg, all once daily. She is completely asymptomatic and, on clinical examination, there are no signs or symptoms to suggest active bleeding.\n\nHer blood results are as follows:\n\nThe patient likes grapefruit juice and occasionally drinks it despite previously being advised not to do so because it will increase the effect of warfarin. You decided to admit the patient and omit warfarin doses until her INR decreases below 5.\n\nWhat is the best next step to consider in her management?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"The patient has an INR of 8 with no bleeding. According to the BNF, we need to withhold 1 or 2 doses of warfarin and then restart the patient on a smaller dose. Vitamin K is not indicated for either IV or oral use using the IV preparation unless the INR is more than 8 or with any type of bleeding. This patient has previously been advised against grapefruit but has continued to drink it despite the previous advice. Therefore, strictly advising her against grapefruit intake is insufficient guidance for this patient. More frequent INR checks may temporarily help, but this is not the best management option."},{"id":"3582","category":"Medicine in the elderly","stem":"An 83-year-old woman is admitted from home following a fall and sustaining a fracture of the humerus. On this occasion, the patient explains to you that she has had increasing problems with weakness, and she fell over, injuring her arm. She has had several falls previously, but on this occasion, she fractured her humerus and was seen by the A&E team, who recommended a sling and immobilisation. They have requested a medical opinion, as it is unlikely the patient can be discharged due to social circumstances. You establish she did not pass out, and this was a mechanical fall.\n\nCurrently she takes amlodipine 10 mg/d, simvastatin 40 mg/d and omeprazole 10 mg/d.\n\nOn examination, she has a BMI of 20 kg/m2 and her left arm is in a sling. There is little else to note other than loss of muscle bulk and proximal weakness.\n\nInvestigations reveal:\n\nWhich of the following is the likely contributory diagnosis to this patient’s fall?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","It is not PMR as this would not account for the hypocalcaemia and similarly, the CRP does not suggest an underlying inflammatory process.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"This elderly woman has fallen and sustained a fracture. She has proximal muscle weakness associated with low calcium and elevated alkaline phosphatase. This suggests vitamin D deficiency – osteomalacia. The patient should be treated with vitamin D supplementation with or without supplemental calcium, depending on her nutritional intake. A reasonable approach to treating vitamin D deficiency is either D3 3200iu daily for 3 months or 60000 weekly for 5 weeks, followed by a maintenance dose of 800iu daily. Guidance suggests a reduction in falls associated with vitamin D therapy and that it is a very common entity in the elderly, a consequence of reduced sunlight exposure and reduced ability to photosynthesise D3 in the skin."},{"id":"7883","category":"Medicine in the elderly","stem":"An 88-year-old woman was admitted to MAU as her daughter found her at home on her weekly visit and felt that she wasn’t quite right. Normally, she is fit and active and self-caring. Her husband died 10 years ago, and since then, she has lived alone but copes well with her daughter calling in.\n\nUsually, she takes omeprazole, citalopram, and bendrofluazide.\n\nOn examination, she was slightly confused with a mini-mental score of 19/30. Her temperature was 37.9 oC, her pulse was 88 beats per minute, and her blood pressure was 122/80 mmHg. Urine analysis revealed leucocytes and nitrites.\n\nWhich of the following is the most appropriate approach to the management of this patient?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"This patient presents with features of acute delirium and, with a previous good level of function, the presence of leucocytes and nitrites on urine analysis suggests a urine tract infection. The most appropriate approach to her management would be an empirical 3-day course of trimethoprim 200 mg twice daily. An alternative is nitrofurantoin. Culture results can then be used to guide treatment if resistance to the likely E. coli pathogen is present."},{"id":"17400","category":"Medicine in the elderly","stem":"A 70-year-old man presents with bradykinesia, tremor, and rigidity. Power is retained in all of the patient’s muscle groups. The patient’s family reports that he has recently been complaining of seeing objects which are not physically present. His memory also appears to be impaired, as evidenced by a reduced mini-mental score (18) done today. On examination, the patient has a short-stepped shuffling gait.\n\nWhat is the most likely diagnosis?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"The presence of typical Parkinsonian features along with visual hallucinations points towards a likely diagnosis of Lewy body dementia. Normal pressure hydrocephalus is characterised by urinary incontinence, ataxia, and memory problems. Multi-infarct dementia is characterised by stepwise deterioration in memory with a background history of cerebrovascular disease. Multiple sclerosis usually begins at an early age with symptoms disseminated in time and space (neurological deficits occurring at different points in time and localising to different segments of the central nervous system, producing different symptoms and signs). Cerebellar syndrome is characterised by cerebellar ataxia, hypotonia, nystagmus, and dysdiadochokinesia."},{"id":"11421","category":"Medicine in the elderly","stem":"A 76-year-old gentleman is currently admitted to the care of the elderly ward. The ward nurse has requested an urgent review from the on-call Acute Medicine team as she has noted that the patient has progressively deteriorated in the past few hours.\n\nThe patient was diagnosed with motor neuron disease 6 months ago and is now admitted for feeding gastrostomy insertion and has been started on the tube feed 48 hours ago. His other past medical history includes chronic alcohol dependence, depression, gout, and hypertension. Before the diagnosis of motor neuron disease, the patient was living alone after his wife had died 1 year previously and only recently moved to live in a residential home.\n\nOn examination, the patient is noted to be agitated and confused. He has a body mass index of 16 kg/m2 (normal 19-25 kg/m2), a pulse rate of 120/minute, blood pressure of 140/80 mmHg, respiratory rate is 20/minute, oxygen saturation on air is 93% and temperature is 37oC. Capillary refill time is 2 seconds. Jugular venous pressure is elevated 3cm above the sternal notch. Bilateral pitting leg oedema is present.\n\nA respiratory examination reveals crepitations in the lung bases. A cardiovascular system reveals normal heart sounds; tachycardic.\n\nThe patient’s abdomen is soft, and there is mild erythema and tenderness around the gastrostomy wound site.\n\nInvestigations reveal:\n\nWhat is the likely cause of the patient’s current clinical deterioration?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","The patient’s abdomen is soft, and there is mild erythema and tenderness around the gastrostomy wound site.","Investigations reveal:","What is the likely cause of the patient’s current clinical deterioration?","Acute hepatitis and CCF are consequences of refeeding syndrome rather than the precipitating cause in this patient.","The normal leucocyte count, ESR, and CRP are against a diagnosis of sepsis; aspiration does not explain the electrolyte abnormalities seen in this patient.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"This is a case of refeeding syndrome due to sudden high-caloric supplementation in a chronically malnourished patient (anabolic shift). This patient probably has had long-standing protein-energy malnutrition due to his social circumstances, depression, chronic alcohol usage, and probable dysphagia due to motor neuron disease. The abrupt introduction of high-calorie carbohydrate-rich nutritional supplementation in such patients can cause a wide range of abnormalities, including fluid and sodium retention, and electrolyte shifts, causing hypokalaemia, hypophosphataemia, and hypomagnesemia. Encephalopathy, including Wernicke’s, and oedematous states with congestive cardiac failure (CCF) and liver involvement, are well-recognised features of refeeding syndrome."},{"id":"10799","category":"Medicine in the elderly","stem":"A 79-year-old man from a nursing home is admitted with a 5-day history of abdominal distention and pain. He has a background history of cognitive impairment, a previous stroke, type-2 diabetes and hypertension. On examination, his abdomen is distended, with mild diffuse tenderness with sluggish bowel sounds. His observations are as follows:\n\nHis abdominal x-ray shows diffuse colonic distention with a caecal diameter of 7cm. Per rectal examination shows an empty rectum. His laboratory results are as follows:\n\nHe is managed conservatively with intravenous fluids, kept nil by mouth and potassium replacement. His repeat X-ray after 48 hours shows a caecal diameter of 9cm. CT abdomen has excluded mechanical obstruction and perforation.\n\nWhat is the next step in the management of this patient?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"facilitating smooth muscle contractions","explanation":"This elderly patient has likely got acute pseudo-obstruction (also referred to as Ogilvie’s syndrome), which is characterised by diffuse colonic dilatation in the absence of mechanical obstruction. This typically is more severe on the right side, mainly the caecum, although the colonic dilatation may extend to the rectum. Risk factors for acute pseudo-obstruction include hospitalised patients, post-operative state, institutionalised patients, presence of multiple co-morbidities and certain medications. There is a 3% risk of spontaneous colonic perforation, and associated with high mortality. Nasogastric suction or decompression can be helpful; furthermore, rectal tube decompression can be therapeutic in some cases and if fails neostigmine can be tried. Neostigmine is a cholinesterase inhibitor that enhances the availability of acetylcholine at neuro-neuronal synapses in the enteric nervous system and at the neuromuscular junction, thus facilitating smooth muscle contractions. Neostigmine has been shown in randomised controlled trials to have an initial response rate of 60% to 90% in patients with acute pseudo-obstruction and should be tried before endoscopic decompression."},{"id":"11420","category":"Medicine in the elderly","stem":"A 75-year-old woman has been experiencing lower back pain, low-grade fever, and fatigue for the past 3 weeks; the lower back pain has been especially worse at night. Her past medical history includes a bicuspid aortic valve, type 2 diabetes mellitus, right hip hemiarthroplasty after fracture neck of the femur, and hypertension.\n\nHer general practitioner has been prescribing her paracetamol and has arranged for some blood tests.\n\nShe now presents with acute severe worsening of her back pain and is noted to have paraparesis with urinary incontinence on clinical examination.\n\nOn examination, she is alert and oriented, with a pulse rate of 75/minute, blood pressure is 120/80 mmHg, respiratory rate is 12/minute, oxygen saturation on air is 99%, and temperature is 37.5oC.\n\nA respiratory system examination reveals normal breath sounds on both sides, and a cardiovascular system examination reveals normal heart sounds.\n\nNeurological exam: normal upper limb exam; bilateral 3/5 muscle power in both lower limbs with sluggish deep tendon reflexes and absent plantar reflexes.\n\nThere was urinary retention on arrival, and the patient is now catheterised.\n\nInvestigation available in the electronic medical record:\n\nWhat is the likely cause of her paraparesis?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Her general practitioner has been prescribing her paracetamol and has arranged for some blood tests.","There was urinary retention on arrival, and the patient is now catheterised.","Investigation available in the electronic medical record:","What is the likely cause of her paraparesis?","Spinal infarction is unlikely given the typical laboratory features and the insidious back pain and constitutional symptoms.","Epidural abscess/infective endocarditis and GBS are unlikely given the typical laboratory features of myeloma.","Vertebral fracture does not explain the constitutional symptoms and the abnormal laboratory values.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"This patient has a concerning history of low back pain, which is worse at night, along with constitutional symptoms. Her acute presentation with paraparesis is due to a spinal pathology, and the investigations show mild pancytopenia, raised ESR, normal alkaline phosphatase, hyperglobulinemia, mild hypercalcemia and renal impairment, which are all very suggestive of multiple myeloma; this is a medical emergency."},{"id":"11961","category":"Medicine in the elderly","stem":"An 87-year-old woman has been referred to ambulatory emergency care (AEC) for assessment due to bilateral mild ankle oedema that has been ongoing for the last year. The swelling is not worsening, and its presence is variable throughout the day. The patient is concerned about what causes this oedema and how to treat it. Her NT pro-BNP was normal when checked by her GP, and her bedside-focused echocardiography in the AEC was unremarkable. Her blood tests were also unremarkable.\n\nOn examination, there was no evidence of varicose veins, and she had mild ankle oedema with a normal general examination. She was on regular metformin for diabetes. You diagnosed her as a possible case of gravitational oedema, and you have explained this to the patient.\n\nWhat is the most appropriate management plan?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"Diuretics are overprescribed in the elderly and should not be prescribed for simple gravitational oedema unless it is for a short time. Increasing activity, leg raising, and support stockings are usually effective. Decreasing total salt may be helpful as well."},{"id":"3765","category":"Medicine in the elderly","stem":"A 70-year-old woman presents to the A&E Department with severe, sudden-onset vertigo. This episode developed over the period of an hour, and now she is unable to stand and feels nauseous. She does not complain of any recent illness, nor tinnitus or hearing loss. She has had no similar episodes previously.\n\nNeurological examination is unremarkable other than a horizontal beat nystagmus to the right. Her gait is markedly unsteady on standing.\n\nShe has a history of hypertension and had a previous cardioversion for atrial fibrillation 15 years ago, following an episode of pneumonia. She is currently taking Ramipril 5 mg once daily for hypertension, with her blood pressure being 124/79 mmHg, and she is in sinus rhythm.\n\nA CT scan of the head is reported as unremarkable, and so are subsequent CT- A and MR-DWI.\n\nShe is adamant she needs to return home as soon as possible, as she is the carer for her brother, who has advanced Parkinson’s disease.\n\nWhat is the next appropriate treatment?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"The patient has likely vestibular neuritis, which can cause rapid onset vertigo with no hearing loss or tinnitus, which are often features of Labyrinthitis. Posterior circulation stroke was excluded on imaging."},{"id":"11414","category":"Medicine in the elderly","stem":"An 85-year-old woman with a past medical history of hypertension, peripheral arterial disease, chronic obstructive pulmonary disease, and hypercholesterolemia is admitted to the Acute Medical Unit. She had developed a sudden-onset sharp upper back pain while she was watching television, associated with profuse sweating; she now has difficulty moving both legs with loss of sensation and is unable to pass urine since the weakness. She says she has been independent and self-caring until now. Her medications include amlodipine, ramipril, salbutamol inhaler as required, Seretide (salmeterol + fluticasone) inhaler, aspirin, and simvastatin; she was also given a 3-day course of ciprofloxacin for a suspected urinary tract infection by her general practitioner 1 week previously.\n\nOn examination, she is alert and well-oriented to time, place, and person. She has a pulse rate of 50/min regular, and her blood pressure is 90/60 mmHg.\n\nAn examination of her respiratory system reveals reduced air entry in both lung bases with scattered expiratory wheezes. A cardiovascular system examination reveals normal heart sounds.\n\nA neurological examination reveals normal speech comprehension and articulation. The patient has normal muscle power, tone, reflexes, and sensation in both upper limbs, flaccid paralysis of both lower limbs (muscle power proximally and distally 2/5), and absent deep tendon reflexes and plantar reflexes. There is bilateral loss of pain and temperature sensation with preserved fine touch, vibratory sense and proprioception; sensory level is noted at the T12 level.\n\nWhat is the diagnosis?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"The sudden onset of paraparesis is suggestive of a vascular event; the preceding upper back pain of sudden onset with diaphoresis is due to aortic dissection, which led to thrombosis of the anterior spinal artery with infarction of the anterior two-thirds of the spinal cord, with the classical clinical features. The patient has a history of atherosclerotic disease and has also been recently exposed to fluoroquinolone, which has been associated with aortic dissections."},{"id":"17399","category":"Medicine in the elderly","stem":"An 80-year-old man presented with progressive cognitive decline, and a diagnosis of moderate Alzheimer's disease was made. The patient is currently taking tamsulosin for benign prostatic hyperplasia (BPH) and has a history of angle-closure glaucoma.\n\nWhich one of the following medications can be added to reduce his progressive cognitive decline?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"memantine","explanation":"The correct answer is memantine, as this has been shown to reduce the rate of cognitive decline in Alzheimer's disease. Galantamine, rivastigmine, and donepezil are all acetylcholine esterase inhibitors, and they all increase the level of acetylcholine, resulting in increased parasympathetic activity. They are contraindicated because of this patient’s previous history of benign prostatic hyperplasia and angle-closure glaucoma, as they will worsen both these medical conditions. Aspirin is indicated for multi-infarct dementia and, as such, will not be effective in reducing the rate of cognitive decline as asked in this question."},{"id":"13637","category":"Medicine in the elderly","stem":"An 85-year-old man who has a past medical history of type 2 diabetes mellitus, hypertension, chronic kidney disease stage 1, and mild senile dementia is admitted to the acute medicine unit with acute confusion. He recently underwent a dental procedure and was given oral co-amoxiclav, paracetamol, lorazepam, and omeprazole for a few days. His regular medications are gliclazide 80 mg once daily, metformin 500 mg twice daily, telmisartan 80 mg once daily, bisoprolol 5 mg once daily, and 1 calcium tablet a day. Before the procedure, he says he was independently mobile and self-caring, requiring no support services.\n\nOn examination, the patient is alert but disoriented to time, place, and person. He has a pulse rate of 75 beats per minute and a blood pressure of 170/80 mmHg. His respiratory rate is 12 breaths per minute, and his oxygen saturation on air is 99%. Temperature is 37oC, and jugular venous pressure is not elevated. Capillary blood glucose is 7.7 mmol/L (4-7.7 mmol/L).\n\nHe has no leg oedema. An examination of the respiratory system revealed normal breath sounds on both sides.\n\nA cardiovascular system examination reveals normal heart sounds. His abdomen is soft, with no tenderness, and there are active bowel sounds.\n\nA central nervous system examination shows normal tone, power, reflexes, and sensation in all 4 limbs, with normal cranial nerves.\n\nInvestigations reveal the following results:\n\nThe patient's chest X-ray is normal.\n\nWhat is the most likely cause of this patient’s delirium?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Investigations reveal the following results:","Urine analysis","The patient's chest X-ray is normal.","What is the most likely cause of this patient’s delirium?","The absence of fever, normal leucocyte count, normal ESR, normal CRP, normal urine routine, and normal chest x-ray are against a diagnosis of infection and sepsis.","TIA is unlikely to present in this manner.","Euglycaemic DKA is also unlikely given this patient’s normal bicarbonate and the absence of urine ketones.","PE is unlikely given normal respiratory rate, pulse rate and oxygen saturations.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"What is the most likely cause of this patient’s delirium?","explanation":"This patient, who has been relatively well and independent until this dental procedure, most likely has drug-induced delirium. Benzodiazepines are known to cause delirium, and these drugs are the most likely cause in this patient."},{"id":"6922","category":"Medicine in the elderly","stem":"An 87-year-old woman presents to you with symptoms of dizziness, which developed a few weeks ago. She finds the symptoms very difficult to describe, but she states she feels very unstable, and it is hard to maintain her balance. These episodes occur on sudden standing and on movement, especially on looking upwards and bending over. She says she feels nauseous during the episodes, which last around a minute, although she feels lightheaded for up to a few hours after the event. She has fallen when getting out of bed and when out shopping in the past week.\n\nShe has a history of hypertension and ischaemic heart disease and is on bisoprolol, ramipril, and clopidogrel.\n\nOn examination, she has a lying blood pressure of 118/78 mmHg and a resting heart rate of 70 beats per minute (sinus rhythm). Her standing blood pressure is 115/75 mmHg immediately and 120/82 mmHg after 3 minutes of standing, and her heart rate remains stable at 70 bpm throughout the examination. She has no obvious focal neurology when reclining on an examination bench, and examination of the cranial nerves is normal.\n\nExamination of her cardiovascular, respiratory and abdominal systems is unremarkable.\n\nWhat is the most likely diagnosis?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","The patient is complaining of dizziness with specific movements of her head; these can include looking upwards, turning in bed or bending over.","Hearing loss and tinnitus are not features of benign paroxysmal vertigo (unless pre-existing).","Beneath is a video of this test:","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"The patient is complaining of dizziness with specific movements of her head; these can include looking upwards, turning in bed or bending over.","explanation":"The patient is complaining of dizziness with specific movements of her head; these can include looking upwards, turning in bed or bending over."},{"id":"10797","category":"Medicine in the elderly","stem":"A 68-year-old man presents to the emergency room with an acute onset of paraparesis and distal paresthesias. An examination reveals hypotonia and reduced reflexes in both the lower limbs. There is no sensory level, and Babinski’s sign is absent. He is afebrile with no bowel or bladder involvement. He has no similar medical history.\n\nA lumbar puncture is performed, and the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) findings are as follows:\n\nWhat is the most likely diagnosis?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","In addition to this, there is no Babinski’s sign, sensory involvement, nor any sensory level, which excludes myelopathy.","There is no significant previous history or any other risk factors, which rule out multiple sclerosis and acute vascular events.","CSF analysis reveals characteristic cyto-albumino dissociation.","The treatment of choice for GBS is IV immunoglobulins and plasmapheresis.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"This is a case of Guillain-Barré syndrome: AIDP variant. This patient presented with an acute onset, bilaterally symmetrical flaccid paralysis with no bowel or bladder involvement and no fever. All these features suggest a diagnosis of GBS (as per Asbury criteria)."},{"id":"13717","category":"Medicine in the elderly","stem":"A 94-year-old woman was brought to the emergency department after being found on the floor at home. She had a history of hypertension and atrial fibrillation (AF) and was taking warfarin.\n\nOn examination, her Glasgow Coma Scale (GCS) was 13/15, and she had a power of 3/5 in her left arm and leg. Her CT head showed a large right subdural haematoma.\n\nWhat is the most appropriate treatment?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","The patient has a large acute subdural haematoma. This is a life-threatening emergency, and the priority is to reverse the effect of warfarin.","Recommendations from the British Journal of Haematology are as follows:","Major Bleeding On warfarin (life-threatening, limb or sight-threatening (intraocular, not sub-conjunctival) haemorrhage on warfarin)","Stop warfarin, check INR, FBC, LFTs and give 5–10 mg vitamin K IV over 2–3 min. Emergency anticoagulation reversal in major bleeding should be with 25–50 U/kg four-factor PCC (1B).","Less severe haemorrhage on warfarin","Withhold warfarin for 1 or more days and re-start at a reduced dose when INR <5.0. Consider vitamin K 1–2 mg IV/PO.","In surgery requiring reversal of warfarin that can be delayed for 6–12 hours, INR can be corrected with intravenous vitamin K.","Emergency surgery and warfarin","For surgery requiring reversal of warfarin but that cannot be delayed, meaning vitamin K does not have time to take effect, then giving PCC and intravenous vitamin K can help correct INR.","PCC, however, should not be used to enable elective or non-urgent surgery (2C).","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"The patient has a large acute subdural haematoma. This is a life-threatening emergency, and the priority is to reverse the effect of warfarin.","explanation":"The patient has a large acute subdural haematoma. This is a life-threatening emergency, and the priority is to reverse the effect of warfarin."},{"id":"17263","category":"Medicine in the elderly","stem":"A 69-year-old woman was brought to the hospital via ambulance services due to agitation and confusion, and her sister was finding it difficult to manage her at home. The patient was unable to provide a history, and the sister reports that the patient is acting differently from her usual self and that she has become more agitated in the last 24 hours. Roughly a year ago, the sister noticed that the patient had occasionally forgotten certain things in her daily life, such as where she left her keys or if the front door was closed. More recently, however, the episodes have become more frequent, and the patient cannot remember what she has done in the morning or whether she has eaten.\n\nWhat should you do as initial management in this case?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"Delirium and dementia are two separate identities, and delirium is commonly superimposed on pre-existing dementia, which seems likely in this patient with potential underlying dementia. This is a long-term condition that can be assessed in primary care and referred to the memory clinic for further investigations. Depression is common in older people with frailty and should be considered an important differential diagnosis for dementia and hypoactive delirium; however, treatment with antidepressants is not routinely prescribed, nor are they indicated in acute episodes of delirium. Investigations with blood tests and brain imaging are relevant for dementia screening, which not only helps to rule out secondary causes of acute confusion and potentially reversible causes of dementia. However, in delirious patients, an MRI scan of the brain is also not indicated and can be challenging to perform in acute episodes. Lumbar puncture is not indicated unless an acute cerebral nervous system infection is suspected in cases of acute confusion. In summary, this patient should get a 4-AT assessment for her delirium and be admitted to the hospital to investigate the cause of her acute confusion. Once improved at baseline, her dementia can be assessed."},{"id":"10273","category":"Medicine in the elderly","stem":"A 72-year-old man was admitted with a painful, swollen left knee for the last 36 hours. He has been well recently but reported increased alcohol consumption before his acute illness.\n\nHe has a past medical history of type-2 diabetes, atrial fibrillation, dyslipidaemia, gout, stage 5 of chronic kidney disease, hypertension and previous bleeding gastric ulcers (2 years ago). His medication list included: linagliptin 5mg od, Humulin I 30 units sc once daily, simvastatin 40 mg once daily, omeprazole 20 mg once daily, warfarin as per international normalised ratio, allopurinol 100 mg once daily, doxazosin 4 mg twice daily, PRN paracetamol.\n\nHis admission observations were:\n\nTemperature 37.4oC\nRespiratory rate 20/min\nBlood pressure 150/90 mmHg\nHeart rate 105 beats per minute\nSats 100% room air (RA).\n\nHis admission blood tests were as follows:\n\nOn examination, the left knee was red, swollen, and tender to the touch with a limited range of movements noted.\n\nThe knee aspirate was sent off, which showed cloudy yellow fluid; WBC 3000 cells/mm3, neut>50% Gram stain negative; no organism seen; needle negative birefringent crystals noted.\n\nWhat is the most appropriate treatment option?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","A 72-year-old man was admitted with a painful, swollen left knee for the last 36 hours. He has been well recently but reported increased alcohol consumption before his acute illness.","His admission observations were:","His admission blood tests were as follows:","What is the most appropriate treatment option?","Acute gout can be managed pharmacologically with:","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"Acute gout can be managed pharmacologically with:","explanation":"Acute gout can be managed pharmacologically with:"},{"id":"18708","category":"Medicine in the elderly","stem":"A 72-year-old woman was brought to the emergency department resuscitation room by ambulance crew with a history of sudden-onset confusion and shortness of breath following a 3-day history of fever, sore throat, and lethargy. There is no chest pain.\n\nOn examination, the patient looks unwell, febrile (39.1oC), has mottled skin, has no pedal oedema, and is in control of her airway. Her breathing is laboured; she has a respiratory rate of 36 cycles per minute, with oxygen saturation of 84% on room air but up to 94% on 10 litres per minute of oxygen via face mask. There is a resonant percussion note throughout the chest. On auscultation, there were bibasilar crackles. She has a blood pressure of 177/77 mmHg, a heart rate of 134 beats per minute, and her ECG showed T-wave inversion.\n\nWhat is the most appropriate first investigation to aid your diagnosis?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","What is the most appropriate first investigation to aid your diagnosis?","This scenario can cause a diagnostic conundrum. The patient presented with respiratory symptoms that may be suggestive of acute pulmonary oedema or sepsis secondary to a chest infection.","All the investigations would be important to do in the management of this patient. However, a chest X-ray would be most appropriate to narrow down a diagnosis.","Blood culture would help in determining definitive treatment and the possible diagnosis. However, the results from a blood culture will not be available until much later.","A full blood count can help in diagnosing sepsis, but it cannot tell the focus (affected body system), and this will not help in ruling out pulmonary oedema.","Electrolytes, urea, and creatinine (renal function) can help in the overall management, but cannot assist in making the actual diagnosis.","RCEMLearning - Cardiogenic pulmonary oedema.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"This scenario can cause a diagnostic conundrum. The patient presented with respiratory symptoms that may be suggestive of acute pulmonary oedema or sepsis secondary to a chest infection.","explanation":"This scenario can cause a diagnostic conundrum. The patient presented with respiratory symptoms that may be suggestive of acute pulmonary oedema or sepsis secondary to a chest infection."},{"id":"3766","category":"Medicine in the elderly","stem":"A 78-year-old man with a history of Parkinson’s disease presents after his relatives became concerned as he had become increasingly confused and had been shaking uncontrollably at times.\n\nOn examination, the patient was drowsy, with increased rigidity in the limbs; pupils were normal. He had a noticeable tremor. Examination of the chest showed a right basal pneumonia, and the chest x-ray confirmed a right basal pneumonia.\n\nOf significance in the investigations:\n\nYou read from his letters on the portal that bloods taken in the Parkinson’s disease clinic 6 days previously had been in the normal range. His Levodopa dose had been increased due to increased rigidity from Sinemet 25/100 one tablet three times daily to 50/100 morning and evening, and 25/100 midday.\n\nRegarding his movement disorder, which treatment is the most appropriate?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","The patient has features consistent with an acute hyperkinetic disorder. This is likely precipitated by increased Levodopa dose, and potentiated by community-acquired pneumonia.","Continued dyskinetic movements can cause exhaustion, dehydration, trauma and rhabdomyolysis.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"The patient has features consistent with an acute hyperkinetic disorder. This is likely precipitated by increased Levodopa dose, and potentiated by community-acquired pneumonia.","explanation":"The patient has features consistent with an acute hyperkinetic disorder. This is likely precipitated by increased Levodopa dose, and potentiated by community-acquired pneumonia."},{"id":"4222","category":"Medicine in the elderly","stem":"An 80-year-old woman was admitted to A&E following a collapse in church. She had a medical history of hypertension maintained on ramipril, amlodipine and atenolol. She also takes aspirin 75 mg daily as she had a TIA in the past. She is usually independent and lives with her husband, who is in good health for his age. Six months ago, she recalls a similar episode whilst waiting at the bus stop on a hot day.\n\nShe recalled standing still during the church service and feeling light-headed and nauseous around the time of the collapse. She believes she blacked out. Witnesses observed her to jerk as she hit the floor, but she was alert and able to speak coherently within minutes of the event.\n\nAssessment revealed a bump on her brow, but her neurological, cardiovascular and systems examinations were otherwise unremarkable. Her GCS was 15. Her ECG revealed sinus rhythm with a heart rate of 50 beats per minute, and her blood pressure was recorded as 110/70 mmHg with no postural drop. Her routine bloods were satisfactory, as was a CT of her head. ECG reveals sinus rhythm with a rate of 50/min.\n\nWhat do you believe is the most appropriate management aside from stopping the atenolol?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"The history here is typical of a vasovagal collapse (vagal symptoms- low BP and Heart rate; lightheadedness and nausea) and does not suggest cardiac syncope (typically no warning symptoms often associated with significant injuries). In addition, her low BP and bradycardia are contributing to her susceptibility to fainting and are probably related to the beta-blockade. Hence, stopping the beta-blocker is appropriate. Because she has bradycardia, she may be experiencing pauses in her heart rhythm that contribute to her falls. A 24-hour Holter monitor, particularly after stopping atenolol, would be a reasonable option if the bradycardia persists."},{"id":"14115","category":"Musculoskeletal system","stem":"A 36-year-old woman is admitted to the acute medicine unit with breathlessness and generalised body swelling. She has been experiencing joint pains on and off in both her hands and wrists for the past month. Her past medical history is otherwise unremarkable.\n\nOn examination, the patient is alert and oriented. She has a pulse rate of 120 beats per minute and a blood pressure of 140/80 mmHg. Her respiratory rate is 29 breaths per minute with oxygen saturation on air of 94%. She has a temperature of 37.0oC.\n\nShe has a capillary refill time of 2 seconds. Jugular venous pressure is not elevated. Gross pitting oedema of all 4 limbs and the abdominal wall is noted, and facial oedema is also noted. Respiratory system examination reveals reduced breath sounds on both bases. Her cardiovascular system examination reveals normal heart sounds. The abdomen is soft with no tenderness, and there are active bowel sounds.\n\nOn central nervous system (CNS) examination, no focal neurological deficits were noted; no features of meningism were noted.\n\nMusculoskeletal examination reveals tenderness bilaterally in the proximal interphalangeal joints, metacarpophalangeal joints, wrists, and elbows.\n\nSkin examination reveals a butterfly-shaped rash noted over the cheeks.\n\nInvestigations results are as follows:\n\nWhat is the most likely diagnosis?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Investigations results are as follows:","What is the most likely diagnosis?","Idiopathic nephrotic syndrome is unlikely given the presence of SLE features.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"This patient has nephrotic range albuminuria, causing hypoalbuminaemia and a clinical picture of anasarca. The pleural effusion and ascites are secondary to the hypoalbuminaemic state. She has symmetric small and large joint polyarthritis, malar rash, pancytopaenia, and raised ESR with normal CRP, which suggests systemic lupus erythematosus (SLE). Lupus nephritis usually presents as a nephritic syndrome (hypertension, acute kidney injury, active urine sediments with RBC casts) but can also present as a nephrotic syndrome (type V lupus nephritis (LN)). This patient’s presentation is consistent with type V LN."},{"id":"17489","category":"Musculoskeletal system","stem":"A 70-year-old Caucasian man presents to the emergency department with an acute onset of severe headache of a one-hour duration. The patient also gives a history of both upper limb pain and stiffness for the past few weeks associated with malaise. On examination, the patient has temporal artery tenderness. His neurological examination was unremarkable.\n\nInvestigations revealed the following results:\n\nWhat is the recommended immediate intervention to start the patient on?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","The dose, duration and route of administration of steroids depend on whether the patient has associated blindness.","Unwin B, Williams CM, Gilliland W. Polymyalgia rheumatica and giant cell arteritis. Am Fam Physician. 2006 Nov 1;74(9):1547-54. PMID: 17111894.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"The dose, duration and route of administration of steroids depend on whether the patient has associated blindness.","explanation":"Polymyalgia rheumatica (PMR) is a clinical condition seen in elderly male patients. Clinical presentation includes shoulder muscle stiffness and pain, and it is also associated with fever, malaise, and weakness. Patients with PMR can also be associated with giant cell arteritis (GCA), where there can be involvement of the temporal artery, leading to blindness on one side. The treatment of PMR depends on whether it is associated with Giant cell arteritis or not."},{"id":"3489","category":"Musculoskeletal system","stem":"A 71-year-old woman with a 10-year history of type-2 diabetes presents to the accident and emergency department with severe intermittent right-sided abdominal pains. There is a long history of arthralgia over many years, together with fatigue and Raynaud's phenomenon.\n\nHer only medications include Metformin 1g twice daily and furosemide 40 mg for mild heart failure. Examination confirms a respiratory rate of 20 breaths per minute, pulse of 90 beats per minute, blood pressure of 110/78 mmHg, and there is abdominal tenderness over the right flank.\n\nInvestigation results are as follows:\n\nUrine dipstick : Blood 3+, ph 5.8, glucose 1+\nChest X-Ray- Clear\n\nWhat is the most likely diagnosis?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","The positive RF, SSA/ Ro, and SSB/ La are seen in Sjogren's and clinical symptoms may be longstanding before presentation. A marked polyclonal rise in IgG is also seen in active Sjogren's syndrome.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"This patient has symptoms and signs suggesting renal colic. Nephrocalcinosis is a recognised feature of hypercalciuria. The distal renal tubules are deficient in excreting H+ ions from the distal tubules. Hypokalaemia may also present as muscle weakness/hypokalaemic paralysis."},{"id":"3479","category":"Musculoskeletal system","stem":"A 78-year-old man with gout, hypertension, and renal impairment is admitted to the acute medical ward with increasing proximal muscle weakness over the last 4 weeks. His current medication is allopurinol 200 mg per day, colchicine 500 mcg twice daily, atenolol 50 mg, and enalapril 10 mg. Examination reveals MRC grade 4/5 power in the proximal muscle groups of both upper and lower limbs and small gouty tophi on both elbows.\n\nInvestigations reveal the following:\n\nEMGs - Myopathic changes of proximal muscle groups.\n\nWhat is the most likely diagnosis?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"Colchicine myopathy is characterised by proximal weakness and elevation of creatine kinase, proximal myopathic changes on electromyography, and axonal polyneuropathy on nerve conduction studies. It is characteristically seen in patients with renal impairment but has rarely been described in patients with normal renal function. Muscle biopsy demonstrates vacuolar myopathy and would be the next investigation of choice for this patient. Treatment consists of drug withdrawal, and it may take some months for muscle power to return and the CK to normalise."},{"id":"3462","category":"Musculoskeletal system","stem":"A 66-year-old woman with a 20-year history of seropositive erosive rheumatoid arthritis presents with a two-week history of deteriorating weakness and neck pain. She has noticed neck pain and a sensation that her head is slumping forward. Her arms and legs feel generally weak, and she has complained of urinary hesitancy and constipation in the past week.\n\nClinical examination reveals painful, restricted neck movements. Tone is increased in the upper and lower limbs. There is proximal weakness graded 4/5 on shoulder abduction and hip flexion bilaterally. Biceps and knee jerk reflexes are bilaterally brisk.\n\nWhat is the most appropriate investigation?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"Atlanto-axial instability affects between 12 and 33% of patients with rheumatoid arthritis 1-3. Assessing the atlantoaxial joint requires cervical spine radiographs in flexion and extension in the first instance, followed by magnetic resonance imaging of the cervical portion of the spinal cord4. An urgent spinal and neurosurgical opinion should be sought."},{"id":"16828","category":"Musculoskeletal system","stem":"A 75-year-old man presented with a 9-month history of progressive lower back pain. The pain radiated from the lower back to both calves and was worsened by walking; he was able to walk approximately 100 metres before the pain occurred, and he found that stopping and resting relieved the pain, allowing him to resume walking until the pain occurred again.\n\nOn examination, an extension of the lumbar spine reproduced the symptoms.\n\nWhat is the most appropriate investigation to confirm the diagnosis?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","It is important to note that these symptoms can be mistaken for a different condition, vascular claudication.","While X-ray and CT scans can provide useful information, false positive and false negative CT scan results may occur.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"Lumbar canal stenosis is characterised by symptoms such as numbness, weakness, and tingling in one or both legs. This condition, known as neurogenic claudication, is often relieved by bending or flexing the lower back, such as sitting down."},{"id":"3477","category":"Musculoskeletal system","stem":"A 69-year-old woman has been seen in the rheumatology clinic for several months with polyarthralgia and mild weight loss. Her GP has requested admission as she has lost a further stone in the last month and is suffering from fevers and a cough productive of rusty sputum.\n\nHer investigations are as follows:\n\nChest x-ray shows diffuse patchy shadowing at both bases.\n\nYou arrange pulmonary function tests.\n\nWhich of the following are Pulmonary Function Tests most likely to show?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"This woman is likely to have developed a degree of alveolar haemorrhage secondary to her ANCA-positive vasculitis. Although over time, recurrent alveolar haemorrhage can lead to fibrosis and a reduced transfer factor, acutely, the presence of haemoglobin in the airways increases the DLCO."},{"id":"3461","category":"Musculoskeletal system","stem":"A 50-year-old housewife presents with a 3-month history of myalgia, fatigue, and ‘aching all over’. She is a non-smoker and not taking any medications. On examination, her BMI is 31 kg/m2 and she has some weakness in shoulder abduction bilaterally with some difficulty in rising from a chair.\n\nInvestigation results are as follows:\n\nWhat is the most likely diagnosis?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","It is unlikely that such a mild CK rise would be associated with inflammatory myositis, and fibromyalgia would not fit with the abnormal investigation pattern seen.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"This patient has a lot of non-specific symptoms. The myalgia, fatigue and a raised BMI suggest weight gain and mild proximal myopathy. The raised MCV and hypertriglyceridaemia are associated features, including mildly raised CK, AST, and LDH due to abnormal muscle membranes."},{"id":"17088","category":"Musculoskeletal system","stem":"A 65-year-old man with a background history of morbid obesity, hypertension, heart failure with severe left ventricular dysfunction, CKD stage 3, and type-2 diabetes mellitus, was admitted with a swollen and painful right knee joint of 3 days duration. His home medications include amlodipine 5 mg once a day, ramipril 2.5 mg once a day, gliclazide 80 mg twice a day, bisoprolol 1.25 mg once a day, bumetanide 3 mg twice a day, metolazone 2.5 mg on alternate days, allopurinol 300 mg twice a day, and sodium bicarbonate 1000 mg twice a day. He is a smoker with a 20-pack-year history and drinks alcohol in moderation.\n\nOn examination, he was morbidly obese with a heart rate of 72 beats per minute, regular. His blood pressure was 123/67 mmHg, respiratory rate was 17 breaths per minute, SaO2 was 92% on room air, and his temperature was 38oC. Systemic examination revealed bilateral leg oedema up to the knees and a swollen right knee, which is warm and tender with effusion. There were reduced breath sounds at the lung bases, jugular venous pressure (JVP) was not raised, and the rest of the examination was unremarkable. He was empirically started on intravenous flucloxacillin 2g four times a day for possible septic arthritis while synovial fluid was sent for analysis.\n\nInvestigations showed the following results:\n\nWhat is the next best step in the management of this patient?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Investigations showed the following results:","What is the next best step in the management of this patient?","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"Hot, swollen joints should be treated as septic arthritis until proven otherwise. So, starting intravenous flucloxacillin empirically was the right step, along with the synovial fluid sent for analysis. The synovial fluid analysis here is indicative of inflammatory arthropathy, and the presence of uric acid crystals is suggestive of gouty arthritis. The first line of treatment for an acute gout attack is colchicine, with a dose range from 500 micrograms twice a day to four times a day. Colchicine is contraindicated if eGFR is < 10 and the dose should be reduced if eGFR is 10 – 50. Urate-lowering agents (ULAs), allopurinol, in this case, should be continued during an acute attack with the aim of bringing target uric levels below 300 microgram/L/L. The dose of allopurinol ranges from 300 mg to 900 mg per day. As the uric acid levels are within the target range, increasing the dose of allopurinol or adding another ULA is not indicated. IV flucloxacillin can be stopped as this is not a case of septic arthritis, and low-grade temperature and raised inflammatory markers are quite common in gouty attacks as signs of the inflammation process. Diuretics (mainly thiazide diuretics like metolazone) can cause hyperuricaemia, and if possible, should be stopped. However, if prescribed for heart failure which cannot be managed without diuretics (like in this case, as indicated by a high dose of bumetanide, metolazone, and end-stage heart failure), diuretics should be continued."},{"id":"17402","category":"Musculoskeletal system","stem":"A 35-year-old woman presents with a 6-month history of symmetrical polyarthritis, malar rash on the face in butterfly distribution, along with photosensitivity on exposure to sunlight; she also has oral ulcers. She also complains of difficulty breathing along with non-specific chest pain.\n\nOn physical examination of her chest, she has reduced breath sounds on both lung bases along with dullness to percussion, and auscultation of the front of the chest also reveals a pericardial rub. Her saturation on room air is 90 per cent (normal SpO2 > 92 per cent). She has been started on supplemental oxygen, and a chest X-ray was done, which reveals borderline cardiomegaly along with bilateral pleural effusions.\n\nWhat is the most likely diagnosis?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"This patient’s history is typical of systemic lupus erythematosus as evidenced by the cutaneous symptoms and bilateral symmetrical polyarthritis. The hypoxemia is attributable to bilateral pleural effusions, likely due to lupus pleuritis. The non-specific chest pain, cardiomegaly, and pericardial rub point towards a likely pericardial effusion, which can be confirmed on a 2D echocardiogram. Rheumatoid arthritis is not associated with cutaneous features. MCTD has mixed features of other autoimmune diseases. Systemic sclerosis is associated with skin tightening, Raynaud's, sclerodactyly, oesophageal dysmotility, calcinosis, and polymyositis is associated with painful proximal muscle weakness."},{"id":"3491","category":"Musculoskeletal system","stem":"A 38-year-old Russian woman attends the emergency department with pain in her right knee on a background of rheumatoid arthritis. Her disease has responded well to sulfasalazine since she was diagnosed 4 years ago. Today, she complains of warmth, pain, and swelling of the right knee, but can bear weight. Her knee has been troublesome for the past month, and last week her GP started her on Prednisolone 7.5 mg. She has recently spent 3 months in Russia caring for her mother, who is recovering from a stroke, and the patient returned to this country 3 weeks ago. Whilst in Russia, she had an adequate supply of sulfasalazine and was able to continue her blood monitoring with a local GP. She suffered a purulent cough for approximately 1 week whilst abroad, but resolved it within 7 days. Her other joints remain quiescent. She has lost 1 stone in weight since her last clinic visit 6 months ago.\n\nClinical examination revealed a large right knee effusion with the knee held in 5 degrees of fixed flexion. The knee was not particularly warm or tender. The small joints of her hands and feet were not swollen or tender.\n\nYou proceed to aspirate the joint and 50 ml of turbid synovial fluid is withdrawn.\n\nResults of joint aspiration reveals:\n\nOther investigations show:\n\nWhich of the following investigations is most likely to yield the diagnosis?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"This woman is likely to have tuberculous arthritis of the knee. Around 80% of new cases of Mycobacterium tuberculosis (MTB) occur in sub-Saharan Africa and Asia, but the infection is increasingly seen in Eastern Europe, particularly multi-drug-resistant forms of the mycobacterium1. Typically, MTB arthritis presents with chronic monoarthritis of the knee or hip, which accounts for 85% of cases. Other joints which are less frequently involved include the shoulder, sacroiliac, elbow, ankle, and small joints of the hands and feet."},{"id":"17264","category":"Musculoskeletal system","stem":"A 66-year-old woman, with a BMI of 28 kg/m2, presented to you with bilateral knee pain of gradual onset with a history of 6 months. The patient denies any past medical history. She has started taking paracetamol 1000 mg once in the morning to help her through the day. On examination, she presents with Heberden’s nodes in both hands, and both of her knees are swollen with no erythema or change in skin temperature to touch. She has pain on active flexion but no change in mobility. With this information, your top differential diagnosis is osteoarthritis.\n\nWhich best characterises this patient’s condition?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Sen R, Hurley JA. Osteoarthritis. [Updated 2022 May 1]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2022 Jan-.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"Osteoarthritis is the most common form of arthritis and is characterised by degeneration of articular cartilage in a synovial joint. An inflammation caused by the accumulation of crystals around synovial joints is crystal arthritis, e.g. gout. Rheumatoid arthritis is an example of joint inflammation related to autoimmune dysfunction, whilst inflammation that spreads through the bloodstream is septic arthritis and a medical emergency. Cellulitis is an infection of the skin that can spread to the joints."},{"id":"3472","category":"Musculoskeletal system","stem":"A 43-year-old butcher is referred to you by her GP with malaise, worsening back pain, and stiffness over the past 8 weeks. Every 2-3 days, she has had undulating fevers, rigours, and sweats at night. She received the BCG vaccination as an adolescent and has never travelled to any areas endemic with tuberculosis. She denies sexual contact with anyone other than her husband and has never used recreational drugs. She lives with her husband and two sons, who are all well.\n\nClinical examination reveals sacroiliac tenderness on the right flexion and crossed adduction of the right hip. There is no tenderness of the left sacroiliac joint.\n\nHer cervical lymph nodes are slightly enlarged but not tender.\n\nAbdominal examination reveals splenomegaly.\n\nLumbar spine x-ray: Narrowed disc space at L3/L4 disc.\n\nL4 vertebral end plate destruction and bony sclerosis.\n\nX-ray Pelvis: normal sacroiliac joints:\n\nWhat is the most likely diagnosis?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","B.mellitensis","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"B.mellitensis","explanation":"Brucellosis is a zoonosis occurring after infection with any of the Brucella species, which include B.mellitensis (from sheep or goats), B.abortus (from cows), and B.suis (from pigs). Individuals at high risk of contracting the disease include farmers, veterinary surgeons, abattoir workers and butchers."},{"id":"3493","category":"Musculoskeletal system","stem":"A 22-year-old man with type-1 diabetes is seen on the acute medical ward with a one-week history of chest pain and localised chest wall swelling. He is a keen rower and has recently increased his training regime. His diabetes is controlled with subcutaneous insulin, although he admits his control is difficult due to his training regimen. His only current medication is topical benzoyl peroxide for facial acne.\n\nHis temperature is 38.2oC, and examination of the chest demonstrates tender swelling over the left third and fourth costochondral cartilages.\n\nInvestigations reveal:\n\nWhich of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"Infective costochondritis is most commonly seen in patients with predisposing factors to infection, such as diabetes mellitus, rheumatoid arthritis and long-term haemodialysis. Although Tietze's syndrome causes swelling and tenderness, it is not associated with fever or leucocytosis. Although this man has acne and costochondritis, he has no other features of the SAPHO (synovitis, acne, pustulosis, hyperostosis and osteomyelitis) syndrome; his facial acne is not likely to be significant as it is reasonably common in young men. Given the rapid onset, sarcoma is highly unlikely. Costochondritis is also commonly seen in athletes, particularly rowers, although this is not usually associated with swelling, fever or leucocytosis."},{"id":"12258","category":"Musculoskeletal system","stem":"A 55-year-old man with a past medical history of obesity, type 2 diabetes mellitus, chronic kidney disease stage 2, and congestive cardiac failure presents to the acute medicine unit with severe right knee swelling and pain. The patient says that the pain and swelling started gradually about a week ago, and he cannot recollect any recent trauma or injuries. He also reports having a low-grade fever with chills in the evening over the past week since the swelling started. He says he has had episodes of right great toe pain and swelling a few times in the past 12 months, which have either settled spontaneously or after taking 1 or 2 ibuprofen tablets.\n\nThe patient’s general practitioner noted that his serum uric acid was very high and advised him on a low-purine diet and febuxostat medication daily, which he has since been taking regularly.\n\nHis other current medications include gliclazide, dapagliflozin, insulin glargine, furosemide, bisoprolol, aspirin, ramipril, and atorvastatin. He is an ex-smoker, and he consumes about 4 units of alcoholic beverages on most days of the week.\n\nOn examination, the patient is alert and oriented. There are firm, hard, small chalky lumps noted over the right ear and the tip of his right thumb.\n\nThe patient has a pulse of 55 beats per minute, a blood pressure of 100/70 mmHg, and a temperature of 37.5 oC. His body mass index is 35.1 kg/m2.\n\nHis right knee is swollen and warm to the touch without any overlying erythema; both active and passive movements are restricted.\n\nNo other joint swelling or tenderness is noted. Both of the 1st metatarsophalangeal joints are unremarkable. The patient’s systemic examination is unremarkable.\n\nWhat is the most important diagnosis to consider with this clinical picture?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Pseudogout is another differential, but should not be diagnosed until septic arthritis has been excluded. Reactive arthritis is rare and is usually a diagnosis of exclusion.","Osteoarthritis should not be diagnosed initially in a patient with features of infection.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"Based on his history, this patient most likely has recurrent gouty arthritis, typically affecting the first metatarsophalangeal (MTP) joint with features of cutaneous tophi in the ear lobes and fingers. He also has chronic kidney disease with hyperuricaemia on febuxostat. His diuretics can worsen hyperuricaemia as well."},{"id":"17401","category":"Musculoskeletal system","stem":"A 60-year-old man presents to the emergency department with severe pain in both his thighs and shoulders. On examination, the muscles are extremely tender to touch, and power is reduced; deep tendon reflexes and sensations are intact. The patient suffered an episode of acute myocardial infarction and was started on high-intensity statins (rosuvastatin) and dual antiplatelets after undergoing primary percutaneous coronary intervention (PPCI) with stenting. Bloods revealed a creatine phosphokinase (CPK) level of 4500 micrograms per litre (mcg/L) (normal range: 10 - 120 mcg/L).\n\nWhat is the most likely diagnosis?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"This patient’s severe pain with markedly elevated CPK levels favours the diagnosis of statin-induced myositis. Osteomalacia is associated with vitamin D deficiency, polymyalgia rheumatica is associated with normal CPK levels, and fibromyalgia is associated with normal CPK levels and multiple tender points. Dermatomyositis is associated with raised CPK levels but has a characteristic rash, Gottron's papules, and heliotrope eyelid rash."},{"id":"3469","category":"Musculoskeletal system","stem":"A 25-year-old Romanian man who has just returned from a holiday to Romania presents with a swollen right knee. He is otherwise well with no constitutional symptoms and no other joint symptoms.\n\nThe knee is aspirated and sent for microscopy and culture. The results are as follows:\n\nWhat is the most likely diagnosis?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","A. Toivanen, Managing reactive arthritis, Rheumatology, Volume 39, Issue 2, February 2000, Pages 117–119, https://doi.org/10.1093/rheumatology/39.2.117","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"This is most likely to be a reactive arthritis. A leucocyte count >50,000 means the effusion is likely to be inflammatory, but without other joint symptoms, it is unlikely to be ankylosing spondylitis or rheumatoid arthritis. And without constitutional symptoms, septic arthritis or TB are less likely. You would also expect positive culture results as yields from the synovial fluid are 85% and 80%, respectively."},{"id":"3475","category":"Musculoskeletal system","stem":"A 42-year-old Caucasian woman on no current medication, no family history or history of foreign travel, presents to A&E with dyspnoea. On examination, she is dyspnoeic at rest, there are bibasal crackles, and she has a loud diastolic murmur heard best at the sternal edge. Her pulse is 106 beats per minute, regular but collapsing in nature. She also has a collapsed nasal bridge. She is ANA, ENA, and ANCA negative.\n\nWhat is the most likely cause for this presentation?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Congenital syphilis can also cause a collapse of the nasal bridge and aortitis, but symptoms appear earlier in life, typically as structures are developing.","Wegener's granulomatosis is unlikely as the ANCA is negative.","Cocaine abuse tends to destroy the nasal septum. It can cause cardiac failure but is associated with arrhythmias rather than valvular disease.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"Relapsing polychondritis is an autoimmune or autoinflammatory condition where recurrent inflammation of the cartilage is the key finding. After auricular inflammation, involvement of the nasal cartilage is the most common cartilaginous finding and can lead to the collapse of the bridge."},{"id":"14112","category":"Musculoskeletal system","stem":"A 25-year-old woman is admitted to the acute medicine unit after she was found wandering in the town centre, confused.\n\nOn examination, the patient is alert but confused and agitated; she is noted to be actively hallucinating.\n\nThe patient has a pulse rate of 110 beats per minute. Her blood pressure is 140/80 mmHg, her respiratory rate is 21 breaths per minute, and her oxygen saturation on air is 99%. Her temperature is 37.6oC.\n\nCapillary refill time is 2 seconds. Jugular venous pressure is not elevated. No leg oedema is noted. Respiratory system examination shows normal breath sounds on both sides. Her cardiovascular system examination shows normal heart sounds. The abdomen is soft with no tenderness, and there are active bowel sounds.\n\nOn central nervous system (CNS) examination, no focal neurological deficits were noted; no features of meningism were noted.\n\nMusculoskeletal examination reveals tenderness bilaterally in the proximal interphalangeal joints and metacarpophalangeal joints; no deformities noted.\n\nSkin examination was unremarkable.\n\nInvestigation results are as follows:\n\nWhat is the most likely diagnosis?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","A 25-year-old woman is admitted to the acute medicine unit after she was found wandering in the town centre, confused.","Investigation results are as follows:","Investigation\tResult\tNormal range","Haemoglobin\t90 g/L\t115-160 g/L","Total leucocyte count\t2 x 109 cells/L\t4-11 x 109 cells/L","Platelet count\t56 x 109 cells/L\t150 - 450 x 109 cells/L","C-Reactive protein\t2 mg/L\t< 10 mg/L","Erythrocyte sedimentation rate\t102 mm/hour\t< 30 mm/hour","Urea\t3 mmol/L\t3.5-7.2 mmol/L","Creatinine\t43 µmol/L\t49-90 µmol/L","Random plasma glucose\t6.1 mmol/L\t< 7.8 mmol/L","Sodium\t137 mmol/L\t135-145 mmol/L","Chloride\t100 mmol/L\t95-105 mmol/L","Bicarbonate\t26 mmol/L\t23-31 mmol/L","Potassium\t3.5 mmol/L\t3.5-5 mmol/L","Urine toxicology screen\tNegative","CT brain\tNormal\t25 – 36 seconds","CSF Analysis","CSF microscopy\tAcellular; gram stain no organisms noted","Cell count\t0","CSF protein\t1.2 g/dL\t0.15-0.40 g/dL","CSF glucose","CSF opening pressure\t10cm of H2O\t< 18cm of H2O","Arterial Blood Gas on Air","pCO2\t5.2 kPa\t4.6 – 6.4 kPa","PO2\t12.1 kPa\t11.0 – 14.4 kPa","Bicarbonate\t24 mmol/L\t22-28 mmol/L","Lactate\t0.9 mmol/L\t0.6- 2 mmol/L","Urine analysis\tNormal","What is the most likely diagnosis?","Schizophrenia should not be diagnosed here, as this is related to lupus and is treatable with steroids and immunosuppression.","Rheumatoid arthritis can cause symmetrical small-joint arthritis but is not associated with such neuropsychiatric manifestations.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"CSF protein\t1.2 g/dL\t0.15-0.40 g/dL","explanation":"This patient has an acute neuropsychiatric disturbance and has small joint arthritis with pancytopenia, which is highly suggestive of SLE/lupus psychosis. The high ESR but normal CRP is also suggestive of lupus. She has no fever or meningism signs to suggest CNS infection, and the CSF is also acellular with only proteins."},{"id":"3460","category":"Musculoskeletal system","stem":"A 25-year-old Armenian man is seen in the outpatient department for follow-up. He presented with a several-year history of intermittent fevers and sharp central chest and abdominal pains. During attacks, he complains of pain in his knees and ankles, as well as a red rash on his legs.\n\nInvestigations for lymphoma and tuberculosis return normal. Serial blood cultures and serum viral PCR analysis were negative. Genetic tests confirmed the presence of the MEFV (Mediterranean fever) gene. You explain the results of the genetic tests to your patient. He has ongoing symptoms and is now having difficulty continuing his work as a carpenter. He asks directly regarding treatment for his symptoms.\n\nWhich of the following treatment options is most appropriate?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"Familial Mediterranean Fever (FMF) is one of several heritable autoinflammatory diseases. It is characterised clinically by attacks of persistent fever, serosal inflammation (peritonitis, pleuritis, scrotitis, pericarditis), arthralgia of large joints, and erythema of the lower limbs reminiscent of erysipelas. Most cases present before the age of 5 years. The length of attacks varies from a few hours to approximately 4 days. Inflammatory attacks may be triggered by stress, viral disease during infancy and drugs including metaraminol and cisplatin. The key complication of chronic FMF is AA amyloidosis, which, if untreated, leads to nephropathy."},{"id":"16826","category":"Musculoskeletal system","stem":"A 68-year-old man was admitted to the acute medical unit with severe central crushing chest pain of sudden onset. Over the previous 6 months, he had lost 10 kg of weight unintentionally and had frequent episodes of sinusitis, muscle pains in his thighs, and numbness in his feet and ankles.\n\nHe had a 6-year history of poorly controlled asthma. He is a retired dock worker who stopped smoking 10 years ago. He had a 25-pack-year smoking history.\n\nHis ECG showed a heart rate of 80 beats per minute, sinus rhythm, QRS axis + 10o, PR interval 180 ms, QRS complexes 0.14 mm wide and a dominant R wave in V1.\n\nInvestigation results are as follows:\n\nWhat is the most likely diagnosis?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","The diagnosis is eosinophilic granulomatosis with polyangiitis (EGPA), formerly known as Churg–Strauss syndrome. It is a vasculitic condition which affects small and medium-sized arteries and veins.","The diagnostic criteria for the diagnosis of Churg–Strauss syndrome are (four out of six needed):","Asthma","Paranasal sinusitis","Pulmonary infiltrates (may be transient)","Histological proof of vasculitis with extravascular eosinophils","Mononeuritis multiplex or polyneuropathy","Patients may experience a variety of symptoms, including:","Investigations may show:","Eosinophilia","Anaemia","Raised inflammatory response (ESR, CRP, plasma viscosity)","Abnormal renal function/urine microscopy with renal involvement","Elevated serum IgE levels","Jones, T. Churg Strauss Syndrome, Vasculitis UK.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"The diagnosis is eosinophilic granulomatosis with polyangiitis (EGPA), formerly known as Churg–Strauss syndrome. It is a vasculitic condition which affects small and medium-sized arteries and veins.","explanation":"The diagnosis is eosinophilic granulomatosis with polyangiitis (EGPA), formerly known as Churg–Strauss syndrome. It is a vasculitic condition which affects small and medium-sized arteries and veins."},{"id":"3470","category":"Musculoskeletal system","stem":"An 82-year-old woman presents with intermittent pain and swelling of the wrists, metacarpophalangeal joints and proximal interphalangeal joints for a year. She also has an olecranon bursitis. In the past, she has had bilateral knee replacements. On examination, she has a warm, swollen left wrist and Heberden's and Bouchard's nodes. She is hypertensive and has moderate renal impairment with a creatinine of 161 (normal range 79-118 µmol/L).\n\nWhat should you do next?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"The most likely diagnosis, in this case, is pseudogout. Pseudogout most commonly affects the knees. Less often, wrists and ankles are involved. It is often associated with inflammatory symptoms such as stiffness, pyrexia, and malaise. A monoarticular presentation is typical."},{"id":"12259","category":"Musculoskeletal system","stem":"A 75-year-old man is admitted to the acute medicine unit in the middle of the night with general deterioration and fever with chills and rigours. He has a past medical history of type 2 diabetes mellitus, hypertension, atrial fibrillation, and right knee osteoarthritis.\n\nHis wife states that his right knee arthritis pain has flared up more than usual, and he was treated by his general practitioner with a course of ibuprofen with no relief.\n\nThe patient’s current medications are warfarin, gliclazide, metformin, amlodipine, metoprolol, and ramipril.\n\nOn examination, he is alert and oriented to time, place, and person. His blood pressure is 140/90 mmHg, with a pulse rate of 120 beats per minute, irregularly irregular. He has a temperature of 38.5 oC, and his respiratory rate is 22 breaths per minute. Oxygen saturation is 98% on room air.\n\nThe patient’s right knee is warm to the touch, swollen, and tender with passive motion, which is very painful and restricted.\n\nInvestigations reveal an international normalised ratio (INR) of 4.0 and a point-of-care capillary blood glucose of 7 mmol/L.\n\nWhat would be the most appropriate management?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","His wife states that his right knee arthritis pain has flared up more than usual, and he was treated by his general practitioner with a course of ibuprofen with no relief.","The patient’s current medications are warfarin, gliclazide, metformin, amlodipine, metoprolol, and ramipril.","The patient’s right knee is warm to the touch, swollen, and tender with passive motion, which is very painful and restricted.","Investigations reveal an international normalised ratio (INR) of 4.0 and a point-of-care capillary blood glucose of 7 mmol/L.","What would be the most appropriate management?","Oral colchicine can be used when suspecting gouty arthritis, but any hot, swollen joint should be considered septic arthritis unless proven otherwise.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"This patient likely has right knee septic arthritis and features of uncomplicated sepsis (3 criteria for SIRS {systemic inflammatory response syndrome} + focus of bacterial infection) and would require assessment and close monitoring to avoid deterioration to severe sepsis."},{"id":"12257","category":"Musculoskeletal system","stem":"A 57-year-old man with a past medical history of obesity, type 2 diabetes mellitus, and hypertension presents early in the morning to the emergency department (ED) with severe right foot pain. The patient reports that his foot felt fine the previous night when going to bed. His current medications include hydrochlorothiazide, amlodipine, gliclazide, and metformin. He smokes one pack of cigarettes per day and drinks about 8 units of beer at the weekends only.\n\nOn examination, the patient has a body mass index of 35.1 kg/m2. His right first metatarsophalangeal joint is exquisitely tender with swelling, along with tenderness over most of the foot. The ED doctors have helpfully aspirated a small amount of synovial fluid from the first metatarsophalangeal joint.\n\nWhat investigation in the synovial fluid sample is likely to be diagnostic in this patient?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"This patient has the typical presentation of a crescendo gout attack overnight involving the first metatarsophalangeal joint. His risk factors include obesity, moderate beer consumption, and the use of a diuretic. The demonstration of monosodium urate (MSU) crystals in the synovial fluid is diagnostic of gouty arthritis. MSU crystals appear as needle-shaped, negatively birefringent crystals when viewed under polarised light microscopy. However, it is important to always exclude septic arthritis in any patient presenting with a hot, swollen joint."},{"id":"3488","category":"Musculoskeletal system","stem":"A 54-year-old man with renal impairment developed a third attack of gouty arthritis this year. He has been taking allopurinol for 2 years at a 300 mg daily dosage. He denies alcohol intake. There is a history of renal calculi previously with no identifiable cause, and he has had removal of tophus from his left first metatarsophalangeal joint 3 years ago. There is no history of heart failure or diuretic use, but he is taking Losartan for hypertension.\n\nWhich treatment is most appropriate?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Sulphinpyrazone and probenecid are not safe for renal impairment, while benzbromarone is, although it is not one of the options given.","The BSR (British Society for Rheumatology) permits colchicine to be given for a maximum of 6 months at 0.5 mg twice daily from the initiation of uricosuric therapy.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"There is no dose adjustment required for febuxostat in mild-moderate renal impairment. It is relatively contraindicated in ischaemic heart disease and heart failure, which this patient does not have. Allopurinol cannot be increased due to very poor renal function."},{"id":"8044","category":"Musculoskeletal system","stem":"A 65-year-old man presents to medical admissions with a 2-day history of painful swelling of the right big toe. He had a similar episode 2 years ago, which was diagnosed as acute gout. He was treated with colchicine, with a resolution of his symptoms. His past medical history includes type 2 diabetes and stage 3 chronic kidney disease. He is receiving ramipril 10 mg daily, atorvastatin 40 mg daily, metformin 1g twice daily, and omeprazole 20 mg daily. His HbA1c is 52 mmol/mol (<48) and his eGFR is 55 ml/min.\n\nOn examination, he has an exquisitely tender, swollen and erythematous right 1st metatarsophalangeal joint. You elect to treat him acutely with colchicine.\n\nWhich of the following would be the most appropriate approach to the future prevention of gout?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","British Society for Rheumatology (2017). Guideline for the management of gout. Guidelines.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"This patient has had a second attack of gout and should receive urate-lowering therapy. febuxostat can be used if eGFR is >30, if patient unable to tolerate allopurinol, otherwise dose escalation of allopurinol is appropriate."},{"id":"3473","category":"Musculoskeletal system","stem":"A 24-year-old girl is referred to you by her GP. She had flitting arthralgia and Achilles tendonitis for 6 weeks and has now developed a swollen left knee. She also had a maculopapular rash across her trunk, although it is now healing. She has felt lethargic and has been pyrexial.\n\nOn examination, her knee is very swollen and warm. There is a fixed flexion deformity, and active and passive flexion are significantly limited. There is mild swelling of the Achilles tendon.\n\nAspiration of the knee is performed, and microscopy and culture reveal Neisseria gonorrhoeae infection.\n\nOn microscopy, the organisms seen would be?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","There are many other causes of septic arthritis:","CDC: Gonorrhea – CDC Detailed Fact Sheet.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"There are many other causes of septic arthritis:","explanation":"Neisseria gonorrhoeae is a gram-negative diplococci. It is sexually transmitted and most commonly affects young people, with current rates highest in males aged 20-24 years and females aged 16-19 years. Only 25 % of men report genital infection (burning dysuria and discharge). Cervicitis is frequently asymptomatic. The associated arthritis is more commonly seen in women (1:3) as are the other disseminated features (endocarditis, myocarditis, pericarditis, conduction abnormalities, hepatitis and meningitis. Frequently, it presents with flitting arthralgia and tenosynovitis, and the patient is often pyrexial (up to 38oc). At the same time, there may be a papular, pustular or vesicular rash that is not itchy and spares the face. Septic arthritis may occur, as may osteomyelitis and pyomyositis. Synovial fluid microscopy and culture are positive in 50% of cases, and there is a similar yield from blood cultures. Cultures from the genital tract are positive in 80%."},{"id":"3485","category":"Musculoskeletal system","stem":"A 74-year-old man is referred urgently by his general practitioner with new-onset arthropathy mainly affecting his hands. This had increased in severity over the last 2 months. His only medication before this event was omeprazole for occasional indigestion.\n\nExamination revealed symmetrical synovitis of his wrists and proximal interphalangeal joints; he also had marked oedema of the dorsum of his hands and pitting oedema up to his knees. He has recently commenced frusemide for the oedema with no benefit.\n\nInvestigations reveal the following:\n\nWhat is the most appropriate initial management of this patient?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"The case presented above is typical for the diagnosis of remitting seronegative symmetrical synovitis with pitting oedema (RS3PE). This is an inflammatory condition of acute onset, which presents with sudden onset polyarthritis associated with bilateral pitting oedema of both hands and lower limbs in older patients (usually men) and is rheumatoid factor negative. The main differentials for this condition are late-onset Rheumatoid arthritis, polymyalgia rheumatica, crystal arthropathy and paraneoplastic syndromes, which have frequently been reported in association with this condition. A particular feature of RS3PE is that it is very sensitive to the introduction of low-dose oral steroids at a dose of 10-15 mg. If there is a poor response to steroids with the typical features of the condition, a paraneoplastic cause may need to be pursued."},{"id":"3474","category":"Musculoskeletal system","stem":"A 66-year-old woman who has type 2 diabetes presents with a hot, swollen knee. She also has cellulitis affecting the same leg distally. Aspiration of the knee is performed, and culture of the fluid grows Staph Aureus. She has been started on IV flucloxacillin and benzylpenicillin as per local protocol.\n\nShe is keen to go home. How long should you tell her she is likely to remain on antibiotics?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"Although there is no strong evidence empirically, clinicians use a regimen of 2 weeks of sensitive IV antibiotics followed by 4 weeks of oral antibiotics. This is guided by the patient's response to therapy and as well as clinical response, white cell count, and CRP should be repeated to monitor the response to antibiotics. As she is diabetic, she is at increased risk of infection in the first place. Other risk factors include:"},{"id":"14113","category":"Musculoskeletal system","stem":"An 85-year-old elderly man is brought to the acute medicine unit following a fall at his home while trying to go to the bathroom. His past medical history includes Alzheimer's disease, type 2 diabetes mellitus, hypertension, hearing loss, and osteoarthritis. His current medications include donepezil, sitagliptin, metformin, losartan, and, when required (PRN), paracetamol. He has been complaining of worsening left hip and thigh pain for the past month, and his general practitioner has been prescribing him PRN codeine as well.\n\nHis clinical examination is unremarkable except for tenderness over the left upper thigh and inability to bear weight.\n\nHis investigation results are as follows:\n\nWhat is the most likely diagnosis?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","PHP is unlikely given normal calcium and phosphorus levels. Osteoporosis is not associated with bone sclerosis.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"This patient has typical sclerotic and osteolytic changes of Paget’s disease in the hemipelvis and femur, high alkaline phosphatase, along with a pathological fracture. His hearing impairment may also be due to Paget’s disease from cochlear involvement."},{"id":"16827","category":"Musculoskeletal system","stem":"A 56-year-old man was referred to the transient ischaemic attack (TIA) clinic with a four-week history of progressive left-sided headache, general malaise, lethargy, and two episodes of amaurosis fugax within the previous 48 hours. He has a history of hypertension, and he smokes ten cigarettes per day, with a 40-pack-year smoking history.\n\nOn examination, he had a thickened, red, tender left temporal artery, moderate temporal scalp tenderness, and mild bilateral expiratory wheeze.\n\nInvestigation results are as follows:\n\nWhat is the most appropriate type of steroid treatment at this stage?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","A temporal artery biopsy (TAB) should be considered, but treatment should not be delayed whilst waiting for a biopsy, especially with visual symptoms.","Where visual loss has occurred, the starting dose of prednisolone is 60 mg per day. In uncomplicated GCA, the starting dose of prednisolone is 40–60 mg per day.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"The diagnosis is giant cell arteritis (GCA). The combination of a new unilateral temporal headache, an abnormal temporal artery, scalp tenderness, constitutional symptoms, and transient visual disturbance in a man over the age of 50 would be compatible with a diagnosis of complicated GCA."},{"id":"13169","category":"Musculoskeletal system","stem":"You see a 67-year-old woman who came for follow-up in the same-day emergency care (SDEC) unit. She has been on prednisolone 20 mg once daily for the last three weeks. The patient has a working diagnosis of polymyalgia rheumatica (PMR) after she presented with bilateral shoulder pain and stiffness, and she had a raised C-reactive protein (CRP) and a raised ESR. She also has chronic stable angina, which was diagnosed a few years ago, and she has been regularly on aspirin 75 mg, atorvastatin 40 mg, and bisoprolol 5 mg, all once a day. The patient mentioned her symptoms have only slightly improved since she was last seen. She denied any headache or visual abnormality. She denied any weight loss or any constitutional or neurological symptoms.\n\nWhat is the best next step in her management?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","RCP: Concise guidance: diagnosis and management of polymyalgia rheumatica, 2010.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"This patient’s symptoms are suggestive of PMR, given her age, typical symptoms, and the fact that she has been started on prednisolone with an appropriate dose. Absent or incomplete response to steroid therapy after three weeks is an indication for specialist referral in patients treated for PMR. The response to steroids is usually dramatic and occurs within the first week, with a 70% improvement of the overall condition."},{"id":"3762","category":"Neurology and ophthalmology","stem":"A 45-year-old man presents with a severe occipital headache that came on suddenly during sexual intercourse. He has otherwise been well without any other medical history of note. He has vomited 4 times. On examination, there is nothing to find, and his GCS is 15 with no focal deficit. His headache started at 6 am, and he underwent a CT brain at 4 pm. The CT is reported as normal.\n\nWhich of the following is most appropriate in the management of this patient?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"The history is suggestive of aneurysmal subarachnoid haemorrhage/leak (SAH). The CT scan is reported normal, and what is now required is a lumbar puncture. LP may be negative if performed less than 2 hours after an SAH occurs; It is most sensitive 12 hours after the onset of symptoms. If a CT head scan done within 6 hours of symptom onset shows no evidence of an SAH, there is usually no need to perform a lumbar puncture, as CT within 6 hours of onset of symptoms is very sensitive."},{"id":"8966","category":"Neurology and ophthalmology","stem":"A 31-year-old woman presented to the acute unit with numbness in her right leg and was noted to have a sensory level up to the level of the umbilicus. There was no other medical history of note.\n\nRoutine blood investigations were normal and the CRP was 5 mg/dl (<5).\n\nA diagnosis of partial myelitis was suspected.\n\nMagnetic resonance imaging (MRI) examination was reported as showing three T2 periventricular lesions, and there was one spinal thoracic lesion. There were no enhancing lesions.\n\nWhat would be the most appropriate next test to establish the diagnosis?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"The presence of CSF-specific oligoclonal bands will enable a diagnosis of multiple sclerosis to be made in this patient. The 2017 revisions of the McDonald criteria for the diagnosis of MS allow for CSF-specific oligoclonal bands to be used in place of dissemination in time. Visual evoked potentials are not part of this diagnostic criterion. The MRI appearances are not in keeping with neuromyelitis optica (NMO or Devic’s disease), where aquaporin-4 Ab or myelin oligodendrocyte glycoprotein Ab might be present. Awaiting a repeat MRI would not be helpful, as it would lead to a delay in diagnosis."},{"id":"12019","category":"Neurology and ophthalmology","stem":"A 79-year-old woman with ovarian cancer has developed bilateral hydronephrosis, which is considered to be due to her large malignant pelvic mass. Her renal function has deteriorated (eGFR = 31 mL/min/1.73m2) and she has become delirious. Nursing colleagues have implemented some non-pharmacological approaches to try and help the delirium. At times, the patient is very agitated and is a risk to herself and others, and the nursing team have therefore asked whether medication could be prescribed for the delirium, in case it is needed.\n\nWhat medication would be most appropriate to prescribe?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"NICE guidelines suggest haloperidol for delirium, where, on balance of risk/benefit, a pharmacological option is needed (as it has a drug licence for this indication). Haloperidol is considered safe for use in patients with renal impairment because it is primarily metabolized by the liver, with minimal excretion of the unchanged drug by the kidneys. However, cautious administration and monitoring are still advised, particularly in patients with severe renal failure."},{"id":"3994","category":"Neurology and ophthalmology","stem":"A 52-year-old woman with only hypertension in her past medical history is brought in as an emergency. Her GCS is 11/15, and her sister informs you she had been complaining of a severe headache and double vision earlier today and reports that she had also complained of a similar but less severe headache two weeks ago. There is no evidence of head trauma.\n\nWhat is the most likely diagnosis?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","This is most likely a SAH from the history with an earlier sentinel bleed. The peak time for rebleeding is around 14 days.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"This is most likely a SAH from the history with an earlier sentinel bleed. The peak time for rebleeding is around 14 days.","explanation":"This is most likely a SAH from the history with an earlier sentinel bleed. The peak time for rebleeding is around 14 days."},{"id":"6921","category":"Neurology and ophthalmology","stem":"A 57-year-old man presents complaining of an episode of sudden onset, severe dizziness, which he noticed on waking. He describes the room spinning violently and has severe nausea and vomiting. He had symptoms of a heavy cold two weeks previously, although he has been well recently.\n\nHe has a history of type two diabetes with an HbA1c of 96 mmol/mol, ischaemic heart disease with a previous myocardial infarction and a transient ischaemic attack two years ago, which left no long-standing neurological deficit.\n\nHe is currently taking gliclazide, metformin, bisoprolol, ramipril and clopidogrel.\n\nHis blood pressure is 165/91 mmHg with a heart rate of 94 bpm, regular, and in sinus rhythm. He was supported on entering the room with the help of his son due to his instability, and he had a broad-based gait. He has gaze-evoked nystagmus, although no weakness, altered sensation or any other deficits of his cranial nerves.\n\nWhat is the most likely diagnosis?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","He has features of central vertigo, including gaze-induced nystagmus and a wide-based gait and is unable to mobilise without help.","The vertigo is of sudden onset and is severe. The above features point to a central cause of nystagmus and therefore require admission to secondary care for urgent investigation.","Nelson, J.A. and Viirre, E., 2009. The clinical differentiation of cerebellar infarction from common vertigo syndromes. Western Journal of Emergency Medicine, 10(4), p.273.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"The patient has risk factors for vascular disease, with poorly treated type 2 diabetes and evidence of hypertension. He has suffered from previous ischaemic heart disease and a transient ischaemic attack, indicating vascular disease."},{"id":"3692","category":"Neurology and ophthalmology","stem":"A 29-year-old woman is admitted after collapsing while at the gym. She was training in a spin class as she wanted to get fit. She reports overdoing her workout and collapsing. On waking, she felt confused and had a headache. She was witnessed and reportedly did not hit her head on falling, and was unconscious for about a minute without any fitting. The event happened about 4 hours previously, as she had been referred to the medics by A&E. She had no medical history of note other than taking the oral contraceptive, microgynon.\n\nOn examination, she appeared well and was communicating and complaining of a headache. Pulse was 82 bpm reg, blood pressure 122/70 mmHg and oxygen saturations were 99% on air. There was no neck stiffness or photophobia. Neurological examination was otherwise normal, and the fundi appeared normal. She underwent a CT head scan, which had been requested by A&E and was reported as ‘normal scan with no evidence of a subarachnoid bleed. A coincidental note is made of a 13mm colloid cyst in the third ventricle.\n\nWhich of the following is the most appropriate approach to the management of this patient?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Which of the following is the most appropriate approach to the management of this patient?","StatPearls: Colloid Brain Cyst.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"This patient presented with a collapse, and a 13mm colloid cyst was noted in the third ventricle. This is a life-threatening lesion that can occlude the third ventricle, producing acute hydrocephalus. The patient may well have had a premonitory event where occlusion occurred, then release. Although often asymptomatic, they can present with acute hydrocephalus as evidenced by headache and collapse. Whilst many colloid cysts are asymptomatic and may not require treatment, some may occlude the Foramen of Monro, causing hydrocephalus and herniation. If, as in this case, they become symptomatic or larger than 10mm, urgent referral to the neurosurgeons is required. An LP must not be performed as this can precipitate occlusion of the Foramen of Monro."},{"id":"10712","category":"Neurology and ophthalmology","stem":"A 58-year-old female was admitted with a headache and deteriorating vision, which had developed over the past 2–3 days, followed more recently by a seizure. She reports that her vision has worsened in conjunction with the headache, and she is currently struggling to see clearly. She describes the headache as throbbing and occipital, persistent throughout the day, without identifiable exacerbating factors. Her family have observed increased restlessness and agitation over the last day, culminating in a seizure that prompted her acute admission.\n\nShe has a complex history, having had a renal transplant 2 years ago due to immune-mediated nephropathy and is currently treated with nifedipine, clopidogrel, atorvastatin, mycophenolate mofetil, tacrolimus, omeprazole, and colecalciferol.\n\nOn examination, she is confused with a GCS of 13/15. Her temperature is 37.6oC, pulse 88 bpm, and blood pressure 166/90 mmHg. There was no focal neurology, plantars flexor and fundi appeared normal with normal vessels and retina. However, testing her visual acuity indicated that she could not see the board. Cardiovascular, abdominal, and respiratory examinations were all normal.\n\nInvestigations revealed:\n\nLumbar puncture showed:\n\nWhich of the following investigations would you request for this patient?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Recognition is vitally important, and CT is often normal. MRI typically reveals flares in the posterior circulation consistent with vasogenic oedema.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"This patient’s history is highly suggestive of Posterior Reversible Encephalopathy Syndrome (PRES), likely due to the tacrolimus. PRES is a rare disorder associated with oedematous ischaemia in the posterior circulation, associated with seizures, visual problems, headaches, and hypertension. It has been reported in association with a variety of disorders, including eclampsia, immune-modulating drugs such as tacrolimus, and chemotherapy."},{"id":"3941","category":"Neurology and ophthalmology","stem":"A 42-year-old man presented with a headache. He was aware of a strain in his neck whilst lifting weights in the gym 2 weeks ago. He felt that this was a muscle strain. The neck strain resolved after a day or so, but since then, he has become aware of debilitating headaches. The headaches are worse as the day progresses and are relieved by lying down. The headaches tend to be focused over his eyes. Sneezing or coughing also makes the headaches worse.\n\nThere were no abnormal findings on neurological examination, and observations were otherwise normal. CT head revealed low-lying cerebellar tonsils.\n\nWhich of the following is the most appropriate approach to the management of this patient?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"This patient presents with typical features of a spontaneous low-pressure CSF headache with orthostatic features. It improves on lying down. This headache began after weight training, with pain in the neck. This is likely to be a spontaneous CSF leak. Low-lying cerebellar tonsils on the CT with this history suggest low-pressure headache rather than this being due to a Chiari malformation. Doing a lumbar puncture could make this headache worse."},{"id":"3987","category":"Neurology and ophthalmology","stem":"A 45-year-old homeless man was admitted after being found collapsed on the street with empty, blank brown plastic medication bottles strewn around him and an empty bottle of vodka.\n\nOn examination, he had a GCS of 10, was agitated, had a temperature of 39 oC and was hyperreflexic with clonus. He had a sinus tachycardia of 120 bpm and a blood pressure of 122/80 mmHg. Pupils were equal and reactive.\n\nWhich of the following is the likely drug that he has taken in overdose?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Frank C. Recognition and treatment of serotonin syndrome. Can Fam Physician. 2008 Jul;54(7):988-92. PMID: 18625822; PMCID: PMC2464814.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"This homeless man has been found collapsed and inebriated, and like many admissions to A&E, the exact poisoning is unknown. He displays features of the serotonin syndrome as suggested by tachycardia, hyperreflexia, agitation and fever. The treatment is with sedation with benzodiazepines and cooling."},{"id":"3693","category":"Neurology and ophthalmology","stem":"A patient has been admitted to the medical admissions unit. The patient is groaning, opens his eyes to painful stimuli and tries to pull his arm away when pressure is applied to a nail bed.\n\nWhich of the following is the correct Glasgow Coma Scale score in this man’s case?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","GCS is based on the following scores:","Glasgow coma scale score gcs.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"GCS is based on the following scores:","explanation":"GCS is based on the following scores:"},{"id":"3935","category":"Neurology and ophthalmology","stem":"A 22-year-old woman has been treated by the dental surgeons for a tooth extraction and received ondansetron for nausea. You are called acutely as she has developed rhythmical and uncontrollable movements of the arms and legs. On review, you find that she is alert and cooperative but is anxious and upset. She usually takes mirtazapine for insomnia, but is otherwise well. She is distressed by these uncontrollable movements of the limbs.\n\nOn examination, her temperature is 37.3 oC, her blood pressure is 138/80 mmHg, and her pulse is 100 bpm. She has rhythmical writhing movements of the arms and legs to a lesser extent and some facial movements. Otherwise, reflexes are normal, and there is no focal neurology.\n\nWhich of the following is the most appropriate treatment for this patient?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"This patient has developed an acute dystonic reaction, which is likely to have been precipitated by the ondansetron. Whilst acute dystonia is most often precipitated by dopamine antagonists such as metoclopramide and prochlorperazine, reports are associated with ondansetron. The differential diagnosis includes serotonin syndrome, but this is associated with high fever, anxiety, hyperreflexia and tachycardia. The treatment of serotonin syndrome is a dopamine antagonist, like chlorpromazine, but this may well make acute dystonia worse. Treatment depends on how problematic the symptoms are, as they often resolve. In this case, where the patient is distressed, the anticholinergic, procyclidine hydrochloride, would be the most appropriate treatment."},{"id":"10815","category":"Neurology and ophthalmology","stem":"A 55-year-old woman attends the medical assessment unit complaining of a deteriorating headache. The headache began 3 days ago, she describes it as being all over with pressure behind the eyes and feels that the intensity is 8 out of 10. She has no other past medical history of note. She takes no medication. She had a SARS-CoV-2 adenovirus vector vaccine approximately 2 weeks ago.\n\nOn examination, she has a GCS of 15, a pulse of 88 beats per minute, regular, a blood pressure of 136/88 mmHg with a temperature of 36.7oC. There is no neck stiffness, but some mild photophobia is present with no focal neurology. Fundal examination reveals no specific abnormalities.\n\nInvestigations reveal:\n\nWhich of the following investigations would help in establishing the likely diagnosis?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"and assessed with CT","explanation":"This patient has a thrombocytopaenia associated with headache 2 weeks after receiving the ChAdOx1 nCoV-19 (AstraZeneca) SARS-CoV-2 vaccine, hence a diagnosis of cerebral venous sinus thrombosis due to vaccine-induced thrombocytopaenic thrombosis should be considered and assessed with CT. The diagnosis of VITT can be supported by measuring antibodies to PF-4. Treatment with IV immunoglobulin plus high-dose glucocorticoids can improve the outcome, together with anticoagulation with non-heparin-based anticoagulation such as argatroban or fondaparinux."},{"id":"8930","category":"Neurology and ophthalmology","stem":"A 56-year-old man is seen in the medical assessment unit (MAU) after his wife is concerned about his behaviour. He undertook a 30 km cycle ride, but on his return home, he could not remember cycling back or where things were in the house. He was repeating questions despite careful and repeated explanations by his wife. These symptoms resolved within approximately 8 hours. She called the GP, who referred her to the MAU with suspected ‘TIA’.\n\nOn examination, he was a fit individual with no neurological deficits. Blood pressure was 120/72 mmHg, and all systems were otherwise unremarkable.\n\nWhich of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"The most likely diagnosis is transient global amnesia, where there is a transient loss of memory with a typical striking loss of recent events. The symptoms are transient (<24 hours) as the name suggests, and the aetiology is largely unknown. TGA is usually a solitary event."},{"id":"8082","category":"Neurology and ophthalmology","stem":"A 70-year-old man is referred to MAU with a left-sided weakness of 2 hours' duration. He has a previous history of hypertension and ischaemic heart disease for which he had a stent inserted 5 years ago. His family informed you that he had an episode of left-sided facial weakness that lasted about 30 minutes, 3 months ago, but he didn’t take this any further.\n\nOn examination, his Glasgow Coma Score was 12/15. His blood pressure was 210/130 mmHg. CT head showed a right basal ganglia haematoma with an approximate volume of 20 ml with no midline shift.\n\nHow should he be managed?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"This patient has developed a right basal ganglia haematoma as a consequence of hypertension. The basal ganglia are a particularly common site for ICH. Most haematomas less than 30mLs by volume without midline shift or compression of the ventricle would be managed conservatively. His hypertension must be treated aggressively to avoid extension of the haemorrhage. The target blood pressure reduction should be aimed at less than 140/90 mmHg, with the blood pressure reduced quickly over the next hour or so."},{"id":"8407","category":"Neurology and ophthalmology","stem":"A 50-year-old man is admitted to the hospital unconscious and smelling of alcohol. His last drink was a couple of hours earlier. One hour after admission, he became suddenly confused and sweaty with a regular tachycardia of 110 bpm and a blood pressure of 100/50 mmHg.\n\nWhat is the likely diagnosis?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"This is a bit early for delirium tremens and alcoholic hallucinosis, particularly as the patient is admitted smelling of alcohol. The most likely diagnosis is hypoglycaemia, which is quite commonly associated with alcohol intoxication. We do not have any clinical findings, such as focal neurology, suggestive of the other diagnoses."},{"id":"4260","category":"Neurology and ophthalmology","stem":"A 24-year-old woman, who is a student, is referred to acute admissions with a 2-week history of unsteadiness of gait and numbness in her feet. She has been aware of paresthesia and deteriorating weakness for a few months, but feels that this has deteriorated more in the last 2 weeks. She provides no medical history of note. Her menstrual cycle is regular as she uses a combined OCP. She smokes very occasionally and drinks 10 units weekly, more so, binge drinking. She also admits to illicit drug intake.\n\nOn examination, her BMI is 23kg/m2, her pulse is 80 beats per minute regular, her blood pressure is 116/76 mmHg, and her temperature is 37oC. She has some unsteadiness on standing, with some gait ataxia. She has loss of peripheral sensation in the feet up to mid tibia, with reduced proprioception in both feet. Ankle reflex is absent, and her knee reflexes are exaggerated. She has a similar peripheral neuropathy in her hands.\n\nWhich of the following is the most appropriate treatment for this patient?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Treatment is with high doses of daily, SC or oral vitamin B12.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"This young woman has features of subacute combined degeneration of the cord, due to vitamin B12 deficiency, which is low. The likely diagnosis in this young woman is chronic nitrous oxide abuse – balloons, causing vitamin B12 deficiency. This is often overlooked in a patient history and needs to be thoroughly questioned. Chronic nitrous oxide oxidises cobalamin to the inactive bivalent form, resulting in a functional vitamin B12 deficiency. Occasionally, B12 concentrations may be normal, yet the neurological features are profound. However, methionine and methylmalonic acid levels are typically elevated."},{"id":"10710","category":"Neurology and ophthalmology","stem":"A 39-year-old man is referred to the acute clinic with complaints of severe headaches during sexual intercourse. These symptoms have deteriorated over the last 2 months. He has no headaches other than those occurring during sexual intercourse. The headache often develops at the point of climax, usually begins occipitally, and he describes it as explosive. The headache then lasts around 10 minutes and subsides completely. It is most intense at the time of climax, and he has, on occasions, stopped sexual activity to avoid climax and the headache.\n\nThere is nothing else of note in his past medical history. He takes no medication but has used sildenafil on several occasions recently, as he has been rather worried about the pain. He does not feel that the sildenafil exacerbates his headache.\n\nThere are no neurological findings on examination. Cranial nerves are entirely intact, and he has normal visual acuity. Fundal examination also appears normal. He has a BMI of 32 kg/m2, and a blood pressure of 138/86 mmHg.\n\nWhich of the following is the likely explanation for this headache?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"This patient has a typical coital headache with severe pain associated with climax. This history is quite typical of type-2 headache associated with sexual activity, and there are no other sinister features. The condition is typically self-limiting, but symptoms can precipitate acute admission and mimic subarachnoid haemorrhage. Treatments such as NSAIDs and prophylactic beta-blockers are useful."},{"id":"3737","category":"Neurology and ophthalmology","stem":"A 24-year-old man is referred to acute admissions by his GP with a 2-week history of deteriorating unsteadiness and numbness in his feet. He has been aware of paresthesia in his limbs and deteriorating weakness for a few months, but feels that this has deteriorated more in the last 2 weeks. He is a student and describes abuse of many illicit substances. He has a normal diet and has no medical history of note. He smokes occasionally and drinks alcohol, roughly 10 units per week.\n\nOn examination, his BMI is 23.8kg/m2, his pulse is 80 beats per minute regular, his blood pressure is 116/76 mmHg, and his temperature is 37oC. He has some unsteadiness on standing, with some gait ataxia. He has loss of peripheral sensation in his feet up to mid tibia, and reduced proprioception in both feet. Ankle reflex is absent, and his knee reflexes are exaggerated. He has a similar peripheral neuropathy in his hands.\n\nUse of which of the following is likely to be responsible for his presentation?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"This young man presents with features of peripheral neuropathy and gait ataxia associated with polysubstance abuse. The differential diagnoses include subacute combined degeneration of the cord related to vitamin B12 deficiency. The likely diagnosis is chronic nitrous oxide abuse – balloons, rather than atrophic gastritis and pernicious anaemia. This is often overlooked in history and needs to be thoroughly questioned. Chronic nitrous oxide oxidises cobalamin to the inactive bivalent form, resulting in a functional vitamin B12 deficiency. Occasionally, B12 concentrations may be normal, yet the neurological features are profound. However, methionine and methylmalonic acid levels are typically elevated. Treatment is with high doses of daily, SC or oral vitamin B12."},{"id":"7753","category":"Neurology and ophthalmology","stem":"A man is brought in as an emergency after being found on the street, and an ambulance is called. He is late-middle-aged and dishevelled, and there is no history available. He smells of alcohol and is homeless.\n\nOn examination, he is unkempt and dirty. He appears to have a graze on the left temple with some bruising. He also has several bruises on his arms and legs. He has a GCS of 9 and has normal reactive pupils. His pulse is 110 bpm, temperature 39 oC and a blood pressure of 128/70 mmHg. His oxygen saturations are 95% on air. He has right-sided weakness and a right upgoing plantar with hyperreflexia on the right.\n\nCardiovascular and respiratory examination is otherwise normal, and he has a smooth palpable liver edge with some spider naevi present on his torso.\n\nWhich of the following is the likely diagnosis?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Which of the following is the likely diagnosis?","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"We are provided with little history here, other than that he is homeless and has been admitted unconscious. However, there is a graze and bruising, and he has right-sided hemiparesis and some signs of alcoholic liver disease. Importantly, he has features of sepsis with a raised temperature, so an associated infection is a possibility."},{"id":"8968","category":"Neurology and ophthalmology","stem":"A 28-year-old woman presents to medical admissions with acute neuro-ophthalmological symptoms. A diagnosis of multiple sclerosis is suspected.\n\nWhich feature would be atypical for a first presentation of multiple sclerosis?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"Whereas unilateral ON is quite common for a first presentation (20%), bilateral optic neuritis is atypical for a first presentation of multiple sclerosis. In such patients, neuromyelitis optica (NMO) spectrum disorders should be considered, which should prompt further investigation with brain and spinal imaging plus measurement of aquaporin-4 antibody and myelin oligodendrocyte glycoprotein. All the other signs would be in keeping with a first presentation of MS. Abducens nerve palsy with lateral rectus weakness, whilst rare, is a presenting feature too."},{"id":"3694","category":"Neurology and ophthalmology","stem":"A 37-year-old man was admitted with generalised weakness. He awoke 3 days ago and was aware of pins and needles in the hands and feet. He had some associated weakness in the legs, which deteriorated, resulting in his admission. He has no past medical history of note.\n\nOn examination, he had a BMI of 31 kg/m2, a pulse of 90 beats per minute, regular, and a blood pressure of 110/72 mmHg. He had diffuse weakness of all four limbs, more marked in the legs than the arms, which was more proximal than distal. He could walk but was weak on rising and was slow and slightly incoordinated. He had a loss of light touch and vibration to the knees and also in the hands. Tendon reflexes were absent in the lower extremities but present in the biceps and triceps.\n\nBlood investigations including FBC, U+Es and LFTs were normal. Calcium was 2.2 mmol/L (2.2-2.6). CRP was 12 mg/dL (<5).\n\nWhich of the following is the likely diagnosis?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"This patient has a typical story of Guillain-Barré (AIDP) with ascending weakness and sensory loss. Often but not always, a premorbid flu-like illness is described, although this may be innocuous and so missed in the history. Diagnosis can be confirmed with LP, which shows acellular CSF with elevated protein."},{"id":"3988","category":"Neurology and ophthalmology","stem":"A 42-year-old businessman attends the clinic following a recent acute admission with an unprovoked generalised tonic-clonic seizure. This was his first-ever seizure. CT and MRI scans of his brain are both normal, as is his EEG. He is very keen to resume driving (standard driving licence).\n\nHow long does the DVLA state he cannot drive for?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Gov.UK. Fits, seizures or convulsions and driving, Gov.uk","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"After a single unprovoked seizure, an individual can resume driving after 6 months, provided there is a low risk of seizure recurrence; this is likely here, given no structural abnormalities were found and no epileptiform activity on EEG."},{"id":"7204","category":"Neurology and ophthalmology","stem":"You are asked to review a 76-year-old man in accident and emergency, who presents with an acute onset of abnormal movements affecting his left upper extremity associated with numbness. His past medical history includes hypertension. On examination, you note irregular, large amplitude, flinging movements of the limb. You suspect he has had a stroke and organise an MRI brain scan.\n\nWhere do you expect to find the lesion?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Shannon KM. Hemiballismus. Curr Treat Options Neurol. 2005;7:203-210.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"Hemiballismus is a rare but dramatic movement disorder, typified by involuntary large-amplitude flailing movements. The underlying pathology may be metabolic dysfunction or a structural lesion in the contralateral region of the subthalamic nucleus, related afferent/efferent pathways, or interconnected deep brain nuclei. There are a variety of underlying causative aetiologies, and in older patients, vascular events should be considered."},{"id":"18614","category":"Neurology and ophthalmology","stem":"A 62-year-old woman with a history of epilepsy managed on phenytoin presents with confusion and a rash. She was started on phenytoin 6 months ago. She also takes lisinopril for hypertension. On examination, she has a diffuse maculopapular rash, lymphadenopathy, and oral ulcers.\n\nShe is oriented to person, but not to time or place. Her vitals include a temperature of 38.2oC, blood pressure of 130/80 mmHg, heart rate of 92 beats per minute, and a respiratory rate of 18 breaths per minute.\n\nLaboratory tests reveal:\n\nA complete blood count shows a WBC of 15,000/mm3 with 15% PMNs, 52% lymphocytes, 28% monocytes, and 8% eosinophils.\n\nWhat is the most appropriate next step in the management of this patient’s condition?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Laboratory tests reveal:","What is the most appropriate next step in the management of this patient’s condition?","Gupta A, Srivastava VK, Rizvi I, et alDRESS syndromeCase Reports 2012;2012:bcr0320126128.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"Discontinuing phenytoin and initiating another antiepileptic drug is the correct answer. The patient's clinical presentation is suggestive of Drug Reaction with Eosinophilia and Systemic Symptoms (DRESS) syndrome, which is a severe drug-induced reaction that requires immediate cessation of the offending agent."},{"id":"7203","category":"Neurology and ophthalmology","stem":"A 63-year-old man presents to the emergency department following a fall, which caused a superficial laceration over his right shoulder blade. His daughter, who attends with him, gives a history of instability and frequent falls over the last 10 months. She feels his falls relate, in part, to ‘taking risky chances’ with his mobility. On examination, the patient has a staring facial expression and reduced blink frequency. Axial rigidity and slow vertical saccadic eye movements are noted.\n\nWhat is the most likely diagnosis for this patient?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","The diagnosis in this case is progressive supranuclear palsy.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"The diagnosis in this case is progressive supranuclear palsy.","explanation":"The diagnosis in this case is progressive supranuclear palsy."},{"id":"7207","category":"Neurology and ophthalmology","stem":"A 48-year-old gentleman presents to the emergency department with left-sided weakness, blurred vision and neck pain for the last 2 days. The left-sided weakness was of a sudden onset, immediately preceded by right-sided neck pain. Further history reveals that he had a minor car accident, incurring a whiplash injury two weeks ago. Usually, he is fit and well with no vascular risk factors. Family history is unremarkable.\n\nNeurological examination shows no cranial nerve deficits. The left side was minimally weak (4/5), and there were no other neurological deficits. Body temperature is 36.4oC; respiratory rate is 18; blood pressure is 128/81 mmHg; heart rate is 78 beats per minute; oxygen saturation (on room air) 98%.\n\nBlood tests reveal the following results:\n\nA CT brain demonstrates a hypointensity in the high frontal region in keeping with an acute ischaemic stroke. There is no intracranial haemorrhage. A CT angiogram (from the aortic arch) found a narrowed eccentric lumen of the right ICA with a crescent-shaped mural thrombus, findings consistent with a right internal carotid artery dissection. There is no evidence of intra- or extracranial aneurysms.\n\nWhat is the most appropriate management for this patient?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Blood tests reveal the following results:","Investigation\tResult\tNormal range\nWBC\t8.2 x 109/L\t4.5 - 11.0 x 109/L\nCRP\t4 mg/L\t<8 mg/L","What is the most appropriate management for this patient?","The CADISS trial investigators. 2015. Antiplatelet treatment compared with anticoagulation treatment for cervical artery dissection (CADISS): a randomised trial, The Lancet 14(4): 361-367.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"The CADISS trial investigators. 2015. Antiplatelet treatment compared with anticoagulation treatment for cervical artery dissection (CADISS): a randomised trial, The Lancet 14(4): 361-367.","explanation":"The CADISS trial published in 2015 found no difference in efficacy between antiplatelet and anticoagulant drugs in preventing stroke and death in patients with symptomatic carotid and vertebral artery dissection. The treatment duration is usually 3–6 months, with vascular imaging to monitor the resolution of the dissection. Vascular interventions are usually reserved for patients with recurrent symptoms."},{"id":"8938","category":"Neurology and ophthalmology","stem":"A 50-year-old woman, who is a smoker, presents with a sudden onset of headache. There were no precipitating factors. At the onset of the headache, she was GCS 15, but on arrival in the emergency department, she had a GCS of 13 (E3 V4 M6). On examination, she has left-sided ptosis with a dilated pupil and the eye looking downwards and outwards. There are extensor plantar responses.\n\nWhat is the most likely cause of her condition?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","This young woman presents with a typical history of subarachnoid haemorrhage associated with a left-third nerve palsy. This suggests a bleed associated with a posterior communicating artery aneurysm.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"This young woman presents with a typical history of subarachnoid haemorrhage associated with a left-third nerve palsy. This suggests a bleed associated with a posterior communicating artery aneurysm.","explanation":"This young woman presents with a typical history of subarachnoid haemorrhage associated with a left-third nerve palsy. This suggests a bleed associated with a posterior communicating artery aneurysm."},{"id":"7749","category":"Neurology and ophthalmology","stem":"A 43-year-old woman presents with bilateral leg pain and urinary hesitancy. She has developed these symptoms over the last 3–4 days. She has no other history of note and takes no medication.\n\nOn examination, she has a BMI of 37 kg/m2, a pulse of 95 beats per minute, regular, and a blood pressure reading of 135/90 mmHg. She has limited straight leg raise bilaterally due to pain and has reduced power due to this pain in her lower back and legs. Tone is normal, as is muscle bulk. Ankle reflexes are difficult to elicit, but knee reflexes are normal. Sensation is impaired on the plantar aspect of the right foot and the back of the right leg.\n\nWhich of the following is the likely diagnosis?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"This obese woman has features of cauda equina syndrome as evidenced by the autonomic features of urinary hesitancy and sensory loss over S1 and S2 dermatomes. One might expect to find sensory loss also around the perineum."},{"id":"7880","category":"Neurology and ophthalmology","stem":"A 62-year-old woman presents to the emergency unit after having had a fall while she was intoxicated. There are no witnesses, and she cannot recall whether or not she had lost consciousness. She has a history of alcohol abuse and has had several admissions with intoxication in the past. On examination, she has a small left-sided temporo-frontal scalp laceration and a bruise which is sealed. She smells of alcohol, is mildly intoxicated, and is confused. There are no neurological abnormalities on examination.\n\nHer blood alcohol concentration is 320 mg/100 ml.\n\nWhich of the following is the most appropriate approach to the management of this patient?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"a CT head scan is recommended under such circumstances","explanation":"This patient would be deemed to be at high risk of a subdural haematoma, and the patient should undergo a CT head scan. New Orleans criteria identify intoxications like alcohol intoxication as an indication for brain imaging; therefore, a CT head scan is recommended under such circumstances. Similarly, the patient should be treated with IV thiamine."},{"id":"8054","category":"Neurology and ophthalmology","stem":"A 72-year-old woman presents with a one-hour history of weakness of the left face and arm. The MAU team suspect a stroke, and imaging is requested.\n\nWhich of the following are the features of acute stroke on neuroimaging?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"Understanding imaging in acute stroke is important to all stroke physicians, radiologists and acute physicians. Currently, non-contrast CT is the primary imaging modality for acute stroke in the UK. The three descriptions of stroke are acute (<24 hours); subacute 24 hours to 5 days and chronic >5 days. Acute changes are evident as loss of the grey-white matter interface and effacement of the cortical sulci. Subacute changes are illustrated by vasogenic oedema with greater mass effect, hypoattenuation and well-delineated margins. Chronic changes are seen as a loss of brain tissue and hypoattenuation. So, a non-contrast CT might reveal features of stroke, but would reveal evidence of bleed. There is a sensitivity of roughly 55% for acute stroke with CT, but high specificity (>90%). Subacute changes (>24hrs) are better detected by MRI than CT; however, MR with diffusion (DWI) improves sensitivity from 50% to 90%, with restricted diffusion being highly suggestive of stroke."},{"id":"8057","category":"Neurology and ophthalmology","stem":"A 72-year-old woman is admitted with a 3 – 4 hour history of right arm and facial weakness. CT scan reveals no haemorrhage and is suggestive of acute ischaemia. She is treated with IV thrombolysis.\n\nWhich of the following is true of IV thrombolysis in acute stroke?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"According to the results of the National Institute of Neurological Disorders and Stroke (NINDS) study group, at least 30% of patients treated with IV rt-PA continue their lives with a mild deficit or no deficit after three months. Time matters, and the swifter the thrombolysis is undertaken, the better the outcome. In this patient’s case, 3-4 hrs after the onset of symptoms, the above full recovery process can be expected. Data suggest the risk of intracerebral haemorrhage is 5-7%. This data suggests that there is no difference between placebo and IV thrombolysis in 90-day mortality. The Rankin score is used to assess functional recovery after a stroke."},{"id":"18617","category":"Neurology and ophthalmology","stem":"A 35-year-old woman with refractory epilepsy is on phenytoin monotherapy. She presents with a 2-day history of diplopia, dizziness, and gait instability. She denies any recent illness, trauma, or changes in medication, but mentions that she has been skipping meals due to stress at work.\n\nOn examination, she is alert but has difficulty with heel-to-toe walking and bilateral horizontal gaze-evoked nystagmus. Her vitals are within normal limits.\n\nLaboratory findings show a phenytoin level of 20 mg/L (10-20), normal liver enzymes with an albumin of 30 g/dL (35-45), and CRP of 5 mg/dl (<5). Her previous phenytoin levels have always been within the therapeutic range.\n\nWhich of the following factors is most likely contributing to her current presentation?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"In this case, the patient displays features of phenytoin toxicity, despite the high but normal phenytoin level. This is likely due to reduced protein binding of phenytoin due to low albumin, leading to increased free drug. Phenytoin is highly protein-bound, and hypoalbuminemia can increase the free (active) fraction of the drug, leading to symptoms of toxicity even when total serum levels are not greatly elevated."},{"id":"8977","category":"Neurology and ophthalmology","stem":"A 55-year-old woman presents to the acute medical unit following a generalised tonic-clonic seizure. 4 days before this seizure, she had developed a flu-like illness with cough and fever, which was associated with increasing drowsiness. More recently, she had been agitated and aggressive when roused. She was previously well and was taking no medication.\n\nOn examination, her pulse was 100 bpm reg, blood pressure 128/76 mmHg, her temperature was 37.5oC, and her respiratory rate was 18/min with sats of 97% on air. She had a Glasgow Coma Scale of 10 (E3, V2, M5) and was moving all four limbs.\n\nInvestigations showed a normal full blood count, U&E's and LFTs with calcium of 2.2 mmol/L (2.2-2.6) and glucose of 3.8 mmol/L (3.5-5.5). Her chest x-ray was normal, and blood cultures were sent.\n\nCT of the brain revealed bilateral subtle diffuse hypodensity within the medial temporal lobes, which was more evident on the right.\n\nWhat is the most appropriate initial management for this patient?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Investigations showed a normal full blood count, U&E's and LFTs with calcium of 2.2 mmol/L (2.2-2.6) and glucose of 3.8 mmol/L (3.5-5.5). Her chest x-ray was normal, and blood cultures were sent.","CT of the brain revealed bilateral subtle diffuse hypodensity within the medial temporal lobes, which was more evident on the right.","What is the most appropriate initial management for this patient?","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"and intravenous aciclovir commenced","explanation":"This woman has an acute presentation of initial flu-like illness, increasing obtundation culminating in a fit. Imaging reveals bilateral temporal lobe hypodensities, and together this suggests acute encephalitis most likely due to herpes simplex virus (HSV). Another possibility is COVID-19 encephalitis, although this is less likely based on the normal CXR and absence of respiratory features. A lumbar puncture (LP) should be performed and intravenous aciclovir commenced."},{"id":"8411","category":"Neurology and ophthalmology","stem":"A 35-year-old woman with alcoholic cirrhosis is admitted with deteriorating confusion and ascites. On examination, she appears slightly jaundiced, has a temperature of 37.5oC, and is agitated and confused. There is a flapping tremor of the outstretched hands. Abdominal examination reveals tense ascites.\n\nInvestigations reveal:\n\nAn ascitic tap is undertaken, which reveals a polymorphonuclear cell count of 350 cells per mm3 and protein of 32 g/L.\n\nWhich of the following is the most appropriate treatment for this patient?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Liou, I. W. Price, J. Recognition and Management of Spontaneous Bacterial Peritonitis. Hepatitis C, 2021.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"This patient has spontaneous bacterial peritonitis (SBP) as suggested by the typical history, ascites and raised polymorphonuclear count within the ascitic tap, which appears to have precipitated the hepatic encephalopathy. It is most commonly seen in alcoholic cirrhosis, and the causative organism is usually E. Coli, Klebsiella, S. Pneumoniae or Enterococci. (Compare this with the mixed growth seen in other forms of peritonitis). Sending some ascitic fluid in blood culture bottles increases the yield. Initial treatment is with broad-spectrum antibiotics such as cefotaxime. Norfloxacin is recommended for short-term prophylaxis."},{"id":"9990","category":"Neurology and ophthalmology","stem":"A 70-year-old man is admitted complaining of involuntary movements on the left side of the body. These symptoms have deteriorated over the last 3 weeks. He has a 10-year history of type-2 diabetes for which he takes ramipril 10 mg/d, metformin 1g bd, sitagliptin 100 mg/d, and atorvastatin 20 mg daily.\n\nOn examination, his pulse is 80 bpm regular, and his blood pressure is 136/88 mmHg. He has writhing movements on the left limbs with some occasional left arm and leg flinging movements. Neurological examination is otherwise normal, with flexor plantars and normal reflexes.\n\nWhich of the following is the likely diagnosis?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Investigations:","Investigation\tResult\tNormal range","FBC\tNormal","U+Es\tNormal","Glucose\t25.9 mmol/L\t3.5-5.5 mmol/L","HbA1c","88 mmol/mol","CT head report\tEvidence of small vessel disease.\nNil acute","Blood ketones\t0.5 mmol/L\t<0.6","Which of the following is the likely diagnosis?","Al Montasir, A. and Sadik, M.H., 2013. Hemichorea-hemiballism in a nonketotic diabetic patient. Journal of Family Medicine and Primary Care, 2(3), p.296.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"FBC\tNormal","explanation":"This is a typical history of the rare but well-described non-ketotic hyperglycaemic (diabetic) hemi-chorea hemi-ballism syndrome characterised by continuous, irregular, and involuntary jerky movements of one side of the body, often the result of a focal lesion of the contralateral basal ganglia. The condition is associated with poor glycaemic control, as in this case, and improved glycaemic control is associated with improvement and resolution of symptoms. The pathophysiology of the disorder is associated with relative ischaemia, possibly a result of hyperviscosity within the striatum. A CT scan may be normal or reveal densities in the putamen/arcuate nucleus, so an MRI is often required and demonstrates T1 hyperintensity in the contralateral putamen."},{"id":"7208","category":"Neurology and ophthalmology","stem":"A 26-year-old woman presents to the emergency department with a 2-week history of headaches (VAS 6-7/10). A collateral history from her partner reveals that for the last 5 days, she has been excessively \"sleepy and tired\". She is a smoker (10 cigarettes per day for the last 7 years) and has taken the combined oral contraceptive pill for two years, but otherwise, her history is unremarkable. Her mother had a DVT after a 4-hour flight at the age of 38.\n\nOn examination, she is drowsy (GCS 13/15 – E3: V4: M6). There is no neck stiffness, but she is mildly photophobic, with mild left-sided weakness (4/5). Fundoscopy is normal, and there are no other neurological findings. Body temperature is 37.4 oC; respiratory rate is 18; her blood pressure is 108/76 mmHg; heart rate is 91 beats per minute; Sats (on room air) is 97%.\n\nBlood tests reveal the following results:\n\nA CT brain with CT venogram reveals a hypodensity in the right parietal region with gyriform hyperdense areas within the hypodensity; findings in keeping with a venous stroke and moderately extensive secondary haemorrhage. Filling defects in the sagittal sinus are consistent with cerebral venous thrombosis. There is no midline shift.\n\nWhat is the most appropriate treatment option?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Blood tests reveal the following results:","Investigation\tResult\tNormal range\nWBC\t13.2 x 109/L\t4.5 - 11.0 x 109/L\nd-dimer\t974 ng/ml\t<230 ng/ml\nCRP\t36 mg/L\t<8 mg/L","What is the most appropriate treatment option?","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"Even in the presence of haemorrhage, anticoagulation is recommended for treatment of cerebral venous thrombosis. The rationale is to prevent thrombus extension, to facilitate recanalisation and to prevent DVT or PE. Initial anticoagulation is usually weight-based low molecular weight heparin or an adjusted dose of unfractionated heparin followed by vitamin K antagonists."},{"id":"7881","category":"Neurology and ophthalmology","stem":"A 50-year-old man is seen in the medical assessment unit as he has become agitated and confused. He was admitted 5 days ago with acute alcohol intoxication and was found on the street by passers-by. He was admitted and has been receiving supported withdrawal from alcohol in the form of chlordiazepoxide. He has been fine and cooperative until today, with the nurses noting a particular deterioration.\n\nOn examination, he is thin with a BMI of 20 kg/m2, confused and agitated with a GCS of 14. His temperature is 35.3°C, pulse is 110 bpm regular, and blood pressure is 100/65 mmHg. Neurological examination reveals general hyperreflexivity and equivocal plantar responses.\n\nWhich of the following is the most likely cause for this presentation?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"This patient, who appears malnourished and has a history of alcohol abuse, presents with a deterioration of consciousness whilst in hospital with features of confusion, agitation and hypothermia. These features suggest early onset Wernicke’s encephalopathy, and this needs to be diagnosed and treated adequately with IV thiamine if the progression to Korsakoff psychosis is to be potentially avoided. The patient may then progress to ophthalmoplegia, quadriparesis and permanent brain injury."},{"id":"3985","category":"Neurology and ophthalmology","stem":"A 79-year-old woman is admitted with left-sided weakness that had developed over the last two to three days. Three weeks ago, she fell on compacted sand on the beach while playing with her grandchildren and hit her head. She reports remaining conscious but was slightly confused. She had a headache afterwards but seemed to recover. She was otherwise fit and well and took no medication.\n\nOn examination, GCS is 15, she had mild left-sided weakness of arm and leg 4/5 with an equivocal plantar response.\n\nCT head scan revealed a right-sided chronic subdural haematoma with some compression of the right ventricle but no midline shift.\n\nWhich of the following is the most appropriate management plan for this patient?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"This patient has a chronic subdural haematoma and associated hemiparesis, which has developed over 3 weeks. The patient should be referred to neurosurgery and treated with burr hole evacuation. In chronic subdural with no midline shift and symptoms such as headache, then observation with re-scanning can be undertaken. However, this patient has developed a significant neurological deficit despite the lack of midline shift and surgery is required."},{"id":"12020","category":"Neurology and ophthalmology","stem":"A 69-year-old man with metastatic prostate cancer is complaining of increased back pain. A previous bone scan showed multiple hot spots throughout his axial skeleton. On examination, he has reduced ability to dorsiflex his right ankle or extend his big toe. He has normal light touch sensation but reduced pinprick sensation over his right knee and outer calf.\n\nYou are concerned about his new symptoms and have contacted the on-call radiologist about arranging an urgent MRI scan.\n\nThe radiologist asks you, \"At what spinal level are you concerned that there may be a problem?\".\n\nWhat would be the most appropriate response?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"The history and examination raise concerns for nerve root or impending malignant spinal cord compression at L4/L5. Ankle dorsiflexion is associated with the L4 myotome, and toe extension with L5. The L4 dermatome is from the outer lower thigh down the anterior of the lower leg medially to the ankle, and L5 from the outer calf to the foot. An MRI would be the investigation of choice to visualise the spinal cord and nerve roots."},{"id":"7206","category":"Neurology and ophthalmology","stem":"A 48-year-old woman with a history of migraine presents to the emergency department. She describes a 2-day history of headaches. Initially, over-the-counter analgesia had provided a degree of relief. However, on the second day, she experienced the worst headache of her life, located in the occiput and associated with vomiting. On examination, she is distressed and has tachycardia. There are no focal neurological deficits. A CT scan shows a subarachnoid haemorrhage, and she is referred to the neurosurgical team for further investigation and management.\n\nConcerning the investigation of subarachnoid haemorrhage, how long after the headache onset should a lumbar puncture ideally be performed?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"A ‘thunderclap’ headache warrants consideration of subarachnoid haemorrhage, and may be preceded by a ‘sentinel headache’. The traditional investigation route includes a plain CT head scan, with or without lumbar puncture, and cerebral angiography in the face of remaining diagnostic uncertainty."},{"id":"8905","category":"Neurology and ophthalmology","stem":"A 35-year-old woman presents to the emergency department with a deteriorating headache. For at least the last year, she has had headaches on and off, but she feels these have deteriorated over the last few months. The headaches are constant and are sometimes associated with a change in vision and occasional flickering lights. She is aware of the headache when she wakes, and it deteriorates as the day progresses. Her pain used to be relieved by paracetamol, which she used to take intermittently, but she has been taking this regularly for the last few months, together with caffeine and codeine, in the form of a combined medication. She admits that work has been more problematic of late, and she works at a computer in reception. She has had her eyes tested and now wears glasses, but the headaches continue to get worse.\n\nOn examination, she has a pulse of 80 bpm, temperature 36.5oC, a blood pressure of 122/80 mmHg and a BMI of 31 kg/m2. There was some tenderness over the trapezius muscles bilaterally, but there was no nuchal rigidity. Her fundal examination revealed normal-appearing discs, though it was difficult to assess for venous pulsation as the patient did not like the light. Tone, bulk power coordination and reflexes were otherwise normal.\n\nInvestigations reveal normal FBC, U+Es and LFTs.\n\nCT head scan is reported as normal.\n\nWhat is the most likely explanation of her presentation?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Kristoffersen, E.S. and Lundqvist, C. (2014) ‘Medication-overuse headache: epidemiology, diagnosis and treatment’, Therapeutic advances in drug safety, 5(2), pp.87-99.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"This is a typical presentation of rebound headache, otherwise termed medication overuse headache (MOH). It is associated with regular and prolonged use of analgesics to treat headaches such as migraines. MOH is a headache occurring on 15 or more days per month, developing as a consequence of regular overuse of acute or symptomatic headache medication (on 10 or more (opiates), or 15 or more (non-opiates) days per month, for more than 3 months. It usually, but not invariably, resolves after the overuse is stopped."},{"id":"8971","category":"Neurology and ophthalmology","stem":"A 25-year-old female presents to the acute medical unit with a headache and confusion. 2-3 weeks before admission, she had a mild coryzal illness with a cough and sore throat, though symptoms resolved within about a week. She took no medication, and her family, who were present, confirmed that she did not use illicit drugs.\n\nOn examination, she had a temperature of 37oC, a pulse of 80 bpm regular and a blood pressure of 122/80 mmHg. She was mildly confused with no focal neurology. Her BMI was 26.8 kg/m2.\n\nFBC, U+Es, LFTs were normal. CRP was 6.8 mg/dl (<5).\n\nA contrast MRI scan of the brain revealed numerous lesions in the cerebral white matter, thalami and basal ganglia. Cerebrospinal fluid analysis showed 40 white cells (100% lymphocytes) per microlitre and a CSF protein of 0.48 g/L (0.15-0.45). Oligoclonal bands were negative.\n\nWhat is the most likely diagnosis?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","FBC, U+Es, LFTs were normal. CRP was 6.8 mg/dl (<5).","What is the most likely diagnosis?","Cleavland Clinic: Acute Disseminated Encephalomyelitis (ADEM).","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"What is the most likely diagnosis?","explanation":"This young woman has developed an acute encephalitic illness, and the preceding coryzal illness is relevant. Together with the multiple enhancing MRI lesions, the most probable diagnosis is acute disseminated encephalomyelitis. The clinical presentation is atypical for multiple sclerosis and neuromyelitis optica (NMO) spectrum disorder, while myelin oligodendrocyte glycoprotein antibody disease is less commonly seen. This is not the picture for other neuro-inflammatory disorders either, such as neurosarcoidosis, where leptomeningeal disease is likely or indeed Neuro-Behçet disease, where features like oro-genital ulcers, rash or arthralgia would be expected. Similarly, this would not be typical of acute Lyme disease, and one might expect other symptoms such as fever with rash."},{"id":"20205","category":"Neurology and ophthalmology","stem":"A 42-year-old woman presents to the acute medical unit with a 12-hour history of right-sided facial weakness and inability to close her right eye. She reports no preceding trauma or systemic symptoms. She is otherwise well with no past medical history of note.\n\nOn examination, she has complete right-sided lower motor neurone facial weakness affecting both the upper and lower face, with loss of forehead wrinkles and inability to raise the right eyebrow. Examination of the ear canal is normal. There are no other cranial nerve abnormalities and no limb weakness.\n\nWhat is the most appropriate initial management?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Bell's palsy is a clinical diagnosis when the presentation is typical.","Evidence does not support the routine addition of antiviral therapy to corticosteroids for uncomplicated Bell's palsy.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"Bell's palsy is a clinical diagnosis when the presentation is typical.","explanation":"Bell's palsy is a clinical diagnosis when the presentation is typical."},{"id":"13721","category":"Neurology and ophthalmology","stem":"A 43-year-old woman was admitted with right-sided weakness, disorientation, and confusion. Her computed tomography (CT) angiogram demonstrates a subarachnoid haemorrhage from an aneurysm that would be amenable to treatment with coiling or clipping. Her systolic blood pressure (SBP) is 154 mmHg.\n\nWhat is the recommended immediate treatment for this patient?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"the recommended first line of treatment","explanation":"While the exact mechanism is unknown, nimodipine is thought to have a significant role in preventing vasospasm and thereby delaying ischaemia. It's given immediately while the work-up for surgical coiling takes place. Securing the aneurysm is the next best step to perform as soon as possible. Coiling and clipping are both technically feasible interventions; however, coiling is associated with better neurological outcomes and is, therefore, the recommended first line of treatment. Antihypertensives are recommended to maintain SBP < 160 mmHg, and phenytoin is not recommended for seizure prophylaxis."},{"id":"3695","category":"Neurology and ophthalmology","stem":"A 67-year-old woman was admitted with a 3-day history of diplopia and clumsiness. She had been feeling unwell a week previously with a fever and flu-like illness, and the symptoms of double vision and difficulty walking had developed over the last 3 days. She had a background history of hypothyroidism for which she took thyroxine and also had a 3-year history of type-2 diabetes for which she took metformin 1g bd.\n\nOn examination, she was orientated, had a temperature of 37 oC and blood pressure of 142/82 mmHg with a pulse of 80 beats per minute, regular. She had weakness of abduction and adduction of the eyes with dilated and unreactive pupils, together with bilateral facial weakness of the upper and lower face. There was also ataxia with difficulty standing upright and impaired finger-to-nose testing. Deep tendon reflexes were impaired, though muscle strength was normal, and there was no impairment of sensation.\n\nWhich of the following is the likely diagnosis?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"This patient has a previous flu-like illness and has developed diplopia, facial weakness and ataxia. The diagnosis based on the history and examination is likely to be Miller Fisher syndrome, a variant of Guillain-Barré. Miller-Fisher is associated with the three features of ataxia, ophthalmoplegia and loss of tendon reflexes. Diagnosis is based on the typical history and examination and is supported by acellular CSF with protein elevation."},{"id":"10814","category":"Neurology and ophthalmology","stem":"A 55-year-old woman attends the medical assessment unit complaining of a deteriorating headache. The headache began 3 days ago, she describes it as being all over with pressure behind the eyes and feels that the intensity is 8 out of 10. She has no other past medical history of note. She takes no medication. She had a SARS-CoV-2 adenovirus vector vaccine approximately 2 weeks ago.\n\nOn examination, she has a GCS of 15, a pulse of 88 beats per minute, regular, a blood pressure of 136/88 mmHg with a temperature of 36.7oC. There is no neck stiffness, but some mild photophobia is present with no focal neurology. Fundal examination reveals no specific abnormalities.\n\nInvestigations reveal:\n\nWhich of the following is the likely diagnosis in this patient?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"and assessed with CT","explanation":"This patient has a thrombocytopaenia associated with headache 2 weeks after receiving the ChAdOx1 nCoV-19 (AstraZeneca) SARS-CoV-2 vaccine, hence a diagnosis of cerebral venous sinus thrombosis due to vaccine-induced thrombocytopaenic thrombosis should be considered and assessed with CT. The diagnosis of VITT can be supported by measuring antibodies to PF-4. Treatment with IV immunoglobulin plus high-dose glucocorticoids can improve the outcome, together with anticoagulation with non-heparin-based anticoagulation, such as argatroban or fondaparinux."},{"id":"3761","category":"Neurology and ophthalmology","stem":"A 60-year-old man presents with a 3-week history of dysphasia and progressive right arm weakness. He has had headaches for 2 months. There is no history of seizures. There is no other history of note.\n\nOn admission, he is confused with a GCS of 14. Pulse is 88 beats per minute, regular, blood pressure 130/78 mmHg, and temperature is 37oC. He had grade 3 power in the right upper limb, but no other deficit. Blood investigations are normal, and the chest X-ray is normal. A CT brain with contrast demonstrates a 5cm irregular enhancing lesion in the left frontal lobe, consistent with a primary brain tumour with surrounding oedema.\n\nWhich of the following is the most appropriate initial management for this patient?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"The most appropriate initial treatment for this man, who has a reduced GCS associated with a likely tumour, is attempting to reduce the associated swelling with dexamethasone, which is the first-line medication for this purpose. He may need antiepileptics if he starts having any seizures."},{"id":"8409","category":"Neurology and ophthalmology","stem":"A 40-year-old man has a 10-year history of chronic alcohol abuse and presents to medical admissions with confusion, agitation and ataxia. He was found wandering the streets at 2 a.m. and was brought in by the police. He had been admitted on numerous occasions previously, all related to alcohol abuse.\n\nOn examination, he was unkempt, confused and smelled of alcohol. His GCS was 14 and he was disoriented in time and place with a mini-mental score of 18/30. His temperature was 37.2 oC, pulse was 80 bpm and blood pressure was 140/82 mmHg. He had bilateral 6th nerve palsies with bilateral gaze nystagmus and was ataxic.\n\nWhich of the following would be the most appropriate treatment for this patient?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"immediately in such a scenario","explanation":"The most likely diagnosis is Wernicke-Korsakoff encephalopathy. It is characterised by confusion, ataxia and gaze palsies. Intravenous thiamine should be given immediately in such a scenario. The commonest cause is chronic alcohol abuse."},{"id":"18610","category":"Neurology and ophthalmology","stem":"A 48-year-old man with a history of seizure disorder is brought to the emergency department with ataxia and nystagmus. He has been on phenytoin therapy for the past 10 years with recent dose adjustments due to breakthrough seizures. He also has a recent diagnosis of type 2 diabetes. His other medications include atorvastatin 20 mg daily, vitamin D 1000 IU daily, and metformin 1g twice daily.\n\nOn examination, he exhibits horizontal nystagmus, a positive Romberg sign, and bilateral symmetrical tremors of the hands. His vitals are stable.\n\nInitial blood tests show normal FBC, renal function, thyroid function and electrolytes. His phenytoin level is reported as 32 mg/L (therapeutic range: 10-20 mg/L). An MRI scan of the brain is unremarkable.\n\nWhich of the following is the most likely cause of this patient’s phenytoin toxicity?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"Long-term use of phenytoin leads to zero-order kinetics. Phenytoin is known for its nonlinear kinetics; as doses increase, it can saturate the liver enzymes responsible for its metabolism, leading to disproportionate increases in drug levels with small dose changes."},{"id":"14110","category":"Neurology and ophthalmology","stem":"A 36-year-old woman is brought to the acute medicine unit in the evening with a 1-hour history of sudden-onset left arm and left leg weakness associated with slurring of speech. Her partner says that since the morning, she has been experiencing severe headaches with numbness in her limbs. He says that she is prone to frequent headaches and uses over-the-counter ibuprofen for relief. About a year ago, the patient had a similar episode of left-sided limb weakness, which, according to reports, was treated with alteplase with complete resolution of her symptoms. She has been taking regular aspirin 75 mg, and atorvastatin 40 mg since.\n\nOn examination, the patient is alert with facial asymmetry and dysarthria. She has a pulse rate of 75 beats per minute, a blood pressure of 140/80 mmHg, and a respiratory rate of 12 breaths per minute with oxygen saturation on air of 99%. The patient has a temperature of 37oC. No leg oedema is noted.\n\nRespiratory system examination reveals normal breath sounds on both sides.\n\nCardiovascular system examination reveals normal heart sounds.\n\nThe abdomen is soft with no tenderness, and there are active bowel sounds.\n\nNervous system examination shows power 1/5 in the left upper and lower limbs with right-sided facial deviation.\n\nNo cranial nerve deficits were noted.\n\nAn emergency CT scan of the brain is done, which is reported as normal. The calculated NIH stroke scale is 9.\n\nInvestigation results are as follows:\n\nWhat would be the most appropriate course of action?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","The abdomen is soft with no tenderness, and there are active bowel sounds.","No cranial nerve deficits were noted.","An emergency CT scan of the brain is done, which is reported as normal. The calculated NIH stroke scale is 9.","Investigation results are as follows:","What would be the most appropriate course of action?","Current guidelines (2023) advocate urgent CTA in anyone with acute stroke symptoms (especially anterior circulation presentation) and an NIHSS >6.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"Current guidelines (2023) advocate urgent CTA in anyone with acute stroke symptoms (especially anterior circulation presentation) and an NIHSS >6.","explanation":"Current guidelines (2023) advocate urgent CTA in anyone with acute stroke symptoms (especially anterior circulation presentation) and an NIHSS >6."},{"id":"4653","category":"Neurology and ophthalmology","stem":"A 55-year-old man presents with a 1-day history of weakness of the left side of his face and drooling. Other than a 2-year history of type-2 diabetes mellitus, he has been well. He currently takes ramipril, simvastatin and metformin. He has recently commenced empagliflozin.\n\nOn examination, he had weakness of the lower and upper face and was unable to raise his eyebrows or purse his lips. There was no abnormality of the ear canal, nor were there any other abnormalities of the cranial nerves. His blood pressure is 132/88 mmHg, and his pulse is 88 beats per minute, regular.\n\nInvestigations reveal:\n\nWhich of the following is most appropriate concerning the management of this patient?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"This man has developed an abrupt onset of VII nerve palsy, which is isolated and unilateral - the most likely diagnosis is Bell’s Palsy. The guidance recommends treatment with oral corticosteroids at a dose of 1mg/kg/day for 7–10 days, within 72 hours of onset, as evidence would suggest improved prognosis and speedier resolution with steroids. There is no requirement for CT/MRI if there are no other features to suggest CPA involvement, and poor glycaemic control in itself does not cause a Lower VII palsy."},{"id":"18603","category":"Neurology and ophthalmology","stem":"A 68-year-old woman was admitted with a fall. She had had numerous admissions with falls over the last year and, at her last admission 2 months ago, she had an evacuation of a right-sided chronic subdural haematoma performed under the neurosurgeons. However, this had not helped her unsteadiness. On this occasion, she fell again at home, injuring her arm, and the family are not happy that her unsteadiness persists.\n\nShe has a long medical history, which includes the excision of a prolactinoma some 30 years earlier. This had resulted in partial hypopituitarism, where she required female hormone replacement therapy (HRT) (stopped 12 years ago), growth hormone (stopped 12 years ago), hydrocortisone 10 mg twice daily (bd), and DDAVP 10 mcg bd. Following surgery 30 years ago, she also had seizures and was commenced on phenytoin 300 mg daily. She also takes amlodipine 5 mg daily for blood pressure and oral vitamin D 1000 IU daily. She has not had any seizures over the last 3 years, despite her recent subdural haematoma. She denies drinking alcohol; however, she used to smoke around 10 cigarettes daily, stopping 8 years ago.\n\nOn examination, she has a BMI of 25 kg/m2, a pulse of 60 beats per minute, regular, blood pressure of 110/80 mmHg, and a temperature of 37oC. On physical examination, the only abnormalities noted were on neurological examination, where she is walking unsteadily and has some sustained bilateral nystagmus.\n\nInvestigations reveal the following results:\n\nWhich of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"Bilateral nystagmus in a patient on phenytoin is most consistent with phenytoin toxicity. Serum levels would confirm the likely diagnosis. The other scenarios are unlikely. Vitamin D toxicity would be associated with hypercalcaemia. There is no specific evidence of underlying Ca, but cerebellar syndrome with this is possible. Gait dyspraxia is also possible, but the cerebellar features would argue against this. The low sodium is not sufficient for a diagnosis of hyponatraemic encephalopathy. The mild hyponatraemia would fit with underlying bronchial Ca, but again, there is nothing to suggest this diagnosis, and with the patient on DDAVP, a slight over-treatment is the most plausible explanation."},{"id":"7205","category":"Neurology and ophthalmology","stem":"A 25-year-old female presents to Accident and Emergency with involuntary movements. Past medical history includes several bouts of depressive illness and an episode of psychosis. On examination, Kayser-Fleischer rings are noted in the eyes. Dystonic movements affecting the right upper limb, a postural tremor, as well as a mildly ataxic gait, are also noted. Blood tests reveal derangement of her liver function tests.\n\nWhich of the following statements is correct about this disorder?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Rorriguez-Castro KI, Hevia-Urrutia JF, Sturniolo GC. Wilson’s disease: a review of what we have learned. World J Hepatol 2015;7:2859-2870.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"Wilson’s disease is an autosomal recessive disorder of copper metabolism, resulting from a mutation in the adenosine triphosphate 7B gene (ATP7B) on chromosome 13. Subsequent impairment in copper excretion into bile contributes to copper accumulation in organs such as the brain and liver. Neurological features include movement disorders such as Parkinsonism, tremor, dystonia and ataxia. Psychiatric features range from behavioural disturbances to mood disorders such as depression, as well as psychosis. Biochemical investigations yield reduced serum caeruloplasmin and increased serum and 24-hour urinary copper. Examples of treatment strategies include a low copper diet, D-penicillamine and zinc supplementation."},{"id":"7920","category":"Neurology and ophthalmology","stem":"A 70-year-old man attends the medical assessment unit with a 2-day history of severe lower back pain and clumsiness in his legs. In his previous history, he had undergone thoracic surgery for a left lower lobe squamous carcinoma of the lung. He was not aware of any metastatic disease and had been well.\n\nOn examination, he had a pulse of 88 bpm regular, a blood pressure of 128/90 mmHg and a temperature of 37.5°C. He has some tenderness over the lumbar spine. Examination of the lower limbs revealed slightly reduced power in both legs (grade 4/5) with no sensory loss. Reflexes were preserved with an equivocal plantar response.\n\nWhich of the following is the most appropriate approach to the management of this patient?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"This patient has features of spinal cord compression likely due to metastases associated with severe back pain and weakness. This is a clinical emergency, and the diagnosis needs to be established with an urgent MRI, but commencing high-dose steroids such as 16 mg dexamethasone to endeavour to reduce any associated swelling."},{"id":"8906","category":"Neurology and ophthalmology","stem":"A 24-year-old woman is referred to acute admissions with a 2-week history of unsteadiness of gait and numbness in her feet. She has been aware of paresthesia and deteriorating weakness for a few months, but feels that this has deteriorated more in the last 2 weeks. She provides no medical history of note. Her menstrual cycle is regular as she uses a combined OCP. She smokes very occasionally and drinks 10 units weekly, more so, binge drinking. She also admits to illicit drug intake.\n\nOn examination, her BMI is 23kg/m2, she has a pulse of 80 bpm regular, blood pressure of 116/76 mmHg, and temperature of 37 oC. She has some unsteadiness on standing, with some gait ataxia. She has loss of peripheral sensation in her feet up to mid tibia and reduced proprioception in both feet. Ankle reflex is absent, and her knee reflexes are exaggerated. She has a similar peripheral neuropathy in her hands.\n\nWhat is the likely cause for her presentation?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Treatment is with high doses of daily, SC or oral vitamin B12.","Stockton, L., Simonsen, C., Seago, S. (2017) ‘Nitrous oxide–induced vitamin B12 deficiency’, Baylor University, Medical Centre, 30(2), 171–172. NCBI.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"This young woman has features of subacute combined degeneration of the cord, due to vitamin B12 deficiency, which is low. The likely diagnosis from those listed in this young woman is chronic nitrous oxide abuse - balloons, which has caused vitamin B12 deficiency. This is often overlooked in a patient's history and needs to be thoroughly questioned. Chronic nitrous oxide oxidises cobalamin to the inactive bivalent form, resulting in a functional vitamin B12 deficiency. Occasionally, B12 concentrations may be normal, yet the neurological features are profound. However, methionine and methylmalonic acid levels are typically elevated."},{"id":"3939","category":"Neurology and ophthalmology","stem":"A 30-year-old woman was transferred from the psychiatric unit to the medical unit with acute confusion. She had been admitted two weeks previously under psychiatry with agitation, auditory hallucinations and catatonia. There was no previous history of note, and she was otherwise well and taking the combined oral contraceptive pill. She was initially commenced on fluoxetine, which failed to improve her condition and then commenced on olanzapine.\n\nOn examination, she was agitated and confused. GCS was 15 and her temperature was 37oC. Her pulse was 88 beats per minute and her blood pressure was 122/88 mmHg. There was no focal neurology, and her reflexes were normal with downgoing plantar responses.\n\nRoutine bloods were normal. CT and MRI scans of the head were reported as normal, and her lumbar results revealed:\n\nWhich of the following is the likely diagnosis?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Routine bloods were normal. CT and MRI scans of the head were reported as normal, and her lumbar results revealed:","Investigation\tResult\tNormal range","Protein\t0.44 g/L\t<0.45","Glucose\t3.7 mmol/L\t>3.5 mmol/L","White cell count","Which of the following is the likely diagnosis?","Shimazaki, H., 2011. Clinical aspects of anti-NMDA receptor encephalitis. Pathogenesis of Encephalitis. New York: InTech, pp.255-66.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"This patient displays typical features of anti-NMDA (N-methyl D-aspartate) receptor encephalitis, presenting with subacute agitation, confusion, and psychiatric symptoms such as hallucinations and catatonia. The condition affects young females in particular and is often paraneoplastic in aetiology, being associated with ovarian tumours. It is treated by identifying any paraneoplastic precipitant and immune therapy – immune globulin and steroids. The condition is diagnosed by demonstrating the antibodies in the cerebrospinal fluid."},{"id":"10846","category":"Neurology and ophthalmology","stem":"A 76-year-old female presents to the MAU with a 4-day history of deteriorating weakness in the legs and paraesthesia. Two weeks previously, she had received the AZ COVID-19 vaccine. In her past medical history, she had a 5-year history of hypertension for which she was treated with losartan and bendrofluazide. She also had a diagnosis of asthma and had been prescribed a steroid inhaler, which she used once daily.\n\nOn examination, she had a temperature of 36.7oC, a pulse of 88 beats per minute, a blood pressure of 128/82 mmHg and a respiratory rate of 18 breaths per minute. She had weakness of the lower limbs 3-4/5, reduced tone, absent plantar, ankle and knee reflexes, but normal sensation to pinprick and light touch. There was also weakness in 4/5 of the upper limbs and loss of biceps and triceps reflexes. Co-ordination appeared intact, and the cranial nerves were normal.\n\nInvestigations revealed the following:\n\nWhich of the following is the likely diagnosis?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","GOV.UK - Guidance - Information for healthcare professionals on Guillain-Barré Syndrome (GBS) following COVID-19 vaccination. Updated 17 December 2021.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"The likely diagnosis with the dissociated ascending motor polyneuropathy with no features of sensory loss is Guillain-Barré, likely due to COVID-19 in the absence of any other obvious cause. This has been rarely reported, but the features here are typical of GBS, as are the LP findings with a dissociated elevation of protein. Hypokalaemic periodic paralysis is unlikely, as the history is very different, with a much shorter episodic weakness. The mild hypokalaemia with hyponatraemia is likely due to the bendrofluazide."},{"id":"4654","category":"Neurology and ophthalmology","stem":"A 55-year-old man presents with a 1-day history of left-sided facial weakness. He had been admitted to the hospital 2 weeks previously under ENT with otitis media requiring IV antibiotics. He had presented with severe left earache and fever. He had had a CT scan at this other centre, which was reported as unremarkable. He had made a good recovery and was discharged after 3 days with a course of oral augmentin. He had made a good recovery and had been aware of some earache, although this was much better than before. There was nothing else of note in his medical history.\n\nOn examination, he had a temperature of 37 oC, a blood pressure of 132/80 mmHg, and a pulse of 62 beats per minute. He had evidence of left upper and lower facial muscle weakness, but no other cranial nerve involvement was noted. Otherwise, balance was preserved, and there were no cerebellar features. He had some cotton wool in his left ear, and there was some reduction in hearing in this ear; an attempt to visualise the ear canal with an otoscope was unsuccessful as there appeared to be some fluid.\n\nWhich of the following is the most appropriate approach to the management of this patient?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"This patient has a history of severe otitis media requiring admission, and he has since developed a left isolated VII lower motor neurone palsy. Whilst Bell’s palsy is a potential diagnosis, this cannot be purely attributed to Bell’s, and one has to consider temporal bone erosion and dehiscence within the fallopian canal of the temporal bone, within which the facial nerve resides. A CT scan would probably provide the most appropriate imaging, and the patient needs to be referred to ENT. Deterioration can result in Gradenigo’s syndrome, which is the involvement of the VIth cranial nerve and periorbital pain due to involvement of the Vth."},{"id":"8060","category":"Neurology and ophthalmology","stem":"A female patient presents to acute admissions with features of acute stroke, which is confirmed with diffusion-weighted MRI with evidence of a clot.\n\nWhich of the following would be the most appropriate indication for thrombectomy in this patient?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"Indications for thrombectomy for ischaemic stroke would be clots evident in the anterior cerebral circulation, where the patient has had these symptoms for less than 24 hours. While a contra-indication to thrombolysis might be considered to be an indication, it is not necessarily the best indicator on this list for thrombectomy. Another indicator in patients with anterior circulation stroke would be an NIHSS of 6 or above. Age represents no specific contraindication."},{"id":"7752","category":"Neurology and ophthalmology","stem":"A 20-year-old woman presents with a 2-day history of deteriorating right lower back pain. It started when she was vacuuming and progressively became worse. The pain radiates down the right lower leg. The pain has deteriorated despite analgesia, including co-codamol. This morning, she went into urinary retention. There is no other history of note.\n\nOn examination, she is in pain, has a pulse of 100 bpm, sats of 99%, a temperature of 39 oC and a blood pressure of 118/70 mmHg. She is exquisitely tender over the right lower back, particularly around the sacroiliac region. Leg raise is limited by pain, power seems intake in both legs, but walking is curtailed by the pain sustained when putting any pressure on the right leg. Sensation appears intact.\n\nAbdominal examination reveals a distended bladder which, on catheterisation, drains 1 litre of clear urine. Dipstick of the urine reveals no abnormality.\n\nWhich of the following is the likely diagnosis?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Which of the following is the likely diagnosis?","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"Which of the following is the likely diagnosis?","explanation":"This patient has a short history of pain and high fever with pain over the sacroiliac joint. There are no other features of neurological impairment to suggest cauda equina, though this does require exclusion. The presentation suggests a diagnosis of sacroiliac joint sepsis, and urinary retention is likely to have ensued through pain and the use of analgesics. The most likely cause of the sepsis is Staphylococcus aureus, and the patient should be treated with IV flucloxacillin together with rifampicin for bony penetration. The patient would require an urgent MRI."},{"id":"12018","category":"Neurology and ophthalmology","stem":"A 71-year-old man with prostate cancer and known multiple vertebral bone metastases has given a history of a fall off a stool onto his back, one day ago. He now has severe pain in his back in the upper thoracic area, corresponding to the level of known vertebral metastases, and weakness in his legs. He was unable to pass urine earlier today and has since developed a severe headache and blurred vision. He is visibly sweating on his face, but does not seem to be sweating in the lower part of his body. His speech is normal. His observation chart shows his systolic blood pressure has gone up by 30 mmHg from his baseline, and his heart rate has dropped relative to his usual baseline.\n\nHis current medications are modified-release oxycodone 20 mg twice daily, immediate-release oxycodone liquid 2.5 mg as required, paracetamol 1g four times daily, simvastatin 20 mg once daily, and aspirin 75 mg once daily.\n\nWhat diagnosis would explain his current presentation?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"Autonomic dysreflexia is a complication of spinal cord injury above T6. A trigger, e.g. distended bladder/urinary retention, results in a sympathetic response from T6 to L2 of hypertension, pallor and cool skin below the lesion. In response to the raised blood pressure, increased vagal parasympathetic tone results in bradycardia and a brainstem response to reduce blood pressure through peripheral vasodilation (but the response is unable to pass below the level of the spinal cord lesion, resulting in unopposed sympathetic activity below this level)."},{"id":"10816","category":"Neurology and ophthalmology","stem":"A 55-year-old woman attends the medical assessment unit complaining of a deteriorating headache. The headache began 3 days ago, she describes it as being all over with pressure behind the eyes and feels that the intensity is 8 out of 10. She has no other past medical history of note. She takes no medication. She had her first dose of the SARS-CoV-2 adenovirus vector (AZ) vaccine approximately 2 weeks ago.\n\nOn examination, she has a GCS of 15, a pulse of 88 beats per minute, regular, a blood pressure of 136/88 mmHg with a temperature of 36.7oC. There is no neck stiffness, but some mild photophobia is present with no focal neurology. Fundal examination reveals no specific abnormalities.\n\nInvestigations reveal:\n\nWhich of the following would be the most appropriate approach to anticoagulation for this patient?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"and assessed with CT","explanation":"This patient has a thrombocytopaenia associated with headache 2 weeks after receiving the ChAdOx1 nCoV-19 (AstraZeneca) SARS-CoV-2 vaccine, hence a diagnosis of cerebral venous sinus thrombosis due to vaccine-induced thrombocytopaenic thrombosis should be considered and assessed with CT. The diagnosis of VITT can be supported by measuring antibodies to PF-4. Treatment with IV immunoglobulin plus high-dose glucocorticoids can improve the outcome together with anticoagulation with non-heparin-based anticoagulation such as DOACs, argatroban or fondaparinux."},{"id":"3736","category":"Neurology and ophthalmology","stem":"A 35-year-old woman presents with an acute onset of back and bilateral leg pain for the last 4 days. She also describes sensory loss in the right. She had not opened her bowels for 3 days, and at 8 am on the day of admission, she was incontinent of urine. She has not passed urine since. She is overweight but otherwise has no significant past medical history.\n\nOn examination, she has a pulse of 80 beats per minute, a blood pressure of 122/80 mmHg, and she is distressed by pain. She has reduced sensation over the sole of the foot on the right and perianally. The ankle reflexes are absent with normal knee reflexes, though the power of the lower limb is intact. There is a flexor plantar response.\n\nInitial investigations are normal, including an X-ray of the spine.\n\nWhich of the following is the most appropriate investigation for this patient?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"This woman has an acute onset of back pain associated with weakness, urinary retention, absent ankle jerks and loss of sensation in the S1 dermatome. The diagnosis is Cauda Equina syndrome, and the most appropriate investigation is an MRI lumbar spine."},{"id":"3722","category":"Renal medicine","stem":"A 50-year-old man of Nigerian origin presents to the Accident & Emergency with worsening shortness of breath for the last 2 weeks and two episodes of haemoptysis this morning. He reports a decrease in urine output in the last 3 days as well. There is no history of fever, night sweats or weight loss. He has no significant medical history and is not on any regular medication.\n\nOn examination, he has a pulse rate of 100/min, blood pressure of 180/100 mmHg and appears pale. He has bilateral pedal oedema with raised JVP. Chest auscultation reveals bilateral lower zone pan-inspiratory crackles with bronchial breathing. His investigations reveal:\n\nChest X-ray (PA view):\n\nNon-homogeneous fluffy shadowing over lower zones bilaterally.\n\nIncreased diffusion gradient of carbon monoxide (DLCO) is seen.\n\nWhat is the most likely diagnosis?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"Goodpasture’s syndrome is a renal pulmonary syndrome characterised by lung haemorrhages and kidney dysfunction. Lung haemorrhages will manifest as infiltrates on chest x-ray and would show an increase in DLCO, as seen in this patient. Renal dysfunction classically manifests as rapidly progressive glomerulonephritis with cellular crescents on renal histology. Antibodies against the basement membrane of glomeruli can be detected in serum to aid diagnosis. Mainstay treatment entails aggressive immunosuppression and plasmapheresis."},{"id":"17403","category":"Renal medicine","stem":"A 72-year-old woman has presented to the emergency department with a 6-month history of anorexia, loss of appetite, and 12 kg of weight loss. She also has sinusitis, offensive nasal discharge, and epistaxis, and her nasal bone is deformed on physical examination and appears saddle-shaped. She presents with new-onset shortness of breath on exertion and is coughing up blood. She has developed polyarthralgia affecting her ankles, wrists, and knees. On examination, this woman looks fatigued and unwell. There is a palpable purpuric rash over her shins. The rest of the examination is unremarkable. A chest X-ray shows diffuse infiltrates.\n\nA complete urine examination shows haematuria and proteinuria. Renal function tests are grossly deranged with hyperkalaemia.\n\nWhat is the likely diagnosis?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Granulomatosis with polyangiitis (GPA)is the new name given to Wegener's granulomatosis.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"Granulomatosis with polyangiitis (GPA)is the new name given to Wegener's granulomatosis.","explanation":"The combination of sinusitis, rapidly progressive glomerulonephritis and pulmonary infiltrates makes Wegener's granulomatosis the most likely diagnosis. Rheumatoid arthritis is associated with bilateral symmetrical polyarthritis and renal and pulmonary involvement. While rheumatoid arthritis could be a possibility, sinusitis is not a feature, which makes this unlikely. Polyarteritis nodosa and microscopic polyangiitis are vasculitides that are also associated with renal involvement, but pulmonary involvement is rare, and sinusitis is not a feature of either. Systemic lupus erythematosus is a multi-organ autoimmune inflammatory disease, but that too is not associated with sinusitis."},{"id":"3913","category":"Renal medicine","stem":"A 62-year-old woman who received a cadaveric renal transplant 5 months ago presents to Accident and Emergency with a feeling of general malaise and persistent diarrhoea. Her current medications include oral prednisolone 7.5 mg once daily, tacrolimus 2 mg twice daily, mycophenolate mofetil 500 mg twice daily, carvedilol 6.25 mg twice daily, metformin 500 mg twice daily, and aspirin 75 mg once daily.\n\nOn examination, she has a low-grade fever and appears icteric and slightly dehydrated with a blood pressure of 134/72 mmHg and a pulse of 80 beats per minute. The rest of the examination is normal.\n\nHer laboratory investigations reveal:\n\nWhat is the most likely diagnosis?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"The most common time for opportunistic infections to occur secondary to immunosuppression is the 1-6 month period post-transplant, as encountered with this patient. CMV infection pneumocystis is an opportunistic systemic infection with varied presentations ranging from colitis and hepatitis to pneumonitis. Diagnostic investigations include DNA polymerase chain reaction assays, antibody assays and organ-specific procedures like colonoscopy, etc."},{"id":"10877","category":"Renal medicine","stem":"A 48-year-old man, who is a smoker, presents with confusion and drowsiness. His only medications are bronchodilators and steroid inhalers. On examination, his blood pressure is 130/84 mmHg, and his pulse rate is 70 beats per minute. He has moist mucous membranes, good skin turgor, jugular venous pressure is normal, lung fields are clear to auscultation, and there is no peripheral oedema. A chest radiograph shows emphysematous changes but is otherwise normal.\n\nWhich of the following would be appropriate to identify the cause of hyponatremia in this patient?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"This is a case of euvolaemic hyponatraemia. The inappropriately high urine osmolality (>100 mOsm/kg) excludes primary polydipsia. Thus, the differential diagnosis is the syndrome of inappropriate antidiuretic hormone secretion (SIADH), hypothyroidism, and hypoadrenalism. In this case, one should have a high index of suspicion for SIADH due to a bronchogenic carcinoma, and a chest CT is mandatory. Screening with a serum TSH is appropriate, but a thyroid scan is not indicated. The normotension and normokalaemia make adrenal insufficiency unlikely."},{"id":"8964","category":"Renal medicine","stem":"A 62-year-old man is admitted with a 2-hour history of chest pain and dyspnoea. He was diagnosed with an unprovoked pulmonary embolism. He has been receiving haemodialysis for chronic kidney disease (CKD) for the last 3 years. It was decided that he requires long-term oral anticoagulation.\n\nWhich oral anticoagulant is the most appropriate treatment for this patient?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"Studies reveal that dialysis patients have an approximately two-fold increased risk of venous thromboembolism. Warfarin is currently the only licensed oral treatment appropriate for this patient. None of the other DOACs is, as yet, licensed for use in dialysis patients. Low molecular weight heparin can also be used in CKD patients where required and is administered subcutaneously."},{"id":"17086","category":"Renal medicine","stem":"A 27-year-old man was referred to the ambulatory care unit by the GP with breathlessness and swelling in both legs. He was treated with a one-week course of amoxicillin 500 mg three times a day by the GP for an upper respiratory tract infection 2 weeks before the onset of his symptoms. On examination, his heart rate was 77 beats per minute, regular, SaO2 was 96% on room air, he had a blood pressure of 147/67 mmHg, and he was apyrexial. Chest examination revealed reduced breath sounds at both bases; however, abdominal, cardiovascular, and neurological examinations were unremarkable. There was marked pitting oedema up to the mid-thigh, and the jugular venous pulse (JVP) was not raised.\n\nInvestigations revealed the following results:\n\nWhich further investigation would you like to do?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Investigations revealed the following results:","Which further investigation would you like to do?","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"Which further investigation would you like to do?","explanation":"The diagnosis here is acute kidney injury, most likely from nephrotic syndrome secondary to post-streptococcal upper respiratory tract infection. The classic triad of nephrotic syndrome comprises hypoalbuminemia, oedema and proteinuria > 3g/24 hours. NICE recommends performing urinalysis in all patients with acute kidney injury of unknown cause. Therefore, the next simple investigation which should be done here is a urinalysis to look for proteinuria and haematuria, followed by 24 hours of urine collection to quantify proteinuria. The abnormal albumin-globulin ratio is because of proteinuria, and there is nothing suggestive of multiple myeloma in the history; therefore myeloma screen is not required. Similarly, an echocardiogram is not indicated as the history is not suggestive of heart failure. Pleural aspiration is not indicated as the pleural effusion is bilateral and will be transudative because of hypoalbuminemia. Hepatitis B and C screening is not indicated as the history is not suggestive of liver disease, and coagulopathy is a complication of nephrotic syndrome."},{"id":"10808","category":"Renal medicine","stem":"A 70-year-old man with a background of end-stage renal disease on peritoneal dialysis, emphysema, diabetes mellitus type 2, and hypertension, presented to the medical admissions unit with a one-day history of abdominal pain and pyrexia. He also noticed that his dialysate fluid had become cloudier. He just returned from a 1-week holiday and admitted that whilst he was away, he did not always use gloves when dealing with the dialysis connector, as he had run out of them.\n\nOn examination, his temperature was 39.2oC, heart rate 101 beats per minute, blood pressure 115/90 mmHg, respiratory rate 18/min and oxygen saturation 95% on room air.\n\nHe had mild abdominal tenderness on abdominal examination.\n\nBlood results are as follows:\n\nPeritoneal dialysis-related peritonitis was suspected, and peritoneal fluid analysis was sent off for analysis alongside blood cultures.\n\nPeritoneal fluid analysis revealed:\n\nWBC 1600/µL with 80%PMNLs (Polymorphonuclear leucocytes); Gram stain reveals PMNLs, but no organism was seen.\n\nHe was commenced on intraperitoneal antibiotics whilst culture results were pending.\n\nWhat is the most likely cause of peritoneal dialysis-related peritonitis in his case?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Blood results are as follows:","Peritoneal dialysis-related peritonitis was suspected, and peritoneal fluid analysis was sent off for analysis alongside blood cultures.","Peritoneal fluid analysis revealed:","He was commenced on intraperitoneal antibiotics whilst culture results were pending.","What is the most likely cause of peritoneal dialysis-related peritonitis in his case?","It is recommended that antibiotics be administered intraperitoneally for maximum efficacy.","Salzer, W.L., 2018. Peritoneal dialysis-related peritonitis: challenges and solutions. International journal of nephrology and renovascular disease, 11, p.173.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"What is the most likely cause of peritoneal dialysis-related peritonitis in his case?","explanation":"Peritoneal dialysis-related peritonitis is the major complication of peritoneal dialysis, with the PD catheter being the main source of infection. The infection is mostly caused by \"touch contamination\"; therefore, coagulase-negative Staphylococci, particularly S.epidermidis, are the most common causative pathogens, followed by S.Aureus (these 2 groups are together responsible for about 50% of infections). Peritonitis can also be caused by exit site and tunnel infections and by an intra-abdominal source (from diverticulitis, cholecystitis, appendicitis or through surgery or abdominal procedures such as a colonoscopy). Gram-negative enteric bacteria, streptococci and anaerobic bacteria are the most common pathogens involved in peritonitis from an intra-abdominal source."},{"id":"10805","category":"Renal medicine","stem":"A 24-year-old man was admitted to the medical assessment unit with nausea, appetite loss, crampy abdominal pain, watery diarrhoea (5-10 times/day), and fever for the last 24 hours. He has a past medical history of Alport syndrome and received an allogeneic renal transplant 21 days ago. His current medications include: prednisolone 30mg OD, tacrolimus 1g BD and mycophenolate mofetil 1g BD.\n\nHis admission observations were: heart rate 105 bpm, blood pressure 105/75 mmHg, respiratory rate 22/min, oxygen saturation 99% RA (room air) and temperature 38.7oC.\n\nThe admission bloods are below:\n\nWhat is the most likely cause of his symptoms?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","The admission bloods are below:","What is the most likely cause of his symptoms?","The differential diagnoses for infections in renal transplant recipients are based on the following timeline, with the opportunistic infections more likely to occur 1–6 months after transplantation:","Nambiar, P., Silibovsky, R., & Belden, K. A. (2018). Infection in Kidney Transplantation. Contemporary Kidney Transplantation.Pp.: 307–327","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"The differential diagnoses for infections in renal transplant recipients are based on the following timeline, with the opportunistic infections more likely to occur 1–6 months after transplantation:","explanation":"The differential diagnoses for infections in renal transplant recipients are based on the following timeline, with the opportunistic infections more likely to occur 1–6 months after transplantation:"},{"id":"3908","category":"Renal medicine","stem":"A 45-year-old Hispanic man known to have diabetes and hypertension for the last 5 years presents to the accident and emergency department with an episode of generalised tonic-clonic seizure. His wife is accompanying him, and she reports her husband to be unwell for the last 4–5 days with a low-grade fever, shortness of breath and a decrease in urine output. He has been on metformin 500 mg twice daily, lisinopril 5 mg once daily, aspirin 75 mg once daily, and simvastatin 20 mg daily with reasonable glycaemic and blood pressure control.\n\nOn examination, he has a GCS of 14/15 with a blood pressure of 170/100 mmHg. Neurological examination is essentially unremarkable. His blood tests reveal:\n\nWhat is the best management strategy for this patient?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"The presence of renal failure, thrombocytopenia and microangiopathic haemolytic anaemia, as evidenced by an elevated LDH and schistocytes, points to a diagnosis of thrombotic microangiopathy. The presence of fever and neurological symptoms makes “Thrombotic Thrombocytopenic Purpura” the likely diagnosis. The mainstay of treatment is plasmapheresis."},{"id":"3907","category":"Renal medicine","stem":"A 27-year-old student who recently returned from a 2-week family vacation in Spain presents to the accident and emergency with 3 episodes of bloody diarrhoea and a decrease in urine output over the past 36 hours. There is no significant previous history.\n\nOn examination, he remains afebrile with normal blood pressure and pulse rate. He appears pale with no other significant findings. His laboratory tests reveal:\n\nWhat is the most likely causative organism?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"The presence of renal failure, thrombocytopenia and microangiopathic haemolytic anaemia, as evidenced by an elevated LDH and schistocytes, points to a diagnosis of thrombotic microangiopathy. The absence of fever and neurological symptoms makes “Haemolytic Uremic Syndrome” the likely diagnosis. Haemolytic uraemic syndrome is typically associated with diarrhoea, the most common causative organism of which is E. Coli 0157:H7."},{"id":"17085","category":"Renal medicine","stem":"A 67-year-old man with a background of pancreas and renal transplant, hypertension, and chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD) is admitted with pleuritic chest pain and breathlessness. His home medications include mycophenolate mofetil 1g twice daily, tacrolimus 100 micrograms twice daily, ramipril 5 mg once a day, salbutamol inhaler 2 puffs as required, and tiotropium inhaler 2 puffs daily. On examination, his heart rate was 107 beats per minute, regular, SaO2 95% on room air, with a blood pressure of 137/67 mmHg, and he is apyrexial. The rest of the systemic examination was unremarkable.\n\nInvestigation results showed the following:\n\nA CT pulmonary angiogram (CTPA) was requested to rule out pulmonary embolism.\n\nWhat is the necessary intervention to prevent contrast-induced nephropathy in this patient?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Investigation results showed the following:","A CT pulmonary angiogram (CTPA) was requested to rule out pulmonary embolism.","What is the necessary intervention to prevent contrast-induced nephropathy in this patient?","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"What is the necessary intervention to prevent contrast-induced nephropathy in this patient?","explanation":"Patients with a renal transplant are at high risk of developing contrast-induced nephropathy and acute kidney injury if they are given the iodine-based contrast media for the scan. Consider intravenous volume expansion with either isotonic sodium bicarbonate or 0.9% sodium chloride in these patients. Ramipril should be suspended in adults who have iodine-based contrast media with chronic kidney disease with an eGFR of less than 40 ml/min/1.73 m2. There is no indication to arrange for haemofiltration, but the renal team should be consulted in renal transplant patients having iodine-based contrast media. N-acetylcysteine infusion has no role in the prevention of contrast-induced nephropathy. Ventilation-perfusion scan will be non-diagnostic in this case, as the chest X-ray is not clear."},{"id":"10876","category":"Renal medicine","stem":"A 30-year-old woman with a subarachnoid haemorrhage becomes hyponatraemic despite treatment with isotonic saline. Her urine output is noted to be 250 ml/hr. The renal registrar on-call seeks your advice on how to differentiate the underlying cause of the hyponatraemia, i.e. between cerebral salt wasting and syndrome of inappropriate antidiuretic hormone (SIADH).\n\nWhat laboratory measurement would best distinguish between cerebral salt wasting and SIADH?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Ellison, D.H. and Berl, T., 2007. The syndrome of inappropriate antidiuresis. New England Journal of Medicine, 356(20), pp.2064-2072.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"Patients with cerebral salt wasting and patients with SIADH who are volume expanded with isotonic saline are indistinguishable by most laboratory measurements. Cerebral salt wasting is a primary response to the release of natriuretic peptides. However, volume-expanded patients with SIADH also have elevated levels of natriuretic peptides and both conditions are associated with low serum uric acid and with the excretion of large volumes of sodium-rich concentrated urine. A diagnosis of cerebral salt wasting requires documentation of inappropriate urinary salt wasting despite a decreased effective arterial blood volume, while in SIADH, sodium excretion is an appropriate physiological response to volume expansion. A contracted plasma volume should increase haematocrit."},{"id":"9413","category":"Renal medicine","stem":"A 66-year-old man is admitted to the acute unit with a 3-day history of feeling unwell associated with visual hallucinations. He had a history of end-stage renal disease secondary to hypertensive nephrosclerosis. One week previously, he was treated for a community-acquired chest infection by his general practitioner with amoxicillin and clarithromycin. He was also taking allopurinol, atenolol, amlodipine, vitamin D and calcium carbonate. He had been treated with continuous ambulatory peritoneal dialysis for the last 5 years. He was now complaining of seeing worms crawling over his body, and these hallucinations had deteriorated over the last two days.\n\nHe stopped smoking 15 years ago and drank very little alcohol.\n\nOn examination, he was oriented in time and person. He had no focal neurology with flexor plantar responses. His blood pressure was 138/86 mmHg, his pulse was 90 beats per minute, and his temperature was 37oC.\n\nHis blood tests, including renal function, were unremarkable. His chest x-ray was normal, and his CT head was unremarkable other than features of small vessel disease.\n\nWhich of the following is the likely diagnosis?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"This patient with ESRD has developed acute hallucinations without any apparent cognitive changes following treatment for a community-acquired chest infection. This implicates clarithromycin in the diagnosis, and studies reveal that hallucinations are described in association with clarithromycin as part of a neurotoxicity. Other neurotoxic effects reported in association with clarithromycin include ototoxicity, CNS depression and excitation, as well as exacerbation of myasthenia gravis."},{"id":"10806","category":"Renal medicine","stem":"A 65-year-old woman with a past medical history of diabetes mellitus type-2, hypertension, congestive heart failure, dyslipidaemia, and CKD 4 was admitted to the medical intake with a few days' history of fever, nausea, vomiting, right flank pain, dysuria, lethargy and confusion.\n\nHer admission observations were: temperature 39oC, respiratory rate 24/min, blood pressure 90 mmHg, heart rate 115 bpm, oxygen saturation 99% on room air.\n\nThe urine dipstick revealed: ery++, leu +++, nit+++, pro+.\n\nThe admission bloods were as follows:\n\nShe was diagnosed with acute chronic renal injury, urosepsis and hyperglycaemic hyperosmolar state. She was catheterised and commenced on empirical antibiotics, 8-hourly intravenous fluids and variable rate insulin infusion.\n\nTwelve hours later, the patient developed acute dyspnoea and oxygen saturation decreased to 79% on room air. Her blood pressure was 180/90 mmHg, respiratory rate 30/min, and heart rate 130 bpm. A chest X-ray revealed pulmonary oedema.\n\nHer urine output has been 150 ml in the last 12 hours, and she failed to improve symptomatically with intravenous furosemide.\n\nThe repeat bloods were:\n\nShe was reviewed by the renal team, and a decision was made to start acute haemodialysis via a central line.\n\nWhilst undergoing dialysis, she deteriorated further with a sudden onset of headache with visual disturbance, worsening nausea, tremors, agitation, and disorientation, and she had a brief episode (45 seconds) of a tonic-clonic seizure.\n\nWhat is the most likely cause of her neurological deterioration?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","The urine dipstick revealed: ery++, leu +++, nit+++, pro+.","The admission bloods were as follows:","Her urine output has been 150 ml in the last 12 hours, and she failed to improve symptomatically with intravenous furosemide.","The repeat bloods were:","She was reviewed by the renal team, and a decision was made to start acute haemodialysis via a central line.","What is the most likely cause of her neurological deterioration?","Mistry, K., 2019. Dialysis disequilibrium syndrome prevention and management. International journal of nephrology and renovascular disease, 12, p.69.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"Dialysis disequilibrium syndrome (DDS) is a clinical constellation of neurological symptoms and signs that occur during or shortly after dialysis, especially when it is first initiated. It is a diagnosis of exclusion in patients who are uraemic and hyperosmolar and undergo renal replacement therapy, where rapid correction of osmolytes leads to cerebral oedema and raised intracranial pressure with resultant clinical neurologic manifestations."},{"id":"3982","category":"Renal medicine","stem":"A 65-year-old man attends for dialysis. He was unable to attend his usual session the previous day. He tells nursing staff he had a \"bad night\" because of back pain and took an extra Amitriptyline to help him sleep. 10 minutes into dialysis, he arrests.\n\nWhich of the following is the most likely mechanism of arrest?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"Sudden cardiac death is the most common cause of death in haemodialysis patients, and ventricular arrhythmia is the usual mechanism. While defibrillation may damage dialysis machines, it is important to minimise any delay in shock to allow for disconnection. Uraemic pericardial effusions evolve gradually and are usually well-tolerated haemodynamically. The treatment of uraemic effusion is dialysis, and a significant effusion would not be expected in this patient."},{"id":"7101","category":"Renal medicine","stem":"A 70-year-old woman is found unconscious and is brought to the accident and emergency unit. She attends alone with little information about her past medical history. On examination, her heart rate is 45 bpm, and she has poor peripheral perfusion. An ECG confirms sinus rhythm with a rate of 45 bpm with changes consistent with inferior myocardial infarction.\n\nWhich one of the following is the most probable cause for the blood picture seen?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"There is a high anion-gap metabolic acidosis in this scenario. In the context of myocardial infarction and hypotension, there is a buildup of lactate (>2 mmol/L) due to tissue hypoperfusion - also known as type A lactic acidosis. Correction of perfusion, by improving cardiac pumping or vascular circulation, will reduce lactate and correct metabolic acidosis. The glucose in this scenario is elevated, not because the patient has diabetes, but because it represents a stress response that accompanies cortisol release."},{"id":"8955","category":"Renal medicine","stem":"A 28-year-old man is admitted to the acute unit with a 3-day history of deteriorating malaise and weakness. There is no past medical history of note. On examination, he was noted to be pale, had a purpuric rash, a blood pressure of 108/70 mmHg and a pulse of 106 beats per minute, regular with a temperature of 37.6oC.\n\nInvestigations revealed:\n\nWhat would suggest a diagnosis of thrombotic thrombocytopenic purpura rather than complement-mediated atypical haemolytic uraemic syndrome?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","National Heart, Lung & Blood Institute. Thrombotic Thrombocytopenic Purpura.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"their presence does not help differentiate the underlying cause of the TMA","explanation":"Thrombotic thrombocytopenic purpura (TTP) is more likely to present with normal renal function, versus the abnormal renal function found with atypical haemolytic uraemic syndrome. Similarly, severe thrombocytopaenia with a platelet count <50 is also more typical of TTP and is diagnosed based on very low ADAMTS13 activity. A family history of thrombotic microangiopathy makes a diagnosis of complement-mediated atypical haemolytic uraemic syndrome (aHUS) more probable, as the complement mutations can be inherited. Schistocytes will be seen in microangiopathic haemolysis of any cause, and therefore their presence does not help differentiate the underlying cause of the TMA."},{"id":"3910","category":"Renal medicine","stem":"A 27-year-old Caucasian lady presents to the emergency department with severe headache and restlessness. Her blood pressure is found to be 210/110 mmHg. She is not known to be hypertensive previously, but was started on amlodipine 10 mg a few months ago by her rheumatologist to improve ‘blood flow to her hands’. You notice microstomia and sclerodactyly.\n\nHer blood work reveals:\n\nWhat is the drug of choice to control her blood pressure?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Severe hypertension in the setting of a patient with systemic sclerosis, as suggested by the sclerodactyly, Raynaud’s and microstomia, should always raise the suspicion of “scleroderma renal crisis”.","ACE inhibitors remain the mainstay treatment considering that hypertension is always hyperreninaemic.","Steen VD, Constantino JP, Shapiro AP, Medsger TA. Outcomes of renal crisis in systemic sclerosis: Relation to availability of ACE inhibitors. Ann Intern Med. 1991;114:249-250.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"Severe hypertension in the setting of a patient with systemic sclerosis, as suggested by the sclerodactyly, Raynaud’s and microstomia, should always raise the suspicion of “scleroderma renal crisis”.","explanation":"Severe hypertension in the setting of a patient with systemic sclerosis, as suggested by the sclerodactyly, Raynaud’s and microstomia, should always raise the suspicion of “scleroderma renal crisis”."},{"id":"3909","category":"Renal medicine","stem":"An 85-year-old man is admitted from a nursing home because of disorientation. The carer accompanying the gentleman reports that the patient had gradually become withdrawn over the past 2 days when he developed a low-grade fever, accompanied by a dry cough, until he became disoriented this morning. He is known to suffer from congestive heart disease, for which he takes spironolactone and furosemide, along with bisoprolol and losartan for his hypertension.\n\nOn examination, he has a temperature of 36.7 oC, a pulse of 100 beats per minute and a blood pressure of 136/70 mmHg. He does not have any pedal oedema, although his mucous membranes appear dry with poor skin turgor. His chest examination reveals coarse pan-inspiratory crackles with increased vocal fremitus over the right lower hemithorax. No focal neurological deficit could be ascertained.\n\nInvestigations reveal:\n\nWhat is the most likely cause of his hyponatremia?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"It is important to note that this patient is dehydrated, hence hypovolaemic hyponatraemia, which narrows the diagnosis down to either cerebral salt wasting syndrome or diuretics. The absence of any history of cerebral insult rules out cerebral salt wasting, leaving diuretics to be the answer. A diagnosis of hyponatremia in hypocortisolism or syndrome of inappropriate ADH secretion is made in euvolaemic patients. Patients with congestive heart failure and hyponatremia are volume-overloaded."},{"id":"19860","category":"Renal medicine","stem":"A 52-year-old woman with diffuse cutaneous systemic sclerosis diagnosed 18 months ago presents to the acute medical unit with a 5-day history of headache, blurred vision, and progressive breathlessness. She has recently commenced prednisolone 20 mg daily for worsening skin disease.\n\nOn examination, blood pressure is 195/118 mmHg, heart rate is 100bpm, respiratory rate is 22/min, saturation is 95% on room air, temperature is 36.8 oC, and she has bilateral crepitations.\n\nUrinalysis shows 3+ proteinuria and 2+ haematuria.\n\nWhat is the most appropriate first-line management?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Blood tests show:","Urinalysis shows 3+ proteinuria and 2+ haematuria.","What is the most appropriate first-line management?","Scleroderma renal crisis is a medical emergency characterised by acute kidney injury, malignant hypertension, and microangiopathic haemolytic anaemia in systemic sclerosis patients.","Treatment should be initiated immediately upon clinical suspicion, without waiting for specialist review or diagnostic confirmation.","Rapid dose escalation (e.g., captopril 6.25-12.5 mg three times daily, increasing to 25-50 mg three times daily within 24-48 hours) is essential.","Recent corticosteroid use (as in this case) is a recognised precipitant.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"Scleroderma renal crisis is a medical emergency characterised by acute kidney injury, malignant hypertension, and microangiopathic haemolytic anaemia in systemic sclerosis patients.","explanation":"Scleroderma renal crisis is a medical emergency characterised by acute kidney injury, malignant hypertension, and microangiopathic haemolytic anaemia in systemic sclerosis patients."},{"id":"17087","category":"Renal medicine","stem":"A 37-year-old woman with a background of systemic lupus erythematosus presented with worsening weakness and palpitations for a few weeks. Her home medications include hydroxychloroquine 200 mg once daily, prednisolone 10 mg once daily, omeprazole 20 mg once daily, and calcium/vitamin D3 (1500 mg/400 IU) 1 tablet twice daily. On examination, she was lean and thinly built with a heart rate of 97 beats per minute, regular, SaO2 97% on room air, with a blood pressure of 117/71 mmHg, and she was apyrexial. Neurological examination revealed generalised reduced power of all four limbs with diminished reflexes. Sensory, coordination and cranial nerve examinations, along with the rest of the systemic examination, were normal.\n\nInvestigations showed the following results:\n\nHow should you investigate further?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Investigations showed the following results:","How should you investigate further?","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"hypokalaemia","explanation":"This is the case of hypokalaemia paralysis with normal anion gap metabolic acidosis. Potassium regulates impulse transmission through nerves and muscle contraction, including the heart and skeletal muscles. Therefore, hypokalaemia, in this case, has resulted in paralysis from weak muscle contraction and abnormal heartbeats, resulting in palpitations. As the serum bicarbonate levels are low and the anion gap is normal [Na – (Cl+HCO3)]= 10 mmol/L, the causes of normal anion gap metabolic acidosis with hyperchloraemia are gastrointestinal, renal losses, and the use of certain drugs. As there is no history suggestive of gastrointestinal losses or drug use, the cause here is renal loss, i.e., renal tubular acidosis (types 1 and 2). The other hints here are the history of systemic lupus erythematosus, which is associated with renal tubular acidosis and urinary pH in the normal range. Therefore, the diagnostic investigation will check urinary electrolytes (sodium, potassium, and chloride) and calculate the urinary anion gap."},{"id":"7102","category":"Renal medicine","stem":"A 35-year-old woman has a history of recurrent urinary tract infections. She attends the Accident & Emergency department with severe left-sided flank pain. Dipstick urine shows blood 2+ protein 1+.\n\nWhich one of the following is the most probable diagnosis in this case?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Yaxley, J. and Pirrone, C., 2016. Review of the Diagnostic Evaluation of Renal Tubular Acidosis. The Ochsner Journal, 16(4), pp.525-530.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"The biochemical picture is consistent with distal renal tubular acidosis (type-I renal tubular acidosis). This includes acidosis, hypokalaemia, low serum bicarbonate levels and relatively high urinary pH. Urine pH remains >5.5 despite severe acidaemia ([HCO3] <15 mmol/L). Renal stone formation and nephrocalcinosis are common in this condition."},{"id":"8962","category":"Renal medicine","stem":"A 68-year-old woman is admitted to the acute unit with a left leg deep vein thrombosis. She is known to have chronic kidney disease stage 3 with an estimated glomerular filtration rate of 50 mL/min/1.73 m2. She is known to have heparin-induced thrombocytopaenia.\n\nWhich of these would provide the most appropriate initial anticoagulation for this patient?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"Fondaparinux is a factor Xa inhibitor and a synthetic pentasaccharide low-molecular-weight heparin that does not cross-react with heparin-induced thrombocytopenia antibodies. All the other choices of low molecular weight heparins and unfractionated heparin would be likely to precipitate HIT with re-introduction."},{"id":"17404","category":"Renal medicine","stem":"A 60-year-old woman presents with a 4-month history of back pain and loss of appetite. She has recently been diagnosed with multiple myeloma and is started on bortezomib therapy. After her bortezomib infusion, she was discharged home with a follow-up appointment in two weeks with the nephrologist. She presented to the emergency department 2 days later with hypocalcaemia, hyperkalaemia, hyperphosphataemia, and hyperuricaemia. Her renal function tests are significantly deranged, where they were normal one week previously.\n\nWhat is the most likely diagnosis?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"The most likely diagnosis, in this case, is tumour lysis syndrome, which is secondary to bortezomib (chemotherapy) started for the treatment of multiple myeloma. The biochemical findings of hypocalcaemia, hyperphosphataemia, hyperkalaemia, and hyperuricaemia are typical for tumour lysis syndrome. The patient has no history of non-steroidal anti-inflammatory drug (NSAID) use, so NSAID-induced renal dysfunction is not possible. Bortezomib is not known to cause renal dysfunction. Myeloma-induced renal dysfunction is a possibility, but biochemical parameters are typical for tumour lysis syndrome."},{"id":"10807","category":"Renal medicine","stem":"A 58-year-old woman with a past medical history of diabetes mellitus type 2, hypertension, CKD stage 3 and dyslipidaemia was referred by her GP with hyperkalaemia of 6.4mmol/L on routine diabetes bloods.\n\nHer medications include: ramipril 10mg od, atorvastatin 40mg od, metformin 500mg bd, canagliflozin 100 mg od, spironolactone 25mg od and Humulin I 16 units once daily.\n\nOn arrival at the Accident and Emergency Department, her observations were: blood pressure 130/80mmHg, heart rate 75bpm, respiratory rate 19/min, temperature 37oC, oxygen saturation 100% on room air. An ECG did not reveal any abnormality.\n\nHer bloods were as follows:\n\nHer ramipril and spironolactone were temporarily stopped, and she was given hyperkalaemia treatment, following which her potassium was 5.8 mmol/L. She was educated regarding a low potassium diet and attended a repeat U&E test a week later. Her repeat potassium was 6.1 mmol/L, despite being off ramipril and spironolactone.\n\nWhat is the cause of the persistent hyperkalaemia?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Her medications include: ramipril 10mg od, atorvastatin 40mg od, metformin 500mg bd, canagliflozin 100 mg od, spironolactone 25mg od and Humulin I 16 units once daily.","Her bloods were as follows:","What is the cause of the persistent hyperkalaemia?","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"What is the cause of the persistent hyperkalaemia?","explanation":"Type IV renal tubular acidosis (Type 4 RTA)/hyporeninemic hypoaldosteronism is often underdiagnosed, and it is known to be more common in diabetes mellitus patients with moderate renal impairment. It should be suspected in patients with persistent hyperkalaemia with no obvious cause (such as renal failure, the use of potassium supplements or a potassium-sparing diuretic). The extent of elevated serum potassium levels is usually disproportional to renal dysfunction and potassium intake."},{"id":"17266","category":"Renal medicine","stem":"A 55-year-old man presented to the emergency department with a history of haematuria in the past week and now has difficulty passing urine. The patient denies any burning sensation before this episode, fever or urgency, and he has no history of trauma. He only has high blood pressure as per his past medical history. He takes regular medication, anti-hypertensive drugs. He is a smoker and has smoked 20 cigarettes per day for 30 years.\n\nOn examination, the bladder is palpable; otherwise, there are no other masses or organomegaly noticed, and the prostate was non-tender and of adequate size.\n\nThe urine microscopy, culture, and sensitivity (MC&S) were positive only for blood (4+). Blood tests were unremarkable with normal haemoglobin (145 g/dL) and coagulation screen.\n\nWhich of the following is the most probable diagnosis?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Sharp VJ, Barnes KT, Erickson BA. Assessment of asymptomatic microscopic hematuria in adults. Am Fam Physician. 2013 Dec 1;88(11):747-54. PMID: 24364522.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"There is a strong association of smoking history with bladder cancer. There is no anticoagulation medication, and his clotting is normal on investigations for increased bleeding. The urine MC&S with only blood associated with no symptoms of frequency/fever/dysuria excludes infection. Kidney stones can cause microscopic or macroscopic haematuria, depending on the size of the stone; however, macroscopic haematuria is more frequent with flank pain in this condition. While haematuria may occur in acute bacterial prostatitis, it is the sudden or rapidly progressive onset of dysuria, frequency, and nocturia with possible urinary retention and infection that is more characteristic of this condition."},{"id":"3914","category":"Renal medicine","stem":"You are asked to review a 40-year-old Asian man urgently in the Acute Haemodialysis Unit. You are informed by the duty nurses that the patient developed an episode of tonic-clonic seizures 2 hours into his dialysis session. On reviewing his medical notes, you notice that he had been advised of arterio-venous fistula and dialysis 6 months ago, which he had refused and had travelled back to India.\n\nYou also note that this is his first session of haemodialysis with the following dialysis orders:\n\nOn examination, he appears significantly emaciated with a blood pressure of 110/70 mmHg, a pulse rate of 96/minute and a temperature of 38oC. He remains unconscious with a GCS of 8/15. There is no focal neurological deficit with bilateral reactive pupils and bilateral downgoing plantar reflexes. His laboratory investigations show:\n\nWhat is the most likely diagnosis?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Mistry, K. (2019). Dialysis disequilibrium syndrome prevention and management. International Journal of Nephrology and Renovascular Disease, 12, 69-77. https://doi.org/10.2147/IJNRD.S165925","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"Patients with severe azotaemia are recommended to have short, more frequent dialysis sessions with a lower blood flow setting for the first few sessions of haemodialysis. This is to prevent transient osmotic disequilibrium known as “dialysis disequilibrium syndrome”, which may manifest with neurological symptoms like restlessness, headache, twitching, tremors or even seizures as in this case."},{"id":"10804","category":"Renal medicine","stem":"A 75-year-old man with a past medical history of end-stage kidney disease on haemodialysis 3 times per week for the last 3 months, hypertension, ischaemic heart disease, heart failure and prostate cancer (managed with radical prostatectomy 5 years ago) is admitted to the medical assessment unit with lethargy, nausea, muscle spasms and bone and joint pains. He takes clopidogrel 75 mg once daily, doxazosin 4 mg twice daily, furosemide 80 mg twice daily, isosorbide mononitrate 10 mg twice daily and amlodipine 5 mg once daily.\n\nOn examination, his heart rate is 85 bpm, blood pressure 160/90 mmHg, respiratory rate 22/min, oxygen saturation 98% on RA (room air), and temperature 37oC.\n\nHis blood results are as follows:\n\nWhat is the most likely cause of his hypercalcaemia?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","His blood results are as follows:","What is the most likely cause of his hypercalcaemia?","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"Tertiary hyperparathyroidism (THPT) is defined as an autonomous parathyroid hyperfunction. It develops in patients with chronic renal disease who previously developed secondary hyperparathyroidism (SHPT). THPT is characterised biochemically by elevated PTH, calcium and phosphate levels as opposed to SHPT, where high PTH is accompanied by low calcium and high phosphate levels. The prolonged hypocalcaemia in SHPT leads to parathyroid gland hyperplasia and subsequent development of THPT. The treatment of choice for THPT is surgery (usually subtotal parathyroidectomy)."},{"id":"10875","category":"Renal medicine","stem":"A 60-year-old man presented to the emergency department feeling generally unwell. He had a history of advanced renal failure secondary to hypertensive nephropathy but had had no nephrology follow-up in the last 6 months. On examination, he appeared drowsy and tachypneic with a blood pressure of 160/80 mmHg. His oxygen saturation was 100% on room air, and he was afebrile. There were no localising neurological signs.\n\nHis serum biochemistry results were as follows:\n\nHe was started on haemodialysis, but after 2 hours, the patient became unresponsive. Again, there were no localising neurological signs. Signs of meningeal irritation were absent, and his blood pressure was unchanged. Blood glucose was 6.7 mmol/L (5-6.7 mmol/L).\n\nWhat is the likely diagnosis?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","His serum biochemistry results were as follows:","What is the likely diagnosis?","Mistry, K. (2019). Dialysis disequilibrium syndrome prevention and management. International Journal of Nephrology and Renovascular Disease, 12, 69-77. https://doi.org/10.2147/IJNRD.S165925","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"What is the likely diagnosis?","explanation":"This patient has likely developed dialysis disequilibrium syndrome. Severe uraemia, old age, metabolic acidosis, hypernatraemia, and pre-existing neurological disease can predispose to this condition. Prevention of this condition requires slow reduction of urea by short, low-efficiency dialysis, repeated frequently. No localising neurological signs likely exclude cerebrovascular accidents (CVA). No history of fever, no signs of meningeal irritation and rapid onset of symptoms during HD exclude meningitis. Stable BP throughout haemodialysis excludes hypertensive encephalopathy. Normal blood sugar excludes hypoglycaemia."},{"id":"4250","category":"Respiratory medicine","stem":"A 42-year-old woman presents acutely, complaining of left-sided pleuritic chest pain of 4 hours duration and a painful cough. She had a recent upper respiratory tract infection, having had a cough and sniffles for 3-4 days. In the past, she was diagnosed with ulcerative colitis and maintained in remission on mesalazine. She is a non-smoker.\n\nOn examination, her pulse is 110 beats per minute, blood pressure 100/60 mmHg, and respiratory rate 22/min with oxygen saturations of 94% on room air. Her temperature is 37.2oC and her chest is clear.\n\nInvestigations reveal:\n\nWhich of the following is the most appropriate next investigation for this patient?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Investigations reveal:","Investigation\tResult\tNormal range\nFBC\tNormal\nCRP\t20 mg/dL\t<5\nU+E\tNormal\nECG\tNormal","Which of the following is the most appropriate next investigation for this patient?","BTS Guideline for the outpatient management of pulmonary embolism.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"a clinical probability of PE)","explanation":"This patient presents with acute breathlessness and chest pain. As her Well score is 4.5 (high pulse and therefore a clinical probability of PE), the patient can go directly to CTPA without needing a D Dimer."},{"id":"4228","category":"Respiratory medicine","stem":"A 72-year-old man presents to the accident and emergency department with a 12-hour history of breathlessness. He also reports some loose stools. He is a current smoker with a 62-pack-year history.\n\nOn examination, he is dyspnoeic, has a pulse of 117 beats per minute, a respiratory rate of 27, with oxygen saturations of 88% on air. He has a temperature of 38.6oC. Auscultation of his chest reveals crackles and reduced air entry at the right base. His abdomen is also distended with dullness in the flanks.\n\nInvestigations are as follows:\n\nWhat is the most likely diagnosis?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","A 72-year-old man presents to the accident and emergency department with a 12-hour history of breathlessness. He also reports some loose stools. He is a current smoker with a 62-pack-year history.","Investigations are as follows:","What is the most likely diagnosis?","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"What is the most likely diagnosis?","explanation":"This patient is very likely to abuse alcohol and have alcoholic liver disease (thrombocytopenia, raised MCV, deranged clotting and deranged LFTs). There is also evidence of ascites on examination. This, combined with the timing of his presentation, suggests that he was very intoxicated, likely ended up on the floor (note the raised CK) and has aspirated. The location of the pneumonia would also be in keeping with an aspiration."},{"id":"17493","category":"Respiratory medicine","stem":"A 25-year-old man with a known case of bronchial asthma presents to the emergency department with a history of cough, left-sided chest pain, and acute onset of breathing difficulty of 2 hours duration. On clinical examination, the patient was comfortable at rest with a respiratory rate of 16 beats per minute, oxygen saturation of 99% on room air, pulse rate of 100 beats per minute, and blood pressure was 100/70 mmHg. Auscultation showed decreased breath sounds on the left side with hyper-resonant notes on percussion.\n\nInvestigations revealed the following results:\n\nA chest X-ray showed a 2 cm pneumothorax on the left side, 2 cm from the lung margin.\n\nWhat is the recommended next line of management for this patient?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Investigations revealed the following results:","Investigation\tResult\tNormal range\nHaemoglobin\t145 g/L\t115-165 g/L\nTotal count\t10.5 x 109/L\t4- 11 x 109/L\nCRP\t2.5\t< 5","A chest X-ray showed a 2 cm pneumothorax on the left side, 2 cm from the lung margin.","What is the recommended next line of management for this patient?","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"Pneumothorax is defined as the air in the pleural space. Pneumothorax can be primary, i.e., spontaneous or secondary to trauma or an underlying disease. The treatment of pneumothorax depends on the size of the pneumothorax, the presence of any underlying lung disease, and the response to treatment."},{"id":"13713","category":"Respiratory medicine","stem":"A 68-year-old woman was admitted to the acute medical unit via the emergency department with an acute exacerbation of chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD). She was alert and oriented. There were no focal abnormalities on her chest X-ray.\n\nOn examination, her heart rate was 110 beats per minute, and her blood pressure was 120/85 mmHg. Her respiratory rate was 28 breaths per minute. On arrival, her oxygen saturation was 83% on room air.\n\nAfter an hour of nebulised bronchodilators, supplemental oxygen, and intravenous steroids, her blood gas showed the following results:\n\nWhat is the most appropriate next step in her management?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","After an hour of nebulised bronchodilators, supplemental oxygen, and intravenous steroids, her blood gas showed the following results:","Investigation\tResult\tNormal range","FiO2","pH\t7.32\t7.35 - 7.45","pO2\t13.1 kPa\t11.3–12.6 kPa","PaCO2\t6.8 kPa\t4.7–6.0 kPa","HCO3\t36 mmol/L\t21–29 mmol/L","Bicarbonate base excess\t4 mmol/L\t±2 mmol/L","What is the most appropriate next step in her management?","If the pCO2 fails to improve despite appropriate oxygen administration, then non-invasive ventilation (NIV) would be appropriate.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"The patient has acute chronic type-2 respiratory failure and should be given controlled oxygen therapy (24–28% FiO2) while continuing with nebulised bronchodilators."},{"id":"10740","category":"Respiratory medicine","stem":"A 65-year-old woman is seen in the emergency department with symptoms of cough, dyspnoea and fever. Her observations on admission reveal a heart rate of 110 bpm, blood pressure of 100/50 mmHg, temperature of 38.2oC, respiratory rate of 26/min and oxygen saturations of 90% breathing room air. She is fully oriented with no evidence of acute cognitive disturbance.\n\nChest X-ray reveals right-sided consolidation, and her blood results on admission are displayed below.\n\nWhat is her CURB-65 score?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Chest X-ray reveals right-sided consolidation, and her blood results on admission are displayed below.","What is her CURB-65 score?","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"What is her CURB-65 score?","explanation":"This woman has a diastolic blood pressure < 60 and is 65 years old; she, therefore, has a CURB-65 score of 2. The other parameters scoring in this mortality index would be urea greater than 7, a respiratory rate greater than or equal to 30, and confusion defined as an AMTS less than or equal to 8."},{"id":"19769","category":"Respiratory medicine","stem":"A 68-year-old man, otherwise fit and well and fully independent, with a history of chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD), presents to the emergency department with a three-day history of worsening breathlessness and increased sputum production. He reports a productive cough with yellow sputum. He is a current smoker with a 40-pack-year history and uses inhalers irregularly.\n\nOn arrival, his vital signs are:\n\nOn examination, he is using accessory muscles of respiration and has widespread wheezing.\n\nArterial blood gas on 28% Venturi oxygen shows:\n\nWhat is the most appropriate immediate next step in his management?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","On arrival, his vital signs are:","Investigation\tResult\tNormal range","Temperature\t38.2oC\t36.1-37.2oC","Respiratory rate\t30 breaths per minute\t12-20","Oxygen saturation","Heart rate\t118 beats per minute\t60-100","Blood pressure\t110/65 mmHg\t100-140/60-90 mmHg","Investigation\tResult\tNormal range\npH\t7.28\t7.35-7.45\nPaCO2\t8.2 kPa\t4.7-6.0 kPa\nPaO2\t6.9 kPa\t10.5-13.5 kPa on room air\nHCO3-\t28 mmol/L\t22-26 mmol/L","What is the most appropriate immediate next step in his management?","High-flow oxygen risks worsening hypercapnia by depressing respiratory drive and causing CO2 retention.","Intravenous corticosteroids are essential to reduce airway inflammation but do not resolve ventilatory failure alone.","Immediate intubation should be reserved for cases where NIV fails or in cases of severe respiratory compromise.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"Oxygen saturation","explanation":"This patient is experiencing an acute exacerbation of COPD complicated by type 2 respiratory failure, as evidenced by respiratory acidosis (pH <7.35), elevated PaCO2, and hypoxia despite oxygen supplementation."},{"id":"17398","category":"Respiratory medicine","stem":"A 45-year-old man presents with a 7-day history of fever, cough, and shortness of breath. His presenting oxygen saturation is 80% on room air (normal range: 94-98%) and is maintaining 94% saturation on 5 litres of oxygen via a face mask. He is admitted to the respiratory ward. A high-resolution computed tomography (HRCT) chest is done and shows bilateral sub-pleural ground glass infiltrates involving almost 60% of lung parenchyma, and his COVID-19 PCR comes back as positive. He is started on dexamethasone 6 mg IV daily, however, his CRP continues to rise (150 on day 4 of admission (normal range: <5 mg/dl)) and on the 4th post-admission day, his oxygen demand has increased to 10 litres of oxygen via NRM (non-rebreather mask) and a chest X-ray reveals increasing lung infiltrates. Serum ferritin and LDH are also 10 times elevated.\n\nWhat should be added to his treatment regimen?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","What should be added to his treatment regimen?","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"Progressively rising oxygen demand and lung infiltrates on chest X-ray, along with increasing CRP, show that the patient has developed signs of severe COVID-19 ARDS and is entering a cytokine release storm as evidenced by the increasing CRP/Ferritin/LDH. The addition of tocilizumab (IL-6 receptor antagonist) has been shown to dampen down the inflammatory response and has a benefit in mortality at this stage in addition to conventional IV dexamethasone."},{"id":"19864","category":"Respiratory medicine","stem":"A 68-year-old woman with severe COPD is admitted with an acute infective exacerbation. She has received nebulised salbutamol 5mg and ipratropium bromide 500mcg, intravenous hydrocortisone 100mg, and intravenous amoxicillin 1g and clarithromycin 500mg. Initial arterial blood gas on controlled oxygen (venturi mask 28%, target saturations 88-92%) showed: pH 7.31 (normal 7.35-7.45), PaCO2 8.4 kPa (normal 4.7-6.0 kPa), PaO2 7.8 kPa (normal 10.6-13.3 kPa on air), HCO3- 32 mmol/L (normal 22-28 mmol/L). Non-invasive ventilation (NIV) was commenced 4 hours ago with IPAP 18 cmH2O, EPAP 4 cmH2O. Despite increasing NIV settings gradually to IPAP 24cmH2O and EPAP 6cmH2O, repeat blood gas now shows: pH 7.23, PaCO2 8.9 kPa, PaO2 8.2 kPa, oxygen saturation 87%. She is increasingly drowsy with a respiratory rate of 32/min and appears exhausted.\n\nWhich single feature most strongly indicates the need for immediate intensive care review with a view to invasive mechanical ventilation?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Which single feature most strongly indicates the need for immediate intensive care review with a view to invasive mechanical ventilation?","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"Which single feature most strongly indicates the need for immediate intensive care review with a view to invasive mechanical ventilation?","explanation":"Worsening pH despite optimal NIV is the key indicator of NIV failure and the need for intubation. BTS/ICS guidelines specifically state that worsening physiological parameters, particularly pH, indicate the need to change management strategy, including considering intubation. A pH <7.25 is traditionally used as a threshold for considering invasive mechanical ventilation. Combined with clinical features (drowsiness, exhaustion, tachypnoea), this represents NIV failure. This patient requires immediate ITU review - delaying intubation risks cardiorespiratory arrest."},{"id":"3942","category":"Respiratory medicine","stem":"A 64-year-old woman is admitted with shortness of breath for last few hours. She was admitted to the hospital 3 weeks ago with the same problem. She became breathless over a few days, and when admitted on the last occasion, you see from the portal that she had a CTPA, which was normal, and she was diagnosed with asthma. After being treated with inhalers, she was discharged. Her Peak Flow rate was 260 l/min. She has an appointment with the respiratory physicians in about 2 weeks.\n\nOn this occasion, she describes this problem with breathlessness, which has deteriorated over the last 24 hours. She has had an unproductive cough. She becomes increasingly breathless on any exertion and has found it particularly difficult to get around the house. She is rather tearful. She is unaware of any chest pain. In the background history, she is obese and has type 2 diabetes.\n\nOn examination, her pulse is 98 bpm, oxygen saturations are 96% on air, temperature is 37oC, respiratory rate is 25/min, and her blood pressure is 120/88 mmHg. She appears dyspnoeic at rest and has a peak flow of 260, which improves to 340 following nebulised salbutamol. She is obese with a BMI of 42 kg/m2. Auscultation of the chest is normal with no audible wheeze. There is no ankle oedema, and the calves are soft and non-tender.\n\nInvestigations show normal FBC, U+Es and a CRP of 20 mg/dl. Chest x-ray is normal, although slightly underpenetrated. Arterial gases show:\n\nWhich of the following is the most appropriate management strategy for this patient?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Investigations show normal FBC, U+Es and a CRP of 20 mg/dl. Chest x-ray is normal, although slightly underpenetrated. Arterial gases show:","Investigation\tResult\tNormal range\npH\t7.37\t7.34-7.44\npO2\t10.2 kPa\t11-13\nPCO2\t4 kPa\t4.5-6","Which of the following is the most appropriate management strategy for this patient?","Wells score.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"Wells score.","explanation":"It is likely that this patient is breathless as a consequence of her morbid obesity with probable asthma and quite an element of a psychological overlay. However, because she was admitted to the hospital just 3 weeks ago and is obese requires the exclusion of PE is required. Therefore, the most appropriate approach would be to initially check a D-dimer concentration, and if this were normal, then no further investigation would be required. That the patient had a CTPA previously would be somewhat irrelevant, as venous thromboembolism could have occurred at home and, because of her co-morbidities, she would be considered a higher risk. However, her Wells score is less than 4, and a negative d-dimer PE would be very unlikely; hence, CTPA is not required."},{"id":"8119","category":"Respiratory medicine","stem":"A 48-year-old woman has recently been diagnosed with metastatic small-cell carcinoma of the lung. She presents with a 1–2 week history of progressive weakness of the limbs and some double vision. She takes no medication.\n\nOn examination, she has proximal muscle weakness in her arms and legs, with a waddling gait, diplopia and diminished reflexes.\n\nInvestigations reveal normal U+Es, Calcium and FBC but raised CRP.\n\nWhich of the following would be the most appropriate approach to her management?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"The clinical description is typical of Lambert-Eaton Myasthenic Syndrome (LEMS) — a paraneoplastic disorder associated with small cell lung cancer. As the syndrome is autoimmune-mediated, treatments such as IV immunoglobulin, plasma exchange, and high-dose steroids may help as well as treat the underlying small-cell lung cancer, which is often very responsive to appropriate chemotherapy. As LEMS is a non-metastatic phenomenon, whole-brain radiotherapy would not be helpful."},{"id":"4225","category":"Respiratory medicine","stem":"A 65-year-old man presents to A&E with a 2-day history of fever, lethargy, and dysuria. He has become confused in the hours prior to admission and drowsy. He is diagnosed with urinary sepsis with associated acute kidney injury and commenced on appropriate antibiotics and IV fluids.\n\n22 hours after admission, he became increasingly breathless as reviewed by the on-call team.\n\nHe is only managing to complete short sentences. He has dry mucous membranes. His respiratory rate is 30, heart rate is 121 beats per minute, blood pressure is 105/64 mmHg, and oxygen saturations are 92% on 15L. Examination shows normal JVP and normal heart sounds. Auscultation reveals fine crackles bilaterally. There is no peripheral oedema, and his calves are soft and non-tender. He has been passing urine with a 400 ml positive balance since admission.\n\nA chest x-ray demonstrated bilateral infiltrates.\n\nA blood gas is also performed on 15L (via non-rebreather mask).\n\nWhat is the most likely explanation for his deterioration?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","22 hours after admission, he became increasingly breathless as reviewed by the on-call team.","A chest x-ray demonstrated bilateral infiltrates.","A blood gas is also performed on 15L (via non-rebreather mask).","Investigation\tResult\npH\t7.32\npCO2\t3.8 kPa\npO2\t8.1 kPa\nHCO3\t18.7 mmol/L","ARDS is an acute injury to the lungs brought about by a variety of insults that causes widespread inflammation and impedes gas exchange at the alveolar level.","Direct pulmonary causes include inhalation of gastric contents (pH <2), infective (pneumonia, etc), pulmonary trauma, near-drowning, toxic gas inhalation and oxygen toxicity.","Indirect causes include sepsis, non-thoracic trauma, uraemia, bowel infarction, anaphylaxis and burns.","The diagnostic criteria include:","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"In the context of sepsis, the most likely explanation of this patient’s current condition is ARDS. Although he has received IV fluids as part of his treatment for sepsis, he is only mildly in positive balance, and he was likely in a profound ‘negative balance’ on admission; there is no evidence clinically that he is overloaded. Whilst he is at risk of pneumonia, the rapid deterioration of chest X-ray findings is more in keeping with ARDS than pneumonia, and a HAP this early on would be unusual."},{"id":"10733","category":"Respiratory medicine","stem":"You are asked to review a 72-year-old woman in the emergency department. She has attended due to feeling generally unwell with a productive cough and fever for the past two days. Her past medical history includes systemic hypertension and previous falls, where she sustained a right fractured neck of femur three years ago. She lives alone in a ground-floor flat and is independent of activities of daily living. She has good social support, and her grown-up children live next to her.\n\nHer observations are as follows: temperature 38.1oC, heart rate 92 beats per minute, blood pressure 130/86 mmHg, respiratory rate 18 and SaO2 96% on room air, AMT 10/10. On auscultation of her chest, there are right basal crepitations, which correspond with an area of right basal consolidation on the chest X-ray.\n\nWhat is the most appropriate further management plan for this patient?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Blood tests show:","What is the most appropriate further management plan for this patient?","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"What is the most appropriate further management plan for this patient?","explanation":"This patient has a diagnosis of community-acquired pneumonia based on the symptoms of an acute lower respiratory tract infection with new radiographic shadowing. The 2009 British Thoracic Society guidelines for the management of community-acquired pneumonia use the CURB65 score as a marker of severity to direct further management. This woman has a score of 1 (scoring on age only). This puts her in the 'low risk of death' category. The guidelines state that, based on this, she may be suitable for home treatment. It also mentions she is independent and has her family living close by, who can act as a safety net."},{"id":"10568","category":"Respiratory medicine","stem":"A 60-year-old male is admitted with a 2-day history of deteriorating shortness of breath. He also has a six-year history of type-2 diabetes, for which he takes metformin 1g bd and Dapagliflozin 10mg daily. His most recent HbA1c is 8%.\n\nOn examination, he is breathless with a pulse of 102 beats per minute, blood pressure of 135/80 mmHg, with a respiratory rate of 22/min. He is apyrexial. He has a BMI of 46 kg/m2. There are no specific findings on cardiovascular or respiratory examination. CTPA reveals multiple pulmonary emboli.\n\nWhich of the following is the most appropriate approach to the management of this patient?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Which of the following is the most appropriate approach to the management of this patient?","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"DOACs are generally considered safe and effective at standard doses for patients with a BMI between 30 and 40 kg/m. The approach is more nuanced in Severe obesity due to the limited data. While some guidelines once recommended against DOACs in severe obesity, updated guidance has removed this limitation, although caution is still advised. The International Society on Thrombosis and Haemostasis (ISTH) advises that DOACs should be avoided in patients with VTE or atrial fibrillation and severe obesity (BMI >40) kg/m or weight >120 kg, but other bodies, including NICE, have provided updated guidance based on newer data that allows their use."},{"id":"10148","category":"Respiratory medicine","stem":"A 57-year-old man presents having woken up breathless. He denies any cough or sputum production. He has a background of hypertension and Meniere’s disease. He works as a bus driver and has smoked 20 cigarettes a day since the age of 18. On examination, there is reduced air entry throughout the left lung field, and he has no peripheral oedema. His oxygen saturations are 88% on air. A chest x-ray shows a left-sided pneumothorax measuring 3 cm.\n\nHow should this patient’s pneumothorax be managed?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","How should this patient’s pneumothorax be managed?","Roberts ME, Rahman NM, Maskell NA, et alBritish Thoracic Society Guideline for pleural diseaseThorax 2023;78:1143-1156.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"How should this patient’s pneumothorax be managed?","explanation":"While this man does not have a formal diagnosis of lung disease, the fact that he is over the age of 50 and has a significant smoking history means that he should be classified as having a secondary pneumothorax. If a patient is breathless or their secondary pneumothorax measures >2cm, the appropriate management would be a chest drain. The new guidelines suggest that in defining a management strategy, the size of a pneumothorax is less important than the degree of clinical compromise, and clinical evaluation is therefore vital in deciding about the need for chest drain."},{"id":"14151","category":"Respiratory medicine","stem":"A 43-year-old man is admitted with right-sided pleuritic chest pain and breathlessness, which has worsened over the past 2 days. He denies any cough, sputum, feeling of hot or cold, weight loss, or bowel or urinary symptoms. He also does not have a history of recent travel or contact with sick people. He is a current smoker with 25 pack years.\n\nOn examination, he is lean-built, haemodynamically stable and well-mobilising without any syncopal or pre-syncopal symptoms. The rest of the examination is unremarkable.\n\nInvestigations done show the following findings:\n\nWhat is the recommended management of this patient?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"does not warrant checking d-dimers","explanation":"The probable diagnosis here is pulmonary embolism (PE) with infarction in the right lung. The well’s score indicates a high probability of PE and therefore does not warrant checking d-dimers. This patient can be managed as an outpatient via an ambulatory pathway, as his sPESI score is 0. Investigations for underlying malignancy are not justified at this point, as he does not have any red flags for malignancy, though once PE is confirmed, this should be explored further."},{"id":"11505","category":"Respiratory medicine","stem":"A 25-year-old man with Duchenne muscular dystrophy, who is usually wheelchair-bound, is admitted to the Acute Medical Unit for progressive general deterioration and drowsiness.\n\nOn examination, his Glasgow coma scale is 13/15, pulse rate is 115/minute, blood pressure is 100/80 mmHg, respiratory rate is 10/minute, oxygen saturation on air is 94% and his temperature is 37 oC. Capillary refill time is 2s, and jugular venous pressure is not elevated. There is no leg oedema.\n\nA respiratory system examination reveals reduced breath sounds on both sides. A cardiovascular system exam reveals normal heart sounds.\n\nHis abdomen is soft, no tenderness is noted, and active bowel sounds are present.\n\nContractures of all 4 limbs are noted with prominent scoliosis.\n\nInvestigations reveal:\n\nArterial blood gas on air\n\nWhat is the primary cause of this clinical deterioration?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","A 25-year-old man with Duchenne muscular dystrophy, who is usually wheelchair-bound, is admitted to the Acute Medical Unit for progressive general deterioration and drowsiness.","His abdomen is soft, no tenderness is noted, and active bowel sounds are present.","Contractures of all 4 limbs are noted with prominent scoliosis.","Investigations reveal:","Arterial blood gas on air","What is the primary cause of this clinical deterioration?","This patient has end-stage muscular dystrophy, and the arterial blood gas shows hypercarbic respiratory failure, which is due to neuromuscular weakness resulting in ventilatory failure.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"Arterial blood gas on air","explanation":"This patient has end-stage muscular dystrophy, and the arterial blood gas shows hypercarbic respiratory failure, which is due to neuromuscular weakness resulting in ventilatory failure."},{"id":"13720","category":"Respiratory medicine","stem":"A 56-year-old man was admitted to the acute medical unit with a 7-day history of fever, headache, breathlessness, and myalgia after returning from a package holiday in Europe.\n\nHis chest x-ray showed consolidation, and a urine test for Legionella antigen was positive. His CURB-65 score was 1. He had no allergies and took no medication. His renal and liver function were normal.\n\nWhat antibiotic is required to treat this patient?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Fluoroquinolones (levofloxacin) are recommended as first-line treatment for low and moderate-severity legionella pneumonia.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"Fluoroquinolones (levofloxacin) are recommended as first-line treatment for low and moderate-severity legionella pneumonia.","explanation":"Fluoroquinolones (levofloxacin) are recommended as first-line treatment for low and moderate-severity legionella pneumonia."},{"id":"11507","category":"Respiratory medicine","stem":"A 55-year-old man is admitted to the Acute Medical Unit with sudden-onset right-sided sharp chest pain and breathing difficulty. His past medical history includes type 2 diabetes and emphysema. He is a current smoker and has a 50-pack-year history.\n\nOn examination, he is alert and oriented. His pulse rate is 100/minute, blood pressure is 120/80 mmHg, respiratory rate is 22/minute, oxygen saturation on air is 95% and temperature is 37 oC.\n\nHe is struggling to complete full sentences; there is mild use of accessory muscles of breathing. Jugular venous pressure is not elevated, and there is no leg oedema.\n\nA respiratory system examination reveals absent breath sounds on the right side with increased resonance to percussion; left side reduced breath sounds with scattered wheezes.\n\nA cardiovascular system examination reveals normal heart sounds.\n\nA chest X-ray reveals a right-sided pneumothorax extending 3cm from the lung margin to the chest wall at the level of the hilum; features of hyperinflation are noted in the left lung.\n\nWhat is the most appropriate management?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","He is struggling to complete full sentences; there is mild use of accessory muscles of breathing. Jugular venous pressure is not elevated, and there is no leg oedema.","A chest X-ray reveals a right-sided pneumothorax extending 3cm from the lung margin to the chest wall at the level of the hilum; features of hyperinflation are noted in the left lung.","What is the most appropriate management?","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"This patient has secondary spontaneous pneumothorax (underlying emphysema) of >2cm and is breathless on examination, and as per the British Thoracic Society (BTS) guidelines. He needs a chest drain."},{"id":"11504","category":"Respiratory medicine","stem":"An 80-year-old man is admitted to the acute medical unit. His past medical history includes mild Alzheimer’s disease, asthma, type 2 diabetes mellitus, and osteoarthritis. He has never had any drug allergies or adverse drug reactions.\n\nHe lives in a residential home and, according to the home staff, the patient has had a low-grade fever, a cough and mild breathing difficulties for the past 3 days. He has been coughing up greenish-yellow phlegm for the past 24 hours. According to the residential home staff, the patient is usually pleasantly confused and forgetful, but he has become slightly more confused than usual.\n\nOn examination, he has a Glasgow coma scale of 14/15 and an abbreviated mental test score of 6/10.\n\nHis pulse rate is 90/minute, blood pressure is 160/80 mmHg, respiratory rate is 26/minute, oxygen saturation on air is 95% and temperature is 38oC.\n\nCapillary refill time is 2 seconds, and jugular venous pressure is not elevated. There is no leg oedema.\n\nA respiratory system examination reveals crepitations in the left lung base with bilateral scattered fine wheezes. A cardiovascular system examination reveals normal heart sounds.\n\nHis abdomen is soft, there is no tenderness, and active bowel sounds are present.\n\nInvestigations reveal:\n\nWhat would be the most appropriate management of this patient?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Capillary refill time is 2 seconds, and jugular venous pressure is not elevated. There is no leg oedema.","His abdomen is soft, there is no tenderness, and active bowel sounds are present.","Investigations reveal:","What would be the most appropriate management of this patient?","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"falls under the high-risk group for community-acquired pneumonia","explanation":"This patient has a CURB65 score of 3 (confusion score-1, urea > 7mmol/L score-1, respiratory rate score-0, blood pressure score-0, age > 65 score-1) and therefore falls under the high-risk group for community-acquired pneumonia. Although he has baseline confusion due to his Alzheimer’s disease, the history suggests worsening of the confusion from his baseline, and it needs to be taken into account in terms of the CURB65 score for the severity of pneumonia."},{"id":"10738","category":"Respiratory medicine","stem":"A 64-year-old woman with known chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD) presents to the emergency department with a 3-day history of increasing dyspnoea and wheezing. Her normal exercise tolerance is approximately 200 yards; however, this morning, this was decreased to a few steps only. She was diagnosed with an acute infective exacerbation of COPD by the on-call medical team and started on oxygen, nebulisers, antibiotics and prednisolone in line with the hospital guidelines. She has no other medical history and reports that, despite the limitation to her exercise tolerance, she has a good quality of life. She had a hospital admission three months ago, and the decision was made that she is for full escalation of treatment.\n\nAfter 4 hours of treatment, she is transferred to the respiratory ward, and you are asked to review her by the nursing staff as they are concerned that she is deteriorating. On review, she is dyspnoeic and reports no improvement with the treatment she has had so far. She looks fatigued, and you notice from her observations that she has required an increasing FiO2 to maintain her oxygen saturations at 96%.\n\nYou perform an arterial blood gas (FiO2 60% via venturi mask), the results of which are as follows:\n\nWhat is the next most appropriate management step?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Investigation\tResult\tNormal range\npH\t7.26\t7.35-7.45\npCo2\t7.8\t4.7-6.0 KPa\npO2\t8.0\t11-13 KPa\nHCO3\t32.0\t22-26 mmol/L","What is the next most appropriate management step?","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"What is the next most appropriate management step?","explanation":"This woman has an acute exacerbation of COPD with acute type II respiratory failure. She is displaying signs of fatigue and increasing oxygen requirements despite treatment. She, therefore, meets the criteria for starting NIV, which would typically be done on a respiratory or acute ward with nursing staff trained to manage NIV (this may vary between hospitals). Whilst she is for full escalation of treatment, it would be most appropriate to trial non-invasive ventilation in the first instance."},{"id":"7780","category":"Respiratory medicine","stem":"In which of the following case scenarios should non-invasive ventilation (NIV) be commenced in the emergency medical department?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","In which of the following case scenarios should non-invasive ventilation (NIV) be commenced in the emergency medical department?","Erkan Göksu; Non-invasive ventilation in the ED: Whom, When, How.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"Erkan Göksu; Non-invasive ventilation in the ED: Whom, When, How.","explanation":"Non-invasive ventilation is frequently used in the emergency medicine setting, with particular uses in acute heart failure or COPD. When used appropriately, NIV reduces intubation rates and mortality. In a recent Cochrane review, NIV was assessed for the management of hypercarbic respiratory failure due to exacerbation of COPD. The use of NIV decreased the risk of mortality and decreased the need for endotracheal intubation. In our scenario, the patient with COPD who has not responded to treatment with elevated PCO2 would be the most appropriate person to treat with NIV."},{"id":"3981","category":"Respiratory medicine","stem":"A 25-year-old asthmatic woman presents with increasing dyspnoea and wheeze over 3 days, requiring repeated doses of salbutamol.\n\nOn examination, she is struggling to complete sentences. Heart rate is 130 bpm, blood pressure is 100/60 mmHg, respiratory rate is 36 breaths/min, and oxygen saturation is 80% on room air. On auscultation, the chest is silent. While receiving continuous nebulised Salbutamol, she suddenly arrests.\n\nWhich of the following is the most likely cause of her arrest?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","A 25-year-old asthmatic woman presents with increasing dyspnoea and wheeze over 3 days, requiring repeated doses of salbutamol.","Which of the following is the most likely cause of her arrest?","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"and may be bilateral","explanation":"Asphyxia due to bronchospasm and mucus plugging is the most common cause of asthma-related death. Hypoxia-driven arrhythmia is another common fatal complication. Salbutamol can cause hypokalaemia, and other drugs used in the treatment of asthma, such as Aminophylline and Magnesium Sulphate, can cause arrhythmia and necessitate cardiac monitoring. Tension pneumothorax should be considered and may be bilateral."},{"id":"7783","category":"Respiratory medicine","stem":"A 29-year-old woman presents with syncope, chest pain and breathlessness. She is 20 weeks pregnant. There was no other medical history of note, and she took no medication. On examination, her temperature was 37oC, she had a pulse of 120/min, blood pressure 108/68 mmHg, a respiratory rate of 24/min and oxygen saturations of 95% on room air. The breath sounds were normal, and examination of the calves revealed them to be soft and non-tender. A chest X-ray revealed some haziness at the left base. The patient is treated with low molecular weight heparin pending further investigation.\n\nWhich of the following is the most appropriate approach to the management of this patient?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Which of the following is the most appropriate approach to the management of this patient?","Royal College of Obstetricians & Gynaecologists - Thromboembolic Disease in Pregnancy and the Puerperium: Acute Management.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"This pregnant woman presents with features suggesting a significant pulmonary embolism. According to guidance, this should be investigated with a CTPA as there is some abnormality with the chest X-ray. In this case, CTPA would be preferred to VQ scan. D-dimer is often positive even with pregnancy, so it offers no diagnostic accuracy in this case, and even if negative, it would be expected to reflect a false negative in the context of this very strong history."},{"id":"10737","category":"Respiratory medicine","stem":"A 57-year-old man presents to the emergency department with slight right-sided chest discomfort, which occurred after what he describes as a ‘coughing fit’. He is a current smoker of 30 cigarettes per day. He previously worked as a builder and is aware that he has been exposed to asbestos in the past. His medical history includes systemic hypertension and chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD). He has had two exacerbations of COPD in the past 12 months, one of which required hospital admission and non-invasive ventilation for type II respiratory failure.\n\nOn arrival to the emergency department, he is alert, haemodynamically stable, and reports right-sided chest discomfort only. Oxygen saturations are 97% on room air. Chest x-ray shows a clear 1.5 cm right-sided pneumothorax.\n\nWhat is the next appropriate management step?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","What is the next appropriate management step?","Roberts ME, Rahman NM, Maskell NA, et alBritish Thoracic Society Guideline for pleural disease. Thorax 2023;78:1143-1156.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"This patient has a secondary spontaneous pneumothorax, which is <2 cm in size, and according to new BTS guidelines should receive a drain as patient has high risk features and has chest pain. A CT scan may be required if it is considered not safe to intervene."},{"id":"17492","category":"Respiratory medicine","stem":"A 65-year-old man presents to the emergency department with fever and a cough with mucopurulent sputum production for three days. On clinical examination, he was oriented, conscious, and mildly tachypnoeic with a respiratory rate of 20 breaths per minute. His temperature was 38oC, his pulse rate was 98 beats per minute, BP 110/70 and his oxygen saturation was 94% on room air. He had coarse crepitations in the left infrascapular region.\n\nHe is a known case of chronic obstructive airway disease, with on-and-off metered dose inhalers and type-2 diabetes mellitus, for which he takes medications.\n\nInvestigations revealed the following results:\n\nWhat is the recommended next line of management for this patient?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","He is a known case of chronic obstructive airway disease, with on-and-off metered dose inhalers and type-2 diabetes mellitus, for which he takes medications.","Investigations revealed the following results:","Investigation\tResult\tNormal range\nComplete blood count\t14.8 x 109/L\t4-11 x 109/L\nCRP\t43\t< 5\nSputum routine\tGram-positive cocci in chains\t \nChest X-ray\tLeft lower lobe consolidation","What is the recommended next line of management for this patient?","The patient's initial line of investigations includes chest X-ray, complete blood picture, CRP, and sputum analysis.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"Community-acquired pneumonia is a common clinical condition seen in the emergency department. Patients’ clinical severity is assessed by CURB-65 (confusion, urea level, respiratory rate, blood pressure, and age). Patients’ treatment options, like choice of antibiotics, route of administration, place of admission and further investigations, are decided by the CURB-65 score."},{"id":"10736","category":"Respiratory medicine","stem":"A 54-year-old man presents to the emergency department with a sudden increase in shortness of breath and a cough. He is a current smoker of 25 cigarettes per day, which he has recently decreased from 40 per day following a diagnosis of chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD) by his GP. He currently works as an engineer and is aware that he has been exposed to asbestos in the past. Other medical history includes systemic hypertension.\n\nOn arrival at the emergency department, he is haemodynamically stable but reports significant left-sided chest pain and breathlessness at rest. Chest x-ray shows a 1.8 cm left-sided pneumothorax.\n\nWhat is the next appropriate management step?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"per the British Thoracic Society (BTS) guidelines","explanation":"This gentleman has a secondary spontaneous pneumothorax, and despite it being <2 cm in size, he is symptomatic; therefore, per the British Thoracic Society (BTS) guidelines, he should be admitted to the hospital for urgent chest drain insertion."},{"id":"11508","category":"Respiratory medicine","stem":"A 55-year-old man is currently admitted to the pulmonary unit following a diagnosis of large right-sided malignant pleural effusion.\n\nThe patient had been experiencing progressive breathing difficulty on exertion for one week, and a therapeutic drain was planned to relieve the effusion and underlying lung collapse. The chest medicine registrar inserted the drain at 5 PM and then assigned the patient to the medical on-call team to monitor him that evening.\n\nThe acute medicine team is requested for an urgent review at 7 PM due to the sudden deterioration of the patient.\n\nOn examination, he is alert and oriented but in respiratory distress. His pulse rate is 140/minute, regular, blood pressure is 90/70 mmHg, respiratory rate is 35/minute, oxygen saturation on air is 86% and his temperature is 37oC.\n\nHe is unable to speak full sentences, and he is using accessory muscles of breathing. Capillary refill time is 3s, and mild pitting leg oedema is noted.\n\nRespiratory system examination: Right intercostal space 12F chest tube in situ; reduced air entry in the base with fine crepitations noted throughout the right lung; left lung clear to auscultation; a total of 3 litres of straw-coloured pleural fluid is noted at the bedside.\n\nA cardiovascular system examination reveals normal heart sounds; tachycardia present.\n\nWhat is the likely cause of the patient’s sudden clinical deterioration?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","A 55-year-old man is currently admitted to the pulmonary unit following a diagnosis of large right-sided malignant pleural effusion.","The acute medicine team is requested for an urgent review at 7 PM due to the sudden deterioration of the patient.","He is unable to speak full sentences, and he is using accessory muscles of breathing. Capillary refill time is 3s, and mild pitting leg oedema is noted.","What is the likely cause of the patient’s sudden clinical deterioration?","This patient’s sudden deterioration is due to rapid, large-volume pleural fluid drainage and re-expansion pulmonary oedema (RPO) of the right lung.","Left ventricular failure is unlikely given unilateral crepitations; leg oedema may be seen in patients with malignancy related to low albumin levels.","This is a classical presentation of RPO, and lung collapse and pulmonary embolism are unlikely; tension pneumothorax is unlikely given audible crepitations in the re-expanded right lung.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"This patient’s sudden deterioration is due to rapid, large-volume pleural fluid drainage and re-expansion pulmonary oedema (RPO) of the right lung.","explanation":"This patient’s sudden deterioration is due to rapid, large-volume pleural fluid drainage and re-expansion pulmonary oedema (RPO) of the right lung."},{"id":"20210","category":"Respiratory medicine","stem":"A 62-year-old man presents to the acute medical unit with a 10-day history of right-sided pleuritic chest pain, fever, and dyspnoea. He has a background of type 2 diabetes mellitus managed with metformin 1g twice daily and sitagliptin 100mg once daily.\n\nOn examination, his temperature is 38.2oC, blood pressure 105/83 mmHg, heart rate 95bpm, respiratory rate 24 breaths per minute, oxygen saturation 92% on room air, and there is reduced air entry and stony dullness to percussion at the right base. A chest radiograph shows a moderate right-sided pleural effusion. Diagnostic pleural aspiration is performed.\n\nPleural fluid analysis results are shown below:\n\nBlood cultures have been sent, and intravenous antibiotics commenced (cefuroxime 750m TDS and metronidazole 500mg TDS).\n\nWhat is the most appropriate next step in management?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Pleural fluid analysis results are shown below:","Investigation\tResult\tNormal range","Appearance\tTurbid, purulent\tClear, pale yellow","pH\t7.08\t7.60-7.64","Glucose\t1.8 mmol/L\tSimilar to plasma (4.0–6.0 mmol/L)","Lactate dehydrogenase (LDH)","2,450 IU/L","Protein\t42 g/L\t<30 g/L (transudate); >30 g/L (exudate)","White cell count","<1,000/µL","Gram stain\tGram-positive cocci in chains\tNegative","Blood cultures have been sent, and intravenous antibiotics commenced (cefuroxime 750m TDS and metronidazole 500mg TDS).","What is the most appropriate next step in management?","The patient has a complicated parapneumonic effusion with pleural fluid pH <7.2, which is an absolute indication for chest drain insertion according to BTS guidelines.","Pleural fluid pH <7.2 indicates established infection requiring drainage, regardless of other parameters.","Additional features supporting complicated effusion include: purulent appearance, low glucose (<1.6 mmol/L in some definitions, <3.4 mmol/L in others), positive Gram stain, and high LDH.","Delaying drainage increases the risk of loculation, empyema formation, prolonged hospital stay, and the need for surgery.","Repeated aspiration is inadequate for managing established pleural infection. Therapeutic aspiration has no role in managing infected pleural fluid.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"The patient has a complicated parapneumonic effusion with pleural fluid pH <7.2, which is an absolute indication for chest drain insertion according to BTS guidelines.","explanation":"The patient has a complicated parapneumonic effusion with pleural fluid pH <7.2, which is an absolute indication for chest drain insertion according to BTS guidelines."},{"id":"11506","category":"Respiratory medicine","stem":"For the past 5 days, a 45-year-old man has had a headache, malaise, a runny nose, dry cough, sore throat and pain in both ears, along with low-grade intermittent fevers. In the past 24 hours, his cough has worsened, and he has come to the Accident and Emergency due to breathing problems.\n\nHe is admitted to the Acute Medical Unit. His past medical history is unremarkable. He denies any history of smoking or alcohol use and says he was fit and well until this admission.\n\nOn examination, he is alert and oriented. His pulse rate is 105/minute, blood pressure is 100/80 mmHg, and respiratory rate is 25/minute.\n\nHe is able to complete sentences only with pauses; mild accessory muscles of breathing use is noted.\n\nHis oxygen saturation on air is 94%, temperature is 38 oC, Capillary refill time is 3s, jugular venous pressure is not elevated. There is no leg oedema.\n\nA respiratory system examination reveals bilateral fleeting wheezes. A cardiovascular system examination reveals normal heart sounds.\n\nHis abdomen is soft, there is no tenderness, and active bowel sounds are present.\n\nInvestigations reveal:\n\nArterial blood gas on air\n\nWhat is the most likely diagnosis?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","He is admitted to the Acute Medical Unit. His past medical history is unremarkable. He denies any history of smoking or alcohol use and says he was fit and well until this admission.","He is able to complete sentences only with pauses; mild accessory muscles of breathing use is noted.","His abdomen is soft, there is no tenderness, and active bowel sounds are present.","Investigations reveal:","Investigation\tResult\tNormal range","Haemoglobin\t110 g/L\t115-160 g/L","Total leucocyte count\t12 x 109 cells/L\t4-11 x 109 cells/L","Platelet count\t300 x 109 cells/L\t150-450 x 109 cells/L","Reticulocyte count","C-Reactive protein\t25 mg/L\t< 10 mg/L","Erythrocyte sedimentation rate\t30 mm/hour\t< 20 mm/hour","Urea\t5 mmol/L\t3.5-7.2 mmol/L","Creatinine\t77 µmol/L\t49-90 µmol/L","Arterial blood gas on air","What is the most likely diagnosis?","This patient has community-acquired pneumonia (CAP) and has no underlying parenchymal lung or airways disease and is immunocompetent.","Streptococcal pneumonia is more likely to be associated with a ‘lobar’ consolidation rather than bilateral patchy infiltration in the chest X-ray.","MRSA, Pseudomonas and Aspergillus pneumonia are unlikely in this young patient without any lung disease or risk factors and immunocompetent status.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"This patient has community-acquired pneumonia (CAP) and has no underlying parenchymal lung or airways disease and is immunocompetent.","explanation":"This patient has community-acquired pneumonia (CAP) and has no underlying parenchymal lung or airways disease and is immunocompetent."},{"id":"13641","category":"Respiratory medicine","stem":"A 65-year-old man is admitted to the acute medicine unit with progressive breathlessness. His past medical history includes type 2 diabetes mellitus, hypertension, and seropositive rheumatoid arthritis. His current medications include insulin glargine 20 units once daily, ramipril 5 mg once daily, amlodipine 10 mg once daily, and hydroxychloroquine 400 mg once daily. He is a non-smoker and drinks 10 units of alcohol per week.\n\nOn examination, the patient is alert and oriented. His pulse rate is 115 beats per minute, and his blood pressure is 110/80 mmHg. Respiratory rate is 42 breaths per minute with oxygen saturation on air of 89%. His temperature is 37.6 oC.\n\nJugular venous pressure is not elevated. No leg oedema is noted.\n\nAn examination of his respiratory system reveals fine crackles throughout the chest, more so at the bases. His cardiovascular system examination shows normal heart sounds.\n\nThe patient’s abdomen is soft, with no tenderness, and there are active bowel sounds.\n\nMultiple deformities of both hands with wasting of the intrinsic muscles of the hands were noted\n\nInvestigations reveal the following results:\n\nHis chest X-ray is shown below:\n\n[Image source: Author].\n\nWhat is the most likely diagnosis?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Jugular venous pressure is not elevated. No leg oedema is noted.","The patient’s abdomen is soft, with no tenderness, and there are active bowel sounds.","Multiple deformities of both hands with wasting of the intrinsic muscles of the hands were noted","Investigations reveal the following results:","His chest X-ray is shown below:","[Image source: Author].","What is the most likely diagnosis?","Lobar pneumonia is unlikely given the history and bilateral chest X-ray findings.","CCF is unlikely given the history, chest X-ray, and normal echocardiogram.","Pulmonary embolism is unlikely to produce such auscultatory and chest X-ray findings, which rules this option out.","Acute exacerbation of COPD is likely to present with expiratory wheeze, and hyperinflation of the lungs is expected on X-ray.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"What is the most likely diagnosis?","explanation":"This patient has seropositive and erosive rheumatoid arthritis with auscultation findings of fibrotic crackles. The chest X-ray shows bilateral lung volume loss with interstitial reticular opacities and indistinct heart borders typical of lung fibrosis. The likely diagnosis, therefore, would be an acute exacerbation of pulmonary fibrosis."},{"id":"14145","category":"Respiratory medicine","stem":"A 27-year-old woman with a background of asthma is admitted to the hospital with worsening breathlessness, dry cough, and a temperature. Her last hospitalisation with asthma exacerbation was 3 months ago, when she was admitted to the high dependency unit (HDU). She was normally on salbutamol and beclomethasone/salmeterol inhalers.\n\nOn examination, she was breathless with audible wheezing from the bedside but able to speak full sentences. Her temperature was 37.7oC, with a respiratory rate of 20 breaths per minute, a heart rate of 117 beats per minute, and SaO2 98% on room air. She has a blood pressure of 121/67 mmHg and a peak expiratory flow rate (PEFR) of 55% predicted. Blood tests and her chest X-ray were unremarkable. She was given prednisolone 40 mg and back-to-back nebulisation with salbutamol and ipratropium. Her nose and throat swab came back positive for a respiratory syncytial virus (RSV). After initial treatment, PEFR improved to 80% and she started feeling better.\n\nWhat would be the best next course of action?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","What would be the best next course of action?","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"This patient has an asthma exacerbation from RSV infection, which does not require any treatment in adults. Similarly, as there is no bacterial infection, antibiotic use is not indicated. Though this patient has improved clinically and symptomatically after initial treatment, the recommendation is to admit and manage the patient as inpatients who have a history of near-fatal asthma attacks. As this patient had an HDU admission from an asthma exacerbation a few months back, she will need close observation and further management as an inpatient."},{"id":"10742","category":"Respiratory medicine","stem":"A 41-year-old man is admitted with progressive symmetrical weakness beginning distally, in the upper and lower limbs. A diagnosis of Guillain-Barré syndrome is suspected, and the diagnosis is confirmed following cerebrospinal fluid analysis showing elevated protein levels. He complains of some intermittent dysphagia and is initiated on intravenous immunoglobulin therapy, and forced vital capacity (FVC) monitoring is started. His initial FVC is measured at 2.5L, and his admission weight is 75kg.\n\nWhat forced vital capacity should raise concern for the development of severe respiratory failure in this patient?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"Guillain-Barré syndrome has several subtypes but is an acute demyelinating neuropathy of the peripheral nervous system. It can progress over days to weeks and may affect the muscles of respiration, leading to severe ventilatory failure requiring intubation. Regular FVC monitoring is warranted for patients admitted to the hospital, and a fall in FVC below 20 ml/kg body weight is considered a marker for the development of severe respiratory failure. Clinicians should consider using the ‘20/30/40 rule’, whereby the patient is deemed at risk of respiratory failure if the vital capacity is <20 ml/kg, the maximum inspiratory pressure is <30 cmH2O or the maximum expiratory pressure is <40 cmH2O."},{"id":"4224","category":"Respiratory medicine","stem":"A 35-year-old patient with known well-controlled atopic asthma presents to the emergency department with an acute asthma attack. She had been over at her friend’s house (who owns a cat), and about 15 minutes later, she felt wheezy and breathless. She decided to go to A&E.\n\nOn examination, she is breathless but able to converse in short sentences. She has a heart rate of 113bpm, BP 121/76mmHg, Saturations 95% on air, and temperature 37.1oC. Auscultation reveals widespread wheeze throughout both lung fields. Her Peak flow is 280 (her best peak flow is 400).\n\nWhat is the most appropriate initial management of this patient?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","What is the most appropriate initial management of this patient?","BTS: Quality improvement guidelines asthma, 2021.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"What is the most appropriate initial management of this patient?","explanation":"This patient has an acute exacerbation of her asthma. As such, the initial management should include nebulised bronchodilators (salbutamol and atrovent) and steroids. Oral steroids are as effective as intravenous delivery, provided the patient can take oral medication. There is no evidence of infection, so antibiotics are not warranted. This patient does not require IV magnesium sulphate as yet, and this should be reserved if she does not respond to the initial treatment."},{"id":"4223","category":"Respiratory medicine","stem":"A 29-year-old female is admitted with a severe exacerbation of her asthma and requires a 2-day stay in the hospital. On discharge, she is seen by a specialist asthma nurse and provided with a personalised asthma plan.\n\nRegarding asthma management plans, which patients should receive one?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"Guidelines recommend that all patients with asthma receive an individualised asthma management plan. The lack of asthma management plans was highlighted in the National Review into Asthma Deaths. Before discharge, following an asthma presentation, all patients should have inhaler technique and compliance checked, be provided with an asthma management plan (if they do not already have one), see their GP within 1 week and have specialist asthma follow-up arranged (either clinician or specialist asthma nurse)."},{"id":"14146","category":"Respiratory medicine","stem":"A 67-year-old man with a background of chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD), hypertension, atrial fibrillation (AF), and chronic back pain following a road traffic accident, is brought in by ambulance with breathlessness and reduced consciousness level. His SaO2 was 87% on room air, and he was started on oxygen inhalation with his SaO2 improving to 98% on 6 litres of oxygen.\n\nHe was recently started in the community on amoxicillin 500 mg three times a day, and prednisolone 30 mg once a day for infective exacerbation of COPD. His home medications include a salbutamol inhaler, tiotropium inhaler, codeine 30 mg four times a day, oramorph 5 mg four times daily as required, paracetamol 1 g four times a day as required, bisoprolol 2.5 mg once a day, edoxaban 60 mg once a day, ramipril 2.5 mg once a day, and Uniphyllin 200 mg three times daily.\n\nOn examination, his Glasgow coma scale (GCS) is 12 (E3V4M5). He has a temperature of 37oC, a heart rate of 106 beats per minute, irregular. His respiratory rate is 21 breaths per minute, and SaO2 is 97% on 60% oxygen via venturi. Chest auscultation reveals scattered wheeze bilaterally, pupils are 4mm equally reactive to light bilaterally, and he is moving all four limbs in response to painful stimuli.\n\nInvestigations reveal the following results:\n\nThe patient is given back-to-back nebulisation with salbutamol and ipratropium, along with IV hydrocortisone 200 mg.\n\nWhat is the recommended next step in his management?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Investigations reveal the following results:","Investigation\tResult\tNormal range","Haemoglobin\t144 g/L\t115-160 g/L","White cell count\t12.1 x 109/L\t4.0-11.0 x 109/L","Neutrophils\t10.3 109/L\t2.0-7.5 x 109/L","Platelets\t242 x 109/L\t150-400 x 109/L","Sodium\t131 mmol/L\t135-145 mmol/L","Potassium\t4.3 mmol/L\t3.5-5.0 mmol/L","Bicarbonate\t37 mmol/L\t20-32 mmol/L","Urea\t4.1 mmol/L\t3.6-10.1 mmol/L","Creatinine\t67 mmol/L\t39-140 mmol/L","CRP\t11 mmol/L\t< 10 mmol/L","Liver function tests\tNormal","Blood glucose\t8.1 mmol/L\t4.0-10.0 mmol/L","Chest X-ray\tProminent broncho vascular\nmarkings in both lungs","The patient is given back-to-back nebulisation with salbutamol and ipratropium, along with IV hydrocortisone 200 mg.","What is the recommended next step in his management?","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"The patient is given back-to-back nebulisation with salbutamol and ipratropium, along with IV hydrocortisone 200 mg.","explanation":"This patient has COPD exacerbation with decompensated type-2 respiratory failure/ acidosis and was given treatment in the community, but did not improve. He was already started on salbutamol and ipratropium nebulisation, and he was also given IV hydrocortisone. COPD patients who are at risk of type-2 respiratory failure are too sensitive to oxygen therapy and can decompensate with CO2 retention and respiratory acidosis if too much oxygen is given, as is the case here. Therefore, instead of aiming for high SaO2 in these patients, the target SaO2 should be set between 88-92% and oxygen should be titrated accordingly. So, the next step would be to reduce his oxygen inhalation levels alongside the nebulisation, which should not be provided with oxygen. In COPD patients, the recommended prednisolone dose is 30 mg once a day or equivalent, whereas 40 mg once a day is recommended in asthma. Aminophylline infusion can be considered if the response to initial treatment is inadequate, and NIV is indicated if hypercapnia and acidosis do not improve despite optimal medical treatment. Although this patient is on opioids, this is not a case of opioid toxicity, as his observations, like his pupil size and respiratory rate, do not point towards this, and naloxone infusion is therefore not indicated."},{"id":"3824","category":"Respiratory medicine","stem":"A 45-year-old man was admitted with chest tightness and a cough of approximately 6 weeks' duration. He denied any fever but had, on occasion, produced greenish sputum. He had seen his GP two weeks previously and was treated with amoxicillin, but his cough had not improved, and on the evening of his admission, he became particularly and suddenly breathless.\n\nOn admission, he was found to have a temperature of 38.3oC, a pulse of 100 bpm and sats of 94% on room air. He had a respiratory rate of 22/min and scattered wheezes on chest examination. Of note, his white cell count was 9 (3-10), CRP was 44 mg/dl, arterial PO2 was noted to be 10.3kPa (10.5-14), PCO2 was 3.8kPa (4.5-6), and chest x-ray revealed no consolidation. ECG was normal. He was treated for community-acquired pneumonia with IV augmentin and oral clarithromycin. He received prophylactic low molecular weight heparin according to the hospital protocol.\n\nWithin 6 hours, his temperature had subsided, but he still felt rather breathless.\n\nThe following day, he was reviewed by the respiratory consultant, who noted a family history of asthma with his son using an inhaler. Observations were stable, but he was found to have an audible wheeze again and was diagnosed with adult-onset asthma. He was treated with nebulised salbutamol and prednisolone 30 mg daily. At 9 pm the following night, the patient became acutely unwell. He is seen by the duty F2. He describes acute breathlessness and is dyspnoeic. He is tachycardic and has a pulse of 105 beats per minute, although he had inhaled salbutamol an hour previously. His oxygen saturations are 92%, his temperature is 36.7oC, and his blood pressure is 128/70 mmHg. His ECG was normal. His peak flow was 390.\n\nInvestigations at this stage reveal:\n\nHe settles down with further nebulisers and his Peak flow is 550.\n\nHe is seen the following morning when his breathlessness has improved, though he remains slightly dyspnoeic, he is apyrexial, and his peak flow is 550. He is now keen to go home.\n\nWhich of the following is the appropriate management for this patient?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Within 6 hours, his temperature had subsided, but he still felt rather breathless.","Investigations at this stage reveal:","Investigation\tResult\nChest x-ray\tNormal\npO2\t8.3 kPa\nPCO2\t3.3 kPa","He settles down with further nebulisers and his Peak flow is 550.","He is seen the following morning when his breathlessness has improved, though he remains slightly dyspnoeic, he is apyrexial, and his peak flow is 550. He is now keen to go home.","Which of the following is the appropriate management for this patient?","Ouellette, D. R. Pulmonary Embolism (PE) Clinical Presentation, Mescape, 2020.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"One must consider PE, in this case, even from the original admission. Subsegmental PEs can cause these symptoms of cough, wheeze and weight loss. These nagging symptoms lasting weeks are well-reported. Whilst one could be forgiven for making the original diagnosis of pneumonia, the fact that he didn’t improve, remaining breathless and then suddenly becoming particularly hypoxic, should point towards a diagnosis of PEs. This patient should remain as an inpatient, with treatment-dose LMWH before having a CTPA."},{"id":"3995","category":"Respiratory medicine","stem":"A 42-year-old man with schizophrenia complains of cough and night sweats for 3/52. No improvement was observed after a 1/52 Amoxicillin from the GP, so his carers brought him to A&E. Clinical examination is consistent with consolidation and a pleural effusion at the right base. His temperature is 37.4oC and his oxygen saturations are 95% on air. CXR confirms right lower and midzone pneumonia with a moderate right pleural effusion. A diagnostic pleural tap was undertaken with blood-stained fluid extracted.\n\nAnalysis of pleural fluid revealed:\n\nThe most likely diagnosis and management is?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Analysis of pleural fluid revealed:","Investigation\tResult\tNormal range\npH\t6.9\t7.35 - 7.45\nGlucose\t1.0 mmol/L\t>3.4 mmol/L\nProtein\t50 g/L\t<20 g/L\nLDH\t5467 iu/L\t<100 iu/L","The most likely diagnosis and management is?","BTS Pleural Disease Guideline 2023","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"There is no pus in the fluid, so by definition, this is not an empyema. As the pH is <7.2, LDH >1000 and glucose is low, this is a complicated parapneumonic effusion, and BTS guidance recommends drainage with a 12 F chest drain. Note that empyemas do not always require a wide-bore drain, and 12-F chest drains are being increasingly used here."},{"id":"4227","category":"Respiratory medicine","stem":"A 68-year-old woman presents to the acute medical unit via her GP on a Friday evening with a 2-week history of increasing breathlessness on exertion. She has a past medical history of breast cancer, radically treated 8 years ago, and hypertension. She is an ex-smoker with a 20-pack-year history. She reports a dry cough and a reduction in her exercise tolerance. She now describes being breathless when walking up 1 flight of stairs.\n\nOn examination, she appears comfortable at rest, her oxygen saturations are 98% on air, and her respiratory rate is 19/min. Her pulse is 88 bpm and her blood pressure is 150/88 mmHg. Examination of her cardiovascular system is entirely normal with no peripheral oedema. Auscultation of her chest reveals reduced air entry at the right base. A chest X-ray shows a moderate right-sided effusion.\n\nHer blood results are as below:\n\nWhat is the most appropriate management of this patient?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Her blood results are as below:","What is the most appropriate management of this patient?","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"What is the most appropriate management of this patient?","explanation":"Although symptomatic, this woman is currently stable. There is nothing in the examination to suggest that this lady requires urgent out-of-hours intervention, and departmental ultrasound marking is not recommended. A chest drain should not be the initial management of choice, and a therapeutic aspiration (with real-time bedside ultrasound), with samples sent for diagnostic purposes, is appropriate. As this patient is unlikely to be seen until Monday by the respiratory team, and as she is stable, she can be managed as an urgent outpatient in the appropriate pleural clinic."},{"id":"3562","category":"Respiratory medicine","stem":"A 43-year-old woman presents with a sudden onset of chest tightness and dyspnoea. She has a recent diagnosis of intestinal lymphoma for which she is under the care of the oncology team. On examination, she is comfortable at rest, has a pulse of 100 beats per minute, regular, a blood pressure of 110/80 mmHg and oxygen saturations of 88% on room air. The VQ Scan reveals several mismatched defects in the chest.\n\nWhich of the following is the most appropriate initial treatment for this patient?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Which of the following is the most appropriate initial treatment for this patient?","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"Which of the following is the most appropriate initial treatment for this patient?","explanation":"This patient has had multiple pulmonary emboli based on her presentation and confirmatory VQ scan. Low molecular weight heparin or DOACs would be the recommended initial treatment for this patient. The clinical features do not suggest that the patient is haemodynamically compromised, which would warrant thrombolysis. Unfractionated heparin again is not indicated here."},{"id":"8021","category":"Respiratory medicine","stem":"A 35-year-old woman presents to the MAU with a 3-day history of deteriorating shortness of breath, fever, and cough. Her past medical history includes a 1-year history of immune thrombocytopaenic purpura (ITP) for which she received oral prednisolone, though poorly responsive and latterly has made a good response to 4 cycles of rituximab. She drinks little alcohol and smokes occasionally. There is little of note in family history other than her mother having hypothyroidism.\n\nOn examination, she has a temperature of 39oC, a pulse of 100 bpm and blood pressure of 122/80 mmHg with oxygen saturations of 92% on air. She has a respiratory rate of 28/min and has evidence of consolidation at the right base.\n\nInvestigations reveal:\n\nChest x-ray confirms right-sided basal consolidation.\n\nWhich of the following is the most likely cause of her presentation?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Investigations reveal:","Chest x-ray confirms right-sided basal consolidation.","Which of the following is the most likely cause of her presentation?","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"This patient has community-acquired pneumonia, but the salient features that should not be missed are the low total protein of 51, yet normal albumin of 36. The difference, ie, 15, is composed mainly of globulins, which should be 21-36. In the context of the previous use of rituximab for ITP, this suggests a diagnosis of rituximab-induced hypogammaglobulinaemia. The diagnosis is important to make as recovery may be significantly impaired without this, and treatment may include immune globulins depending on the extent of the immune paresis. The likelihood of developing rituximab-induced hypogammaglobulinaemia is increased with multiple cycles of therapy and can occur many months/years after treatment."},{"id":"4256","category":"Respiratory medicine","stem":"A 45-year-old man is admitted with acute breathlessness and some associated central chest pain. He has no past medical history of note. CTPA confirms a diagnosis of pulmonary embolism. On examination, he has a heart rate of 100 bpm, a blood pressure of 106/60 mmHg, a respiratory rate of 22/min, a SaO2 of 94% on room air, a temperature of 37.2 oC, and her GCS is 15/15.\n\nHow long should this patient be treated with anticoagulation?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","How long should this patient be treated with anticoagulation?","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"How long should this patient be treated with anticoagulation?","explanation":"This man has a low-risk PE as suggested by his PESI score of 0, and so evidence suggests that the patient can be managed as an ambulatory case. However, one must consider here that this man appears to have an entirely unprovoked PE, in which case guidance recommends lifelong anticoagulation. With a provoked PE, the patient can be treated for 3 months unless there is an ongoing risk factor, in which case 6 months’ treatment is required. In an unprovoked PE, at least 3 months duration is recommended, with consideration for longer treatment, weighing up risks/benefits at that stage. With recurrent PE, lifelong anticoagulation is recommended. If PE occurs during pregnancy. Anticoagulation should be continued throughout pregnancy and for at least 6 weeks postpartum with a minimum total duration of 3 months. Where PE is associated with cancer, a minimum of 3 months of anticoagulation is required, but increasingly lifelong/indefinite treatment is recommended or at least until malignancy is in remission."},{"id":"7108","category":"Respiratory medicine","stem":"A 34-year-old man, with no significant past medical history and who is a non-smoker, presents with acute onset chest pain on the right side and is found to have a pneumothorax on chest X-ray. The chest X-ray is otherwise unremarkable. On measurement, it is found to be approximately 1 cm from the lung margin to the chest wall at the level of the hilum.\n\nThe patient’s observations are as follows:\n\nWhat is the next step?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","The patient’s observations are as follows:","Investigation\tResult\tNormal ranges","Temperature\t36oC\t36.1–37.2","Respiratory rate\t22 breaths/min\t16–20","Heart rate\t110 bpm\t50–80","Blood pressure\t110/50 mmHg\t120/80","Oxygen saturations on air","95 - 100","What is the next step?","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"Oxygen saturations on air","explanation":"The definition of a ‘large’ pneumothorax, as per the clinical practice guidelines, is a pneumothorax of >2 cm measurement from the lung margin to the chest wall at the level of the hilum. This patient has primary spontaneous pneumothorax (PSP), is less than 50 years old and is a non-smoker, and there is no evidence of underlying lung disease on examination or chest x-ray. Conservative management is the treatment of choice for a small PSP without significant breathlessness and in the absence of a persistent air leak. The PSP will gradually resolve as air is reabsorbed into the pulmonary capillaries. Patients with a small PSP without breathlessness should be considered for discharge with an early outpatient review in 2–4 days. These patients should also receive clear written advice to return in the event of worsening breathlessness. Supplemental high-flow oxygen is recommended when patients are admitted for observation."},{"id":"13714","category":"Respiratory medicine","stem":"A 65-year-old man was admitted to the acute medical unit with a 3-week history of breathlessness on exertion. His exercise tolerance has fallen from approximately 1 mile to 0.25 miles, limited by breathlessness. He has no chest pain or other symptoms. He has no significant past medical history and takes no medication. He had dullness to percussion and decreased vocal resonance at the left base. Cardiovascular, abdominal, and neurological examinations were all normal. His temperature and ECG were normal.\n\nA chest X-ray revealed moderate left-sided pleural effusion. A diagnostic aspiration of 50 millilitres of straw-coloured fluid was performed.\n\nInvestigation results are as follows:\n\nWhat is the most appropriate next step in management?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","This patient has an exudative effusion by Light’s criteria. Light’s criteria for an exudate are as follows:","The ratio of pleural fluid protein to serum protein is more than 0.5","The ratio of pleural fluid LDH to plasma LDH is more than 0.6","If the CT scan is also non-diagnostic, a pleural biopsy under direct vision is the next step (either via VATS or medical thoracoscopy).","Bronchoscopy should not be done when investigating an exudative pleural effusion unless there is a specific lesion suspected on the chest X-ray or CT scan.","BTS Guidelines For Pleural Disease.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"This patient has an exudative effusion by Light’s criteria. Light’s criteria for an exudate are as follows:","explanation":"This patient has an exudative effusion by Light’s criteria. Light’s criteria for an exudate are as follows:"},{"id":"10743","category":"Respiratory medicine","stem":"A 32-year-old man was admitted to the acute intake with acute shortness of breath and palpitations. Two hours earlier, he had been at a rave and had consumed alcohol and some other drugs offered to him by an acquaintance. Shortly after ingesting this, he had become unwell.\n\nOn examination, he looked cyanosed, with a pulse of 110 beats per minute, regular, blood pressure of 120/78 mmHg, a temperature of 37 oC and oxygen saturations of 82% on 5L of oxygen with a respiratory rate of 22/min.\n\nOn venesection, his blood is noted to be a chocolate brown colour. He has normal FBC and U+Es. His blood gases show:\n\nWhich of the following is the most appropriate treatment for this patient?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","On venesection, his blood is noted to be a chocolate brown colour. He has normal FBC and U+Es. His blood gases show:","investigation\tResult\tNormal range","pH\t7.44\t7.35 – 7.45","pCO2\t4 kPa\t3.5-5.5 kPa","pO2\t20 kPa\t10-14 kPa","Bicarbonate\t21 mmol/L\t22-26 mmol/L","Lactate\t4.4 mmol/L\t<1.5 mmol/L","Methaemoglobin","Which of the following is the most appropriate treatment for this patient?","Drugs such as dapsone, primaquine, chloroquine, sulphonamides, nitrofurantoin and lignocaine can also cause methaemoglobinaemia.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"Methaemoglobin","explanation":"Poppers or amyl nitrite are a drug of abuse associated with aphrodisiac and hallucinogenic effects. The drug is usually inhaled as it is a volatile liquid, but inhalation and particularly oral intake are associated with the development of methaemoglobinaemia. The Fe2+ component of haem is oxidised to the Fe3+ component by nitrites, resulting in conformational changes to haem, shifting the oxygen dissociation curve to the left, making the haem less able to give up oxygen at the tissue level. Increasing met-Hb levels result in increasing cellular hypoxia. This explains why oxygen saturations are low (the oxidised Fe3+ is not picked up on the sat machine wavelength), yet PO2 may be unaffected or high as the oxygen is not released."},{"id":"13712","category":"Respiratory medicine","stem":"A 28-year-old woman presented to the acute medical unit with an acute exacerbation of asthma. She uses a salbutamol inhaler infrequently. Previously, she had never been admitted before with an exacerbation of asthma. She had recently moved to a new apartment.\n\nHer temperature is 37.2 oC with a pulse rate of 120 beats per minute. Her respiratory rate is 30 breaths per minute, and her oxygen saturation is 93% on air. Her peak expiratory flow rate is 40% of her predicted rate.\n\nArterial blood gas on air:\n\nWhat level of asthma exacerbation severity does this patient have?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Arterial blood gas on air:","Investigation\tResult\tNormal range\npH\t7.35\t7.35 – 7.45\npO2\t10.5 kPa\t11.3 – 12.6 kPa\npCO2\t5.6 kPa\t4.7 – 6.0 kPa","What level of asthma exacerbation severity does this patient have?","Life-threatening asthma is ‘severe asthma’ plus any one of the following:","Altered conscious level","Exhaustion","Silent chest","Poor respiratory effort","Cyanosis","Arrhythmia","Hypotension","Near-fatal asthma is defined as patients with a raised pCO2 and/or requiring mechanical ventilation with raised inflation pressures.","Acute severe asthma is when any one of the following is present:","Heart rate ≥110 beats per minute,","Inability to complete sentences in one breath.","Moderate asthma exacerbation is defined as:","increasing symptoms,","Predicted peak expiratory flow values should be used only if the recent best peak expiratory flow (within two years) is unknown.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"Moderate asthma exacerbation is defined as:","explanation":"Life-threatening asthma is defined as life-threatening because the patient has a normal pCO2 along with features of severe asthma. A normal arterial partial pressure of carbon dioxide in a patient experiencing an acute, severe asthma attack is indeed considered a sign of life-threatening asthma (or impending respiratory failure). In a typical, mild-to-moderate asthma exacerbation, the patient hyperventilates due to breathlessness and hypoxia. This increased breathing rate and depth cause them to \"blow off\" more CO2, resulting in a low PaCO2 (respiratory alkalosis). As the asthma attack becomes severe, the airways become extremely obstructed, and the respiratory muscles begin to fatigue from the excessive work of breathing. The patient can no longer maintain the high level of ventilation needed to expel CO2 effectively."},{"id":"4226","category":"Respiratory medicine","stem":"A 19-year-old man presents to the hospital with a 1-day history of left-sided pleuritic chest pain. He feels a little breathless. He smokes 15 cigarettes per day and admits to some cannabis use. He has no past medical history of note.\n\nOn examination, he looks comfortable. He is approximately 1.90m tall and has a BMI of 19 kg/m2. He is not dyspnoeic. Examination of his chest is unremarkable except for a clicking sound heard in association with the heart sounds.\n\nA chest X-ray is unremarkable.\n\nGiven the most likely diagnosis, which of the following initial investigations may help with diagnosis?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Lateral decubitus chest X-rays may provide additional information, but an expiratory chest X-ray is of little benefit. CT thorax should be the gold standard.","Roberts ME, Rahman NM, Maskell NA, et alBritish Thoracic Society Guideline for pleural disease. Thorax 2023;78:1143-1156.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"A synchronous click with the heart sounds is associated with a small apical (left) pneumothorax, which can be missed on a traditional PA film. He is tall and, in addition, smokes – both known to be risk factors for developing pneumothorax."},{"id":"10741","category":"Respiratory medicine","stem":"You review a 72-year-old woman who is admitted to the High Dependency Unit (HDU) following an episode of acute exacerbation of COPD. She is being given 6 L O2/min via facemask. Her SpO2 on pulse oximetry is 96%. ABGs show the following results:\n\nWhat will you do to address her rising pCO2?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Investigation\tResult\tNormal range\npH\t7.35\t7.35 - 7.45\npCO2\t6.4 kPa\t4 - 6 kPa\npO2\t14.2 kPa\t10 - 14 kPa","What will you do to address her rising pCO2?","Global Initiative for Chronic Obstructive Lung Disease.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"Patients with COPD have hypoxia-driven ventilation. High pressures of O2 can suppress this drive and cause retention of CO2. This patient has high pCO2 and her pH is also on the lower side. Her high pCO2 indicates that she is over-oxygenated. In this condition, the British Thoracic Society recommends setting the O2 flow to the lowest level to maintain the target saturation of 88 - 92% and recheck ABGs. Abrupt cessation of oxygen therapy can lead to rebound hypoxemia. The need for NIV or endotracheal intubation can be considered if the patient continues to retain CO2 despite lowering oxygen flow. Increasing oxygen flow will lead to worsening of pCO2."},{"id":"10734","category":"Respiratory medicine","stem":"A 24-year-old man presents to the emergency department with right-sided chest pain and dyspnoea, which has been getting progressively worse over the past three days. He is normally fit and well and has no known medical history, no allergies and takes no regular medications. He reports that the symptoms came on suddenly, and there is no history of trauma. He is haemodynamically stable.\n\nPA chest radiograph shows a right-sided pneumothorax with a depth of 2.6 cm at the hilum. Blood tests, including a coagulation screen, were all normal.\n\nWhat is the most appropriate further management?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"This patient has a primary spontaneous pneumothorax. Per the British Thoracic Society guidelines on the management of spontaneous pneumothorax, in patients not deemed suitable for conservative or ambulatory management, needle aspiration or tube drainage should be considered for the initial treatment of primary spontaneous pneumothorax in adults. If unsuccessful, the guideline states that you would proceed to an 8-14 F chest drain."},{"id":"10146","category":"Respiratory medicine","stem":"A 22-year-old man presents with sudden onset of breathlessness. Oxygen saturations are 97% on air. A chest x-ray shows a right-sided pneumothorax. You decide to measure the size of the pneumothorax to determine your further management.\n\nAt what point on the X-ray should you measure?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","At what point on the X-ray should you measure?","The size of the pneumothorax should be measured at the level of the hilum. If there is a >2cm rim of air between the lung edge and the chest wall, the pneumothorax can be deemed as ‘large’.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"The size of the pneumothorax should be measured at the level of the hilum. If there is a >2cm rim of air between the lung edge and the chest wall, the pneumothorax can be deemed as ‘large’.","explanation":"The size of the pneumothorax should be measured at the level of the hilum. If there is a >2cm rim of air between the lung edge and the chest wall, the pneumothorax can be deemed as ‘large’."},{"id":"10739","category":"Respiratory medicine","stem":"A 28-year-old woman is seen in the emergency department. She has asthma for which she takes a long-acting beta2 agonist/inhaled corticosteroid inhaler. She is 24 weeks pregnant. She has had a 1-day history of increased cough, breathlessness, and wheezing with some green sputum production.\n\nHer observations include a respiratory rate of 24/min, oxygen saturations of 95% on room air, a temperature of 38.2°C and a pulse rate of 100 beats per minute. Widespread expiratory polyphonic wheeze is heard on auscultation of the chest. A chest x-ray has been performed, which shows no consolidation.\n\nWhat would be the most appropriate initial treatment in addition to nebulised bronchodilators?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","What would be the most appropriate initial treatment in addition to nebulised bronchodilators?","SIGN/BTS Asthma guideline 2019.\nGINA Pocket Guide 2022 Front Cover 5.5x8.5 (ginasthma.org).\nManagement of Life-Threatening Asthma - CHEST (chestnet.org).","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"This lady has an infective exacerbation of asthma and should be treated with steroids and antibiotics. Doxycycline should be avoided in pregnancy. There is no reason why she could not have both the steroids and amoxicillin orally in this case."},{"id":"13170","category":"Respiratory medicine","stem":"A 58-year-old man is being seen by you in the same-day emergency care (SDEC) unit. The patient was initially seen by his GP due to left leg swelling that started a few days ago and shortness of breath. His doctor started him on low molecular weight heparin (LMWH) and referred him for an investigation of possible pulmonary embolism (PE). He had a CT pulmonary angiogram that confirmed a diagnosis of a small PE. The patient worked as a teacher in a primary school, had no previous significant medical history, and was not on any regular medications. He has no identifiable provocative factor for his PE. He denied weight loss, loss of appetite, night sweats, cough, or bleeding from any site. The patient also confirmed that he was previously fit and well.\n\nThe patient’s chest, abdomen, and cardiac examination were normal. His blood tests, including full blood count, coagulation profile, liver and kidney functions, and electrolytes, were all normal. You diagnosed him as unprovoked PE.\n\nWhat is the most suitable strategy to consider in managing this patient?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","HAS-BLED score.\nVenous thromboembolic diseases: diagnosis, management and thrombophilia testing.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"The NICE guidelines regarding unprovoked PE suggest that the benefits of lifelong anticoagulation outweigh the risk if the bleeding risk is low. The patient's HAS-BLED score is 0, suggesting that the benefits of continuing anticoagulation outweigh the risk. If in other cases the HAS-BLED score is 4 or more, a discussion regarding stopping anticoagulation should be made. Patient preferences should always be explored. While HASBLED was originally designed for patients with atrial fibrillation, it has been validated for use in venous thromboembolism (VTE), which includes PE."},{"id":"7870","category":"Uncategorised","stem":"A 50-year-old woman presents to the medical admissions unit with abdominal pain, nausea and vomiting. She admitted to taking a paracetamol overdose 24 hours previously but was unsure of the exact quantity taken. There was no other history of note, and she had taken paracetamol as a consequence of having a row with her partner.\n\nOn examination, she was drowsy and had some abdominal tenderness, with a pulse of 100 beats per minute, a blood pressure reading of 110/68 mmHg and a respiratory rate of 28 breaths per minute. She was apyrexial.\n\nImmediate point of care tests showed the following results:\n\nWhich of the following is the most appropriate immediate management for this patient?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","British Journal of Clinical PharmacologyVolume 87, Issue 3 Mar 2021 Pages703-1630. The changing face of paracetamol toxicity and new regimens for an old antidote N-acetylcysteine.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"This patient took a paracetamol overdose roughly 24 hours ago; the exact amount is unclear, although she now presents with features of toxicity and associated lactic acidosis. The patient should be treated immediately with NAC infusion plus IV fluids whilst awaiting the results of paracetamol levels as well as other investigations, particularly liver function tests and INR. The following case report illustrates the acute onset of action of paracetamol overdose and how it can prove fatal despite treatment."},{"id":"10379","category":"Uncategorised","stem":"A 78-year-old man presents with a haematoma of the right lower leg. This evolved over the last 12 hours and had become increasingly large, bruised and painful. He has been struggling to walk on his leg. He was unaware of any particular injury to this. Over the last 12 months, he had noticed an increased propensity to bruises which had occurred on his back, arms and legs, but he had not sought medical attention for this.\n\nThe patient has a 6-year history of type-2 diabetes for which he takes metformin 1g bd together with empagliflozin 10 mg daily. He also takes atorvastatin 20 mg daily and ramipril 10mg daily for hypertension. The patient also completed a Covid-19 vaccination 2 months ago; he noticed a bruise after this too.\n\nOn examination, he is noted to have extensive deep bruising of the right calf. Pulses are all palpable. There is another bruise noted over the right scapula. Pulse is 88 bpm regular, and his blood pressure is 128/88 mmHg.\n\nWhich of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Investigations:","Investigation\tResult\tNormal range","Hb\t126 g/L\t120-160 g/L","Platelets\t219 x 109/L\t140–400 x 109/L","White blood cell count\t6.9 x 109/L\t3-10 x 109/L","Sodium\t140 mmol/L\t134–144 mmol/L","Potassium\t4.2 mmol/L\t3.5–5.5 mmol/L","Urea\t8.2 mmol/L\t3–8 mmol/L","Creatinine\t108 micromol/L\t50–100 micromol/L","LFTs\tNormal","Prothrombin time\t10 sec\t9–14","aPTT\t62 sec\t30–40","Mixing test\tNo correction of aPTT","HbA1c","Ultrasound of the leg\tLarge calf muscle haematoma","CXR\tNormal","ECG\tSinus rhythm","Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"LFTs\tNormal","explanation":"This elderly patient presents with a year's history of what seems to be increasing spontaneous bruising and an acute presentation with a larger deep haematoma in the calf. This is associated with normal platelet count, normal PT, but exaggerated aPTT. The history and the prolonged aPTT are suggestive of acquired haemophilia, which presents more commonly in the elderly and is not correctable with the mixing test. (Lupus anticoagulant is slightly paradoxical in that it is also associated with aPTT, which may not correct with mixing, but unlike AHA is not associated with bleeding, but thrombosis). Acquired haemophilia is associated with autoimmune conditions in roughly 50% and idiopathic in the other 50%. The condition is associated with inhibitors of FVIII, which results in the prolongation of the aPTT, not reversed on correction studies (due to inhibitors of FVIII) and associated bleeds. Unlike hereditary haemophilia, the bleeds are not into joints but are more associated with soft tissue bruising, nose bleeds, GI/GU haemorrhages."},{"id":"11675","category":"Uncategorised","stem":"A 75-year-old man is currently admitted to the Care of the elderly ward. He is being treated for suspected cystitis with intravenous antibiotics. His past medical history includes severe Parkinson’s disease, cognitive impairment, recurrent falls, orthostatic hypotension, constipation, and benign prostatic hyperplasia with urinary incontinence.\n\nDuring the night, the ward nurse is concerned about the patient’s behaviour and requests a review from the Acute Medical team. The patient has been agitated, anxious and threatening staff. He has also been noted to be visually hallucinating.\n\nOn examination, he is frail, confused, distressed and agitated. He has resting tremors and severe bradykinesia, and postural instability. His blood pressure is 90/60 mmHg, pulse rate is 90 beats per minute, oxygen saturation on air is 99% and his temperature is 36.5 oC.\n\nRespiratory and cardiovascular examinations are normal. The patient’s abdomen is soft and non-tender. A recent ECG revealed sinus rhythm; non-specific ST-T changes and corrected QT interval 400ms (normal < 430 ms).\n\nWhich of the following would be the most appropriate medication to reduce this patient’s delirium?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Which of the following would be the most appropriate medication to reduce this patient’s delirium?","Haloperidol, which is usually the first-choice medication in delirium, is a first-generation antipsychotic and is not ideal in this situation.","Donepezil is an acetylcholinesterase inhibitor, used in the management of dementia and is not suitable for use in delirium.","Benzodiazepines have a limited role in the management of delirium, and can worsen the clinical situation in this patient, given hypotension, frailty and fall risk.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"This patient has severe Parkinson’s disease (PD) with postural instability and orthostatic hypotension, and he is prone to falls. First-generation antipsychotics (typical antipsychotics) can have severe extrapyramidal side effects, which can worsen PD due to their antidopaminergic effects, and also have undesirable antimuscarinic effects, including urinary retention and constipation, both of which are undesirable in this patient."},{"id":"3434","category":"Uncategorised","stem":"Which of the following scenarios is most likely to be an anaphylactic reaction?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Which of the following scenarios is most likely to be an anaphylactic reaction?","Anaphylaxis is highly likely when any one of the following three criteria is met:","Acute onset of an illness (this means minutes to several hours) with skin and/or mucosal tissue involvement PLUS at least one of:\nrespiratory compromise\nreduced blood pressure","Patients at risk of anaphylaxis should be prescribed an adrenaline auto-injector (such as an EpiPen) to carry with them at all times, in case of an emergency.","If in doubt, it is best to assume anaphylaxis and to treat it as an emergency with IM adrenaline.","Suggested points for reflection:","What differentiates anaphylaxis from an allergic reaction?\nWhat is urticaria?\nWhat investigations may be useful in confirming a diagnosis of suspected anaphylaxis?","Anaphylaxis UK.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"Anaphylaxis is highly likely when any one of the following three criteria is met:","explanation":"Anaphylaxis is highly likely when any one of the following three criteria is met:"},{"id":"8773","category":"Uncategorised","stem":"A 24-year-old woman is admitted to the acute medical intake with swelling of the right hand and abdominal pain. The abdominal pain is central in origin and associated with 2 episodes of vomiting. The symptoms evolved over the last day, and she describes similar episodes over the last 6 years since the age of 18. She has had 2–3 events over the last year, which usually subside over 3–4 days. Occasionally, her foot is also involved.\n\nOn examination, her temperature is 37oC, her pulse is 80 beats per minute, regular, and her blood pressure is 122/80 mmHg. The appearance of the hand is shown. Only the right hand is swollen. There is central abdominal tenderness.\n\nInvestigations reveal the following:\n\nWhich of the following is the most appropriate investigation for this patient?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Treatment is usually with C1-INH concentrates.","Harding, M. (2018). Hereditary angio-oedema. Patient.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"Harding, M. (2018). Hereditary angio-oedema. Patient.","explanation":"The history and clinical signs suggest a diagnosis of hereditary angioedema, of which there are 2 types. Type 1 is associated with these symptoms often from a young age and with a stronger family history. Type 2 is more common in females and tends to present in the late teens. The appropriate investigation in this patient would be the C1-INH and C4 concentrations. C4 would be low in both types, but in type 1, C1-INH would also be low."},{"id":"3760","category":"Uncategorised","stem":"A 76-year-old man presents to the unit with a 1-week history of deteriorating skin rash. His skin has become increasingly inflamed and red. He has had little sleep over the last couple of days as he feels unwell and has been itching intensely.\n\nHe has no particular history of note other than some mild eczema of the flexural areas. He has been taking Lisinopril, amlodipine, aspirin and simvastatin for many years for hypertension.\n\nWhat is the most likely diagnosis?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"erythroderma","explanation":"This elderly man with a history of eczema has a widespread erythematous rash involving the majority of his skin. The diagnosis is therefore erythroderma, and this may be due to several disorders, including eczema, psoriasis and mycosis fungoides. In this patient’s case, the likely diagnosis is erythrodermic eczema, and the patient should be treated with cooling baths with emollients and topical steroids. Where infection is also considered, antibiotics such as Flucloxacillin should be employed."},{"id":"11590","category":"Uncategorised","stem":"You are the lead clinician in your Acute Medicine department and want to improve the acute care of patients admitted with diabetic ketoacidosis (DKA). You note that all the patients need multiple evidence-based interventions, including acid-base assessments, laboratory tests, infection screening, insulin infusion protocol, fluid regimes, and venous thromboembolism (VTE) prophylaxis. There have been reports of missing interventions during post-take ward rounds, and you have decided to address this problem.\n\nWhat would be most useful to ensure that all individual interventions are adhered to and provide better outcomes when performed together, rather than individually?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","A DKA care bundle is likely to ensure adherence to the important aspects of care and ensure a minimum standard of care.","Clinical proformas are mostly associated with the admission clerking of patients in a structured format.","Clinical audit is a method of objective assessment of the performance of a clinical process against defined standards.","Induction training and bedside training are unlikely to consistently ensure adherence in this scenario, unlike a care bundle.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"A DKA care bundle is likely to ensure adherence to the important aspects of care and ensure a minimum standard of care.","explanation":"A DKA care bundle is likely to ensure adherence to the important aspects of care and ensure a minimum standard of care."},{"id":"10381","category":"Uncategorised","stem":"A 46-year-old man is admitted after collapsing at home in the morning following his return from a night shift. He was unsure what had happened, but his partner described him as being clumsy, drowsy, and collapsing and shaking. He was like this for roughly 10 minutes before the paramedic arrived. The paramedic noted that the patient was drowsy, shaking, and had a glucose of 2.2 mmol/L. He treated him with oral glucose, and he recovered. He describes a similar episode where he was out shopping with his partner, and he became light-headed and needed to sit down. He was confused but had a sandwich and recovered after about 10 minutes. This was about 6 weeks ago.\n\nHe is otherwise well and takes no medication. He is gay and married. He works as a hotelier and often feels tired after night shifts. He drinks about 10 units of alcohol weekly and does not smoke.\n\nOn examination, he is alert and orientated. Blood pressure is 122/88 mmHg, and his pulse is 78 beats per minute. Cardiovascular, neurological and abdominal examinations are otherwise normal.\n\nHis results are as follows:\n\nWhich of the following is the most appropriate investigation for this patient?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Fasting hypoglycaemia\nSymptoms compatible with hypoglycaemia\nSymptoms relieved by food or glucose","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"Fasting hypoglycaemia\nSymptoms compatible with hypoglycaemia\nSymptoms relieved by food or glucose","explanation":"This patient is admitted following what appears to be spontaneous hypoglycaemia associated with fasting, and his previous history of drowsiness being relieved by a sandwich is in agreement with Whipple’s triad, i.e.:"},{"id":"17180","category":"Uncategorised","stem":"A 58-year-old man presents to the emergency department with severe epistaxis. He developed a nosebleed in the last 3 hours, which has not stopped and continues to leak. He has not had nosebleeds previously. He informs you that he has been drinking a bottle of wine about 3–4 times per week for the last 2 years since his divorce. He takes no medication and does not smoke.\n\nOn examination, his pulse is 88 bpm, and he has a blood pressure of 122/80 mmHg. He has evidence of bleeding from his nose, and you also notice that he has some bruising on his arms and legs.\n\nResults of investigations reveal:\n\nWhich of the following is the most likely cause of his epistaxis?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","ITP as a cause of nosebleeds.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"ITP as a cause of nosebleeds.","explanation":"ITP is a condition that causes a low platelet count, which can lead to bleeding disorders such as epistaxis. Patients with a history of alcoholism may have liver disease, which can also affect their blood clotting factors. However, in this case, the low platelet count suggests ITP as the most likely cause of epistaxis."},{"id":"11591","category":"Uncategorised","stem":"A 35-year-old man is admitted to the Acute Medical Unit. His partner says that he suffers from bipolar disorder and is currently taking olanzapine and fluoxetine daily. She is concerned that the patient has stopped talking, eating and drinking for the past 24 hours, and has now stopped moving for the past 3 hours.\n\nOn examination, the patient’s eyes are open and staring, but he does not make eye contact with the examiner. Nor is he speaking or engaging with the examiner. Grimacing of the face is noted, and the patient is resisting the examiner's attempts to move his limbs.\n\nPulse rate is 75/minute, blood pressure is 120/80 mmHg, respiratory rate is 12 breaths per minute, oxygen saturation on air is 99%, temperature is 37oC. Capillary refill time is 1s, and jugular venous pressure is not elevated. No leg oedema is noted.\n\nA respiratory system examination reveals normal breath sounds on both sides. A cardiovascular system examination reveals normal heart sounds. The patient's abdomen is soft, no tenderness is noted, and there are active bowel sounds.\n\nInvestigations reveal:\n\nBefore the patient can be reviewed by a psychiatrist, what initial medication would you administer that may improve this patient and assist in the diagnosis?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Investigations reveal:","Before the patient can be reviewed by a psychiatrist, what initial medication would you administer that may improve this patient and assist in the diagnosis?","Catatonia is a behavioural neuropsychiatric syndrome characterised by an inability to move normally, which occurs in association with many psychiatric disorders.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"This patient with bipolar disorder has classic symptoms of catatonia, and the medication of choice in this acute circumstance would be intravenous lorazepam. It may resolve this patient’s symptoms and can do so dramatically in certain patients. It is often used as a diagnostic tool (the lorazepam challenge test)."},{"id":"19873","category":"Uncategorised","stem":"A 67-year-old man presents to the acute medical unit with a 5-day history of progressive widespread rash, fever, and rigours. He has a background of psoriasis, currently managed with moisturising creams alone.\n\nOn examination, he appears unwell with a temperature of 38.7oC, heart rate of 112/min, blood pressure of 108/65 mmHg, and respiratory rate of 22/min. Over 90% of his body surface area shows confluent erythema with scaling and exfoliation. He is shivering despite the warm ambient temperature.\n\nShe was diagnosed with erythroderma, admitted to a warm side room and commenced on intravenous 0.9% saline.\n\nWhat is the most appropriate topical emollient therapy for this patient?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Blood results show:","What is the most appropriate topical emollient therapy for this patient?","Aqueous cream contains sodium lauryl sulfate, which can cause irritation and is no longer recommended as a leave-on emollient, particularly in inflamed skin.","Emulsifying ointment is primarily a soap substitute and is less effective as a leave-on emollient compared to 50:50 paraffin preparations.","Urea-based creams can cause stinging and irritation in acutely inflamed erythrodermic skin and are not appropriate for initial management.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"What is the most appropriate topical emollient therapy for this patient?","explanation":"In erythroderma, the skin barrier is severely compromised, leading to excessive transepidermal water loss, hypothermia, and high-output cardiac strain. The mainstay of initial topical management is intensive emollient therapy using bland, occlusive preparations. 50:50 white soft paraffin and liquid paraffin ointment provides maximal hydration and barrier restoration without risk of irritation, and should be applied liberally and frequently (every 2–4 hours if tolerated)."},{"id":"7041","category":"Uncategorised","stem":"A 24-year-old man presented with an acute onset of evolving pain over 10 minutes in the right hand. He was aware of redness and pain in that arm and hand, and went to the accident & emergency department, where he was referred to medicine. By the time he was seen, about 3 hours later, the pain and redness had subsided. He described this pain as 8/10, which developed when he was asleep. He described a similar episode occurring about one month before, after taking a bath. There was no other medical history of note.\n\nHe had some purplish discolouration of the tips of the fingers of the right hand. Neurological examination was normal. All pulses were palpable, and cardiovascular examination was otherwise normal. There were no splinter haemorrhages, and examination in all other parts of the body was normal.\n\nFBC – Normal, U+Es/Calcium/LFTs – Normal, CRP 5 g/l. CXR - Normal.\n\nWhich of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"Erythromelalgia is a rare disorder associated with redness and pain, which can be bilateral and is usually precipitated by the person being hot. It can be primary or secondary, and treatment includes cooling and NSAIDs. Infrared thermography can often help in the diagnosis."},{"id":"7747","category":"Uncategorised","stem":"A 42-year-old man presents with these painful lesions on his chest, which appeared 36 hours ago and were preceded by pain for 5 days. He has a 25-year history of type 1 diabetes for which he takes insulin and has no specific complications associated with this.\n\nOn examination, this painful rash was present, he had a temperature of 37°C, pulse of 90 beats per minute, and blood pressure of 124/80 mmHg.\n\nInvestigations reveal the following:\n\nTogether with adequate analgesia, which of the following is the most appropriate treatment for this patient?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"should be treated with acyclovir as first-line therapy","explanation":"This man has shingles in the T8-9 dermatomes. He would be regarded to be immunocompromised associated with the T1DM and therefore should be treated with acyclovir as first-line therapy. Early treatment (within 72 hours of the rash emerging) is associated with reduced pain and the development of further crops. Acyclovir 800 mg five times daily is recommended, and valacyclovir, which is used 3 times daily, is an alternative if compliance is a problem. IV acyclovir is not required in this stable patient."},{"id":"11672","category":"Uncategorised","stem":"A 74-year-old man is admitted to the Acute Medical Unit with features of acute alcohol withdrawal syndrome. His past medical history includes chronic alcoholism, alcohol-induced liver cirrhosis (Child C Pugh class), and severe chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD).\n\nOn examination, he is alert and oriented but anxious and agitated. He is frail, and generalised muscle wasting is noted. Pulse rate is 115 beats per minute, blood pressure is 120/80 mmHg, respiratory rate is 17 breaths per minute, oxygen saturation on air is 94%, and temperature is 37 oC.\n\nBilateral palpable gynecomastia and mild pitting ankle oedema are present, and spider naevi are noted over the chest wall. A respiratory system examination reveals reduced air entry on both sides, and a cardiovascular system examination reveals normal heart sounds. His abdomen is soft and non-tender.\n\nWhich of the following medications would be ideal for this patient for the management of his alcohol withdrawal?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Which of the following medications would be ideal for this patient for the management of his alcohol withdrawal?","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"Which of the following medications would be ideal for this patient for the management of his alcohol withdrawal?","explanation":"This patient needs a benzodiazepine (BZD) for alcohol withdrawal syndrome as a first-choice medication; usually, chlordiazepoxide is the first-line as it is long-acting, treats the withdrawal symptoms, and also prevents rebound symptoms. However, given this patient’s old age, frailty, advanced liver cirrhosis, and severe COPD, a long-acting BZD (chlordiazepoxide/diazepam) would not be ideal due to impaired metabolism leading to accumulation of active metabolites, and adverse effects including respiratory depression; a short-acting drug like lorazepam (or oxazepam) would be preferred in such patients."},{"id":"11596","category":"Uncategorised","stem":"A 19-year-old woman with a past medical history of difficult atopic asthma since childhood and atopic dermatitis has been brought to the emergency department after she collapsed at home. Her father tells you that she has been complaining of worsening of her asthma for 2 days. She had been prescribed amoxicillin, salbutamol inhalers, and oral prednisolone by her general practitioner only a few hours before her collapse.\n\nExamination reveals a Glasgow Coma Scale of 12/15: eye opening - 3/4, verbal response - 4/5, motor response - 5/6. Her pulse rate is 144/minute, blood pressure is 70/30 mmHg, respiratory rate is 32/minute, and oxygen saturation on a high-flow non-rebreather mask is 90%.\n\nA respiratory system examination reveals widespread polyphonic wheezing. A cardiovascular system examination reveals normal heart sounds. Hyperpigmented scaly patches are noted around the mouth, forearms and the back of the knees. Urticarial lesions are noted over the chest and abdominal wall.\n\nWhat would be the most appropriate initial management?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","What would be the most appropriate initial management?","Patients with asthma also have up to a 5-fold increased risk for anaphylactic reactions compared to the general population.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"This patient is in circulatory shock, which cannot be explained by acute severe asthma alone; the history of atopic asthma with atopic dermatitis and the presence of urticarial lesions strongly suggest the possibility of an anaphylactic reaction in this patient. This patient likely had anaphylaxis after the administration of amoxicillin."},{"id":"3773","category":"Uncategorised","stem":"An 18-year-old student is admitted after she became acutely unwell after going to a restaurant. She became lightheaded, short of breath, and thinks she may have momentarily lost consciousness. An ambulance was called, and she was given oxygen and recovered. She has a history of eczema, but nothing else. On examination, there is nothing to find, and she seems fine. Blood results are normal.\n\nWhich of the following tests could be used to assess if this were an anaphylactic reaction?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Resuscitation Council Guidelines anaphylaxis.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"Mast cell tryptase is the molecule to measure in suspected anaphylaxis as the mast cells release this in abundance in anaphylaxis, with concentrations rising abruptly within 30 minutes to 1 hour. C1 esterase deficiency is a cause of repeated episodes of anaphylaxis, but this is not the molecule to measure. As in this case, the measurement of mast cell tryptase may differentiate between a faint and anaphylaxis where doubt exists."},{"id":"11677","category":"Uncategorised","stem":"An 18-year-old man has been admitted to the Acute Medical Unit with acute meningitis, and a cerebrospinal fluid culture has confirmed a Neisseria meningitidis infection. The electronic medical records show that this patient had a severe meningococcal infection about 2 years ago and was treated.\n\nWhich of the following tests would you perform in this patient to determine the cause of the recurrent meningococcal infection?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"he needs to be evaluated for complement deficiency","explanation":"This patient has had recurrent meningococcal infections and is a young adult. Therefore, he needs to be evaluated for complement deficiency, which is a known risk factor for recurrent meningococcal infections."},{"id":"11594","category":"Uncategorised","stem":"A 35-year-old man is admitted to the Acute Medical Unit with sudden onset swelling of his face, lips, eyes and tongue. He first noticed the issue this morning and thought he must have been bitten by an insect whilst he was sleeping. He denies any rash, itching, or breathing difficulty. He says his voice is unaffected.\n\nHis past medical history includes uncontrolled hypertension, hypercholesterolemia, type 2 diabetes, and depression. His current medications include amlodipine, ramipril, fluoxetine, simvastatin and metformin. He has been taking these medications for 3 years without any problems.\n\nOn examination, he is alert and oriented. His pulse rate is 95/minute, blood pressure is 120/80 mmHg, respiratory rate is 16 breaths per minute, oxygen saturation on air is 99%, and temperature is 37 oC. Capillary refill time is 1 second, and jugular venous pressure is not elevated.\n\nThere is spongy swelling of the face, lips, and peri-orbital soft tissues, with mild tongue swelling and no urticaria. There is no dependent leg oedema.\n\nA respiratory system examination reveals normal breath sounds on both sides. A cardiovascular system examination reveals normal heart sounds.\n\nHis abdomen is soft, and there is no tenderness. Active bowel sounds are present.\n\nWhich of his current medications are likely to be implicated in his current clinical condition?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","There is spongy swelling of the face, lips, and peri-orbital soft tissues, with mild tongue swelling and no urticaria. There is no dependent leg oedema.","His abdomen is soft, and there is no tenderness. Active bowel sounds are present.","Which of his current medications are likely to be implicated in his current clinical condition?","Of all his medications, ramipril would be the most likely associated with angioedema and needs to be stopped.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"This patient has features of angioedema without urticaria or bronchospasm, which is likely bradykinin-mediated and most likely due to ramipril; angiotensin-converting enzyme inhibitor (ACEi) related angioedema can occur even after years of use."},{"id":"11593","category":"Uncategorised","stem":"A 25-year-old woman is being given intravenous immunoglobulin (IVIG) in the day-care unit, and she is on her second infusion. The patient’s past medical history includes dermatomyositis, steroid-induced Cushing’s syndrome, and a history of recurrent giardiasis 3 years ago.\n\nWithin minutes of starting the infusion, she developed urticaria, a choking sensation, lip and tongue swelling, wheezing, and hypotension. She is immediately given intramuscular epinephrine by the medical doctor. The patient improves and stabilises and is being moved to the acute medical unit for observation.\n\nWhat test would likely identify the cause of this anaphylactic reaction?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"This patient has had an anaphylactic reaction with intravenous immunoglobulin (IVIG) infusion. IVIG infusion reactions are reported in 5-15% of all infusions. Anaphylaxis to IVIG is rare and can be seen in patients with underlying IgA deficiency with serum anti-IgA antibodies, especially of the IgE class."},{"id":"11680","category":"Uncategorised","stem":"A 25-year-old man is admitted to the Acute Medicine Unit after he collapsed whilst dining with his friends. Before the collapse, he had complained of feeling flushed and warm and found it difficult to breathe. He was given adrenaline by the paramedics and recovered. Since admission, a diagnosis of suspected anaphylaxis has been made.\n\nWhich of the following investigations might help in the confirmation of anaphylaxis in this patient?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Suspected anaphylaxis can be confirmed by measuring serum tryptase, which is a biomarker for mast cell activation.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"Suspected anaphylaxis can be confirmed by measuring serum tryptase, which is a biomarker for mast cell activation.","explanation":"Suspected anaphylaxis can be confirmed by measuring serum tryptase, which is a biomarker for mast cell activation."},{"id":"17179","category":"Uncategorised","stem":"A 42-year-old woman with a history of recurrent epistaxis presents to the emergency department with severe bleeding from both nostrils. She reports using cocaine regularly.\n\nWhich of the following is the most appropriate initial management for her condition?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"Nasal packing is the most appropriate initial management for severe epistaxis in patients with a history of cocaine use. Cocaine use can cause vasoconstriction, leading to damage to the nasal mucosa and subsequent bleeding. However, intranasal cocaine use should be avoided as it can further exacerbate the bleeding."},{"id":"12021","category":"Uncategorised","stem":"You have been asked to provide some teaching for a mixed group of health care professionals around DNAR (‘Do Not Attempt Resuscitation’) decision-making. The group have been discussing the significance of the ‘Tracey judgement’ (relating to the 2014 Court of Appeal decision in the case of Tracey v Cambridge University Hospitals NHS), and how far patients should be involved in DNAR decision-making. A participant has asked whether patients should always be directly involved in DNAR decisions, as a result of this legal case.\n\nWhat precedent did this legal case establish concerning the legal framework in England and Wales around DNAR decision-making?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","GMC - Guidance: Treatment and care towards the end of life.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"This was a significant legal case concerning how and when DNAR orders should be discussed with patients and others. Whilst a DNAR decision remains ultimately a clinical one, there must be a presumption of involvement of the patient in DNAR decisions unless it will cause significant ‘psychological harm’. There is no specific requirement for patients to countersign DNAR forms. Whilst there must be a presumption of involvement of patients in DNAR decisions, the General Medical Council also suggests that the discussion should not be forced on a patient who has stated that they do not wish to know about, or discuss, a DNAR decision."},{"id":"11679","category":"Uncategorised","stem":"A 25-year-old woman is re-admitted to the acute medical unit with high-grade fever, headaches, chills, rigour, persistent vomiting, and a worsening confusional state. She had been admitted to the hospital a week earlier with a fever and rash and was treated with intravenous fluids and supportive therapy for a suspected viral infection; she was later discharged. Her mother is very concerned about her progressive deterioration over the past few days and notes that the rash has been getting worse with the appearance of peeling in both palms and soles today.\n\nThe patient has a past medical history of menorrhagia and irregular menses and has had difficulties with managing her periods for the past month. Her only medication has been oral tranexamic acid prescribed by her gynaecologist, which she has been using intermittently for the past year.\n\nOn examination, she is alert but disoriented; she appears toxic and very unwell. Pulse rate is 140 beats per minute, blood pressure is 90/70 mmHg, respiratory rate is 27 breaths per minute, oxygen saturation on air is 94%, and temperature is 40 oC.\n\nDiffuse macular erythrodermic rash with desquamation of both palms and soles is noted. A respiratory system examination reveals normal breath sounds on both sides, and a cardiovascular system examination reveals normal heart sounds. Her abdomen is soft, and there is moderate diffuse tenderness present in the lower quadrants. A central nervous system examination reveals no signs of meningism; she is encephalopathic, but no focal neurological deficits are apparent.\n\nWhat is the most likely diagnosis?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","What is the most likely diagnosis?","Ross A, Shoff HW. Toxic Shock Syndrome. [Updated 2021 Aug 11]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2022 Jan-.\nNORD - Rare Diseases Database - Toxic Shock Syndrome.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"What is the most likely diagnosis?","explanation":"This patient has menorrhagia and likely has an infected tampon in situ, which has caused staphylococcal toxic shock syndrome (STSS). The presence of severe systemic features, high-grade fever, hypotension, tachycardia, lower abdominal tenderness, and multi-organ involvement with characteristic desquamation of the palms and soles is consistent with STSS. The next step in management would be to perform a vaginal exam for the presence of any retained tampons."},{"id":"4137","category":"Uncategorised","stem":"A 50-year-old man returns home from a business trip to India, complaining of watery and offensive diarrhoea. This started 2 days after the end of his trip and is associated with abdominal pains and watery diarrhoea at least 5–6 times per day. The symptoms have continued over the last 10 days, and now he seeks treatment advice. He is up to date concerning immunisations, including hepatitis A and B.\n\nHis GP has undertaken 3 separate stool cultures together with microscopic examination for cysts and ova, all of which were negative. Similarly, C. diff toxin was not detected.\n\nWhich of the following is the most appropriate approach to the management of this patient?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","This patient has had traveller’s diarrhoea for longer than 5 days and is badly affected by it. Guidance would recommend stand-by treatment with 3 days of ciprofloxacin or a macrolide.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"This patient has had traveller’s diarrhoea for longer than 5 days and is badly affected by it. Guidance would recommend stand-by treatment with 3 days of ciprofloxacin or a macrolide.","explanation":"This patient has had traveller’s diarrhoea for longer than 5 days and is badly affected by it. Guidance would recommend stand-by treatment with 3 days of ciprofloxacin or a macrolide."},{"id":"3532","category":"Uncategorised","stem":"A 21-year-old man presents with a long history of weakness, muscle cramps and ease of fatigue. He denied the use of any illicit substances and was otherwise fine. His mother had type 2 diabetes and he had two other brothers who were well. There was little of note on examination, his BMI was 29 kg/m2 and the following results were obtained:\n\nWhich of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","NHS: mcardle disease adult.pdf","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"NHS: mcardle disease adult.pdf","explanation":"The most likely diagnosis in this scenario is McArdle's disease, a type V glycogen storage disorder associated with myophosphorylase deficiency resulting in a reduction in glycogenolysis within muscle. This is not likely to be thyrotoxic periodic paralysis, as typically the CPK (creatinine phosphokinase) is normal. Nor is this likely to be Becker’s Muscular dystrophy as weakness is reported without any obvious muscle loss or fasciculation. The so-called ‘liver enzymes’ are also found in muscle and signify damage. Often, the CPK may be elevated after doing some exercise."},{"id":"3563","category":"Uncategorised","stem":"A 55-year-old woman with recently diagnosed lung carcinoma presents with painful swelling of the left leg and is diagnosed with a proximal deep vein thrombosis. She is initially treated with low molecular weight heparin.\n\nConcerning longer-term anticoagulation, which of the following is the most appropriate treatment for this patient?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"For people with active cancer and confirmed proximal DVT or PE, consider a direct-acting oral anticoagulant. If this is unsuitable, consider low molecular weight heparin (LMWH) alone or LMWH concurrently with a vitamin K antagonist (VKA) for at least 5 days, or until the INR is at least 2.0 in 2 consecutive readings, followed by a VKA on its own."},{"id":"18385","category":"Uncategorised","stem":"An 18-year-old man presented to the emergency department with sudden-onset dyspnoea, stridor, and swelling of the tongue and lips. The patient denied having any recent exposure to drugs or having any known food allergies. He was also complaining of severe generalised abdominal pain of about 8/10 in intensity. The patient appeared anxious and was struggling to breathe. On physical examination, there were no wheals or urticaria. There was significant swelling of the oropharynx and larynx, with diminished air entry. His abdomen was tender to palpation. His vital signs were as follows: blood pressure 130/80 mmHg, heart rate 140 beats per minute, respiratory rate 32 breaths per minute, oxygen saturation 92% on room air. He was given injectable steroids, epinephrine and antihistamines, but his clinical condition did not improve. The patient was intubated secondary to respiratory distress.\n\nHis family reported a similar episode four years ago, which was also unprovoked, milder in intensity and resolved after taking antihistamines. His younger sister, aged 10, also had a similar episode five years ago.\n\nWhich of the following tests will help in diagnosing the case and performing further confirmatory tests?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Which of the following tests will help in diagnosing the case and performing further confirmatory tests?","Systemic lupus erythematosus, characterised by ANA levels and malar rash, does not typically cause angioedema.","High eosinophils seen in CBC film may indicate allergic reactions, but are not specific findings.","Allergic angioedema is an IgE-mediated type 1 hypersensitivity reaction induced by certain allergens, but IgE levels are not associated with HAE and would not aid in diagnosing the case.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"This is a case of hereditary angioedema (HAE), first described in 1882. It is an autosomal dominant hereditary disorder caused by a C1 inhibitor defect. Clinically, HAE presents as recurrent bouts of nonpruritic subcutaneous and submucosal swelling, which can be localised to the extremities, face, bowels, or upper respiratory tract. Abdominal episodes may occur, accompanied by severe nausea and pain mimicking an acute abdomen. Laryngeal oedema, if present, can significantly contribute to mortality, which is reported in around 15%-30% of the literature (Sabeen Ahmed A., Fayyaz S. 2020)."},{"id":"10843","category":"Uncategorised","stem":"An 84-year-old woman is admitted acutely as the GP is concerned due to the purple discolouration of the urine in the catheter bag. She has a long-term urine catheter in place, as she had a stroke 5 years ago. She had incontinence and is a resident in a care home. The staff were concerned that the urine in the bag was purple. She has also been a little more constipated of late.\n\nThere is nothing else of note, and she feels reasonably well. She takes losartan, bisoprolol, atorvastatin, apixaban and omeprazole.\n\nOn examination, she has a pulse of 76 bpm AF, a blood pressure of 108/78 mmHg and a temperature of 37oC. Aside from a right-sided hemiparesis, there are no other abnormalities other than purple discolouration of the urine in the catheter bag.\n\nInvestigations reveal:\n\nWhich of the following is the likely cause for her presentation?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Beetroot produces a red discolouration of the urine.","Al Montasir, A., & Al Mustaque, A. (2013). Purple urine bag syndrome. Journal of family medicine and primary care, 2(1), 104–105. https://doi.org/10.4103/2249-4863.109970.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"Beetroot produces a red discolouration of the urine.","explanation":"This is a typical description of purple urine bag syndrome, where there is a urine tract infection that results in the increased production of a blue pigment (indigo) and a red pigment (indirubin), which results in the purple discolouration of the urine. Treatment is focused on replacing the catheter, identification and treatment of the causative organism, together with treatment of constipation. Whilst this patient remains well, it is important to recognise that a UTI is the cause of her presentation and this should be treated to prevent its progression."},{"id":"17178","category":"Uncategorised","stem":"A 35-year-old woman presents to the emergency department with a 2-hour history of persistent epistaxis. She reports a history of frequent nosebleeds since childhood, and her father had a similar condition.\n\nOn examination, her vital signs are stable, and there are no other significant findings. A full blood count is performed, which reveals the following:\n\nWhich of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","ITP and nosebleeds.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"ITP and nosebleeds.","explanation":"The patient's history of frequent nosebleeds and family history suggest a possible genetic predisposition to bleeding disorders. The low platelet count found on the full blood count is suggestive of thrombocytopenia. Idiopathic thrombocytopaenic purpura (ITP) is a condition characterised by low platelet count and easy bruising or bleeding due to the autoimmune destruction of platelets. Therefore, ITP is the most likely diagnosis in this case scenario. Nasal septal deviation, hereditary haemorrhagic telangiectasia, coagulation factor deficiency, and hypertension do not typically present with low platelet counts."},{"id":"11595","category":"Uncategorised","stem":"A 25-year-old woman suffers an anaphylactic reaction during intravenous administration of radiocontrast during a CT scan in the radiology suite. She has a well-functioning large-bore intravenous line in her right arm.\n\nWhat is the initial dose of adrenaline that should be given to this patient?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Resuscitation Council UK - Emergency Treatment of Anaphylaxis. Guidelines for healthcare providers: Working Group of Resuscitation Council UK. May 2021.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"The first dose of adrenaline for anaphylaxis should be intramuscular, and the dose for adults would be 500 mcg - 0.5 mL of a 1:1000 concentration of adrenaline (1 mg/mL). Intramuscular adrenaline is the first-line treatment for anaphylaxis, even if intravenous access is readily available. Anaphylaxis is considered refractory when there is no improvement in respiratory or cardiovascular symptoms despite two appropriate doses of intramuscular adrenaline, in which case intravenous boluses of fluids and intravenous adrenaline infusion can be started."},{"id":"11673","category":"Uncategorised","stem":"A 50-year-old man is admitted to the Acute Medical Unit after he was found collapsed at home, where he lives on his own. He is chronically alcohol dependent and drinks about 50 units of alcohol per week; he has had multiple recurrent admissions to the hospital with alcohol-use-related issues. He is currently very agitated and restless; he says he can see insects all over the floor. His last drink of alcohol was 2 days ago.\n\nOn examination, he is alert but is not cooperative for a mini-mental state assessment. He is noted to have fine tremors, and he is sweating.\n\nHe has a body mass index of 20 kg/m2, a pulse rate of 110 beats per minute, a blood pressure of 180/80 mmHg, a respiratory rate of 20 breaths per minute, oxygen saturation on air of 99%, and temperature of 37 oC. Jugular venous pressure is not elevated, and there is no leg oedema.\n\nA respiratory system examination reveals normal breath sounds on both sides. A cardiovascular system examination reveals normal heart sounds. A neurological examination reveals fine tremors in both hands. The patient is moving all 4 limbs well, and his gait is normal. He has normal eye movements, no nystagmus, and his pupils are normal.\n\nWhat is the first-line medication to be used to treat and prevent the progression of his current symptoms?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","What is the first-line medication to be used to treat and prevent the progression of his current symptoms?","This patient has features of severe alcohol withdrawal with hallucinosis. The first-line medication to be used would be a long-acting benzodiazepine like chlordiazepoxide.","Haloperidol has no role in the management of alcohol withdrawal syndromes. Clomethiazole may be considered an alternative to benzodiazepine and carbamazepine, but it is not the first-choice drug.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"This patient has features of severe alcohol withdrawal with hallucinosis. The first-line medication to be used would be a long-acting benzodiazepine like chlordiazepoxide.","explanation":"This patient has features of severe alcohol withdrawal with hallucinosis. The first-line medication to be used would be a long-acting benzodiazepine like chlordiazepoxide."},{"id":"8413","category":"Uncategorised","stem":"A 55-year-old woman has metastatic breast cancer. You discuss the option of future treatment with her, including resuscitation. She informs you that she wants life-sustaining treatment and has made an advanced decision in which she requests this. She is entirely competent concerning this decision.\n\nWhich of the following is correct relating to the request for life-sustaining treatment?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","NHS UK: Advance decision (Living Will).\nAge UK: Advance decision (Living Will).","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"NHS UK: Advance decision (Living Will).\nAge UK: Advance decision (Living Will).","explanation":"Regarding advanced decisions, the patient can refuse this treatment, but cannot make an advanced decision requesting specific treatment. Ultimately, treatment decisions are those of the medical team, although all these decisions need to be discussed fully with the patient."},{"id":"18387","category":"Uncategorised","stem":"A 28-year-old man presents to the emergency department with a history of recurrent respiratory tract infections. He reports frequent episodes of pneumonia, sinusitis, and otitis media. Upon further investigation, the patient is found to have decreased levels of serum immunoglobulin (Ig) A, IgG, and IgM.\n\nWhat is the most likely underlying immunodeficiency disorder in this patient?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Selective IgA deficiency is characterised by an isolated deficiency of IgA, whereas this patient has decreased levels of multiple immunoglobulin classes.","Hyper-IgM syndrome is characterised by normal or elevated levels of IgM but decreased levels of other immunoglobulin classes. This patient has decreased levels of IgM along with IgA and IgG.","Pescador Ruschel MA, Vaqar S. Common Variable Immunodeficiency. 2023 May 8. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2023 Jan–. PMID: 31747194.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"Selective IgA deficiency is characterised by an isolated deficiency of IgA, whereas this patient has decreased levels of multiple immunoglobulin classes.","explanation":"The clinical presentation of recurrent respiratory tract infections and decreased levels of multiple immunoglobulin classes (IgA, IgG, and IgM) suggests a humoral immunodeficiency disorder. Among the options provided, the most likely underlying immunodeficiency disorder in this patient is common variable immunodeficiency (CVID)."},{"id":"11678","category":"Uncategorised","stem":"A 21-year-old man is admitted to the emergency department following a collapse in a restaurant when dining with his friends. He had suddenly become unwell with swelling in his throat and breathing difficulties. He was given intramuscular (IM) adrenaline followed by a 2nd dose after 5 minutes by the paramedics, after which he was brought to the emergency department.\n\nOn examination, a stridorous sound is noted, with his airway at risk. His respiratory rate is 30 breaths per minute, and a faint bilateral rhonchi is heard. Oxygen saturation on 15L oxygen with a non-rebreather mask is 93%. His pulse rate is 140 beats per minute, and his blood pressure is 70/40 mmHg.\n\nA diagnosis of refractory anaphylaxis is made; the patient has a large-bore cannula inserted, and fluid boluses have commenced.\n\nWhat would be the most important step in the management of this patient?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","A diagnosis of refractory anaphylaxis is made; the patient has a large-bore cannula inserted, and fluid boluses have commenced.","What would be the most important step in the management of this patient?","Resuscitation Council UK - Emergency treatment of anaphylaxis Guidelines for healthcare providers Working Group of Resuscitation Council UK May 2021.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"A diagnosis of refractory anaphylaxis is made; the patient has a large-bore cannula inserted, and fluid boluses have commenced.","explanation":"Refractory anaphylaxis is defined as when there is no improvement in respiratory or cardiovascular symptoms despite two appropriate doses of IM adrenaline. The patient requires intravenous adrenaline along with fluid boluses, but this should be administered by trained healthcare professionals in a controlled environment and under close monitoring. Glucocorticoids are routinely used as they can prevent protracted symptoms and possibly biphasic reactions, but there is not enough evidence that they are effective. Antihistamines are only helpful in relieving cutaneous symptoms."},{"id":"11589","category":"Uncategorised","stem":"A 45-year-old man is admitted to the Acute Medical Unit for right leg swelling and is noted to have severe cellulitis of his right leg.\n\nHis past medical history is significant only for schizophrenia, for which the patient is on regular maintenance clozapine. The admission was arranged by his general practitioner during a routine clinic review, as the cellulitis had not responded to oral antibiotics.\n\nWithin a few minutes of admission, he tells you that he is leaving the hospital and asks you to remove his intravenous line, which was placed to start intravenous (IV) flucloxacillin.\n\nHe otherwise appears calm and composed, but is noted to be avoiding direct eye contact. He says he understands that his leg infection is bad and can worsen without intravenous antibiotics, but he still does not want to have treatment or stay in the hospital.\n\nAs an acute medical consultant, what should you do in this circumstance?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"This patient has a leg infection that is unrelated to his mental health disorder, and the Mental Health Act (MHA) cannot be used to treat a physical disorder unless it is directly linked to a mental health disorder, which is not the case here."},{"id":"11597","category":"Uncategorised","stem":"A 25-year-old man with homozygous sickle cell disease is admitted to the Acute Medical Unit with a fever, cough, and general deterioration. His chest x-ray shows right lower lobe pneumonia. This is his second admission in 1 year with lobar pneumonia. His CURB65 score is 3, and he has been commenced on intravenous co-amoxiclav and oral clarithromycin.\n\nHis investigations are as follows:\n\nWhat is the underlying cause of recurrent pneumonia in this patient?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"Patients with sickle cell anaemia are at risk of functional asplenism/auto-splenectomy, which can predispose the patient to infections with encapsulated bacteria like pneumococcus, Haemophilus, and meningococcus. The presence of Howell-Jolly bodies is suggestive of asplenia in this patient."},{"id":"8014","category":"Uncategorised","stem":"A 55-year-old woman presents to the medical assessment unit with recurrent episodes of feeling faint, associated with flushing, abdominal cramps and diarrhoea. The episodes last for 15-30 minutes typically. The patient had previously experienced an anaphylactic reaction to a sting and required hospitalisation 8 months ago. She had been provided with an adrenaline auto-injector.\n\nOn examination, she had a pulse of 88 beats per minute, a blood pressure of 132/88 mmHg, and saturations of 98% on air. There was no overt rash visible, and cardiovascular, respiratory and abdominal examination was otherwise normal.\n\nBaseline FBC, U+ES, LFTs and CRP were unremarkable.\n\nYou suspect a mast cell activation disorder. Which of the following would be the most appropriate next investigation for this patient?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Baseline FBC, U+ES, LFTs and CRP were unremarkable.","You suspect a mast cell activation disorder. Which of the following would be the most appropriate next investigation for this patient?","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"Mastocytosis is a rare disorder that may affect children (cutaneous) and adults (systemic). Adult mastocytosis can be indolent, with mild to moderate symptoms as above or aggressive with proliferation of mast cells in the internal organs and more severe symptoms. Systemic mastocytosis may also be secondary to an associated haematological malignancy. Similarly, individuals with mastocytosis are more prone to develop anaphylaxis as in the story above."},{"id":"18709","category":"Uncategorised","stem":"A 23-year-old woman was brought to the emergency department by ambulance after driving her car into a wall under the influence of cocaine and alcohol.\n\nHer primary survey showed the following results:\n\nCirculation - she has a heart rate of 91 beats per minute and blood pressure of 126/67 mmHg. A Kendrick splint is applied to the right leg, and her right arm is immobilised.\n\nAirway - The patient can speak in full sentences. She is breathing spontaneously, with no flail chest. Her respiratory rate is 16 cycles per minute with an oxygen saturation of 99%. There is no chest tenderness, she has normal percussion, and there are normal breath sounds with equal air entry bilaterally.\n\nAn ECG showed a normal sinus rhythm.\n\nGlasgow coma scale - E-4, V-4, M-6=14/15, the pupils are constricted (2mm) bilaterally, and there is a normal light reflex.\n\nAbdomen - There is marked tenderness on the right upper quadrant and epigastric area.\n\nWhat is the most important investigative modality to be carried out?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","A 23-year-old woman was brought to the emergency department by ambulance after driving her car into a wall under the influence of cocaine and alcohol.","Her primary survey showed the following results:","Circulation - she has a heart rate of 91 beats per minute and blood pressure of 126/67 mmHg. A Kendrick splint is applied to the right leg, and her right arm is immobilised.","An ECG showed a normal sinus rhythm.","Glasgow coma scale - E-4, V-4, M-6=14/15, the pupils are constricted (2mm) bilaterally, and there is a normal light reflex.","Abdomen - There is marked tenderness on the right upper quadrant and epigastric area.","What is the most important investigative modality to be carried out?","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"A CT trauma series is most appropriate for this scenario as the patient has multiple injuries that need to be identified. A Trauma CT is not time-consuming and can help emergency medicine clinicians make life-saving decisions on time. An abdominal ultrasound will not highlight any bony injuries, such as fractures, which are present in this patient. A chest X-ray would be of no benefit as the patient has no symptoms suggestive of chest injury. MRI and PET scans are both specific investigations that have no diagnostic value in acute trauma."},{"id":"11676","category":"Uncategorised","stem":"A 48-year-old woman is admitted to the Acute Medical Unit feeling tired, with low-grade fever, breathlessness and new-onset Raynaud’s phenomenon with cyanosis of fingertips and tip of the nose on exposure to cold weather for the past week. Her past medical history is unremarkable except for a bout of pneumonia 10 days ago, which was treated by her GP with oral antibiotics. Before this illness, she was a fit and healthy woman.\n\nOn examination, she is alert and oriented. Pallor and icterus are evident, and there is a net-like violaceous rash over both legs. Her pulse rate is 115 beats per minute, blood pressure is 120/80 mmHg, respiratory rate is 20 breaths per minute, oxygen saturation on air is 97%, temperature is 37 oC, and capillary refill time is 1 second.\n\nJugular venous pressure is not elevated, and there is no leg oedema. A respiratory system examination reveals scattered fine crackles bilaterally. A cardiovascular system examination reveals normal heart sounds. Her abdomen is soft, no tenderness is noted, and active bowel sounds are present.\n\nInvestigations reveal:\n\nWhat is the likely cause of the present symptoms?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Investigations reveal:","Investigation\tResult\tNormal range","Haemoglobin\t68 g/L\t115–160 g/L","Total leucocyte count\t12 x 109 cells/L\t4–11 x 109 cells/L","Platelet count\t158 x 109 cells/L\t150-450 x 109 cells/L","Reticulocyte count","C-Reactive protein\t80 mg/L\t< 10 mg/L","Erythrocyte sedimentation rate\t70 mm/hour\t< 30 mm/hour","Urea\t6 mmol/L\t3.5–7.2 mmol/L","Creatinine\t82 µmol/L\t49–90 µmol/L","Sodium\t134 mmol/L\t135–145 mmol/L","Chloride\t100 mmol/L\t95–105 mmol/L","Bicarbonate\t22 mmol/L\t23–31 mmol/L","Potassium\t4.3 mmol/L\t3.5–5 mmol/L","Total bilirubin\t65 µmol/L\t0–21 µmol/L","Indirect bilirubin\t59 µmol/L\t0–11 µmol/L","Aspartate aminotransferase (AST)\t88 IU/L\t15–42 IU/L","Alanine aminotransaminase (ALT)\t45 IU/L\t10–45 IU/L","Gamma glutamyl transferase (GGT)\t16 IU/L\t15–40 IU/L","Alkaline Phosphatase (ALP)\t100 IU/L\t30–130 IU/L","Total protein\t80 g/L\t60–80 g/L","Albumin\t40 g/L\t32–50 g/L","Globulin\t40 g/L\t20–35 g/L","Chest X-ray\tScattered infiltrates\nin both lung fields","What is the likely cause of the present symptoms?","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"Indirect bilirubin\t59 µmol/L\t0–11 µmol/L","explanation":"This patient currently has features of atypical pneumonia, symptomatic decompensated haemolytic anaemia (anaemia, indirect hyperbilirubinemia, and reticulocytosis), livedo reticularis, and features of cold-induced symptoms. The most likely diagnosis would be mycoplasma pneumonia-induced secondary cold agglutinin disease."},{"id":"8023","category":"Uncategorised","stem":"A 55-year-old woman presents to the medical assessment unit with recurrent episodes of feeling faint, associated with flushing, abdominal cramps and diarrhoea. The episodes last for 15-30 minutes typically. 8 months previously, she had experienced an anaphylactic reaction to a sting and required hospitalisation. She had been provided with an adrenaline auto-injector.\n\nOn examination, her pulse was 88 bpm, blood pressure 132/88 mmHg and sats 98% on air. There was no overt rash visible, and cardiovascular, respiratory and abdominal examination was otherwise normal.\n\nBaseline FBC, U+ES, LFTs and CRP were unremarkable.\n\nWhich of the following is the likely diagnosis?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Baseline FBC, U+ES, LFTs and CRP were unremarkable.","Which of the following is the likely diagnosis?","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"This adult patient presents with features suggesting adult systemic mastocytosis with recurrent episodes of faintness, flushing, abdominal pains and diarrhoea. Patients are also prone to anaphylaxis, so this patient’s recent episode of anaphylaxis also fits. The mastocytosis would be described as indolent in this case, and there are no features of organomegaly."},{"id":"8738","category":"Uncategorised","stem":"A 60-year-old woman is admitted with a 2-hour history of chest pain. Her past medical history includes type 2 diabetes and hypertension. She was being treated with metformin 1g twice daily, ramipril 5 mg daily, and atorvastatin 10 mg daily. The patient is a non-smoker.\n\nOn examination, she has a BMI of 24 kg/m2, a pulse of 110 beats per minute, regular, a blood pressure of 160/100 mmHg, a temperature of 37 oC, and oxygen saturations of 95% on room air. No other abnormalities were present. BM glucose was 11.2 mmol/L without ketones. Troponin was 66 ng/L (<20).\n\nHer ECG reveals anterior ST-segment elevation, and she undergoes coronary angiography.\n\nHowever, coronary angiography reveals normal coronary arteries. An echo showed left ventricular apical wall hypokinesis with an ejection fraction of 35-40%.\n\nWhich of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Her ECG reveals anterior ST-segment elevation, and she undergoes coronary angiography.","Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"This patient has a type-2 myocardial infarction (MI) as demonstrated by normal coronary arteries, yet STEMI and a troponin rise. The patient has type 2 diabetes and hypertension, but has a normal BMI. Similarly, she has tachycardia and hypertension. The EF is impaired at <40%. This suggests a diagnosis of Takotsubo cardiomyopathy associated with a potential underlying diagnosis of phaeochromocytoma."},{"id":"8020","category":"Uncategorised","stem":"A 62-year-old woman with heart failure is commenced on treatment with ramipril. Roughly 6 weeks after commencing this, she develops swelling of the face, lips, and tongue. A diagnosis of ACE-induced angioedema is made.\n\nWhich of the following is correct regarding ACE-inhibitor angioedema?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Sica, D.A. and Black, H.R., (2002). ACE Inhibitor-Related Angioedema: Can Angiotensin-Receptor Blockers Be Safely Used?. The Journal of Clinical Hypertension, 4(5), pp.375-380.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"the drug needs to be stopped","explanation":"This patient has ACE-induced angioedema and therefore the drug needs to be stopped. AT blockers can be tried, as there are many questions regarding the accuracy of diagnosis of AT inhibitor-induced angioedema, as it seems to be very rare in trials of AT blockers."},{"id":"3436","category":"Uncategorised","stem":"You attend to an 18-year-old man who has developed facial swelling, light-headedness, and difficulty breathing following exposure to food suspected to have nut content. On immediate assessment, you note that he has swelling of the lips and eyes with a widespread red blotchy rash. He is particularly wheezy, with a respiratory rate of 28/min, a pulse of 110 beats per minute, and a supine blood pressure of 100/70 mmHg.\n\nWhich of the following would be the most appropriate immediate treatment for this patient?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Anaphylaxis Uk: Allergy Factsheet.\nResuscitation Council UK. Emergency treatment of anaphylactic reactions: Guidelines for healthcare providers.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"This patient has developed a severe allergic reaction to nuts, causing swelling and rash, but more worryingly, he also has features of anaphylaxis, with difficulty breathing and wheeze. He requires urgent treatment, and the acknowledged first-line treatment for anaphylaxis is IM adrenaline. The dose varies according to age, and in a child of this age, the recommended dose should be 0.5 mL of 1:1000 adrenaline (with the preferred site being the outer upper thigh). The injection can be repeated every 5–10 minutes until the patient's condition stabilises. Adjuvant therapies can be given in severe cases. These include high-flow oxygen, IV fluids and nebulised bronchodilators. Adjunctive treatments like steroids and antihistamines are no longer recommended. IV adrenaline is not recommended as a first-line treatment and should only be given by experienced specialists."},{"id":"18386","category":"Uncategorised","stem":"A 35-year-old woman was brought to the emergency room after being found unconscious by her family. An empty bottle of benzodiazepine tablets was found next to her. There was also a suicide note present. A gastric lavage was done, and the patient gradually regained consciousness. The family reported two similar events in the last 6 months. She has been unemployed for a year and was divorced 8 months ago.\n\nThe next day, the patient was alert and oriented to time, place, and person. Her laboratory and clinical parameters were normal. Her chest X-ray was normal. The psychiatry nurse visited the patient and counselled her. The patient wanted to be discharged from the hospital.\n\nWhat is the recommended next management step for this patient?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Her medical condition was stable, but on psychiatric grounds, it would still be risky to discharge her home.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"Assessing the patient's intent is crucial in understanding their mindset at the time of the drug overdose. This can be determined by reviewing any available evidence, such as suicide notes, previous suicidal statements, or communication with others regarding suicidal thoughts."},{"id":"3534","category":"Uncategorised","stem":"A 32-year-old woman presents with hypokalaemia and metabolic alkalosis. She has a blood pressure of 124/76 mmHg. Her biochemistry shows:\n\nWhat is the likely underlying diagnosis?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Gitelman's syndrome.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"Gitelman's syndrome.","explanation":"Gitelman's syndrome is characterised by a mutation in the SCL12A3 gene that encodes for a Na-Cl transporter at the distal convoluted tubule. As a result, the affected individuals develop Na loss (salt wasting), hypovolemia, hypocalciuria, hypomagnesaemia and metabolic alkalosis. The fluid loss prompts activation of the Renin-Angiotensin system, leading to an increase in both renin and aldosterone levels. The main differential diagnosis for Gitelman's syndrome includes Bartter's syndrome, which usually affects children (rarely young adolescents). In contrast to Gitelman's syndrome, the primary defect in Bartter's syndrome is at the Na-K-Cl transporter in the ascending limb of the loop of Henle; hypomagnesaemia is absent, and patients usually have hypercalciuria."},{"id":"7109","category":"Uncategorised","stem":"A 67-year-old woman, who normally uses a stick to walk, is admitted following a fall. She describes a feeling of her head spinning and frequent dizzy spells, which are worse when she leans forward. She has had 2 falls in the last 2 days.\n\nShe has a history of diabetes, hypertension and previous CABG for coronary artery disease. She takes metformin 500 mg twice daily (BD), ramipril 5 mg once daily (OD), aspirin 75 mg OD, bendrofluazide 2.5 mg OD and atorvastatin 80 mg OD.\n\nClinical examination is unremarkable with no cardio-respiratory or neurological abnormalities. There is no postural drop in her blood pressure.\n\nWhat is the most likely cause of her falls?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"Benign paroxysmal positional vertigo (BPPV), the most common cause of vertigo encountered in clinical practice, is defined as 'a disorder of the inner ear characterised by repeated episodes of positional vertigo', meaning that symptoms occur with changes in the position of the head (NICE, 2017). It can present in patients of any age but commonly appears between the fifth and seventh decades of life. Women are more commonly affected than men."},{"id":"11598","category":"Uncategorised","stem":"A 70-year-old woman is admitted to the Acute Medical Unit with a 24-hour history of diffuse colicky abdominal pain and vomiting. She says the abdominal pain started suddenly and progressed in minutes. She has had two similar episodes in the past month, which resolved on their own, but she had to come to the hospital this time due to severe pain.\n\nHer past medical history includes type 2 diabetes mellitus, hypertension, non-Hodgkin’s lymphoma, and hypothyroidism.\n\nOn examination, she is alert and oriented, but she is in mild distress due to abdominal pain. Her pulse rate is 100 beats per minute, and blood pressure is 150/80 mmHg; her respiratory rate is 17 breaths per minute, her oxygen saturation on air is 99% and her temperature is 37 oC. Jugular venous pressure is not elevated, and there is no leg oedema. She has swollen peri-orbital areas, and upper lip spongy swelling is evident. No urticaria or rash is noted.\n\nA respiratory system examination reveals normal breath sounds on both sides. A cardiovascular system examination reveals normal heart sounds.\n\nHer abdomen is soft, and diffuse tenderness is present with sluggish bowel sounds.\n\nArterial blood gas on air\n\nA urine analysis was Normal; ketone negative.\n\nA contrast-enhanced CT scan of the abdomen revealed edematous swelling of the small bowel wall with incomplete obstruction and mild ascites.\n\nWhat is the likely cause of her acute abdominal pain?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Her past medical history includes type 2 diabetes mellitus, hypertension, non-Hodgkin’s lymphoma, and hypothyroidism.","Her abdomen is soft, and diffuse tenderness is present with sluggish bowel sounds.","Investigations:","Arterial blood gas on air","Investigation\tResult\tNormal range\npH\t7.38\t7.35–7.45\npCO2\t5.1 kPa\t4.6–6.4 kPa\nPO2\t12.1 kPa\t11.0–14.4 kPa\nBicarbonate\t24 mmol/L\t22–28 mmol/L\nLactate\t0.7 mmol/L\t0.6–2 mmol/L","A urine analysis was Normal; ketone negative.","A contrast-enhanced CT scan of the abdomen revealed edematous swelling of the small bowel wall with incomplete obstruction and mild ascites.","What is the likely cause of her acute abdominal pain?","Mesenteric arterial occlusion is unlikely given normal acid-base status.","Necrotising bowel wall infection is unlikely given the absence of fever or systemic inflammatory response syndrome, and a normal CRP and ESR.","The clinical presentation is inconsistent with malignant bowel infiltration.","Hypothyroid myxoedema is unlikely given insignificant TSH elevation.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"What is the likely cause of her acute abdominal pain?","explanation":"This patient has sudden-onset abdominal pain with bowel wall oedema and clinically has features of mucocutaneous angioedema. The cause of the abdominal pain is likely angioedema of the bowel, and in the absence of angiotensin-converting enzyme inhibitor (ACEi) use, acquired angioedema should be considered. B-cell lymphoproliferative neoplasms can cause acquired C1 inhibitor deficiency."},{"id":"11674","category":"Uncategorised","stem":"A 32-year-old woman has been referred and admitted to the Acute Medicine Unit by her General practitioner (GP) for management of her anorexia nervosa. The GP noted that the patient has progressively weakened over the past 3 days and is not able to walk or stand up on her own.\n\nOn examination, she has a body mass index of only 13 kg/m2. She is alert and oriented and appears to have full capacity. Apart from dehydration and skin exfoliation, the examination is otherwise unremarkable.\n\nInvestigations reveal:\n\nYou have decided to start intravenous fluids and potassium replacement. However, the patient states that she wants to leave the hospital immediately and wants no further treatment.\n\nWhat would you initially do as the Acute Medicine consultant?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","The Mental Capacity Act is not applicable in this scenario as the patient has capacity but has a serious eating disorder.","The use of physical constraints and sedation without formally detaining the patient should not be done.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"The Mental Capacity Act is not applicable in this scenario as the patient has capacity but has a serious eating disorder.","explanation":"The NICE guidance on eating disorders section ‘usage of the MHA and compulsory treatment’ states that: \"If a person's physical health is at serious risk due to their eating disorder, they do not consent to treatment, and they can only be treated safely in an inpatient setting, follow the legal framework for compulsory treatment in the Mental Health Act 1983.\""},{"id":"9434","category":"Uncategorised","stem":"A 34-year-old man is referred by his GP to the medical assessment unit (MAU) with this rash.\n\nHe noticed that this rash started four days ago as a cold sore but has since spread to involve his face. He has a background of eczema, for which he receives topical emollients and steroids. He takes no medication. His temperature is 36.7oC, his pulse is 80 beats per minute, and he has no associated lymphadenopathy. The rash is confined to his face, and each lesion has a reddish base with an umbilicated centre.\n\nWhich of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"This rash and history are typical of eczema herpeticum or varicelliform eczema. This is a dermatological emergency and will often be referred to the acute unit. The history is quite typical, and usually, the umbilicated vesicular lesions have the appearance of herpetic vesicles. The lesions evolve on damaged eczematous skin and are due to HSV type 1 or 2 infection. Treatment is with acyclovir/valaciclovir."},{"id":"8745","category":"Uncategorised","stem":"A 32-year-old man was admitted to the acute intake with acute shortness of breath and palpitations. Two hours earlier, he had been at a rave and had consumed alcohol and some other drugs offered to him by an acquaintance. Shortly after ingesting this, he had become unwell.\n\nOn examination, he looked cyanosed, with a pulse of 110 beats per minute, regular, blood pressure of 120/78 mmHg, a temperature of 37°C and oxygen saturations of 82% on 5L of oxygen with a respiratory rate of 22/min. On venesection, his blood is noted to be a chocolate brown colour. He has normal FBC and U+Es. His blood gases show:\n\nWhich of the following is the most appropriate treatment for this patient?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Investigation\tResult\tNormal range","pH\t7.44\t7.35–7.45","pCO2\t4 kPa\t3.5–5.5 kPa","pO2\t20 kPa\t10–14 kPa","Bicarbonate\t21 mmol/L\t22–26 mmol/L","Lactate\t4.4 mmol/L\t<1.5 mmol/L","Methaemoglobin","Which of the following is the most appropriate treatment for this patient?","Drugs such as dapsone, primaquine, chloroquine, sulphonamides, nitrofurantoin and lignocaine can also cause methaemoglobinaemia.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"Methaemoglobin","explanation":"Poppers or amyl nitrite are a drug of abuse associated with aphrodisiac and hallucinogenic effects. The drug is usually inhaled as it is a volatile liquid, but inhalation, and particularly oral intake, is associated with the development of methaemoglobinaemia. The Fe2+ component of haem is oxidised to the Fe3+ component by nitrites, resulting in conformational changes to haem, shifting the oxygen dissociation curve to the left, making the haem less able to give up oxygen at the tissue level. Increasing met-Hb levels result in increasing cellular hypoxia. This explains why oxygen saturations are low (the oxidised Fe3+ is not picked up on the sat machine wavelength), yet PO2 may be unaffected or high as the oxygen is not released."},{"id":"3554","category":"Clinical pharmacology & poisoning","stem":"Following discharge from hospital, a 77-year-old woman was reviewed by her GP and found to have the following urea and electrolytes:\n\nShe has a history of osteoarthritis, ischaemic heart disease, hypertension, and atrial fibrillation does not smoke and drinks a glass of wine daily. She takes warfarin, bumetanide, isosorbide mononitrate, bisoprolol, co-codamol, spironolactone, simvastatin and ramipril. On examination, she had a BMI of 31 kg/m2, a heart rate of 72 bpm irregular and a blood pressure of 130/84 mmHg. Her pulse was irregularly irregular.\n\nThe GP is concerned about the results, which are confirmed on repeat and asks you about them.\n\nInteraction between which of the following drugs is most likely to be the cause of her presentation?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Spironolactone and renin-angiotensin system drugs in heart failure: risk of potentially fatal hyperkalaemiaFebruary 2016 article.\nDiuretic sites of action","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"This patient has hyperkalaemia with a potassium of 5.3 mmol/L. This is likely to be a consequence of the co-prescription of an ACE inhibitor together with spironolactone. Spironolactone is a potassium-sparing diuretic. It acts on the late distal tubule in the nephron by blocking the action of aldosterone, an aldosterone antagonist. It binds to the aldosterone-dependent receptors at the sodium-potassium exchange site and causes increased amounts of sodium and water to be excreted while potassium excretion is inhibited. Consequently, the reabsorption of sodium (in exchange for potassium) is inhibited. ACE inhibitors such as lisinopril enhance this effect because reduced levels of angiotensin II result in reduced aldosterone secretion."},{"id":"3539","category":"Clinical pharmacology & poisoning","stem":"A 54-year-old man with a recent history of hypertension and type-2 diabetes is admitted with marked muscle pains and tiredness, which have developed over the last month and have become more profound over the last week.\n\nHe is currently taking aspirin, metformin, simvastatin, losartan, omeprazole, and amlodipine as regular therapies.\n\nWhich of the following is most likely to have caused his presentation?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"The presentation is suggestive of a statin-induced myositis. This occurs in approximately 5% of those treated with statins and usually presents with vague muscle aches and pains. CPK is often elevated, and the patients respond to withdrawal of the offending drug. Myositis is also associated with fibrates and can be exacerbated with the concomitant use of a statin and a fibrate. Alternative agents to treat hyperlipidaemia, such as ezetimibe, could be used. It is also important to note that when used with amlodipine, the maximum dose of simvastatin should be 20 mg, as simvastatin in higher doses with amlodipine does increase the risk of myopathy."},{"id":"3568","category":"Clinical pharmacology & poisoning","stem":"A 78-year-old man is admitted with a 4-day history of nausea, vomiting, and visual disturbances. He had a previous history of congestive heart failure and atrial fibrillation for which he was taking stable doses of losartan, warfarin, bisoprolol, and digoxin. Recently, he was diagnosed with H. Pylori-associated gastritis and had been treated with esomeprazole, clarithromycin, and amoxicillin. In the last month, he also had spironolactone 25 mg added to his anti-failure therapy.\n\nA diagnosis of digoxin toxicity was suspected and confirmed with a digoxin level of 3.3 ng/mL (therapeutic range 0.5-1).\n\nWhich of the following is most likely to have precipitated the digoxin toxicity?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"This patient has developed digoxin toxicity, which is most likely due to interaction with clarithromycin. Clarithromycin increases digoxin levels by inhibiting the P-glycoprotein transporter, which normally removes digoxin from the body. This inhibition occurs in the intestine, increasing digoxin's absorption, and in the kidneys, reducing its tubular secretion and excretion. The net result is higher concentrations of digoxin in the blood."},{"id":"7107","category":"Clinical pharmacology & poisoning","stem":"A 52-year-old man is found collapsed at home with an empty box of amitriptyline tablets beside him. On arrival in the hospital, the patient is agitated and has a generalised tonic-clonic convulsion.\n\nWhich of the following is the most appropriate initial step in his management?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Kerr, G.W., McGuffie, A.C. and Wilkie, S., 2001. Tricyclic antidepressant overdose: a review. Emergency Medicine Journal, 18(4), pp.236-241.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"Serum alkalinization with intravenous sodium bicarbonate has been the mainstay of therapy in tricyclic antidepressant (TCA)-induced cardiovascular toxicity. QRS prolongation is most often the indication for serum alkalinization in TCA toxicity."},{"id":"9988","category":"Clinical pharmacology & poisoning","stem":"A 26-year-old woman is admitted to the acute medicine unit after a citalopram overdose of 60 tablets each of 20 mg (Total 1.2g) roughly 3 hours ago, which she took after breaking up with her long-term partner. There is no other history of note.\n\nOn examination, her pulse is 110 bpm, blood pressure 138/88 mmHg, temperature 37oC, and she is lucid, communicative and conscious. Neurological examination is normal, and the ECG shows a sinus tachycardia.\n\nWhich of the following would be the most appropriate approach to the management of this patient?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Long, N., 2020. MAOI toxicity. Toxicology.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"Long, N., 2020. MAOI toxicity. Toxicology.","explanation":"This patient has taken a large overdose of citalopram (above 600 mg). The typical toxicity symptoms are agitation, tremor, and pyrexia, developing from about 4 hours, and serotonin toxicity developing over about 12 hours. Similarly, citalopram, like escitalopram, is associated with QT prolongation, which is dose-dependent. Fatal cases of arrhythmias, such as torsades de pointes, are reported. In this case, the most appropriate initial treatment would be activated charcoal in an effort to limit absorption, and it is recommended in patients who have taken SSRIs up to 4 hours previously. As features ensue, then benzodiazepines such as diazepam and lorazepam can be used, as seizures can occur."},{"id":"3556","category":"Clinical pharmacology & poisoning","stem":"An 80-year-old man presents with a three-day history of shortness of breath and ankle swelling. He has a previous history of hypertension and diabetes for which he takes rosuvastatin, losartan, aspirin, amlodipine, and metformin. Recently, his HbA1c has deteriorated slightly to 57 mmol/mol (it was previously less than 53 mmol/mol) and he was commenced on pioglitazone.\n\nOn examination, he has bilateral ankle oedema with a blood pressure of 134/86 mmHg and pulse of 80 bpm.\n\nInteraction between pioglitazone and which of the following is likely to be responsible for this patient's presentation?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"Thiazolidinediones, such as pioglitazone, may have an antagonistic effect on myocardial calcium channels, thereby enhancing the effect of calcium channel blockers and may exacerbate oedema associated with either agent or may indeed precipitate heart failure."},{"id":"18483","category":"Clinical pharmacology & poisoning","stem":"A 35-year-old man recently travelled to the northern coast of Spain for a vacation. On the fifth day of his visit, he went to a restaurant where he ordered local dishes, including pickled sardines, oysters, mushrooms and fish. The morning after the meal, he developed nausea, vomiting, and some abdominal cramps. He flew home that afternoon, and over the next 1224 hours, he noticed increasing fatigue and weakness in his shoulders and upper arms. By the following morning, his symptoms had progressed, including blurred vision, difficulties swallowing and more generalised weakness.\n\nHe went to the A&E at the local hospital, where he was noted to be afebrile with normal vitals except a respiratory rate of 30 with oxygen saturations of 92%. On examination, he displayed bilateral ptosis, diminished gag reflex, and generalised muscle weakness, particularly in the upper extremities, with diminished reflexes. Sensation to pinprick was generally intact.\n\nBaseline investigations revealed a normal full blood count, normal U&Es, LFTs and Calcium. CRP was 8 mg/dl (<5).\n\nWhich of the following is the most appropriate management for this patient?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Baseline investigations revealed a normal full blood count, normal U&Es, LFTs and Calcium. CRP was 8 mg/dl (<5).","Which of the following is the most appropriate management for this patient?","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"The most likely diagnosis here is botulism, with descending paralysis beginning with the cranial nerves following the ingestion of preserved seafood  this contrasts with the ascending paralysis associated with Guillain-Barré."},{"id":"11960","category":"Clinical pharmacology & poisoning","stem":"You see a 52-year-old woman who is known to be diabetic and who was admitted a few hours ago with sepsis secondary to community-acquired pneumonia (CAP). She has had a fever, headache, and productive cough for 5 days and was started on oral amoxicillin by her GP. She also had a COVID-19 PCR test, which came back negative. She did not feel any improvement and had to present to the accident and emergency department. On examination, the patient is icteric with no peripheral stigmata of chronic liver disease. Her BP is 90/60 mmHg, and her heart rate is 103/min.\n\nHer chest x-ray is shown below:\n\n[Image source: author]\n\nHer blood tests are as follows:\n\nWhat single antimicrobial may be useful in this case?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Legionellosis; WHO.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"Patients with severe pneumonia, especially if admitted to the Intensive Therapy Unit (ITU), should be tested for atypical pneumonia. The likely diagnosis here is atypical pneumonia, given the patients resistance to treatment and the severe picture, with Legionella pneumonia as the likely causative organism. The overall mortality of patients with Legionnaires disease ranges from 5% to 10%. Beta-lactam antibiotics are better combined with macrolides if severe or atypical pneumonia is suspected on initial assessment."},{"id":"3550","category":"Clinical pharmacology & poisoning","stem":"A 65-year-old man presents with a 3-year history of erectile dysfunction. His libido is unimpaired, but he has been unable to have intercourse with his wife for some months, which they both find distressing. His GP prescribed sildenafil. However, he is admitted as an emergency after developing profound weakness and giddiness an hour or so after having had the sildenafil. He is noted to be hypotensive at 70/50 mmHg.\n\nWhich of the following concomitant therapies is likely to have precipitated this effect with sildenafil?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"be used in patients who also use a GTN spray","explanation":"Sildenafil is a phosphodiesterase-5 (PDE-5) inhibitor drug that is well known to interact with nitrates, resulting in dramatic hypotension. Nicorandil will also produce this reaction. These drugs should not, therefore, be used in patients who also use a GTN spray."},{"id":"3558","category":"Clinical pharmacology & poisoning","stem":"A 58-year-old woman presented to her GP with tremor and agitation. She has a previous history of depression for which she has been on long-term lithium therapy, which has provided effective control. More recently, her GP noted that she was hypertensive and commenced new therapies.\n\nInitiation of which of the following is most likely to have precipitated her lithium toxicity?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"Lithium is a drug used for bipolar affective disorder. It is a drug that needs to be kept within a narrow therapeutic range. If the drug level goes above this range, lithium toxicity occurs. Lithium toxicity ranges in severity from mild tremors, agitation, and confusion to ataxia, convulsions and arrhythmias. Interactions can occur between lithium and other agents that precipitate toxicity; in particular, diuretics, both loop and thiazides, through sodium depletion and reduction of excretion, can increase the potential for lithium toxicity. ACE inhibitors may also cause lithium toxicity, as can NSAIDs."},{"id":"9296","category":"Clinical pharmacology & poisoning","stem":"A 64-year-old female came to the A&E unit with a sore mouth after tooth extractions. She described the pain as excruciating and throbbing. She had been prescribed carbamazepine by the GP for potential trigeminal neuralgia and was also taking paracetamol like smarties to ease the pain. In total, she had taken 32 tablets over the last 24 hours and had also taken 800 mg carbamazepine in the last 24 hrs. The pain in the mouth is constant.\n\nOn examination, she is 70 Kg and is well, other than having pain in her mouth. Examination of her mouth reveals three teeth extractions on the left side of the mouth, which look clean and not actively bleeding. She is alert and oriented. Her pulse is 80 bpm regular, blood pressure 122/80 mmHg and her temperature is 37oC.\n\nRoutine bloods are normal, including a CRP of 5 mg/dl (<5).\n\nA paracetamol level is less than 5 mg/L. Carbamazepine levels are 10 mg/L (therapeutic reference range 4-12 mg/L).\n\nWhich of the following is the most appropriate approach for this patient?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Paracetamol overdose: an evidence-based flowchart to guide management FREE C I Wallace, P I Dargan, A L Jones","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"This patient has taken a significant dose of paracetamol (16g) over the last 24 hours, and despite the paracetamol level being less than 5 at this measurement, one needs to treat this potential overdose. The quantity consumed over the 24 hours is 16g, giving a total dose of roughly /kg. Anything above 150 mg/kg should receive NAC. The carbamazepine levels are also at a therapeutic level, and whilst she has taken a high, de novo dose over the last 24 hours, the concentration of 10mg/l is within a therapeutic range, with a toxic range being above 20. However, some authorities suggest that enzyme induction may increase the risk of paracetamol toxicity, which is another reason to treat with NAC."},{"id":"3938","category":"Clinical pharmacology & poisoning","stem":"A 36-year-old woman was admitted to the hospital with marked agitation. She had taken an overdose of Citalopram, at least 20 tablets of 20 mg per tablet, about 6 hours before admission.\n\nOn examination, she was confused and agitated. Her pulse was 110 bpm regular, her blood pressure was 130/80 mmHg, and her temperature was 38.5 oC. She was noted to have hyperreflexia. The patient was treated with IV fluids.\n\nWhich of the following should be the approach to managing this patient?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"This patient has serotonin syndrome associated with an SSRI overdose. The condition is life-threatening, and this patient requires specific treatment that is supportive with IV fluids and moderate sedation with benzodiazepines. It is suggested that drugs with anticholinergic side effects, such as haloperidol and chlorpromazine, should be avoided due to the effect of reducing sweating. Similarly, beta-blockers are contraindicated."},{"id":"3940","category":"Clinical pharmacology & poisoning","stem":"A 45-year-old man was admitted feeling acutely unwell, breathless and ashen in appearance. He had gone out with friends the previous night, drank alcohol and taken some pills about 8 hours before his admission. He was otherwise well with no other history of note.\n\nOn examination, he was blue-grey in appearance, had a pulse of 110 bpm, regular, a blood pressure of 120/80 mmHg, a temperature of 37oC and oxygen saturations of 69%. Investigations revealed normal FBC, U&E's and a CRP of 12 mg/dL (<5).\n\nArterial gases reveal the following results:\n\nWhich of the following is the most appropriate treatment for this patient?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Arterial gases reveal the following results:","Investigation\tResult\tNormal range","Ph\t7.32\t7.34-7.44","pO2\t29 kPa\t11-13 kPa","pCO2\t3.3 kPa\t4.5-6 kPa","Bicarbonate\t13 mmol/L\t22-26 mmol/L","Methaemoglobin","Which of the following is the most appropriate treatment for this patient?","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"Methaemoglobin","explanation":"This patient has methaemoglobinaemia, which is likely associated with the use of drugs, of which there are many, but includes cocaine. The most appropriate initial treatment is methylene blue, with hyperbaric oxygen being a second-line agent."},{"id":"3541","category":"Clinical pharmacology & poisoning","stem":"A 56-year-old woman has a confirmed diagnosis of type 2 diabetes for which she is prescribed metformin, losartan, atenolol, and simvastatin. She is also noted to be particularly depressed and has been commenced on fluoxetine.\n\nThree months later, she had gone to see her GP recently as part of her diabetes review and complained that she felt more unwell, feeling lethargic and achy. Her GP measured some blood tests and found that her HbA1c was satisfactory at 55 mmol/mol, yet requested admission as he found that her sodium was 125 mmol/L (134-144).\n\nWhich of the following would be the most likely to cause this problem?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"urine sodium concentration should be measured","explanation":"Selective serotonin reuptake inhibitors (SSRIs) are known to cause hyponatraemia. While it is more common in older patients, this effect is not exclusively seen in that age group. SSRIs are thought to cause hyponatraemia by inducing a syndrome of inappropriate antidiuretic hormone (SIADH). Antidiuretic hormone causes water to be absorbed from the collecting ducts of the kidneys, resulting in concentrated urine. Therefore, urine sodium concentration should be measured. A concentration of >20 mmol/L and a urine osmolality of >500 mOsmol/kg, in the presence of hyponatraemia, is diagnostic. Treat by stopping fluoxetine and consider alternative antidepressant therapy for this patient."},{"id":"3551","category":"Clinical pharmacology & poisoning","stem":"A 55-year-old woman presents with nausea, vomiting, headache and sweating. On examination, she is apyrexial, has a heart rate of 98 bpm, a blood pressure of 138/90 mmHg and a respiratory rate of 18 breaths per minute. Four months ago, she was found to have hypertension and was prescribed ramipril and atenolol. Three days ago, she was prescribed amoxicillin, metronidazole and omeprazole in response to a positive urea breath test.\n\nWhat drug interaction may have occurred?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"acetaldehyde accumulates","explanation":"Metronidazole can cause the disulfiram reaction when taken with alcohol. Alcohol is metabolised by the enzyme alcohol dehydrogenase to acetaldehyde. Acetaldehyde is further metabolised by acetaldehyde dehydrogenase; both metronidazole and disulfiram inhibit this enzyme, therefore acetaldehyde accumulates. Unfortunately, acetaldehyde produces the rather unpleasant symptoms described above. For most, overindulging significantly is required before achieving a relatively mild hangover, but if alcohol is consumed even in small quantities while a patient is taking metronidazole, they will rapidly experience severe symptoms. Therefore, it is important to warn patients not to drink alcohol whilst taking it. This effect is utilised deliberately in disulfiram therapy, which alcoholics take to overcome the temptation to drink."},{"id":"3553","category":"Clinical pharmacology & poisoning","stem":"A 58-year-old man attends the clinic complaining of muscle aches and pains. He does not smoke and drinks only occasionally. On examination, he is obese, has some muscle tenderness, a heart rate of 62 bpm and a blood pressure of 142/88 mmHg. His medical history includes hypertension and type-2 diabetes for which he has taken stable medication for the last 6 months, including amlodipine 10 mg daily, metformin 500 mg tds, ramipril 5 mg daily, aspirin 75 mg daily and atorvastatin 40 mg daily.\n\nOn further discussion, the only other piece of information that is relevant is that over the last month or so, he has begun to take his diet more seriously and has substituted fruit juices for some of his usual tea and coffee beverages.\n\nWhich of the following foodstuffs is likely to be responsible for his presentation?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"Statins can cause myalgia/myositis and, in its most severe form, rhabdomyolysis. The most likely cause of this patient's presentation is myalgia related to statins. Many patients experience these symptoms without any drug interaction taking place. Statins are metabolised by cytochrome P450. Grapefruit juice is known to inhibit this, resulting in increased concentrations of atorvastatin if taken concurrently. Consequently, there is a greater risk of adverse reactions such as myositis."},{"id":"9297","category":"Clinical pharmacology & poisoning","stem":"A 22-year-old woman is admitted following a paracetamol overdose. She consumed 50 x 500 mg tablets, which she drank with alcohol four hours previously. The paracetamol concentration was 180 mg/L, and she was treated with IV N-acetylcysteine (NAC). Within an hour after commencing the infusion, she developed a diffuse red rash and intense itch.\n\nWhich of the following is the most appropriate approach to the treatment of this patient?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"This is a typical case of a patient developing a reaction to NAC  rash, an itch that occurs typically within the first hour. Rash and pruritus are common symptoms with NAC infusion, and the approach to treatment is to temporarily stop NAC, give IV chlorpheniramine (plus or minus IV steroids), wait for symptoms to settle and then reinstate the NAC infusion at a reduced rate. The following is an interesting Dutch overview that explains how safe NAC is in treating paracetamol, with very few reports in the world literature of anaphylaxis."},{"id":"6427","category":"Clinical pharmacology & poisoning","stem":"A 26-year-old man is admitted after taking 15g of paracetamol about 6-8 hours ago, together with alcohol. He has a history of depression and left a note stating that he wanted to kill himself. He was commenced on IV N-acetylcysteine (NAC).\n\nPlasma paracetamol concentration is 90 mg/L (nomogram >70 to merit treatment at 6 hours).\n\nAbout 30 minutes into the NAC infusion, the patient becomes rather red and is aware of pruritus. What is recommended in this case?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"Adverse effects with flushing, redness, and itch are common side effects associated with NAC occurring in roughly 15% of patients. However, the risk of hepatotoxicity is high in this persons case, and the small risk of anaphylaxis is outweighed by the risk of hepatotoxicity if one does not give the treatment. The recommended approach is to briefly stop the NAC, give antihistamines and restart the infusion at a slower rate."},{"id":"3546","category":"Clinical pharmacology & poisoning","stem":"A 20-year-old woman attends the admissions unit as she is concerned about some hard, painful lumps that have developed on her shins over the last 2 months. She reports no other symptoms, and she has a background history of asthma. She is taking salbutamol and beclomethasone inhalers, montelukast, microgynon, and minocycline.\n\nYou look at her shins and there are multiple raised erythematous macules that have the appearance of bruises, which are slightly tender and about 5-10 cm in diameter.\n\nWhat is the likely cause of these lesions?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"This is a description of erythema nodosum, which is a symptom of several diseases, and an adverse reaction to various drugs, including the oral contraceptive pill. The patient may prefer to rely on barrier contraception, though in this case, she mustn't become pregnant whilst taking a retinoid (isotretinoin). It may therefore be worth experimenting with other oral contraception or a long-acting reversible contraceptive (LARC) method. Erythema nodosum will take weeks to disappear even after the cause is removed, so patients may require symptomatic relief in the form of non-steroidal anti-inflammatory drugs (NSAIDs) such as ibuprofen or diclofenac."},{"id":"3548","category":"Clinical pharmacology & poisoning","stem":"A 59-year-old man attended his GP surgery to review his blood pressure. As this was the third hypertensive reading, the GP prescribed lisinopril.\n\nTwo weeks later, the patient calls into the pharmacy to ask for your advice as he feels unwell. He has passed very little urine in the past 18 hours and is feeling nauseous.\n\nYou signpost him urgently to the local hospital, where he is diagnosed with Acute Kidney Injury (AKI).\n\nWhat is the most likely underlying condition which was exacerbated by his new medication?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"This man has acute kidney injury (AKI) because he suffers from bilateral renal artery stenosis and takes ACE inhibitors. Glomerular filtration rate (GFR) is usually dependent on the rate of blood flow; an increase in flow results in an increased GFR. In patients with renal artery stenosis, this flow is restricted. This activates the renin-angiotensin system, resulting in hypertension. It also means that GFR is dependent on angiotensin II-mediated efferent arteriolar vasoconstriction. Consequently, preventing angiotensin II production with an ACE inhibitor will cause a fall in GFR and renal failure. This effect will only occur in patients with bilateral renal artery stenosis. It is important to be vigilant in prescribing ACE inhibitors to patients with any known arterial disease."},{"id":"3544","category":"Clinical pharmacology & poisoning","stem":"A 64-year-old woman has a history of osteoarthritis and hypercholesterolaemia for which she takes co-codamol and simvastatin. She was recently prescribed lisinopril as she had a third successive hypertensive reading at her GP surgery. Additionally, she has been prescribed cinnarizine for motion sickness.\n\nA week later, she presents in the pharmacy asking for something to treat a raised, red rash on her legs, arms, and trunk.\n\nWhat medication is most likely to be responsible for these symptoms?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"ACE inhibitors are known to cause urticarial rash, especially lisinopril. The lisinopril should be stopped since there is some risk of anaphylaxis, and alternative antihypertensive medication should be considered. A suitable antihistamine should be prescribed, but in this case, the patient should be warned not to take it with cinnarizine, which is also an antihistamine."},{"id":"18482","category":"Clinical pharmacology & poisoning","stem":"A 35-year-old man recently travelled to the northern coast of Spain on holiday. On the fifth day of his vacation, he visited a restaurant and ordered local dishes, including pickled sardines, oysters, mushrooms, and fish for dinner. The morning after the meal, he developed nausea, vomiting, and some abdominal cramps. He flew home that afternoon, and over the next 1224 hours, he noticed increasing fatigue and weakness in his shoulders and upper arms. By the following morning, his symptoms had progressed, including some blurred vision, difficulties swallowing, and more generalised weakness.\n\nHe visited the A&E at the local hospital, where he was noted to be afebrile with normal vitals except a respiratory rate of 30 with oxygen saturations of 92%. On examination, he displayed bilateral ptosis, diminished gag reflex, and generalised muscle weakness, particularly in the upper extremities, with diminished reflexes. Sensation to pinprick was generally intact.\n\nBaseline investigations revealed a normal full blood count, normal U&Es, LFTs and Calcium. CRP was 8 mg/dl (<5).\n\nWhich of the following is the most appropriate diagnostic test to confirm this patient's diagnosis?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Baseline investigations revealed a normal full blood count, normal U&Es, LFTs and Calcium. CRP was 8 mg/dl (<5).","Which of the following is the most appropriate diagnostic test to confirm this patient's diagnosis?","The most likely diagnosis is botulism with descending paralysis beginning with the cranial nerves following the ingestion of preserved seafood.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"The most likely diagnosis is botulism with descending paralysis beginning with the cranial nerves following the ingestion of preserved seafood.","explanation":"The most likely diagnosis is botulism with descending paralysis beginning with the cranial nerves following the ingestion of preserved seafood."},{"id":"3937","category":"Clinical pharmacology & poisoning","stem":"A 25-year-old man, who is a heroin addict, is arrested after he had shoplifted and, upon detention by the police, had taken his entire supply of heroin. The patient had some heroin toxicity but had recovered. The following morning, he was able to be discharged from MAU into police custody. However, he was concerned about the likelihood of withdrawal and wanted to know if there was any treatment he could have.\n\nOn assessment, the patient is felt to be at high risk of withdrawal from opiates.\n\nWhich of the following is the approach to managing this patient who will now be transferred to police custody?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Department of Health - Drug misuse and dependence - UK guidelines on clinical management.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"In this patient, assessment has indicated a high risk of withdrawal. Withdrawal is itself associated with significant physical and psychological morbidity, with some reports of suicide in custody. Therefore, the approach to managing this patient would be one of prescribing opiate substitutes such as methadone or buprenorphine. NICE guidance suggests methadone is the drug of choice."},{"id":"18481","category":"Clinical pharmacology & poisoning","stem":"A 35-year-old man recently travelled to the northern coast of Spain for a vacation. On the fifth day of his visit, he went to a restaurant and ordered local dishes, including pickled sardines, oysters, mushrooms and fish. The morning after the meal, he developed nausea, vomiting, and some abdominal cramps. He flew home that afternoon, and over the next 1224 hours, he noticed increasing fatigue and weakness in his shoulders and upper arms. By the following morning, his symptoms had progressed, including some blurred vision, difficulties swallowing, and more generalised weakness.\n\nHe went to the A&E at the local hospital, where he was noted to be afebrile with normal vitals except a respiratory rate of 30 with oxygen saturations of 92%. On examination, he displayed bilateral ptosis, diminished gag reflex, and generalised muscle weakness, particularly in the upper extremities, with diminished reflexes. Sensation to pinprick was generally intact.\n\nBaseline investigations revealed normal full blood count, normal U+Es, LFTs, and Calcium. CRP was 8 mg/dl (<5).\n\nWhich of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Baseline investigations revealed normal full blood count, normal U+Es, LFTs, and Calcium. CRP was 8 mg/dl (<5).","Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"Descending flaccid paralysis without sensory loss beginning with the cranial nerve after eating improperly preserved fish is a classic sign of foodborne botulism. Botulinum toxin blocks acetylcholine release, leading to the symmetric descending weakness. Respiratory failure often occurs, and mechanical ventilation may be required."},{"id":"17494","category":"Clinical pharmacology & poisoning","stem":"A 35-year-old woman is brought to the emergency department in a semi-conscious state with a history of an unknown drug overdose. The patients mother is a known case of breast cancer with bone metastasis, on morphine and antidepressants. On examination, the patients Glasgow Coma Scale (GCS) is 9/15. The patient has a pulse rate of 94 per minute, blood pressure of 92/62 mmHg, and her pupils are normal in size and sluggishly reactive to light. Respiratory rate is 14 per minute, and oxygen saturation is 95% on room air.\n\nArterial blood gas (ABG) test revealed the following findings:\n\nAn ECG showed broad-complex tachyarrhythmia.\n\nWhat is the recommended next step in this patients management?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Arterial blood gas (ABG) test revealed the following findings:","Investigation\tResult\tNormal range\nPH\t7.15\t7.35-7.45\nBicarbonate\t18\t22-26 Meq/L\nPCO2\t32 mmHg\t35-45 mmHg","An ECG showed broad-complex tachyarrhythmia.","What is the recommended next step in this patients management?","Guidelines in Emergency Medicine Network (GEMNet): guideline for the management of tricyclic antidepressant overdose. Richard Body, Tom Bartram, Fawad Azam, Kevin Mackway-Jones.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"Tricyclic antidepressant overdose can present with severe acidosis and ventricular arrhythmias. There is no specific antidote. The treatment includes the treatment of complications like arrhythmias with anti-arrhythmic, and bicarbonate infusion for acidosis."},{"id":"3585","category":"Clinical pharmacology & poisoning","stem":"A 30-year-old woman is admitted after being found at home by her friends, intoxicated and having taken a paracetamol overdose. She had consumed a bottle of vodka and taken a couple of boxes of paracetamol, possibly 30-40 tablets, approximately 4-8 hours earlier. On examination, she was stuporous with otherwise normal observations. Her results were normal, and her paracetamol level was 100 mg/L.\n\nThe paracetamol nomogram is shown below.\n\nWhich of the following is the most appropriate approach for the initial management of this patient?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","BNF treatment of overdoses\nAntoine, D.J. and Dear, J.W., 2016. How to treat a paracetamol overdose and when to do it. Expert review of clinical pharmacology, 9(5), pp.633-635.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"cannot have oral acetylcysteine/methionine","explanation":"This patient has a paracetamol concentration above the paracetamol nomogram for treatment. She has also consumed a paracetamol overdose with alcohol, which may act as an enzyme inducer. She is stuporous and, therefore, cannot have oral acetylcysteine/methionine, which is also an option for treatment, and therefore, she should receive IV acetylcysteine."},{"id":"3542","category":"Clinical pharmacology & poisoning","stem":"A 56-year-old woman developed a subdural haematoma following a road traffic accident. It was surgically repaired, and she made a good recovery. Her medication at discharge consisted of lisinopril, bendroflumethiazide, simvastatin, and phenytoin.\n\nThree months later, she re-attends the acute clinic and informs you that her dentist said that she had something called 'gingival hyperplasia'.\n\nWhich drug is likely to have caused this?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"Phenytoin, along with calcium channel blockers and cyclosporine, causes gingival hyperplasia. It is often asymptomatic, though patients with poor dental hygiene may report pain and bleeding on tooth brushing, and in extreme cases, displacement of the teeth and periodontal disease have been reported. It is the role of the dentist to educate on the matter of dental hygiene, though it does not hurt to make sure that this occurs. The patient will need to have her medication changed at the neurology clinic."},{"id":"9987","category":"Clinical pharmacology & poisoning","stem":"A 32-year-old male with a history of depression was admitted to the acute medicine unit after taking an overdose of sertraline 8 hours previously. He took 30 x 100 mg tablets. There was no other history of note.\n\nOn examination, he was agitated, slightly sweaty, with lip-smacking and some twitching movements of his legs associated with his agitation. His pulse was 120 bpm, temperature 37oC, and his blood pressure was 138/76 mmHg. He had exaggerated deep tendon reflexes and flexor plantar responses. Cognitively, he was lucid and fully oriented.\n\nAn ECG revealed sinus tachycardia, and electrolytes were normal.\n\nWhich of the following is the most appropriate approach to the management of this patient?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Ables, A.Z. and Nagubilli, R., 2010. Prevention, recognition, and management of serotonin syndrome. American family physician, 81(9), pp.1139-1142.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"The most appropriate approach to the acute management of this young man with a sertraline overdose is oral diazepam at a dose of 5-10 mg. He presents with serotonin syndrome based on Hunters criteria. In this case, he had exaggerated reflexes with agitation and sweating. Treatment is supportive with the use of benzodiazepines such as diazepam and lorazepam to control the agitation and tremors. Unlike citalopram and escitalopram, QT prolongation is very rarely reported in conjunction with sertraline."},{"id":"3540","category":"Clinical pharmacology & poisoning","stem":"A 68-year-old man presents a prescription for co-amoxiclav and paracetamol after being bitten on the hand by his pet dog. He has a history of epilepsy for which he takes sodium valproate.\n\nSix days later, he returns feeling unwell and would like to know if his medication may be the cause.\n\nHe says he has been passing very pale stools but dark urine, abdominal pain and an intense itch.\n\nWhich drug is most likely to be the cause of this mans symptoms?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Although paracetamol overdosage is associated with liver damage, there is nothing to indicate that this patient has received an overdose.","However, valproate is contraindicated in patients with active liver disease, and treatment should be reviewed if the patients liver dysfunction continues to deteriorate after stopping co-amoxiclav.","EMC Manuals: Co-amoxiclav.\nMedline plus: Drug-induced Cholestasis.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"Cholestatic jaundice can occur either during or shortly after the use of co-amoxiclav. The risk of acute liver toxicity is about 6 times greater with co-amoxiclav than with amoxicillin. Cholestatic jaundice is more common in males and in patients over the age of 65 years. Jaundice is usually self-limiting and very rarely fatal. The duration of treatment should be appropriate to the indication and should not usually exceed 14 days."},{"id":"3543","category":"Clinical pharmacology & poisoning","stem":"At a routine GP consultation, a 58-year-old man had a blood pressure of 158/116 mmHg. The patient was advised on lifestyle modification in order to help lower his blood pressure.\n\nOn review a couple of months later, he was still hypertensive with a reading of 156/112 mmHg. The GP initiated antihypertensive medication.\n\nFour weeks later, he was admitted with abdominal pains and was noted to have marked constipation. He described the stools as hard, but normal in colour and odour. He had always taken care to eat a high-fibre diet and drink plenty of fluid.\n\nWhich antihypertensive drug would be most likely to cause this mans problems?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"Nifedipine, along with other calcium channel blockers, is known to cause constipation. There is evidence to suggest that this is because it reduces the myoelectric response to eating. If constipation does not resolve once it has been stopped, another cause should be sought. Notably, this man has constipation despite a high-fibre diet. Other antihypertensive medications are unlikely to cause constipation."},{"id":"3547","category":"Clinical pharmacology & poisoning","stem":"A 72-year-old man presented to his GP with polydipsia, sight problems, and general fatigue. He had a confirmed diagnosis of type 2 diabetes mellitus. He was prescribed metformin, simvastatin, aspirin and lisinopril.\n\nA couple of years later, he is noted to have a macrocytic anaemia and the GP requests a further opinion.\n\nWhich of his medications is the most likely to be the cause of this?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"Metformin is known to cause vitamin B12 deficiency, so it should always be suspected as a cause of raised MCV or megaloblastic anaemia. It is thought to inhibit vitamin B12 absorption from the ileum by affecting the calcium-dependent membrane action. When metformin is stopped, the vitamin B12 deficiency resolves; if it does not, an alternative cause must be sought. Long-term metformin therapy has been known to cause a much more severe condition, with deterioration in mental state and peripheral neuropathy."},{"id":"3545","category":"Clinical pharmacology & poisoning","stem":"A 76-year-old man has a history of mild exercise-induced angina, atrial fibrillation, hypertension and type-2 diabetes mellitus.\n\nHe is taking pioglitazone, metformin, isosorbide mononitrate, digoxin, atorvastatin, bendroflumethiazide, and warfarin.\n\nHe is admitted after presenting with increasing breathlessness, a blood pressure of 148/100 mmHg, an irregular pulse of 84 bpm, and swollen ankles.\n\nWhich of the medications is most likely to have been responsible for his presentation?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"Studies suggest that approximately 5% of patients taking glitazones develop oedema, which may precipitate heart failure. Oedema is often worsened with the addition of other therapies such as calcium antagonists. NICE recommends that pioglitazone should be avoided in people with heart failure and those at risk of fracture. If used in patients taking insulin, the danger is further increased. Treatment is to stop pioglitazone and treat heart failure as usual."},{"id":"20209","category":"Clinical pharmacology & poisoning","stem":"A 24-year-old woman is brought to the emergency department 2 hours after deliberately ingesting approximately 2 grams of amitriptyline. She is drowsy but responds to verbal commands. Her vital signs show heart rate is 118 beats per minute, blood pressure is 102/68 mmHg, respiratory rate is 16 breaths per minute, and oxygen saturation is 98% on room air. An ECG demonstrates sinus tachycardia with a QRS duration of 128 milliseconds and a terminal R wave in aVR. She has received activated charcoal and supportive care. Fifteen minutes later, she develops a broad complex tachycardia at 180 beats per minute, and her blood pressure falls to 78/52 mmHg. She remains conscious but is increasingly confused.\n\nWhat is the most appropriate next step in management?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","What is the most appropriate next step in management?","This can be repeated every 5 minutes as necessary until the arrhythmia resolves or haemodynamic stability is achieved.","Target arterial pH is 7.457.55.","Sodium bicarbonate works by increasing extracellular sodium concentration and raising serum pH, which reduces TCA binding to cardiac sodium channels (fast sodium channel blockade reversal).","This is the first-line antidote treatment and takes priority over other interventions. Response is often rapid, with improvement in QRS duration and arrhythmia within minutes.","Amiodarone is contraindicated in TCA-induced arrhythmias; As a class III antiarrhythmic, amiodarone prolongs the QT interval and can worsen cardiac toxicity.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"The patient has developed ventricular arrhythmia (broad complex tachycardia) and haemodynamic instability (hypotension), which are clear indications for immediate intravenous sodium bicarbonate in tricyclic antidepressant poisoning."},{"id":"3549","category":"Clinical pharmacology & poisoning","stem":"A 60-year-old man was diagnosed with herpes zoster (shingles) and treated with aciclovir. The rash subsided, but significant pain remained, which was managed with co-codamol 30/500 and amitriptyline.\n\nHis regular medication consists of metformin, gliclazide, lisinopril and simvastatin. He is admitted with acute lower abdominal pain and an inability to pass urine.\n\nWhich drug has caused this mans problems?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","It is not recommended that patients with depression take amitriptyline since it is particularly dangerous in overdose.","Drug Bank: Amitriptyline.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"Drug Bank: Amitriptyline.","explanation":"This man has acute urinary retention. Tricyclic antidepressants, including amitriptyline, have anticholinergic adverse effects, including dry mouth, blurred vision, constipation, urinary retention, and drowsiness. Some tolerance develops to these effects, and patients should be encouraged to persevere as long as these effects are mild. Severe adverse effects, such as acute urinary retention, require prompt treatment. It can be difficult and demoralising when the adverse effects of a drug manifest themselves before the beneficial ones, so it is important to know when this will happen."},{"id":"3552","category":"Clinical pharmacology & poisoning","stem":"A 66-year-old woman presents as her GP is concerned about her INR, which is now 6. She has taken warfarin for approximately 2 years as anticoagulation for atrial fibrillation, with the INR kept around 2.5 on a dose of 3-4 mg of warfarin daily. Her only other treatment includes losartan and amlodipine for hypertension.\n\nOn this occasion, her INR is 6.2. On further discussion, she informs you that she has most recently embarked on lifestyle and dietary changes.\n\nWhich of the following products is likely to be responsible for this change in INR?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Sullivan, D.M., Ford, M.A. and Boyden, T.W., 1998. Grapefruit juice and the response to warfarin. American journal of health-system pharmacy, 55(15), pp.1581-1583.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"There is some evidence to suggest that cranberry juice enhances the anticoagulant effect of warfarin. It is important to recall that many patients take cranberry juice as prophylaxis against urinary tract infection. It is also taken by some for the flavonoids (antioxidants) that it contains, which are thought to reduce the risk of developing various malignancies. Unfortunately, they are also known to inhibit cytochrome P450 enzymes. Warfarin is predominantly metabolised by P450 CYP2C9, and if this is inhibited, the INR will rise."},{"id":"3555","category":"Clinical pharmacology & poisoning","stem":"A 35-year-old woman presents to the A&E as she has become excessively tired. The GP has not done anything about her problems. She has been treated with thyroxine 100 micrograms for the last 5 years for hypothyroidism, and all previous TFTs have been normal. She informs you that she is compliant with taking her thyroxine. On this occasion, her thyroid function tests reveal:\n\nWhich of the following drugs that she is taking is likely to have contributed to the adverse change in thyroid function test results?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"This patient has had stable thyroid function on 100 micrograms of thyroxine, but her most recent TFTs reveal that the dose is now inadequate. Of the drugs listed, the use of ferrous sulphate may be responsible for reduced absorption of thyroxine through chelation of thyroxine in the stomach. It is important to remind patients to take their thyroxine 2 hours before taking ferrous sulfate."},{"id":"19875","category":"Clinical pharmacology & poisoning","stem":"A 28-year-old woman is admitted to the acute medical unit 60 hours after taking a staggered paracetamol overdose (estimated 30 g over 12 hours). She was commenced on N-acetylcysteine on arrival.\n\nInitial blood results show:\n\nTwelve hours later, she has deteriorated and is now drowsy and disoriented with a GCS of 13/15 (E3, V4, M6), with a flapping tremor and grade 2 hepatic encephalopathy.\n\nRepeat blood results show:\n\nArterial blood gas on room air shows: pH 7.28 (7.35-7.45), pO2 11.4 (10.6-13.3) kPa, pCO2 3.6 (4.7-6) kPa, bicarbonate 16 mmol/L (22-26), base excess -9 ( -2 to +2).\n\nWhat is the most appropriate next step in the management of this patient?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","King's College Criteria for paracetamol-induced ALF:","Arterial pH < 7.3 after adequate fluid resuscitation (pH now 7.28), OR\nAll three of the following:\nINR > 6.5 (or PT > 100 seconds)\nCreatinine > 300 µmol/L\nGrade 3 or 4 hepatic encephalopathy","This patient meets KCC with an arterial pH < 7.3 despite ongoing resuscitation. Additionally, she has multiple other adverse prognostic features indicating rapid deterioration:","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"This patient has acute liver failure following paracetamol overdose with clear clinical and biochemical deterioration over 12 hours, demonstrating progression to fulminant hepatic failure. Early recognition and timely referral to a specialist liver transplant centre is life-saving."},{"id":"8743","category":"Clinical pharmacology & poisoning","stem":"A 32-year-old man was admitted acutely with acute shortness of breath. Two hours earlier, he had been at a rave and had drunk alcohol as well as consumed some liquid from a bottle that a friend had given him, which made him feel 'high'. However, shortly after, he became ill, feeling very short of breath and having palpitations.\n\nOn examination, he looks cyanosed, with a pulse of 106 bpm, regular, blood pressure of 120/78 mmHg, a temperature of 37oC and oxygen saturations of 82% on room air with a respiratory rate of 22/min.\n\nWhich of the following drugs is he likely to have taken?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Which of the following drugs is he likely to have taken?","Drugs such as dapsone, primaquine, chloroquine, sulphonamides, nitrofurantoin and lignocaine can also cause methaemoglobinaemia.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"Poppers or amyl nitrite are a drug of abuse associated with aphrodisiac and hallucinogenic effects. The drug is usually inhaled as it is a volatile liquid. Inhalation and particularly ingestion are associated with the development of methaemoglobinaemia and hence cyanosis. The Fe2+ component of haem is oxidised to the Fe3+ component by nitrites, resulting in conformational changes to haem, shifting the oxygen dissociation curve to the left, making the haem less able to give up oxygen at the tissue level. Increasing met-Hb levels result in increasing cellular hypoxia. This explains why oxygen saturations are low (the oxidised Fe3+ is not picked up on the sat machine wavelength), yet PO2 may be unaffected or high as the oxygen is not released."},{"id":"11361","category":"Critical care medicine","stem":"A 57-year-old woman with type 2 diabetes mellitus was admitted with urosepsis and required initial resuscitation with crystalloids. She is now recovering in the acute unit and is stable. Her pulse rate is 90/min, blood pressure is 110/80 mmHg, respiratory rate is 12 breaths per minute, oxygen saturation on breathing room air is 99% and capillary blood glucose is 5 mmol/L. She has no dependent oedema, and jugular venous pressure is not elevated. Respiratory and cardiovascular examinations are normal. Her body mass index is 22kg/m2.\n\nHer latest investigations are as shown:\n\nYou decide to give her routine maintenance intravenous fluids as she is still unwell and not able to drink or eat much.\n\nWhat are the daily requirements of water, sodium, potassium, and chloride in this patient based on actual body weight for routine maintenance intravenous fluids?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Her latest investigations are as shown:","You decide to give her routine maintenance intravenous fluids as she is still unwell and not able to drink or eat much.","What are the daily requirements of water, sodium, potassium, and chloride in this patient based on actual body weight for routine maintenance intravenous fluids?","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"What are the daily requirements of water, sodium, potassium, and chloride in this patient based on actual body weight for routine maintenance intravenous fluids?","explanation":"This patient is recovering from sepsis and has normal cardiac and renal function, with no complex ongoing losses or fluid/electrolytes requirements and has a normal body mass index. The NICE guidelines on intravenous fluid therapy in adults in the hospital setting state that patients require IV fluids for routine maintenance alone, and to restrict the initial prescription to 2530 ml/kg/day of water and approximately 1 mmol/kg/day of potassium, sodium, and chloride.' In patients who are obese, the IV fluid prescription should be adjusted to their ideal body weight. You should employ lower range volumes per kg (patients rarely need more than a total of 3 litres of fluid per day) and 'seek expert help if their BMI is more than 40 kg/ m2.' Furthermore, you should consider prescribing less fluid (e.g. 2025 ml/kg/day fluid) in older or frail patients, those who have renal impairment or cardiac failure, and patients who are malnourished, and in cases of risk of refeeding syndrome."},{"id":"10810","category":"Critical care medicine","stem":"A 48-year-old woman was admitted to the accident and emergency department following an intentional overdose of amitriptyline (40x50 mg tablets) 3 hours ago. On admission, she was drowsy with a Glasgow Coma Scale of 13/15, pupils were dilated bilaterally at 8mm.\n\nHer observations were: blood pressure 88/60 mmHg, heart rate 130 bpm, oxygen saturation 97% on room air, temperature 37.5oC, respiratory rate 21/min. She had a dry mouth, was flushed, and had increased muscle rigidity and myoclonic muscle twitching. Whilst being assessed, she had 2-3 minute episodes of tonic-clonic seizures. Intravenous fluids (0.9%NaCl) were commended, and she was given 4 mg of IV lorazepam.\n\nHer admission ECG was presented below:\n\nShe is awaiting ITU review.\n\nHow should she be managed further based on the above findings?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Her ABG revealed:","Investigation\tResult\tNormal range","pH\t7.22\t7.35 - 7. 45","pO2\t10.5 kPa\t11 - 14 kPa","pC02\t6.5 kPa\t4.6 - 6.4 kPa","Bicarbonate\t10 mmol/L\t22-26 mmol/L","Base excess\t-6\t-2 + 2","Lactate\t3.5 mmol/L\t0.5-2.2 mmol/L","Saturation","Her admission ECG was presented below:","She is awaiting ITU review.","How should she be managed further based on the above findings?","Magnesium sulphate can be used for refractory dysrhythmias and to treat torsade de pointes.","Phenytoin should be avoided.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"Bicarbonate\t10 mmol/L\t22-26 mmol/L","explanation":"Tricyclic antidepressants (TCA) overdose can lead to a variety of ECG abnormalities, including: sinus tachycardia, widened QRS complex, prolonged QTc and PR intervals, ventricular arrhythmias including torsade de pointes, bradyarrhythmias, heart blocks and asystole. Administration of sodium bicarbonate, even in the absence of acidosis, may reverse TCA-induced arrhythmias because alkalinization is thought to increase the protein binding of TCA, thus promoting its excretion and decreasing cardiotoxicity."},{"id":"12397","category":"Critical care medicine","stem":"A 67-year-old man presented to the emergency department with shortness of breath. He is known to have chronic kidney disease and is on regular haemodialysis, but he has missed the last two haemodialysis sessions. He had pulmonary congestion and orthopnea on admission and was given 15 litres of oxygen, which improved his shortness of breath. His potassium level on his initial venous blood gases was 7.4 mmol/L (3.5-5.5 mmol/L), and his ECG showed hyperacute T wave changes. Treatment was started by the emergency doctor, and the patient was given 30 ml of 10% calcium gluconate, 50 mL of glucose 50% plus 10 units of insulin given over 15 minutes and a salbutamol 10 mg nebuliser, which is still ongoing. The staff nurse has contacted you as he is concerned about the cardiac monitor showing a hyperacute T wave, which has been persistent, despite having his medicine.\n\nWhat is the best next step in the management of this patients hyperkalaemia?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","What is the best next step in the management of this patients hyperkalaemia?","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"The dose required in treating hyperkalaemia is 30 ml of 10% calcium gluconate that can be repeated every 5-10 minutes if there is no ECG improvement or in case of reappearance of ECG changes. (Please note that calcium chloride contains an average of three times more calcium than calcium gluconate - an ampule of calcium gluconate  typically 10 ml of the 10% formulation  contains 8.9 mg/ml of elemental calcium. In contrast, an amp of 10% calcium chloride provides a threefold higher concentration of elemental calcium (27.2 mg/ml). He will need a repeat dose of glucose plus insulin, and he may need continuous infusion if the repeated potassium level check does not show a satisfactory improvement. He may also need haemodialysis, probably in an intensive care setting, but the best next step would be repeating the calcium gluconate to protect the cardiomyocytes and decrease the chances of ventricular fibrillation."},{"id":"10268","category":"Critical care medicine","stem":"A 46-year-old homeless man with a known medical history of alcohol excess is admitted to the Accident & Emergency unit with drowsiness, visual disturbance, nausea, vomiting and abdominal pain. His admission Glasgow Coma Scale is 13/15.\n\nHis observations are as follows:\n\nHeart rate 115bpm,\nBlood pressure 110/60mmHg,\nRespiratory rate 18,\nSats 97% room air (RA),\nTemperature 36oC.\n\nHis admission bloods show:\n\nHow do you interpret his blood results?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","His observations are as follows:","His admission bloods show:","How do you interpret his blood results?","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"he has respiratory acidosis as well","explanation":"pH is 7.13= acidosis\nBicarbonate is 10 mmol/L = metabolic acidosis\nWhen metabolic acidosis is present, each drop by 1 mmol/L in serum bicarbonate should be accompanied by a 1.25 unit decrease in pCO2; hence, this patients partial pressure of carbon dioxide (pCO2) should be 3 Kpa. There has not been a decrease in this patients pCO2; therefore, he has respiratory acidosis as well.\nThe anion gap is 22 {Sodium-(Bicarbonate+Chloride)}= high anion gap metabolic acidosis\nFinal interpretation: metabolic acidosis with high anion gap (22) and respiratory acidosis\nThe common causes of high anion gap metabolic acidosis are: methanol and ethanol poisoning, salicylate poisoning, diabetic ketoacidosis (DKA), lactic acidosis, and renal failure."},{"id":"10269","category":"Critical care medicine","stem":"A 25-year-old woman was admitted to the Accident & Emergency unit with a 24-hour history of nausea, vomiting and diarrhoea. She has a past medical history of diabetes mellitus type 1 diagnosed 3 years ago, for which she is prescribed insulin glargine 15 units and insulin aspart 4-8 units tds with meals. She had not taken any insulin in the 24 hours before admission.\n\nOn examination, she was clinically dehydrated and drowsy (Glasgow Coma Scale (GCS) 13/15).\nHer blood pressure was 95/60 mmHg,\nHeart rate 125 bpm,\nRespiratory rate 28/min,\nSats 99% RA,\nTemperature 37oC.\n\nHer capillary glucose was 27mmol/L and ketones were 5.5mmol/L.\n\nThe admission bloods revealed:\n\nShe was commenced on FRII 6 units/hour, intravenous fluids and was given long-acting insulin. One hour later, her capillary glucose and ketones were 26 mmol/L and 6.5 mmol/L, respectively; hence, her FRII infusion rate was increased.\n\nWhich of the patients parameters indicate severe Diabetic ketoacidosis (DKA) requiring senior review for consideration of critical care involvement for level 2/HDU care?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Her capillary glucose was 27mmol/L and ketones were 5.5mmol/L.","The admission bloods revealed:","Which of the patients parameters indicate severe Diabetic ketoacidosis (DKA) requiring senior review for consideration of critical care involvement for level 2/HDU care?","Severe DKA is defined by the presence of one or more of the following criteria:","Blood ketones > 6 mmol/L","Bicarbonate level < 5 mmol/L","Venous/arterial pH < 7.0","Hypokalaemia on admission (under 3.5 mmol/L)","GCS less than 12 or abnormal AVPU scale","Systolic BP < 90 mmHg","Pulse > 100 or < 60 bpm","Anion gap > 16 [Anion Gap = (Na+ + K+) (Cl- + HCO3-) ]","Patients who show any of these signs/symptoms should be reviewed by a senior decision-maker and considered for level 2/HDU care.","Joint British Diabetes Societies for Inpatient care (JBDS-IP), 2013, The Management of Diabetic Ketoacidosis in Adults 2nd edition, ABCD.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"Severe DKA is defined by the presence of one or more of the following criteria:","explanation":"Severe DKA is defined by the presence of one or more of the following criteria:"},{"id":"11100","category":"Critical care medicine","stem":"You have been asked to review an 84-year-old woman for the evaluation of shortness of breath that started suddenly 12 hours ago. She suffered from an acute haemorrhagic stroke leading to right-sided weakness and dysphasia two months ago and made a reasonable recovery after conservative management. She has a background history of hypertension, type 2 diabetes and dyslipidaemia.\n\nShe also complains of central chest pain. On examination, she is comfortable at rest; her blood pressure is 135/56, pulse 98 BPM, temperature 37.6oC, respiratory rate 18/min and SpO2 of 95% on room air. Her jugular venous pulse is not raised; her cardiovascular examination is normal, and her lungs are clear.\n\nHer ECG shows sinus tachycardia and t-wave inversions in lead V1-V4. CTPA confirms the presence of the right pulmonary artery embolisation.\n\nWhat is the next management plan for her?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Her ECG shows sinus tachycardia and t-wave inversions in lead V1-V4. CTPA confirms the presence of the right pulmonary artery embolisation.","What is the next management plan for her?","Once the patient is stabilised, arrangements can be made for the IVC filter.","Velez, F.G.S. and Garcia, J.G.O., 2021. Management dilemmas in acute ischemic stroke and concomitant acute pulmonary embolism: Case series and literature review. Eneurologicalsci, 23, p.100341.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"This patient has pulmonary embolism with a background of acute haemorrhage stroke. While it is true that recent hemorrhagic stroke would prevent the use of alteplase in thrombolysis for acute stroke (as it is a complete contraindication within 3 months and relative thereafter), the same is not true of LMWH or IV heparin infusion. They are relatively contraindicated. In reality, most hemorrhagic strokes will completely resolve after 2 months, unless they are massive. It would be wise to have a risk/benefit discussion with the patient and family (especially given the dysphasia) and discuss starting the treatment dose of LMWH/DOAC to treat the PE. It is likely provoked by recent immobility from the stroke and right-sided weakness, and the risk of propagation is very high if nothing is done."},{"id":"10267","category":"Critical care medicine","stem":"A 28-year-old fit and young man was admitted following an intentional paracetamol overdose (35 X 500 mg tablets) 8 hours earlier. He felt nauseated afterwards and reported abdominal discomfort. His admission observations were:\n\nBlood pressure 115/70 mmHg,\nRespiratory rate 18/min,\nSats 100% room air (RA)\nTemperature 36.0oC,\nHeart rate 90 bpm.\n\nHis initial bloods were:\n\nHe was commenced on IV N-Acetylcysteine (NAC) infusion as per the protocol.\n\nThe following day, he developed malaise and mild confusion, nausea and vomiting, abdominal pain and jaundice. His repeat bloods revealed:\n\nHis 16-hourly IV NAC was continued, and he was discussed with the regional transplant team, as his King's College Criteria (KCC) score was 2.\n\nWhich of the following parameters are used as per the KCC to determine the degree of multiorgan dysfunction from paracetamol overdose in this patient?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","His initial bloods were:","He was commenced on IV N-Acetylcysteine (NAC) infusion as per the protocol.","The following day, he developed malaise and mild confusion, nausea and vomiting, abdominal pain and jaundice. His repeat bloods revealed:","His 16-hourly IV NAC was continued, and he was discussed with the regional transplant team, as his King's College Criteria (KCC) score was 2.","Which of the following parameters are used as per the KCC to determine the degree of multiorgan dysfunction from paracetamol overdose in this patient?","The following parameters are used as adjuncts to KCC or alternative early prognostic markers:","Lactate >3.5 mmol/L following a short period of fluid resuscitation (<4 hrs) or Lactate >3 mmol/L following fluid resuscitation for 12 hours\nPhosphate >1.2 mmol/L at 48-96 hours","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"Which of the following parameters are used as per the KCC to determine the degree of multiorgan dysfunction from paracetamol overdose in this patient?","explanation":"King's College Criteria (KCC) determine the degree of multiorgan failure from paracetamol-induced liver injury. They can help to identify patients with a poor prognosis and those who should be referred/transferred for an emergency liver transplant. It can be used for patients with acute liver failure following both acute and chronic paracetamol ingestion."},{"id":"12398","category":"Critical care medicine","stem":"You are the medical registrar on call, and you are responding to an adult arrest call in the catheterisation laboratory. The patient was admitted from the emergency department with ST-segment elevation myocardial infarction and has been moved to the catheterisation laboratory for primary angioplasty.\n\nWhen you arrive, you realise that it is a pre-arrest situation with the patient having had two episodes of non-sustained ventricular tachycardia (NSVT), for which the team has started amiodarone 300 mg IV over one hour.\n\nWhile you are there, the patient develops sustained ventricular tachycardia with unresponsiveness. You ask a member of the resuscitation team to deliver a DC shock, which is unsuccessful with the persistence of VT.\n\nAccording to the Resuscitation Council guidelines, what is the next step in managing this patient?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Resus.Org - Advanced life support algorithm.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"As recommended by The Resuscitation Council, witnessed, and monitored VF/VT in the cardiac catheter laboratory should be managed by giving up to three successive shocks (stacked shocks), then starting cardiac massage immediately after the third shock. The reason for this is the high chance of success when DC cardioversion is given as early as possible in the case of VT/VF."},{"id":"10812","category":"Critical care medicine","stem":"A 68-year-old man was admitted with melena and haematemesis. He had a past medical history of hypertension, atrial fibrillation and osteoarthritis, and his regular medications were: apixaban 5 mg twice daily, ramipril 10 mg once daily, bendroflumethiazide 2.5 mg once daily and PRN co-codamol 30/500. He admitted that he has been using ibuprofen over the counter for the last 2 weeks for flare-ups of his osteoarthritis pain.\n\nOn arrival, he was pale and clammy. He vomited 250 ml of fresh blood and passed a black stool again.\n\nHis observations were: blood pressure 80/60 mmHg, heart rate 130 bpm, oxygen saturation 95%, respiratory rate 25/min, temperature 35.8oC. His admission blood gas analysis revealed:\n\nHe was reviewed immediately, and the major haemorrhage protocol was activated.\n\nWhat is the most appropriate next step to reverse the effects of apixaban in this patient?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","On arrival, he was pale and clammy. He vomited 250 ml of fresh blood and passed a black stool again.","Investigation\tResult\tNormal range","pH\t7.31\t7.35 - 7.45","pO2\t10k Pa\t11-14.4 kPa","pCO2\t4.9 kPa\t4.6-6.4 kPa","Lactate\t6.0 mmol/L\t0.5-2.2 mmol/L","Saturation","Bicarbonate\t18 mmol/L\t22-26 mmol/L","Base excess\t-6\t-2-+2","Hb\t60 g/L\tMen: 130-180 g/L\nWomen: 115-165 g/L","He was reviewed immediately, and the major haemorrhage protocol was activated.","What is the most appropriate next step to reverse the effects of apixaban in this patient?","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"Andexanet alfa has been licensed by NICE for reversal of apixaban and rivaroxaban in uncontrolled/life-threatening bleeding (under specialist supervision)."},{"id":"12400","category":"Critical care medicine","stem":"An 80-year-old woman with dementia has been referred from the care home as she had a fall 3 hours ago and sustained a head injury. You assess the patient, and she has a small scalp wound that has been sutured by the emergency doctor.\n\nUnder which of the following circumstances can this patients CT head scan be delayed for more than one hour?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"If the patient has been on anticoagulation treatment, a CT head is recommended within 8 hours of the injury and not within one hour. Other choices are all indications of an urgent CT head after sustaining a head injury within one hour of identifying any of them, with NICE advising a written radiological report to be available within one hour of the test."},{"id":"11365","category":"Critical care medicine","stem":"A 57-year-old man is admitted with severe community-acquired pneumonia and he is noted to have a blood pressure of only 80/50 mmHg along with a respiratory rate of 24/min, pulse rate of 120/min, oxygen saturation on air of 92%, and a temperature of 40oC. He has mottled skin with cool peripheries, a capillary refill time of 4 seconds, but no dependent oedema; jugular venous pressure is not elevated; left base crepitations are heard, and heart sounds are normal on auscultation.\n\nHis past medical history includes type-2 diabetes and asthma. You note from the electronic portal that his blood tests done by his general practitioner about 2 weeks ago, including urea, creatinine, and electrolytes, were normal.\n\nA large-bore intravenous cannula is inserted, and blood has been drawn, including for cultures.\n\nWhat is the recommended sodium concentration of the crystalloid that should be used for initial resuscitation in this patient?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","A large-bore intravenous cannula is inserted, and blood has been drawn, including for cultures.","What is the recommended sodium concentration of the crystalloid that should be used for initial resuscitation in this patient?","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"What is the recommended sodium concentration of the crystalloid that should be used for initial resuscitation in this patient?","explanation":"NICE guidelines on the use of intravenous fluid therapy in adults in the hospital setting recommend the use of crystalloids containing sodium in the range 130154 mmol/L, with a bolus of 500 ml over less than 15 minutes in patients who need IV fluid resuscitation."},{"id":"13638","category":"Critical care medicine","stem":"A 55-year-old woman with a past medical history of systemic hypertension on atenolol 100 mg once daily is admitted to the emergency department following an anaphylactic reaction.\n\nShe has already had 2 doses of intramuscular adrenaline administered 5 minutes apart and 3 litres of intravenous fluid boluses.\n\nShe remains unresponsive with a pulse rate of 50 beats per minute, a respiratory rate of 35 breaths per minute, an oxygen saturation of 81% on high-flow oxygen, and a blood pressure of 70/30 mmHg. She is commenced on an intravenous adrenaline infusion.\n\nWhich of the following medications should be considered in this patient to improve the effectiveness of adrenaline?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","A 55-year-old woman with a past medical history of systemic hypertension on atenolol 100 mg once daily is admitted to the emergency department following an anaphylactic reaction.","She has already had 2 doses of intramuscular adrenaline administered 5 minutes apart and 3 litres of intravenous fluid boluses.","Which of the following medications should be considered in this patient to improve the effectiveness of adrenaline?","Chlorpheniramine is an antihistamine (H1 blocker) and has no role in the treatment of respiratory or cardiovascular symptoms of anaphylaxis.","Vasopressors (phenylephrine) as a second-line can be used in refractory anaphylaxis, but glucagon should be given first in this scenario.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"This patient with refractory anaphylaxis is on a beta-blocker (atenolol), which can render the administered adrenaline less effective. Glucagon can be administered to reduce/bypass beta-blocking as it has inotropic and chronotropic effects which are beta-receptor independent, as it mediates its effects through adenylyl cyclase/cAMP."},{"id":"11099","category":"Critical care medicine","stem":"You have been asked to review a 64-year-old woman patient for the evaluation of shortness of breath that started suddenly 4 hours ago. She suffered from an acute ischemic stroke leading to right-sided weakness and dysphasia a week back and made a good recovery with conservative management. She has a background history of hypertension, type 2 diabetes, and dyslipidaemia.\n\nShe is also complaining of central chest pain. On examination, she is comfortable at rest; her blood pressure is 108/56 mmHg, pulse rate 98 beats per minute, temperature 37.6oC, respiratory rate 18/min, and SpO2 of 95% on room air. Her jugular venous pulse is not raised; her cardiovascular examination is normal, and her lungs are clear.\n\nHer ECG shows sinus tachycardia and t-wave inversions in lead V1-V4. Her CT pulmonary angiogram confirms the presence of the right pulmonary artery embolisation.\n\nWhat is the next management plan for her?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Her ECG shows sinus tachycardia and t-wave inversions in lead V1-V4. Her CT pulmonary angiogram confirms the presence of the right pulmonary artery embolisation.","What is the next management plan for her?","Pulmonary embolism (PE) is the most common cause of death 2-4 weeks post-stroke, and in the setting of concurrent acute stroke, hypoxia resulting from PE can worsen existing cerebral ischemia.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"This patient has a pulmonary embolism; however, since she is not haemodynamically compromised, she needs to be on anticoagulation to prevent the expansion of the thrombus, and IV heparin is the reasonable choice for anticoagulation in acute settings."},{"id":"11367","category":"Critical care medicine","stem":"A 55-year-old woman had a day of fever with rigour followed by multiple episodes of diarrhoea with abdominal pain lasting for 7 days approximately 4 weeks ago, but she had recovered uneventfully. However, for the past 6 days, she has experienced difficulty in getting up from her bed, and it has progressed to the point of not being able to walk without support and difficulty in weight-bearing when standing. She says her legs also feel numb, and she feels pins and needles in both her feet and legs. She also states that her grip has weakened in both hands in the past few hours. She says that her bladder and bowel function are unchanged. Her past medical history is unremarkable.\n\nOn examination, she is alert and oriented. Her pulse rate is 120 beats per minute, blood pressure is 100/70 mmHg, respiratory rate is 14 breaths per minute, and temperature is 36.8oC. Oxygen saturation is 100% on breathing air. An examination of her respiratory system reveals normal vesicular breath sounds bilaterally. A cardiovascular exam reveals normal heart sounds and no murmurs. An examination of the abdomen is normal.\n\nA Neurology exam revealed normal cranial nerve function, normal speech comprehension and articulation. Both upper limb shoulder muscle power is 5/5, but the elbow, wrist and finger muscle power is 4/5; bilateral biceps, triceps and supinator deep tendon reflexes are sluggish. There is preserved sensation in both the upper limbs. Power 2/5 in both lower limbs with reduced tone; knee, ankle and plantar reflexes are absent bilaterally; preserved sensations in both lower limbs.\n\nOther investigations included a full blood count, renal function test and liver function test, which were all normal. An ECG revealed sinus tachycardia.\n\nWhat investigation would be critical to detect deterioration in this patient?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Investigation:","Investigation\tResult\tNormal range\nArterial pH\t7.38\t7.35  7.45\nArterial PO2\t12 kPa\t11.0  14.4 kPa\nArterial PCO2\t5.1kPa\t4.6 - 6.4 kPa\nC-reactive protein\t7 mg/L\t< 5 mg/L","Other investigations included a full blood count, renal function test and liver function test, which were all normal. An ECG revealed sinus tachycardia.","What investigation would be critical to detect deterioration in this patient?","Peak flow measurements are not considered adequate substitutes for serial FVC.","Arterial blood gas monitoring is not adequate, as it tends to remain normal until the patient is about to have a respiratory arrest.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"What investigation would be critical to detect deterioration in this patient?","explanation":"This patient has progressive symmetric flaccid quadriparesis, areflexia, and subjective sensory loss consistent with Guillain-Barré syndrome (GBS) with an antecedent history of an acute infectious diarrhoeal illness suggestive of Campylobacter jejuni infection. Patients with GBS are at risk of neuromuscular weakness and rapid ventilatory failure and it is critical to monitor serial forced vital capacity every few hours to detect an impending respiratory failure and initiate/plan mechanical ventilation without delay. Emergency intubation may be complicated by severe autonomic problems, and it can be avoided by serial respiratory assessment using FVC/pulmonary function tests and early detection of respiratory failure. Non-invasive ventilation is not a safe option for patients with GBS."},{"id":"11359","category":"Critical care medicine","stem":"A 65-year-old man was found unresponsive at home by his neighbour and brought to the Emergency Department, and has now been admitted to the high dependency unit. The neighbour is unsure about any past medical history and says that the patient had only recently moved to the property and has been living alone.\n\nOn examination, the patient is obese, with a Glasgow Coma Scale of 12/15.\n\nHis respiratory rate is 25/min, with oxygen saturation on air 89%; oxygen saturation on a 4L/min simple face mask 98%.\n\nHe has a pulse rate of 110/min regular, blood pressure is 136/90 mmHg, and his temperature is 37.5oC. His pupils are equal and normally reactive to light.\n\nA chest examination reveals reduced breath sounds bilaterally. A cardiovascular system examination reveals normal heart sounds. Mild bilateral pitting ankle oedema is present. A few myoclonic jerks are noted.\n\nHis capillary blood glucose is 7.2 mmol/L.\n\nHis chest X-ray is as follows:\n\nWhich of the following investigations is likely to provide the diagnosis for this patient?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","He has a pulse rate of 110/min regular, blood pressure is 136/90 mmHg, and his temperature is 37.5oC. His pupils are equal and normally reactive to light.","His capillary blood glucose is 7.2 mmol/L.","His chest X-ray is as follows:","[Authors own image]","Which of the following investigations is likely to provide the diagnosis for this patient?","Pitting oedema may be due to right heart failure secondary to the lung disease, but echocardiography would not be the initial test to ascertain the cause of the low GCS.","A CT brain is not indicated immediately, as hypercapnic respiratory failure needs to be excluded first. Myoclonic jerks may be seen in patients with carbon dioxide narcosis.","Serum sodium is important and needs to be done, but an ABG is likely to provide the diagnosis.","Serum ammonia is useful in acute liver failure assessment; this scenario is likely to be respiratory failure rather than acute liver failure.","BTS/ICS Guideline for the Ventilatory Management of Acute Hypercapnic Respiratory Failure in Adults.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"His chest X-ray is as follows:","explanation":"The patients chest x-ray shows features of hyperinflated lungs and reduced breath sounds bilaterally, with the initial hypoxia on breathing air, all pointing to an underlying chronic obstructive airway disease or emphysema. An arterial blood gas (ABG) is likely to show hypercapnic respiratory failure, which would explain the low GCS."},{"id":"3952","category":"Critical care medicine","stem":"You attend a cardiac arrest on MAU. A 75-year-old man has collapsed, and upon assessing his airway, breathing and circulation, you determine that he has no cardiac or respiratory output. You secure his airway and commence cardiopulmonary resuscitation. You perform an ECG rhythm trace (below):\n\nWhat is the correct initial management?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Resus: 2021 resuscitation guidelines adult advanced life support guidelines.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"The rhythm above shows pulseless electrical activity. The correct management according to guidelines is to give 1 mg adrenaline IV and continue with CPR. PEA is not a shockable rhythm, so it is not appropriate, and external pacing should only be used if the patient has a cardiac output."},{"id":"11362","category":"Critical care medicine","stem":"A 55-year-old woman is admitted to the acute medicine unit with breathlessness and dizziness. She has had sharp inspiratory pain on the right side of her chest for the past week, but for the past 24 hours, her breathing has deteriorated.\n\nShe has also been having epigastric pain, loss of appetite, and loss of weight for the past month. She was evaluated by her general practitioner, who noted that she had low serum albumin, anaemia, and hyperbilirubinaemia and had referred her for a specialist gastroenterologist consultation, which is in a few days. Her past medical history is otherwise insignificant. She has a 40-pack-year smoking history and consumes alcohol rarely.\n\nOn examination, the patient is alert and oriented but distressed. Her respiratory rate is 26 breaths per minute, using the accessory muscles of respiration. Her pulse rate is 140 breaths per minute, and her blood pressure is 140/70 mmHg on arrival to the unit.\n\nOxygen saturation is 86% when breathing air and 99% on 15L oxygen via a reservoir bag mask.\n\nHer temperature is 36.5oC and she has a capillary blood glucose of 7 mmol/L.\n\nExamination of the respiratory system reveals normal vesicular breath sounds, and a cardiovascular exam reveals normal heart sounds.\n\nHer abdomen is soft, no tenderness felt, and no masses palpable. An ECG reveals sinus tachycardia/incomplete right bundle branch block.\n\nThe CT pulmonary angiogram image of the patient is as shown:\n\nAfter her return from the CT suite, the patient became very dizzy and is noted to have a blood pressure of 70/60 mmHg. The patient is given a 250 ml bolus of isotonic normal saline by the senior house officer, but her blood pressure remains 90/60 for the next 30 minutes.\n\nWhat would be the most appropriate management for this patient at this stage?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Her temperature is 36.5oC and she has a capillary blood glucose of 7 mmol/L.","Her abdomen is soft, no tenderness felt, and no masses palpable. An ECG reveals sinus tachycardia/incomplete right bundle branch block.","The CT pulmonary angiogram image of the patient is as shown:","[Authors own image]","What would be the most appropriate management for this patient at this stage?","If the patient had remained haemodynamically stable, the treatment of choice would be an intravenous bolus of heparin followed by enoxaparin.","Hydrocortisone, intercostal chest drain, and antibiotics have no role in the management of this current clinical situation.","British Thoracic Society - BTS Guideline for the outpatient management of pulmonary embolism","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"This patient has clinical features of an acute pulmonary embolism and had normal blood pressure at the time of arrival. The CTPA shows a clot in the right main pulmonary artery along with multiple clots in the proximal pulmonary arterial branches, but the patient deteriorates with hypotension and has significantly dropped her BP from baseline and remains hypotensive, which is concerning for impending circulatory collapse and requires emergency thrombolysis with alteplase."},{"id":"10270","category":"Critical care medicine","stem":"A 79-year-old woman nursing home resident was admitted with a one-week history of decreased food and fluid intake, fever, and worsening drowsiness. She had a past medical history of vascular dementia, hypertension, diabetes mellitus type 2, and recurrent urinary tract infections (UTIs). Her pre-admission medications include metformin 1g twice daily, sitagliptin 100 mg once daily, and bendroflumethiazide 2.5 mg once daily. She was reviewed by her GP 2 days before, who diagnosed her with UTI and prescribed nitrofurantoin MR 100 mg twice daily.\n\nHer admission observations were:\n\nBlood pressure 90/60 mmHg,\nHeart rate 115 bpm,\nSats 98% room air (RA),\nTemperature 38.5oC,\nRespiratory rate 24/min,\nGlasgow Coma Scale (GCS) 12/15.\nHer capillary glucose was unrecordable (high), and ketones were 1.5mmol/L. Venous pH was 7.32, lactate 2.8 mmol/L.\n\nHer blood results were as follows:\n\nShe was diagnosed with urosepsis, acute kidney injury and hyperosmolar hyperglycaemic state (HHS), based on her results and calculated serum osmolality.\n\nWhat is the first crucial step in the management of this patients HHS?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Her admission observations were:","Her blood results were as follows:","She was diagnosed with urosepsis, acute kidney injury and hyperosmolar hyperglycaemic state (HHS), based on her results and calculated serum osmolality.","What is the first crucial step in the management of this patients HHS?","The characteristic features of HHS are:","Hypovolaemia\nMarked hyperglycaemia (30 mmol/L or more) without significant hyperketonaemia (<3 mmol/L) or acidosis (pH>7.3, bicarbonate >15 mmol/L)\nOsmolality usually 320 mOsmol/kg or more","Joint British Diabetes Societies for Inpatient Care (JBDS-IP), 2012, The management of the hyperosmolar hyperglycaemic state (HHS) in adults with diabetes, ABCD.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"The characteristic features of HHS are:","explanation":"The characteristic features of HHS are:"},{"id":"10811","category":"Critical care medicine","stem":"A 27-year-old woman with a background of asthma and hay fever is admitted with a dry cough, shortness of breath and wheeze for the last 48 hours. Her baseline peak flow is 420L/min, and she uses regular inhaler budesonide/formoterol and salbutamol as required (PRN).\n\nShe was admitted with asthma exacerbation twice in the last 6 months but never required ITU admission.\n\nOn arrival at the Accident and Emergency Department, her observations were: blood pressure 120/90 mmHg, heart rate 100 beats per minute, respiratory rate 25 breaths per minute, oxygen saturation 97% on room air, temperature 37oC, and the peak-flow was 180L/min. She was started on nebulised salbutamol and ipratropium and oral prednisolone 40mg.\n\nA Chest X-ray did not reveal any consolidation, and the blood results were:\n\nDespite \"back-to-back\" nebulisers, she continued to experience chest tightness and wheeze. Her repeat observations 1 hour later are: blood pressure 95/70 mmHg, respiratory rate 30/min, heart rate 125 bpm, oxygen saturation 91% on room air, temperature 36.9oC. Repeat peak flow is 130L/min. She was commenced on supplemental oxygen.\n\nThe ABG analysis reveals:\n\nWhat is the next most important step in her management plan?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","She was admitted with asthma exacerbation twice in the last 6 months but never required ITU admission.","A Chest X-ray did not reveal any consolidation, and the blood results were:","The ABG analysis reveals:","Investigation\tResult\tNormal range","pH\t7.35\t7.35-7.45","pO2\t7.9 kPa\t11-14.4 kPa","pCO2\t6.4 kPa\t4.6-6.4 kPa","Lactate\t2.5 mmol/L\t0.5-2.2 mmol/L","Saturation","What is the next most important step in her management plan?","Indications for admission to level 2/3 care include patients who require ventilatory support and patients who have developed acute severe asthma as determined by:","BTS/SIGN British Guideline on the Management of Asthma.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"The clinical signs and measurements of life-threatening asthma include: Altered conscious levels, exhaustion, arrhythmia, hypotension, cyanosis, silent chest and poor respiratory effort, PEF<33% best or predicted, SpO2<92%, PaO<8kPa and normal PaCO2 (4.6-6 kPa)."},{"id":"19768","category":"Critical care medicine","stem":"A 55-year-old woman is brought to the Emergency Department by her family because of a two-day history of feeling unwell, with fever, shaking chills, lower abdominal discomfort and increasing frequency and pain during urination. On the morning of the assessment, she became drowsy and confused. Her medical history includes type 2 diabetes mellitus (well-controlled on metformin) and hypertension. She does not smoke or drink alcohol and has had no recent hospital admissions.\n\nOn examination, she is drowsy but arousable (Glasgow Coma Scale 13/15), with mottled skin and cool extremities.\n\nObservations are as follows:\n\nInitial laboratory results reveal:\n\nA urine dipstick is strongly positive for leukocytes and nitrites.\n\nWhat is the most appropriate immediate next step in her management?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Observations are as follows:","Investigation\tResult\tNormal range","Temperature\t39.1oC\t36.1-37.2oC","Heart rate\t125 bpm\t60-100 bpm","Blood pressure\t82/48 mmHg\t100-140/60-90 mmHg","Respiratory rate\t32/min\t12-20/min","Oxygen saturation","Initial laboratory results reveal:","A urine dipstick is strongly positive for leukocytes and nitrites.","What is the most appropriate immediate next step in her management?","Hydrocortisone is reserved for cases of septic shock refractory to fluids and vasopressors, and is not recommended as first-line treatment.","Urgent imaging may be needed to identify the source of sepsis, but should not delay time-critical administration of antibiotics and fluids.","Urinary catheterisation is important to monitor renal function and fluid status, but should not precede antibiotics and fluid resuscitation.","Vasopressors such as norepinephrine are reserved for patients who remain hypotensive despite an initial trial of intravenous fluids.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"Blood pressure\t82/48 mmHg\t100-140/60-90 mmHg","explanation":"This woman presents with a history, signs, and laboratory findings strongly suggestive of urosepsis with septic shock: hypotension, tachycardia, fever, elevated lactate, acute kidney injury, and mental status changes. According to Sepsis-3 definitions, septic shock is diagnosed when there is sepsis with persistent hypotension requiring vasopressors to maintain a mean arterial pressure of =65mmHg and serum lactate >2mmol/L despite adequate fluid resuscitation."},{"id":"11366","category":"Critical care medicine","stem":"A 35-year-old woman has been experiencing fatigue, fevers, multiple joint pains, muscle pains, dry mouth and eyes, and episodic cold discoloured fingers on exposure to cold weather for the past 3 months. She has just seen a rheumatologist and has been diagnosed with mixed connective disorder (MCTD), and she has been prescribed oral prednisolone, which she has not yet started. She, however, is admitted to the acute care unit with sharp chest pains and breathlessness.\n\nAt admission to the acute medicine unit overnight, on examination, she is alert and oriented and is speaking full sentences comfortably without any use of accessory muscles for breathing. Her pulse rate is 100/min, and no pulse deficits are noted. Blood pressure is 130/80 mmHg, temperature is 36.8oC, oxygen saturation on air 100%, and respiratory rate is 19/min.\n\nJugular venous pressure is elevated. Mild pitting ankle oedema is noted bilaterally.\n\nA respiratory system examination reveals normal vesicular breath sounds on both sides. A cardiovascular system examination reveals normal but muffled and distant heart sounds.\n\nAn abdomen examination is unremarkable.\n\nInvestigations reveal:\n\nWithin a few hours, the patient suddenly becomes very breathless and unwell.\n\nShe is noted to have the following observations:\n\nShe is highly distressed, using accessory muscles of breathing and leaning forward in her bed.\n\nRespiratory rate 35/min, Saturation on air 92%; on 15L high-flow oxygen saturation 100%. Pulse rate 140/min, blood pressure 90/50 mmHg.\n\nJugular venous pressure is elevated.\n\nA respiratory system examination reveals normal vesicular breath sounds. A cardiovascular system examination reveals distant and muffled heart sounds.\n\nWhat next investigation would help in the emergency management of this patient?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Jugular venous pressure is elevated. Mild pitting ankle oedema is noted bilaterally.","Investigations reveal:","Within a few hours, the patient suddenly becomes very breathless and unwell.","She is noted to have the following observations:","She is highly distressed, using accessory muscles of breathing and leaning forward in her bed.","Jugular venous pressure is elevated.","What next investigation would help in the emergency management of this patient?","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"Jugular venous pressure is elevated.","explanation":"This patient was admitted with likely pericarditis (secondary to an autoimmune connective tissue disorder), with effusion that progressively deteriorated to pericardial tamponade. Hypotension, tachycardia, raised jugular venous pressure, clear lung auscultation, muffled heart sounds and low-voltage ECG complexes are all suggestive of pericardial tamponade, which is a medical emergency, and the patient needs a point-of-care echocardiography followed by pericardiocentesis."},{"id":"18389","category":"Critical care medicine","stem":"A 20-year-old woman presented to the emergency department with a painful foot, following a simple fall. While being examined by an emergency doctor, she became agitated. An X-ray of her ankle and foot was normal. She then suddenly developed shortness of breath.\n\nOn examination, she was frightened and distressed. Besides a heart rate of 120 beats per minute, her cardiorespiratory examination was normal. An ECG and chest X-ray were also normal.\n\nHer ABGs were as follows:\n\nWhat is the most likely cause of her breathlessness?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"This scenario demonstrates a case of psychogenic hyperventilation. There is no A-a gradient in ABGs, excluding other pulmonary/respiratory causes of breathlessness. This patient also has a normal chest X-ray, which rules out pneumothorax as a possibility. Her ABGs show respiratory alkalosis suggestive of hyperventilation with a low PaCO2 level. The incidence of psychogenic hyperventilation among adults visiting the ER is around 0.3%. Its symptoms include dizziness, paresthesia, and anxiety. Breathlessness is a common presentation with hyperventilation, due to an increase in respiratory rate. The low PaCO2 as seen in this patients ABGs is due to an increased respiratory rate, causing respiratory alkalosis and a pH of 7.53. Given her anxiety, the only plausible option here is psychogenic hyperventilation."},{"id":"11358","category":"Critical care medicine","stem":"A 55-year-old woman with a past medical history of type 2 diabetes and hypertension has been having a burning sensation on passing urine along with right-sided loin pain for the past week. Her GP had requested a urine analysis, which was positive for nitrites and leucocytes, and had prescribed her oral nitrofurantoin tablets one day previously. However, the patients husband noted that she had become very unwell with high-grade fever, associated with chills and rigours, so he brought her to the emergency department (ED) as she had become drowsy. Her current medications include metformin, empagliflozin, gliclazide, amlodipine, ramipril, aspirin and atorvastatin. Her recent weight was noted to be 70 kg.\n\nThe ED doctors diagnosed the patient with severe sepsis due to urosepsis/pyelonephritis and instigated the sepsis six care bundle promptly.\n\nExamination findings on admission to ED resuscitation:\n\nOxygen saturation on breathing air was 89%; with 40% oxygen supplementation, saturation increased to 95%.\n\nCapillary refill time 6s (< than 2s); Jugular venous pressure was not elevated.\n\nNo dependent oedema was seen, but mottling of the skin was noted over both legs.\n\nA respiratory system examination revealed normal vesicular breath sounds on both sides.\n\nA cardiovascular system examination revealed normal heart sounds; tachycardic.\n\nThe ED team has managed to administer 2500 ml of crystalloids to the patient in the past 60 minutes and has also managed to insert a triple-lumen venous catheter in the right internal jugular vein and a urinary catheter. Two sets of blood cultures and a urine culture have been taken. They have also started empiric meropenem 500mg QDS as per the local trust guideline.\n\nYou review her and note that the latest central venous pressure (CVP) (after the 2500 ml of crystalloids) is 10 mmHg (normal 8-12 mmHg) and the blood pressure is 76/40 mmHg. The urine output in the last hour is 10ml only, and the urine is noted to be purulent. The patient still has a GCS of 13, and oxygen saturation is 95% on 40% FiO2.\n\nUrgent laboratory results so far:\n\nWhat would be the most appropriate next step in management?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","The ED doctors diagnosed the patient with severe sepsis due to urosepsis/pyelonephritis and instigated the sepsis six care bundle promptly.","GCS\t13/15\nPulse rate\t130/min\nBlood pressure\t70/40 mm Hg\nRespiratory rate\t25/min\nTemperature\t40oC","Capillary refill time 6s (< than 2s); Jugular venous pressure was not elevated.","No dependent oedema was seen, but mottling of the skin was noted over both legs.","Urgent laboratory results so far:","What would be the most appropriate next step in management?","Intravenous furosemide has no role in this acute scenario and is likely to be detrimental.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"This patient is in florid septic shock with refractory hypotension (from likely urosepsis) despite having received 30 ml/kg of crystalloids within an hour. She also has organ dysfunction, including drowsiness and low urine output. However, her CVP is normal and further intravenous fluid resuscitation alone is unlikely to improve her blood pressure, and the use of vasopressors like norepinephrine is warranted to maintain a mean arterial pressure (MAP) more than or equal to 65mmHg."},{"id":"10813","category":"Critical care medicine","stem":"A 44-year-old man was admitted with dyspnoea, cough, and severe pleuritic chest pain for 4 days. He had a past medical history of Diabetes mellitus type 2 (on metformin 1g BD and dapagliflozin 10mg OD), dyslipidaemia (on simvastatin 40 mg ON) and obesity (BMI 42kg/m2). He underwent knee arthroscopy and ligament repair 2 weeks ago and had been on PRN co-codamol.\n\nOn arrival, his observations were: respiratory rate 21/min, blood pressure 120/80 mmHg, oxygen saturation 95% on room air, temperature 38oC, heart rate 110 bpm.\n\nHis ECG showed sinus tachycardia, and a chest X-ray revealed right basal consolidation. He was commenced on antibiotics (amoxicillin and clarithromycin) and intravenous fluids.\n\nAs he was waiting for a CT-pulmonary angiogram (CT-PA), he suddenly became more breathless, sweaty and clammy, and his chest pain worsened. A repeat ECG showed a new right bundle branch block with HR 140 bpm. The observations are: blood pressure 65/50 mmHg, heart rate 140 bpm, respiratory rate 30/min, temperature 37.8oC, oxygen saturation 81%.\n\nWhat would be your immediate management of this patient whilst CT-PA is awaited?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","His ECG showed sinus tachycardia, and a chest X-ray revealed right basal consolidation. He was commenced on antibiotics (amoxicillin and clarithromycin) and intravenous fluids.","His bloods revealed:","What would be your immediate management of this patient whilst CT-PA is awaited?","Submassive PE is defined as the presence of right heart strain and myocardial injury and a large clot burden whilst the BP is maintained in the normal range.","Thrombolysis should not be used as a first-line treatment in non-massive PE.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"within 1 hour","explanation":"Massive pulmonary embolus (PE) can be diagnosed by CT-PA and/or echocardiography, and imaging should be performed within 1 hour. Systolic BP <90 mmHg or a drop of >40 mmHg for more than 15 mins with no alternative explanation indicates a diagnosis of massive PE."},{"id":"10168","category":"Critical care medicine","stem":"A 56-year-old woman was found unconscious at her house and brought in by ambulance in an unconscious state. On arrival, she was drowsy with a blood pressure of 80/50, a pulse rate of 54 BPM and a temperature of 25oC. She had a background history of type 2 diabetes mellitus, chronic kidney disease, stroke, ischaemic heart disease and hypothyroidism. While moving her to the resuscitation room, she became unresponsive and without a pulse. Her ECG showed ventricular fibrillation (VF). CPR was started, and a defibrillator shock was given three times after every 2-minute cycle, along with adrenaline every 3 minutes.\n\nWhat is the next step?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","This patient is likely to have a myxoedema coma. However, she is in cardiac arrest due to severe hypothermia.","Hypothermia is diagnosed in any patient with a core temperature < 35oC, or where measurement is unavailable, a history of exposure to cold, or when the trunk feels cold.","The staging system is used to estimate core temperature.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"This patient is likely to have a myxoedema coma. However, she is in cardiac arrest due to severe hypothermia.","explanation":"This patient is likely to have a myxoedema coma. However, she is in cardiac arrest due to severe hypothermia."},{"id":"18388","category":"Critical care medicine","stem":"A 60-year-old woman with a known case of myasthenia gravis was admitted to the acute care unit with myasthenic crisis and was started on therapy accordingly.\n\nOn day four of her illness, she was found to have the following biochemistry results:\n\nWhat is the recommended next step in the management of her hyponatraemia?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Free water restriction is not needed in this case, and is a treatment for a syndrome of inappropriate antidiuretic hormone (SIADH).","The patient does not exhibit any neurological symptoms of hyponatremia like drowsiness or seizures; therefore, hypertonic saline, which is used in symptomatic hyponatremia, is not indicated.","Normal saline and oral rehydration therapy can be used in cases of true hyponatremia, which is not the case here.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"Treatment for myasthenic crisis is intravenous immunoglobulin (IVIG). IVIG therapy results in post-infusional hyperproteinemia or an increase in the non-aqueous phase of plasma. IVIG is thought to cause pseudohyponatraemia rather than true hyponatraemia."},{"id":"13107","category":"Critical care medicine","stem":"A 45-year-old Indian man is admitted to the acute medicine unit with progressive deterioration and drowsiness. His detailed past medical history is unclear, as he immigrated to the UK about a year ago; his wife states that he was diagnosed with peripheral neuropathy secondary to type 2 diabetes mellitus 3 years ago. She adds that the patient has had difficulty walking recently, which his general practitioner (GP) attributed to peripheral neuropathy from long-standing diabetes. His current medication list from his GP includes thiamine, Vitamin B complex, pregabalin, and metformin.\n\nAn examination reveals the following results:\n\nGlasgow coma scale: eye opening 3; Motor response-5; verbal response-4 (12/15).\n\nHe has a pulse rate of 120 beats per minute and a blood pressure of 110/80 mmHg.\n\nThe patient has a respiratory rate of 40 breaths per minute with abdominothoracic breathing. His oxygen saturation on air is 97% and his temperature is 37oC.\n\nCapillary blood glucose is 6 mmol/L. Jugular venous pressure is not elevated.\n\nHis respiratory system reveals normal breath sounds on both sides; no rhonchi or crackles are present. A cardiovascular system examination reveals normal heart sounds. The abdomen is soft with no tenderness, and there are active bowel sounds. No dependent oedema is present.\n\nHis legs and left-hand pictures are shown below:\n\nHis arterial blood gas on-air is as follows:\n\nHis chest X-ray is normal.\n\nWhat is the most likely diagnosis?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Glasgow coma scale: eye opening 3; Motor response-5; verbal response-4 (12/15).","He has a pulse rate of 120 beats per minute and a blood pressure of 110/80 mmHg.","Capillary blood glucose is 6 mmol/L. Jugular venous pressure is not elevated.","His legs and left-hand pictures are shown below:","Image source: author","His arterial blood gas on-air is as follows:","Investigation\tResult\tNormal range\npH\t7.29\t7.35  7.45\npCO2\t14 kPa\t4.6  6.4 kPa\npO2\t9 kPa\t11.0  14.4 kPa\nLactate\t2 mmol/L\t0.5  2.2 mmol/L\nBicarbonate\t38 mmol/L\t22-28 mmol/L","His chest X-ray is normal.","What is the most likely diagnosis?","CCF is unlikely given normal lung auscultation, no dependent oedema, relatively normal oxygen saturation, and a normal chest x-ray.","IPF and ARDS are unlikely given clear lung auscultation, normal oxygen saturation, and chest x-ray.","PE is unlikely to cause severe type-2 respiratory failure as seen here.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"IPF and ARDS are unlikely given clear lung auscultation, normal oxygen saturation, and chest x-ray.","explanation":"This patient is in type-2 (hypercapnoeic) respiratory failure with chronic decompensated respiratory acidosis. The clinical images show features of severe muscle wasting disease in the legs and hand (clawing and wasting of the intrinsic hand muscles are evident), and the patient likely has a degenerative neuromuscular disease, possibly motor neuron disease. He is tachypnoeic and has an abdomino-thoracic breathing pattern with clear lung auscultation and normal oxygen saturation consistent with ventilatory failure."},{"id":"10809","category":"Critical care medicine","stem":"A 25-year-old usually fit and well man was admitted on acute medical intake with a 2-day history of headache, nausea and confusion. His next of kin reported that the patient had been drinking 5-6 litres of water a day over the last 2 weeks as part of a healthy lifestyle plan he started following recently.\n\nHis initial observations were: heart rate 60bpm, blood pressure 120/80 mmHg, temperature 36.8oC, respiratory rate 20/min, oxygen saturation 100% on room air, Glasgow Coma Scale 14/15.\n\nWhilst waiting to be seen, he had 2 brief episodes of tonic-clonic seizures lasting 30-45 seconds each.\n\nHow would you manage his hyponatraemia at this stage?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Whilst waiting to be seen, he had 2 brief episodes of tonic-clonic seizures lasting 30-45 seconds each.","Investigation\tResult\tNormal range\nSodium\t108 mmol/L\t135 - 145 mmol/L\nPotassium\t3.4 mmol/L\t3.5 - 5.3 mmol/L\nUrea\t1.7 mmol/L\t2.5 - 7.1 mmol/L\nCreatinine\t78 µmol/L\t59-104 µmol/L","How would you manage his hyponatraemia at this stage?","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"How would you manage his hyponatraemia at this stage?","explanation":"Severe symptomatic hyponatraemia (both acute and chronic) should be managed with an IV infusion of 150mls of 3% NaCl over 20 minutes. Serum sodium should be repeated 20 minutes later. This treatment can be repeated twice or until a target of 5 mmol/L increase in serum sodium concentration is achieved. Patients should be managed in a closely monitored environment."},{"id":"11098","category":"Critical care medicine","stem":"You have been asked to review a 72-year-old man for the evaluation of shortness of breath that started suddenly 2 hours ago. He was admitted to the hospital 7 days ago with an acute ischaemic stroke leading to right-sided weakness and dysphasia, for which he was managed conservatively, as he presented out of the thrombolysis window. Post-stroke, with conservative treatment, he showed a good clinical response. He has a background history of hypertension, type 2 diabetes, and dyslipidaemia.\n\nThe patient complains of central chest pain associated with severe shortness of breath. On examination, he is sitting upright, looks unwell and diaphoretic, with a blood pressure of 80/50 mmHg, a pulse rate of 114, a temperature of 37.6oC, respiratory rate 40/min, and SpO2 of 72% on room air. His jugular venous pulse is raised, and his peripheries are cold and cyanosed. His cardiovascular examination revealed an S3 gallop at the 4th intercostal space. His lungs are clear.\n\nHis ECG shows sinus tachycardia. His CT pulmonary angiogram confirms the presence of saddle pulmonary embolism.\n\nWhat is the next management step for this patient?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","His ECG shows sinus tachycardia. His CT pulmonary angiogram confirms the presence of saddle pulmonary embolism.","What is the next management step for this patient?","Eswaradass, P.V., Dey, S., Singh, D. and Hill, M.D., 2018. Pulmonary embolism in ischemic stroke. Canadian Journal of Neurological Sciences, 45(3), pp.343-345.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"What is the next management step for this patient?","explanation":"This patient has a massive pulmonary embolism and is likely at high risk of death if left untreated. Pulmonary embolism (PE) is the most common cause of death 2-4 weeks post-stroke, and in the setting of concurrent acute stroke, hypoxia resulting from PE can worsen existing cerebral ischemia."},{"id":"11363","category":"Critical care medicine","stem":"A 25-year-old man is brought to the emergency department by his partner in an unresponsive state after he collapsed when he was eating breakfast. The patient had been complaining of a severe headache, which had started abruptly the previous day while watching television, and he felt as if he had been hit on the head. He had then taken some co-codamol (paracetamol with codeine) but continued to suffer from a persistent headache and neck stiffness. He had also experienced two episodes of vomiting (which he attributed to the co-codamol).\n\nHe did not have any past medical history of note.\n\nHis father is undergoing treatment for chronic renal disease due to polycystic kidney disease, and his mother suffers from chronic asthma.\n\nOn examination, he has a Glasgow Coma Scale of 10/15. His pulse rate is 42/min, and his respiratory rate is 16/min. His oxygen saturation on 4 litres of supplemental oxygen through a facemask is 99%. His blood pressure is 150/90 (mean arterial pressure -110 mmHg). An electrocardiogram reveals sinus bradycardia.\n\nHis CT brain is shown below:\n\nWhich medication is necessary for preventing serious neurological deterioration in this patient?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","He did not have any past medical history of note.","His father is undergoing treatment for chronic renal disease due to polycystic kidney disease, and his mother suffers from chronic asthma.","Investigation\tResult\tNormal range\nCapillary blood glucose\t6 mmol/L\t<7.8mmol/L\nUrea\t9 mmol/L\t3.2 - 7.4 mmol/L\nCreatinine\t180 µmol/L\t49-90 µmol/L","His CT brain is shown below:","[Authors own image]","Which medication is necessary for preventing serious neurological deterioration in this patient?","This patients history and renal impairment are suggestive of an autosomal dominant polycystic kidney disease, and his SAH may be of aneurysmal aetiology.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"within 48 hours of the diagnosis","explanation":"The CT brain scan shows acute subarachnoid haemorrhage (SAH), and nimodipine should be started within 48 hours of the diagnosis, prophylactically to prevent/reduce the devastating effects of vasospasm and cerebral infarction and improve outcomes in SAH. It must be given orally or enterally preferentially. In circumstances where enteral/oral nimodipine cannot be given or there are concerns of inadequate drug absorption, the use of intravenous nimodipine may be considered and should occur only after discussion with a neurosurgeon or intensive care consultant, as it can precipitate profound hypotension and worsen existing cerebral ischaemia. Its given for 21 days after the bleed."},{"id":"11360","category":"Critical care medicine","stem":"A 55-year-old man presents with sudden-onset right-sided upper and lower limb weakness. His past medical history includes hypertension, non-valvular atrial fibrillation, and hypercholesterolemia. His current medications include dabigatran, ramipril, atorvastatin, and metoprolol.\n\nExamination reveals a Glasgow Coma Scale of 15/15. Right upper and lower limb MRC muscle power grading is 3/5. Left upper and lower limb MRC muscle power grading is 5/5. Dysarthria is noted.\n\nHis CT brain scan is shown below:\n\nWhat is the diagnosis?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","McGurgan, I.J., Ziai, W.C., Werring, D.J., Salman, R.A.S. and Parry-Jones, A.R., 2021. Acute intracerebral haemorrhage: diagnosis and management. Practical Neurology, 21(2), pp.128-136.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"This patient has had an acute left-sided intracerebral haemorrhage as seen in the CT brain, showing parietal-temporal lobe haematoma with surrounding oedema causing the clinical right hemiparesis; the patient is on dabigatran and may need reversal of its anticoagulant effect if there is progressive clinical deterioration."},{"id":"8895","category":"Diabetes and endocrine medicine","stem":"A 71-year-old man is admitted with cramps and twitching, which have deteriorated over the last 2 weeks. He has a history of type 2 diabetes and hypertension, and denies any change in bowel habit. He was taking metformin and recently started sitagliptin. He also takes bendrofluazide, ramipril, and omeprazole for gastro-oesophageal reflux disease (GORD).\n\nOn examination, trousseau’s sign was positive, his pulse was 88 bpm, and his blood pressure was 128/88 mmHg.\n\nHis investigations revealed:\n\nWhich of the following would you request?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","The FDA released a warning regarding the potential impact of PPIs on hypomagnesaemia back in 2005.","Florentin, M. and Elisaf, M.S. (2012) Proton pump inhibitor-induced hypomagnesemia: A new challenge. World Journal of Nephrology, 1(6), p.151.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"This patient has low calcium and lowish phosphate, and a just slightly high PTH concentration, which is rather inappropriate for this level of hypocalcaemia. This does suggest hypoparathyroidism, with the likely cause of this being hypomagnesaemia, probably due to PPI treatment. PPI therapy is associated with hypomagnesaemia due to inhibition of magnesium uptake in the small bowel. PPIs may also inhibit calcium uptake, but their effect is potentially more profound through inhibiting PTH release from parathyroid cells through interference with calcium-sensing receptors."},{"id":"6421","category":"Diabetes and endocrine medicine","stem":"A 71-year-old woman was admitted with a 2-day history of increasing fatigue and decreasing level of consciousness. She had otherwise been well. She had type 2 diabetes for which she was being treated with metformin 500 mg twice daily, empagliflozin 10 mg daily, ramipril 10 mg daily, and atorvastatin 10 mg daily.\n\nOn examination, she had a temperature of 38 oC, a blood pressure of 100/70 mmHg and a pulse of 100 beats per minute with a respiratory rate of 28 breaths per minute. Her Glasgow Coma Scale score was 12. There was nothing of note on abdominal, respiratory, neurological or cardiovascular examination. Results revealed:\n\nWhich of the following is the likely cause of her presentation?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Plewa MC, Bryant M, King-Thiele R. Euglycemic Diabetic Ketoacidosis. [Updated 2020 Apr 30]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2020 Jan-.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"This patient has developed severe metabolic acidosis as suggested by the low pH and low bicarbonate with some respiratory compensation. The ketones are high, which is highly relevant here, particularly as the lactate is only modestly high and does not suggest lactic acidosis. A good-going lactic acidosis would be above 5. Also, the glucose is only modestly elevated. This fits the picture of a drug-induced ketoacidosis due to the SGLT-2 inhibitor, empagliflozin. Whilst a very effective diabetic medication, all SGLT-2 inhibitors have been rarely implicated in euglycaemic or modestly hyperglycaemic ketoacidosis, an effect of their mechanism of action relying on urinary glucose excretion. Often, illness, fasting, and vomiting exacerbate ketosis."},{"id":"8097","category":"Diabetes and endocrine medicine","stem":"A 50-year-old woman is admitted with a 1-week history of deteriorating lethargy, vomiting, and fatigue. A short synacthen test reveals a peak cortisol response of 230 nmol/L (>450) 30 mins after synacthen. She is treated with hydrocortisone 10 mg twice daily and has a good response.\n\nWhich of the following should she also receive before discharge?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","All patients with a diagnosis of hypoadrenalism should be counselled on the recognition and management of acute hypoadrenalism and receive an emergency hydrocortisone kit.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"All patients with a diagnosis of hypoadrenalism should be counselled on the recognition and management of acute hypoadrenalism and receive an emergency hydrocortisone kit.","explanation":"All patients with a diagnosis of hypoadrenalism should be counselled on the recognition and management of acute hypoadrenalism and receive an emergency hydrocortisone kit."},{"id":"11332","category":"Diabetes and endocrine medicine","stem":"You review a 19-year-old woman who is referred to the Medical Assessment Unit by the GP, querying Diabetic ketoacidosis (DKA). She has been diagnosed with T1DM for 6 years. Her glycaemic control is poor with the most recent HbA1c of 100 mmol/mol(<48). She is currently on a basal-bolus regimen with Novorapid 5 units three times daily and Tresiba 12 units once daily. Her weight is 40 kg, height is 158cm, and BMI is 16 kg/m2.\n\nInvestigations reveal the following:\n\nHer pregnancy test is negative.\n\nWhat is the likely diagnosis?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"The key points here are the very low BMI associated with type-1 diabetes plus the elevated ketones. In the absence of acidaemia, as reflected by the normal pH of 7.37, one should consider an eating disorder in this young woman. This is not uncommon in younger patients and should be suspected with very low BMI plus poor glycaemic control, which assists the individual in losing weight. Careful counselling and psychiatric support are often required for such patients."},{"id":"14114","category":"Diabetes and endocrine medicine","stem":"A 25-year-old woman is admitted to the acute medicine unit with a general worsening of her condition with dizziness upon standing and nausea. She states that this all happened 3 days ago, after a sudden onset of headache associated with double vision.\n\nHer past medical history has been unremarkable except for a recent 3-month history of reduced visual acuity, for which she was seen by an optometrist. She had been prescribed glasses, but there was no significant improvement.\n\nOn examination, the patient is alert and oriented but very lethargic. Her pulse rate is 115 beats per minute. She has a blood pressure of 70/40 mmHg, a respiratory rate of 22 breaths per minute, and an oxygen saturation on air of 99%. Her temperature is 37oC. Capillary refill time is 6 seconds. Jugular venous pressure is not elevated. No leg oedema is noted. Respiratory system examination reveals normal breath sounds on both sides. Cardiovascular system examination reveals normal heart sounds.\n\nThe abdomen is soft with no tenderness, and there are active bowel sounds.\n\nNeurological examination reveals no meningism signs; right superior temporal hemianopia is noted. Her cranial nerve exam is normal. No focal neurological deficits were noted in the limbs.\n\nInvestigation results are as follows:\n\nWhat is the most likely diagnosis?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","The abdomen is soft with no tenderness, and there are active bowel sounds.","Investigation results are as follows:","What is the most likely diagnosis?","Sepsis is unlikely with the history and normal WBC, ESR and CRP.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"This patient previously had a pituitary adenoma that suddenly bled inside, causing the sudden enlargement of the adenoma, causing diplopia, headache and visual field defect with associated hypopituitarism features (predominantly ACTH deficiency and secondary adrenal insufficiency causing hypotension, hypoglycaemia, lethargy, hyponatremia and hyperkalaemia)."},{"id":"11333","category":"Diabetes and endocrine medicine","stem":"A 24-year-old man with type 1 diabetes mellitus is admitted with diabetic ketoacidosis and has been on the DKA pathway for 10 hours. He is responding well to IV fluid and fixed-rate intravenous insulin infusion (FRIII). The most recent blood glucose is 8 mmol/L, blood ketone 1.0 mmol/L, and pH 7.32. His long-acting insulin (Lantus) is due now. The nurse asks you whether the DKA pathway can be discontinued and whether the Lantus insulin should be omitted due to the normal blood glucose level. She is worried that the patient will develop hypoglycaemia.\n\nWhat is the next step of management in this case?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","The Management of Diabetic Ketoacidosis in Adults* Revised March 2023.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"This patient is being treated for DKA and is recovering with the FRII. The protocols all indicate that the patient should receive their usual evening dose of long-acting insulin, and in our case, this would be in preparation for a switch to his usual oral agents too."},{"id":"8100","category":"Diabetes and endocrine medicine","stem":"A 70-year-old woman is referred to emergency admissions by her GP. She has been feeling fatigued for about 2 months, and her blood tests were normal. However, during a follow-up visit, her calcium was found to be 2.75 mmol/L (2.2-2.6 mmol/L), for which the GP referred her to acute medicine.\n\nThere was nothing else of note in her history other than tiredness, and she had put on roughly 3 kg in weight over the last year. She takes vitamin D supplements and sertraline 100 mg daily. There was nothing of note on examination, and her blood pressure was 132/70 mmHg. Other investigations on the clinical portal revealed a creatinine of 80 µmol/L (50-100), urea of 5.5 mmol/L (3-8), normal FBC, and PTH was 20.3 pmol/L (3-8) with a vitamin D of 70 nmol/L (>50). She had had a DEXA scan roughly one year ago with a nadir T score of –2.0.\n\nWhich of the following is the most appropriate approach to the management of this patient?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"This patient has mild primary hyperparathyroidism as revealed by the high calcium and raised PTH, and her fatigue is probably unrelated to this. Her vitamin D is fine. She can be conservatively managed according to the NIH criteria."},{"id":"3449","category":"Diabetes and endocrine medicine","stem":"You are called via the arrest bleep to a 43-year-old woman who is on the surgical ward. She had a laparoscopic cholecystectomy performed 2 days ago and has since had nausea and vomiting and has been receiving IV dextrose. It transpires that she had a fit for which the nursing staff requested the arrest team. She is now drowsy. Her past medical history is unremarkable, and U&E before surgery were reported to be within normal range.\n\nOn examination, she is drowsy with a GCS of 13. Her pulse is 88 bpm and blood pressure 132/88 mmHg with oxygen sats of 100% on air. There is no focal neurology, and her plantar responses are equivocal.\n\nOf note, her blood results reveal:\n\nWhich of the following is the most appropriate initial treatment for this patient?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Of note, her blood results reveal:","Which of the following is the most appropriate initial treatment for this patient?","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"Which of the following is the most appropriate initial treatment for this patient?","explanation":"This patient is likely to have hyponatraemic encephalopathy, which is life-threatening, and she has presented with a fit. Post-operative hyponatraemia is not uncommon and is likely to be due to a combination of SIADH, which develops in the post-op period and the infusion of inappropriate IVIs. The European Endocrine Society Guidelines on severe hyponatraemic encephalopathy recommend a rapid correction of sodium by approximately 5 mmol/L. This can ameliorate the cerebral oedema that underlies this disorder. It is believed that with severe or moderately severe symptoms, the risk of brain oedema outweighs the risk of osmotic demyelination syndrome."},{"id":"9412","category":"Diabetes and endocrine medicine","stem":"A 66-year-old man presented with a 3-day history of fatigue and generalised pain. He was a type-2 diabetic with an HbA1c of 7% (53 mmol/mol) and was receiving metformin, ramipril, and simvastatin. One month before admission, he underwent an endoscopy for dyspeptic symptoms, which revealed H. Pylori infection for which he was treated with clarithromycin, omeprazole, and amoxicillin. He did not smoke but drank 15-20 units of alcohol weekly.\n\nOn examination, he appeared unwell with a temperature of 37.8oC, a pulse of 110 bpm regular, and a blood pressure of 136/88 mmHg. There was proximal muscle tenderness and weakness.\n\nResults revealed the following:\n\nWhich of the following is the likely precipitant of this man’s rhabdomyolysis?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Results revealed the following:","Which of the following is the likely precipitant of this man’s rhabdomyolysis?","Lee, A.J. and Maddix, D.S., 2001. Rhabdomyolysis secondary to a drug interaction between simvastatin and clarithromycin. Annals of Pharmacotherapy, 35(1), pp.26-31.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"Which of the following is the likely precipitant of this man’s rhabdomyolysis?","explanation":"This patient presents acutely with rhabdomyolysis, and this is likely to have been precipitated by the co-prescription of clarithromycin with simvastatin. Simvastatin is metabolised by cytochrome CYP3A4, which is inhibited by macrolides, resulting in increased plasma concentrations of the statin and hence increased propensity to rhabdomyolysis. We should avoid the co-prescription of these agents and also other statins such as atorvastatin metabolised through this enzyme."},{"id":"7824","category":"Diabetes and endocrine medicine","stem":"You see a 40-year-old woman in the MAU after she was found by her mother in the house, unresponsive. She was noted to be hypoglycaemic by the ambulance staff and responded to glucose. She is now awake and conscious. The patient is 26 weeks pregnant in her first pregnancy and has a 15-year history of type 1 diabetes. She conceived through IVF. The patient is treated with a basal-bolus insulin regimen and has good glycaemic control, with a pre-pregnancy HbA1c of 42 mmol/mol (6%).\n\nWhich of the following would be a risk factor for severe hypoglycaemia in pregnancy in type-1 diabetes?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Which of the following would be a risk factor for severe hypoglycaemia in pregnancy in type-1 diabetes?","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"Which of the following would be a risk factor for severe hypoglycaemia in pregnancy in type-1 diabetes?","explanation":"The most serious risk factor for the development of severe, neuroglycopaenic hypoglycaemia in this patient would be impaired hypoglycaemic awareness. This would be a greater risk factor than a basal-bolus (qds) insulin regimen, as it is more about total daily dose rather than frequency. Other contributory factors include duration of diabetes and a pre-pregnancy HbA1c less than <6.5, with severe hypoglycaemia being more problematic in the first trimester."},{"id":"11328","category":"Diabetes and endocrine medicine","stem":"A 68-year-old man with type 2 diabetes of 5 years takes metformin 850 mg three times daily and gliclazide 160 mg twice daily. His fasting and preprandial plasma glucose levels are greater than 20 mmol/L. He attended his GP surgery for advice. His most recent HbA1C was 80 mmol/mol, and his blood sugar measurement was 23 mmol/L. He reported weight loss and lethargy, for which his GP referred him to the Medical Assessment Unit.\n\nOn examination, he is alert and communicating, his blood pressure of 135/80 mmHg and his examination is otherwise normal. Besides the glucose of 25 mmol/L, other laboratory results show:\n\nWhich of the following is the best management approach for this patient?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"As per NICE guidelines, consider starting both NPH and short-acting insulin (particularly if the person's HbA1c is 75 mmol/mol (9.0%) or higher, administered either separately or as a pre-mixed (biphasic) human insulin preparation."},{"id":"7819","category":"Diabetes and endocrine medicine","stem":"A 28-year-old woman presents to acute medicine with a 2-day history of feeling unwell with polyuria. She has a glucose of 22 mmol/L and a pH of 7.2 and high ketones. She is unaware of any specific family history of diabetes of note.\n\nOn examination, she is generally well with a BMI of 32 kg/m2.\n\nWhat would be the most useful investigation for this patient?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"The patient presents with diabetic ketoacidosis, and the most important investigation would be the demonstration of autoimmunity as reflected by anti-GAD or anti-islet cell antibodies. Autoantibodies would be expected in roughly 80% of individuals with type-1 diabetes and would, of course, dictate longer-term insulin initiation. HbA1c is not that relevant in this acute setting and adds little to the management. Rarely, MODY can present like this, but this patient does not have anything to suggest this other than the raised BMI, and it is relevant that even in obese patients, DKA can occur."},{"id":"3378","category":"Diabetes and endocrine medicine","stem":"A 26-year-old woman is reviewed in the clinic. She has a 10-year history of type 1 diabetes and admits to frequently missing insulin doses. Her current medication includes insulin glargine 42 units at night and Novorapid 12 units before each meal. On examination, her BMI is 21 kg/m2 and her blood pressure is 105/65 mmHg.\n\nInvestigations reveal:\n\nWhich of the following is a feature of urine ketone testing?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","DKA Guideline amended v2 June 2021.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"Urine ketone testing measures acetoacetate in urine, which is produced by the metabolism of beta-hydroxybutyrate. Ketonuria persists despite the correction of acidaemia in patients with ketoacidosis and does not correlate with the degree of acidosis. Ketonuria is not a marker of absolute insulin deficiency and may occur as a normal response to exercise or fasting."},{"id":"3786","category":"Diabetes and endocrine medicine","stem":"A 60-year-old woman is admitted with a history of being acutely unwell, diarrhoea, and, more recently, confusion. She gives no other history of note and is agitated on admission. Her husband informs you that she has little of note in her history but has become increasingly agitated and has lost weight over the last month.\n\nExamination reveals that she is confused with a GCS of 14. She has a BMI of 18 kg/m2, a pulse of 120 beats per minute, irregular, blood pressure of 110/65 mmHg and a temperature of 38.9oC. She has an obvious goitre with an audible bruit.\n\nWhich of the following is the most appropriate initial treatment for this patient?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"at least 1 hour before the use of iodides","explanation":"This patient appears to be developing thyroid storm as revealed by a temperature, agitation, confusion, atrial fibrillation, and goitre. We are not provided with the TFTs as these will often take some time to process, even if asked for acutely. In this case, the IV beta-blockers would be the most appropriate approach as a treatment for atrial fibrillation, and these also prevent the peripheral conversion of T4 to T3. Either oral propylthiouracil or carbimazole should be given, but both will take 2 hours to affect the production of thyroid hormone, and of course, neither will prevent the release of stored hormone. THIONAMIDE must be given at least 1 hour before the use of iodides, which block the release of stored hormone. The patient should also receive IV steroids."},{"id":"3381","category":"Diabetes and endocrine medicine","stem":"A 20-year-old woman is admitted to A&E with abdominal pain, nausea and vomiting. She has a 5-year history of type 1 diabetes with poor adherence to her therapy. Her current insulin regimen comprises insulin glargine and Novorapid via a basal-bolus regimen. On examination, she is dehydrated and breathing deeply, her blood pressure is 98/66 mmHg, and her pulse is 105 beats per minute.\n\nInvestigations reveal the following results:\n\nWhich of the following is a feature of the pathophysiology of diabetic ketoacidosis?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Calimag, A.P.P., Chlebek, S., Lerma, E.V. and Chaiban, J.T., 2023. Diabetic ketoacidosis. Disease-a-Month, 69(3), p.101418.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"Diabetic ketoacidosis (DKA) is an extension of the normal fasting state. Hepatic glucose production rises rapidly over the first 2 to 4 hours following insulin withdrawal, reaching a plateau after around 4 hours. These changes correlate with the initial acute rise in glucagon concentrations, with other counter-regulatory hormones being little affected initially."},{"id":"3530","category":"Diabetes and endocrine medicine","stem":"A 52-year-old woman is admitted with an intracranial bleed. She underwent clipping of a cerebral arterial aneurysm and was well the following morning. The following biochemistry is noted post-operatively: (Normal ranges: sodium 135-145, potassium 3.5 -5, Urea 3-8, Creatinine 50-100).\n\nOn day 4, she was commenced on a fluid restriction of 1 litre per day. The following were noted at that stage: Plasma osmolality 258 mosmol/L (275-305), urine osmolality 688 mosmol/L with urine sodium 84 mmol/L.\n\nWhich of the following is the most likely diagnosis to explain the hyponatraemia?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"SIADH. There is no evidence of hypoadrenalism","explanation":"This patient has deteriorating hyponatraemia with an inappropriately elevated urine osmolality and urine sodium excretion (should be less than 20 mmol/L). The most likely diagnosis is therefore SIADH. There is no evidence of hypoadrenalism. Diabetes insipidus would produce excessive fluid loss with hypernatraemia. Fluid overload is a potential diagnosis, yet we are informed that the patient underwent fluid restriction."},{"id":"3380","category":"Diabetes and endocrine medicine","stem":"A 21-year-old woman with a 10-year history of type-1 diabetes has a most recent Hba1c of 61 mmol/mol (< 55 ) and is admitted to A&E following an overdose of her basal insulin. On examination, she is conscious but pale and sweaty, her blood pressure is 96/66 mmHg, her pulse is 135 beats per minute, and her plasma glucose is 1.8 mmol/L.\n\nAt what plasma glucose level would you expect significant autonomic counter-regulatory responses to develop in patients with type-1 diabetes?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Sprague JE, Arbeláez AM. Glucose counterregulatory responses to hypoglycemia. Pediatr Endocrinol Rev. 2011 Sep;9(1):463-73; quiz 474-5. PMID: 22783644; PMCID: PMC3755377.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"Autonomic counter-regulatory responses, including beta-adrenergic stimulation, and catecholamine secretion, commence at a threshold plasma glucose level ≤ of 3.9 mmol/L in non-diabetic individuals and often occur at a lower level in patients with diabetes (especially well-controlled diabetics), which means that adrenergic symptoms of hypoglycemia do not appear until the blood glucose drops to the lowered threshold that elicits the epinephrine response. This change in epinephrine response does not appear to be related to a structural abnormality of the adrenal medullae since diabetic patients with defective epinephrine response to hypoglycaemia have normal epinephrine responses to other stimuli such as exercise, standing or a meal."},{"id":"9427","category":"Diabetes and endocrine medicine","stem":"You are called to see a 42-year-old woman who has become particularly confused. She was admitted three days prior following an accident on her bike and had sustained a cerebral contusion. This did not require any neurosurgical intervention. On examination, she was drowsy with a GCS of 13 and bilateral upgoing plantars, but no focal neurology. Her pulse is 68 beats per minute with a blood pressure of 128/80 mmHg. Oxygen saturations are 99% on air.\n\nHer blood results reveal the following:\n\nWhich of the following would be the most appropriate initial treatment for this patient?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Her blood results reveal the following:","Investigation\tResult\tNormal range\nSodium\t118 mmol/L\t134-144 mmol/L\nPotassium\t3.8 mmol/L\t3.5-5.5 mmol/L\nUrea\t4.5 mmol/L\t3-8 mmol/L\nCreatinine\t80 µmol/L\t50-100 µmol/L\nGlucose\t4.8 mmol/L\t3.5-5.5 mmol/L","Which of the following would be the most appropriate initial treatment for this patient?","Steroids will not help in this scenario despite the cerebral oedema. The patient does not have hypoadrenalism as reflected by normal potassium and blood pressure.","Hyponatremia Treatment & Management. Updated: Aug 18, 2022. Author: Seyed Mehrdad Hamrahian, MD; Chief Editor: Vecihi Batuman, MD, FASN.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"urgent treatment is required","explanation":"This patient appears to have developed a hyponatraemic encephalopathy associated with severe and acute hyponatraemia. This seems likely due to either SIADH or cerebral salt wasting. In this scenario, the acute development of hyponatraemia results in cerebral oedema associated with an osmotic influx of water into the brain cells and swamping of the counter-regulatory sodium-potassium pump. The resulting cerebral oedema is life-threatening and manifests as headache, drowsiness, seizure and potentially death. Therefore, urgent treatment is required, and guidance recommends a rapid increase in sodium by approximately 5 mmol/L through the use of 150 ml boluses of 3% hypertonic saline."},{"id":"3784","category":"Diabetes and endocrine medicine","stem":"An 81-year-old man is admitted acutely with a 1-week history of feeling increasingly unwell and weak. He has a history of type-2 diabetes for which he takes metformin 1g bd and gliclazide 80 mg bd. His last HbA1c was 101 mmol/mol. He also takes ramipril and simvastatin.\n\nOn examination, he appears dehydrated and unwell. His temperature is 37 oC, blood pressure 116/70 mmHg, and a pulse of 102 beats per minute. Oxygen saturation is 98% on air, and he has a respiratory rate of 22/min.\n\nBlood results reveal:\n\nWhich of the following is the likely diagnosis?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Blood results reveal:","Which of the following is the likely diagnosis?","The most likely diagnosis is HHS as plasma osmolality 367 mosmol/L (2*155 + 20.5 + 37.2 = 367.7) with glucose above 33, bicarbonate above 15 and a pH >7.3. A trace of ketones may be noted (<3).","JBDS The Management of Hyperosmolar Hyperglycaemic State (HHS) in Adults* February 2022.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"The most likely diagnosis is HHS as plasma osmolality 367 mosmol/L (2*155 + 20.5 + 37.2 = 367.7) with glucose above 33, bicarbonate above 15 and a pH >7.3. A trace of ketones may be noted (<3).","explanation":"The most likely diagnosis is HHS as plasma osmolality 367 mosmol/L (2*155 + 20.5 + 37.2 = 367.7) with glucose above 33, bicarbonate above 15 and a pH >7.3. A trace of ketones may be noted (<3)."},{"id":"11331","category":"Diabetes and endocrine medicine","stem":"A 72-year-old woman presents with a 2-month history of deteriorating fatigue, feeling generally unwell, intermittent abdominal pain, weight loss of 2 stones, plus a 1-month history of polyuria, polydipsia, and thirst. She has no significant past medical history or family history of autoimmune disease. She is a non-smoker and is teetotal. She is not on any medication.\n\nOn examination, she appears jaundiced and unwell with a blood pressure of 90/65 mmHg, a pulse rate of 108 beats per minute, a respiratory rate of 22 breaths per minute, and Sats 97% on air. She also has a tender epigastrium, and the liver edge is palpable.\n\nWhat is the likely diagnosis?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Investigations show:","What is the likely diagnosis?","Diabetes UK: What is type 3c diabetes?","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"Diabetes UK: What is type 3c diabetes?","explanation":"The key factors here are that the patient has diabetic ketoacidosis (DKA) with high ketones, high glucose, and low pH, but the fact that she is also jaundiced suggests obstruction. So, the unifying diagnosis of pancreatic cancer-causing secondary diabetes, insulin deficiency, and DKA has to be considered."},{"id":"3600","category":"Diabetes and endocrine medicine","stem":"A 50-year-old man with type-2 diabetes treated with Novomix-30 16 units twice daily, empagliflozin 10 mg once daily, and sitagliptin 100 mg once daily is admitted with traumatic brain injury. He is managed in the ITU after neurosurgical intervention. He is being established on long-term enteral feed through a PEG starting at 8 a.m. and running for 16 hours. His HbA1C pre-admission was 65 mmols/mol (<55).\n\nWhat advice should be given regarding his diabetes management?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","It is not advisable to crush tablets and use them via NG tube as the efficacy may be lost. JBDS advises one of the three following options:","Glycaemic management during the inpatient enteral feeding of stroke patients with diabetes. Joint British Diabetes Societies (JBDS) for inpatient care, November 2019.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"It is not advisable to crush tablets and use them via NG tube as the efficacy may be lost. JBDS advises one of the three following options:","explanation":"It is not advisable to crush tablets and use them via NG tube as the efficacy may be lost. JBDS advises one of the three following options:"},{"id":"3990","category":"Diabetes and endocrine medicine","stem":"A 28-year-old woman presents with a 3-week history of flu-like symptoms followed by severe pain in her neck. Examination reveals a mild tremor and pulse of 90 bpm reg and tenderness to palpation of a mildly enlarged goitre.\n\nThyroid function tests reveal:\n\nThe best treatment to control her symptoms is:","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"This is thyroiditis. This is usually a temporary condition believed to be caused by a viral infection, usually associated with pain or tenderness in the thyroid gland, and sometimes also sore throat, flu-like symptoms and/or fever. Steroids and anti-thyroid drugs are not beneficial here. Her main symptoms are pain and tenderness, which should improve rapidly with anti-inflammatories. There is no evidence of tachycardia or overt hyperthyroidism, upon which a non-cardioselective B-blocker such as propranolol would be preferred."},{"id":"8094","category":"Diabetes and endocrine medicine","stem":"A 78-year-old man was admitted with a 2-day history of deteriorating abdominal pain and diarrhoea. He had a past medical history of polymyalgia rheumatica for which he took prednisolone 3 mg daily, reduced gradually over the last year from 20 mg daily. On examination, he had a temperature of 39 oC, a pulse of 110 bpm reg and a blood pressure of 120/74 mmHg. He had marked tenderness in the left iliac fossa with scant bowel sounds. CT abdomen revealed an acute diverticular abscess. He was treated with IV antibiotics and a surgical drainage is being planned.\n\nHow should his steroid dose be managed?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Society of Endocrinology (2019) Adrenal Crisis Information","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"This patient may well have adrenal suppression based on the cumulative dose of steroids. Therefore, the patient should receive IV hydrocortisone as above until he has made a recovery from the acute illness. Going forward, the patient can be investigated at a later stage to assess for adrenal recovery with a short synacthen test."},{"id":"3559","category":"Diabetes and endocrine medicine","stem":"A 42-year-old man is admitted with a 2-hour history of vomiting and central abdominal pain that radiates into the back. He has a history of type 2 diabetes and takes atorvastatin and metformin. On examination, his temperature is 37.8oC, his pulse is 102 beats per minute, regular, his blood pressure is 122/74 mmHg, and oxygen saturation is 96% on air. He has central abdominal guarding with no palpable masses.\n\nInvestigations reveal normal FBC, Normal U+Es, CRP 102 mg/dl (<5) and an amylase of 980 u/L (50-110) and glucose 10.8 mmol/L (3.5-5.5). His lipid profile shows cholesterol of 10.8 mmol/L and a triglyceride of 40.8 mmol/L (0.9-1.5).\n\nHe is considered to have a diagnosis of pancreatitis and is treated with IV fluids, NG tube suction and analgesia.\n\nWhich of the following is the most appropriate approach to the management of this patient?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","He is considered to have a diagnosis of pancreatitis and is treated with IV fluids, NG tube suction and analgesia.","Which of the following is the most appropriate approach to the management of this patient?","Apheresis (not haemodialysis) has been considered as an approach to the treatment of hypertriglyceridaemia in conjunction with pancreatitis, but there is no hard evidence to support this.","Ewald, N. and Kloer, H.U., 2012. Treatment options for severe hypertriglyceridemia (SHTG): the role of apheresis. Clinical research in cardiology supplements, 7(1), pp.31-35.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"Which of the following is the most appropriate approach to the management of this patient?","explanation":"This man has pancreatitis associated with severe hypertriglyceridaemia. He is receiving appropriate treatment for pancreatitis and requires a fixed-dose insulin regimen rather than an insulin sliding scale to reduce hypertriglyceridaemia. A higher dose of insulin is required to drive lipoprotein lipase activity and reduce triglycerides, which differs from a sliding scale where the insulin is tapered at low glucose. Even if this patient were to have normal glucose, then a fixed-dose insulin regimen would be the most appropriate treatment."},{"id":"7827","category":"Diabetes and endocrine medicine","stem":"A 25-year-old woman is admitted to the MAU with a 2-day history of feeling unwell and thirsty. She has a 15-year history of type 1 diabetes for which she takes a basal-bolus regimen. She has been struggling with control of her diabetes, whereas in her youth, her glycaemic control had been pretty good. She informs you that she has lost weight. However, her records reveal that over the last few years, she has been seen in the diabetes, ophthalmology and renal clinics with proliferative retinopathy, amenorrhea, and proteinuria.\n\nOn examination, she has a BMI of 17.8 kg/m2, a pulse of 90 bpm, apyrexial, a blood pressure of 120/80 mmHg and a sweet smell to her breath. Investigations confirm diabetic ketoacidosis. Her glucose is 23 mmol/L, pH 7.26 and her HbA1c is 89 mmol/mol.\n\nWhat is the likely diagnosis?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Diabetes UK: Eating disorders and diabetes.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"The history is of a decline in glycaemic control over the last few years associated with weight loss in a young T1DM female. Younger females are often concerned about weight gain with insulin therapy and omit doses for weight loss, and associated with this, there is disordered eating behaviour rather than anorexia. In conjunction with weight loss and poor glycaemic control, hypogonadotropic (secondary) hypogonadism would be expected. Addison’s would result in improved insulin sensitivity, with an increased likelihood for hypoglycaemia, and the blood pressure would maybe be lower. There is an increased risk of coeliac disease in people with T1DM, but the presentation is rather unusual for this, and one might expect features of malabsorption, diarrhoea, etc."},{"id":"14109","category":"Diabetes and endocrine medicine","stem":"A 25-year-old man was admitted to the acute medicine unit after he developed epistaxis and was noted to have a blood pressure of 220/130 mmHg in the emergency department.\n\nAfter local nasal treatment, the bleeding is controlled, and he remains well. He has received amlodipine 10 mg and is currently doing well except for fatigue.\n\nHe says that, in the past, he has seen his general practitioner for fatigue and was noted to have a blood pressure of 170/90 mmHg; he was also noted to have a blood potassium level of only 2.5, for which he was given oral potassium supplements and asked to closely monitor his blood pressure. He is a non-smoker and drinks beer once or twice a week only.\n\nOn examination, the patient is alert and oriented. He has a body mass index of 19 kg/m2. His pulse rate is 75 beats per minute, and he has a blood pressure of 190/100 mmHg. The patient has a respiratory rate of 12 breaths per minute with oxygen saturation on air of 99%. Temperature is 37oC, and jugular venous pressure is not elevated. Mild leg oedema is noted, and he has a normal skin exam.\n\nRespiratory system examination reveals normal breath sounds on both sides.\n\nCardiovascular system examination reveals normal heart sounds.\n\nThe abdomen is soft with no tenderness, and there are active bowel sounds, with no bruits.\n\nInvestigation results are as follows:\n\nWhat is the most likely diagnosis?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","A 25-year-old man was admitted to the acute medicine unit after he developed epistaxis and was noted to have a blood pressure of 220/130 mmHg in the emergency department.","After local nasal treatment, the bleeding is controlled, and he remains well. He has received amlodipine 10 mg and is currently doing well except for fatigue.","The abdomen is soft with no tenderness, and there are active bowel sounds, with no bruits.","Investigation results are as follows:","What is the most likely diagnosis?","This patient has severe chronic hypertension with left ventricular hypertrophy and persistent hypokalaemia and needs to be screened for Conn's syndrome (primary hyperaldosteronism).","In a young patient with hypertension, it is mandatory to assess secondary causes for hypertension, and primary hypertension should not be diagnosed without consideration of secondary causes.","Pheochromocytoma symptoms are typically paroxysmal, with hypertension usually associated with headache, sweating, and tachycardia.","Obstructive sleep apnoea is a recognised cause of secondary hypertension, but it is unlikely in this patient who has a low body mass index and persistent hypokalaemia.","Renal artery stenosis is a secondary cause for hypertension, but this is unlikely in this patient with a normal ultrasound abdomen, normal renal function, no bruits, and persistent hypokalaemia.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"This patient has severe chronic hypertension with left ventricular hypertrophy and persistent hypokalaemia and needs to be screened for Conn's syndrome (primary hyperaldosteronism).","explanation":"This patient has severe chronic hypertension with left ventricular hypertrophy and persistent hypokalaemia and needs to be screened for Conn's syndrome (primary hyperaldosteronism)."},{"id":"11329","category":"Diabetes and endocrine medicine","stem":"A 35-year-old woman was reviewed by her GP after being diagnosed by her GP one month ago. The GP started her on metformin, provided lifestyle advice and requested some laboratory tests 2 weeks ago. However, she continued to report fatigue and noted a further 2 KG weight loss, despite eating a lot. She had also noted her home BMs were typically 15-20, so the GP arranged admission. She is concerned about the weight loss, and the letter asks ‘if there is something else going on’, as her GP had also found her HbA1c to be 48 mmol/mol.\n\nOn examination, she looks well and has a BMI of 28 kg/m2, blood pressure of 122/80 mmHg, and pulse of 66/min. BM glucose is 17.8 mmol/L.\n\nHer laboratory results show:\n\nWhich of the following is the likely diagnosis here?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Useful investigations at diagnosis would be pancreatic auto-antibodies. In this case, with her young age, pancreatic Ca is a possibility, but most unlikely.","Diabetes UK - Types of diabetes.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"one has to pay attention to the rapid onset of symptoms","explanation":"An important point to note here is that an increase in HbA1c may not be detected until a few weeks after diagnosis of T1DM; thus, one has to pay attention to the rapid onset of symptoms, weight loss, and potential ketosis."},{"id":"3599","category":"Diabetes and endocrine medicine","stem":"An 18-year-old student presents to A&E after just arriving from a beach holiday. She uses an insulin pump to manage her type 1 diabetes. She started feeling unwell whilst flying back home. She denies any fever or gastrointestinal symptoms. She has judiciously used the pump and only took it off whilst she went swimming. She has even changed the injection site and needle in flight as her blood glucose was 20 mmol/L.\n\nOn admission to A&E her blood tests were as below:\n\nWhat is the likely reason for developing DKA?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"There are several reasons for worsening glycaemic control, and recognition of the cause is vital to early intervention. High temperatures and exposure to light increase the degradation of insulin to transformation products (deaminated insulin, covalent dimers, and higher oligomers) and increase the formation of fibrils, potentially causing a loss in biological potency."},{"id":"3782","category":"Diabetes and endocrine medicine","stem":"A 62-year-old man is admitted acutely with a 1-week history of feeling increasingly unwell and tired. He has a history of type-2 diabetes for which he takes metformin 1g bd and gliclazide 80mg bd. His last HbA1c was 98 mmol/mol\n\nOn examination, he appears dehydrated and unwell. His temperature is 37 oC, blood pressure 116/70 mmHg and a pulse of 102 bpm. Oxygen saturation is 98% on air, and he has a respiratory rate of 22/min.\n\nBlood results reveal:\n\nWhich of the following is the likely diagnosis?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Blood results reveal:","Which of the following is the likely diagnosis?","Joint British Diabetes Societies Inpatient Care Group: The Management of hyperosmolar hyperglycaemic state (HHS) in adults with diabetes, 2012.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"Which of the following is the likely diagnosis?","explanation":"The most likely diagnosis is HHS (patient is slightly acidotic with serum osmolality of 350) in a poorly controlled type 2 patient. Lactic acidosis with metformin is very rare, and patients usually have severe renal impairment and would not be expected at this patient's level of dehydration."},{"id":"20206","category":"Diabetes and endocrine medicine","stem":"A 78-year-old woman with type 2 diabetes mellitus managed with metformin 1g twice daily and saxagliptin 5mg once daily, is brought to the acute medical unit with a 5-day history of progressive confusion and weakness. She has been taking minimal oral fluids.\n\nOn examination, she is drowsy but rousable, with a heart rate of 110 beats per minute, blood pressure of 95/60 mmHg, a respiratory rate of 24/min, oxygen saturation 98% on room air and a temperature of 37.7 oC. She has dry mucous membranes and is clinically dehydrated. Capillary blood glucose is 52 mmol/L.\n\nBlood results are shown below:\n\nIntravenous fluid resuscitation with 0.9% sodium chloride has been commenced.\n\nWhat is the most appropriate approach to insulin therapy in this patient?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Blood results are shown below:","What is the most appropriate approach to insulin therapy in this patient?","JBDS guidelines for HHS recommend delaying insulin therapy until glucose is no longer falling with intravenous fluids alone.","In HHS, intravenous fluid replacement alone typically causes a significant fall in blood glucose due to rehydration and improved renal perfusion.","Early insulin administration risks an overly rapid fall in glucose and osmolality, increasing the risk of cerebral oedema.","When insulin is required, the recommended rate is 0.05 units/kg/hour (lower than the 0.1 units/kg/hour used in diabetic ketoacidosis).","Insulin should only be started if glucose is not falling or if significant ketonaemia develops.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"JBDS guidelines for HHS recommend delaying insulin therapy until glucose is no longer falling with intravenous fluids alone.","explanation":"JBDS guidelines for HHS recommend delaying insulin therapy until glucose is no longer falling with intravenous fluids alone."},{"id":"11335","category":"Diabetes and endocrine medicine","stem":"An 80-year-old man from a nursing home presents with confusion. He has type 2 diabetes, hypertension, hypercholesterolaemia, and ischaemic heart disease. He is on metformin 1g twice daily, linagliptin 5 mg once daily, ramipril 10 mg once daily, bisoprolol 5 mg once daily, aspirin 75 mg once daily, simvastatin 40 mg and lansoprazole 15 mg once daily. His recent HbA1c was 64 mmol/mol. On examination, he is confused and agitated. He has a blood pressure of 110/68 mmHg, a pulse rate of 110 bpm, a respiratory rate of 26, Sat 93% on air, and a temperature of 37.5 oC.\n\nInvestigations are shown in the following table:\n\nWhat is this patient’s plasma osmolality?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Investigations are shown in the following table:","What is this patient’s plasma osmolality?","This should be a pretty straightforward calculation.","Osmolality =2(Na)+urea+glucose.","In this case, it is 2(138)+25+42 = 343 mosmol/L.","Serum Osmolality/Osmolarity.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"This should be a pretty straightforward calculation.","explanation":"This should be a pretty straightforward calculation."},{"id":"13719","category":"Diabetes and endocrine medicine","stem":"A 19-year-old woman with type 1 diabetes admits to not having taken her insulin for several days. She has a respiratory rate of 32 breaths per minute, her O2 saturations are 98% on air, and she has a Küssmaul respiratory pattern. Her heart rate is 112 beats per minute, and her blood pressure is 94/62 mmHg. The patient’s blood results demonstrate a PH of 6.91 (7.35-7.45), a glucose of 28 mmol/L, and a ketone level of 5.7 mmol/L (< 0.6 mmol/L).\n\nWhich of the following is recommended next for this patient?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Which of the following is recommended next for this patient?","JBDS-IP - The Management of Diabetic Ketoacidosis in Adults* Revised March 2023.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"Which of the following is recommended next for this patient?","explanation":"This patient is in a state of diabetic ketoacidosis (DKA), and fluids and insulin form the mainstay of treatment. Fluid boluses should only be given if the systolic blood pressure is <90 mmHg. The patient's normal long-acting insulin should be continued, and a fixed-rate (not variable-rate) IV insulin infusion should be commenced; however, these can be initiated following the onset of fluid administration."},{"id":"3379","category":"Diabetes and endocrine medicine","stem":"An 18-year-old woman is admitted to the acute medical unit with nausea, vomiting, and abdominal pain. She gives a history of approximately 5 kg weight loss over the past month - 2 months, and also complains of persisting thirst and polyuria over the last 2 weeks. On examination, her blood pressure is 105/65 mmHg, her pulse is 92 beats per minute, and her body weight is 64.8 kg.\n\nInvestigations reveal the following results:\n\nWhich of the following is the most appropriate management of this patient?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"Fluid replacement is the cornerstone of therapy in the management of diabetic ketoacidosis (DKA). The total body deficit of fluid is around 5 - 8 litres, and rehydration by reopening renal perfusion may, on its own, reduce blood glucose by up to 2%. Infusion of large quantities of hypotonic fluid may result in circulatory collapse and possibly cerebral oedema. Consequently, most authorities recommend initial hydration with 0.9% sodium chloride saline, switching to hypotonic saline or dextrose if plasma sodium rises beyond 155 mmol/L. Current practice advocates fluid replacement at a rate of 2 litres over 4 hours, 2 litres over 8 hours, and subsequently 1 litre every 8 hours. This rate of rehydration results in slower increases in sodium and chloride concentrations. Once the glucose has fallen to around 14 mmol/L, an infusion of 10% glucose should be substituted for saline. This will allow continued infusion of insulin to correct metabolic acidosis and ketosis. Saline may be given simultaneously if the patient is still dehydrated."},{"id":"9169","category":"Diabetes and endocrine medicine","stem":"A 52-year-old woman presents with a 2-week history of deteriorating fatigue, nausea, thirst, and polyuria. Most recently, she reported problems keeping fluids down, and the GP had advised admission. She has a 3-year history of type 2 diabetes for which she takes metformin and empagliflozin. Her most recent body mass index is 31. Her glucose is measured at 8.7 mmol/L, and her most recent HbA1c is 67 mmol/mol.\n\nWhich of the following is the most appropriate approach to the management of this patient?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Plewa MC, Bryant M, King-Thiele R. Euglycemic Diabetic Ketoacidosis. [Updated 2020 Apr 30]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2020 Jan-.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"in this context","explanation":"A diagnosis of euglycaemic diabetic ketoacidosis should be considered in this context, yet the other possibility is that she has LADA. This patient has a rather short history of diabetes, and islet cell and GAD auto-antibodies could also be checked, yet the most appropriate investigation here is the ketones and venous gases. In this scenario, it is important to measure capillary ketones to consider/exclude euglycaemic diabetic ketoacidosis (DKA), a potentially life-threatening complication seen with SGLT2 inhibitors."},{"id":"8090","category":"Diabetes and endocrine medicine","stem":"A 31-year-old woman presented to the medical emergency department with a 1-week history of dizziness and weakness, together with a 2-day history of vomiting and diarrhoea. In her past medical history, she was diagnosed with hypothyroidism 3 years ago and has been taking a stable dose of thyroxine 100 micrograms daily.\n\nOn examination, she seemed unwell and dehydrated, had a temperature of 37°C, a pulse of 105 bpm, a blood pressure of 94/68 mmHg and a BMI of 21. There was diffuse abdominal tenderness without any focal signs. Bowel sounds were normal. Initial investigations revealed:\n\nWhich of the following is the most appropriate approach to the management of this patient?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"This patient has a prior autoimmune condition and presents with a seeming chronic hyponatraemia (acute hyponatraemia would more probably result in features of encephalopathy), lower than normal potassium (vomiting and diarrhoea), together with tachycardia and hypotension. These features suggest an unrecognised adrenal crisis, most likely due to associated Addison’s disease, and the patient requires urgent IV hydrocortisone and fluid resuscitation with normal saline at this point."},{"id":"11334","category":"Diabetes and endocrine medicine","stem":"A 42-year-old man of Afro-Caribbean descent is referred to you by his GP. He has a 2-year diagnosis of type 2 diabetes and was started on metformin 500 mg twice daily. His HbA1c 3 months ago was 70 mmol/mol. In the last week, he has been unwell with a productive cough, breathlessness and fever for 3 days. He is not a smoker. He has a strong family history of T2DM. His home blood glucose readings have been persistently high at around 20 marks.\n\nOn examination, BMI is 34kg/m2, blood pressure is 120/70 mmHg, pulse rate is 100 bpm, respiratory rate is 22, Sat 94% on air, temperature is 38 oC.\n\nHe has reduced breath sound on the left lower base, and a chest X-ray showed left basal consolidation. U&E is unremarkable. FBC shows:\n\nWhat is the likely diagnosis?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","He has reduced breath sound on the left lower base, and a chest X-ray showed left basal consolidation. U&E is unremarkable. FBC shows:","What is the likely diagnosis?","Umpierrez, G.E., 2006. Ketosis-prone type 2 diabetes: time to revise the classification of diabetes.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"Umpierrez, G.E., 2006. Ketosis-prone type 2 diabetes: time to revise the classification of diabetes.","explanation":"This patient is Afro-Caribbean in origin and has developed type-2 diabetes, yet has also developed a ketoacidosis with low pH and ketones. This is suggestive of either the patient being wrongly diagnosed with Type-1 DM, yet he has pretty reasonable glycaemic control just with metformin before this. So, the other probable cause is ketosis-prone type-2 diabetes, which typically occurs in the Afro-Caribbean population and is sometimes termed type 1.5 diabetes."},{"id":"3450","category":"Diabetes and endocrine medicine","stem":"A 62-year-old woman with acute symptomatic hyponatraemia likely due to SIADH and associated with drowsiness is considered to be appropriate for immediate treatment with hypertonic saline. Her serum sodium is 115 mmol/L.\n\nWhat is the target sodium to which you would treat this patient over the next 4 hours?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"A decision has been taken to treat this patient with hypertonic saline as she has acute symptomatic hyponatraemia, which reflects underlying cerebral oedema. In this context, treatment with 150 ml 3% hypertonic saline given over three hours can be lifesaving. The target sodium level by which one should elevate the sodium is 5 mmol/L over the first 4 hours. The increase in sodium should then be limited to 10mmol/L over the next 24 hours based on a clinical improvement."},{"id":"14149","category":"Diabetes and endocrine medicine","stem":"A 27-year-old woman with a background of type-1 diabetes mellitus and asthma was admitted to the hospital with worsening symptoms of lightheadedness, mainly on trying to stand up too quickly from the sitting or lying position. These symptoms have resulted in a few falls lately.\n\nOn examination, she was lean built, clinically euvolaemic with a heart rate of 87 beats per minute regular, a blood pressure of 87/65 mmHg with no significant postural drop, a temperature of 37 oC, a respiratory rate of 18 breaths per minute, SaO2 97% on room air.\n\nHer last asthma exacerbation was 6 months ago, which required hospitalisation. She was managed with amoxicillin 500 mg three times a day, prednisolone 40 mg once in the morning, salbutamol 5 mg, and ipratropium 500 mcg nebulisations four times a day. Her home medications include salbutamol and beclomethasone inhalers and montelukast 10 mg.\n\nInvestigations revealed the following results:\n\nWhat next investigation should be considered?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Investigations revealed the following results:","What next investigation should be considered?","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"The symptoms point towards postural hypotension with a background history of T1DM and asthma, showing a risk of other autoimmune conditions, autoimmune adrenal insufficiency in this case. The use of concurrent steroid inhalers can also sometimes cause adrenal suppression. Lean built, low resting blood pressure, and biochemical picture of mild hyponatraemia also justify an investigation for underlying adrenal insufficiency, and the first step will be to check for an early morning 8 am cortisol."},{"id":"17491","category":"Diabetes and endocrine medicine","stem":"A 40-year-old man who has a known case of type 1 diabetes mellitus presents to the emergency department with a history of abdominal pain, vomiting, and altered sensorium. On examination, the patient was in an altered sensorium, with a pulse rate of 100 beats per minute, and blood pressure of 100/60 mmHg.\n\nInvestigations revealed the following results:\n\nThe patient is started on a fixed dose of insulin 0.1 U/Kg per hour. After 3 hours, his blood glucose reaches 10 mmol/L.\n\nWhat should the patient be started on next?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","JBDS-IP. The Management of Diabetic Ketoacidosis in Adults*. Revised March 2023.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"Diabetic ketoacidosis (DKA) is an important endocrinological emergency and is more commonly seen in type 1 diabetes mellitus. Diabetic ketoacidosis should be differentiated from hyperglycaemic hyperosmolar coma (HHC), as the main treatment for DKA is insulin, while hyperosmolar coma is treated with IV Fluids."},{"id":"19869","category":"Diabetes and endocrine medicine","stem":"A 58-year-old man presents to the acute medical unit with a 2-day history of severe left leg pain and fever. He initially noticed a small area of redness on his shin following minor trauma. He has a past medical history of type 2 diabetes mellitus for which he takes metformin 1g BD and dapagliflozin 10mg OD.\n\nOn examination, he appears unwell with a temperature of 38.9oC, heart rate of 118/min, blood pressure of 95/60 mmHg and oxygen saturations of 97% in air. His left lower leg is swollen, dusky red, and exquisitely tender, extending beyond the area of visible skin changes. There is crepitus palpable in the soft tissues and areas of skin necrosis.\n\nWhat is the most appropriate scoring tool to support the clinical diagnosis of this patient?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Blood results show:","What is the most appropriate scoring tool to support the clinical diagnosis of this patient?","Immediate management should include urgent surgical referral for exploration and debridement, broad-spectrum intravenous antibiotics, fluid resuscitation, and critical care involvement.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"What is the most appropriate scoring tool to support the clinical diagnosis of this patient?","explanation":"This patient presents with clinical features highly suggestive of necrotising fasciitis: severe pain disproportionate to physical findings, systemic toxicity, rapidly progressive infection, crepitus, skin necrosis, and risk factors (diabetes, trauma). This is a surgical emergency requiring urgent diagnosis and intervention."},{"id":"19867","category":"Diabetes and endocrine medicine","stem":"A 52-year-old woman is admitted to the acute medical unit 48 hours following total thyroidectomy for multinodular goitre. She reports severe perioral paraesthesia and carpopedal spasm. On examination, she is alert with a positive Chvostek's sign. Her ECG shows a prolonged QTc interval of 485 ms (N<460ms for females).\n\nWhat is the most appropriate initial intravenous calcium replacement regimen?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Society for Endocrinology (SfE) emergency guidance for severe hypocalcaemia:","Magnesium replacement should also be initiated, given concurrent hypomagnesaemia.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"Society for Endocrinology (SfE) emergency guidance for severe hypocalcaemia:","explanation":"This patient has severe symptomatic hypocalcaemia (adjusted calcium 1.62 mmol/L with tetany and ECG changes) secondary to post-thyroidectomy hypoparathyroidism, constituting a medical emergency requiring urgent intravenous calcium replacement."},{"id":"3533","category":"Diabetes and endocrine medicine","stem":"An Asian man is admitted with a history of weight loss, lethargy, nausea, and vomiting.\n\nOn examination, he looks dehydrated and pigmented. His biochemical profile is as shown below:\n\nThe CT image shows the presence of calcification within the adrenal gland. What is the likely aetiology of his adrenal insufficiency?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Medicine and dentistry: adrenal tuberculosis.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"Medicine and dentistry: adrenal tuberculosis.","explanation":"Adrenal tuberculosis remains one of the commonest causes of adrenal insufficiency in the developing world, with about 5% of the patients with disseminated tuberculosis (Miliary Koch's) developing significant adrenal insufficiency. A low threshold of suspicion to seek adrenal insufficiency is warranted in patients with tuberculosis, as the symptoms and signs are non-specific and at times are attributed to an underlying condition (Tuberculosis). Adrenal tuberculosis is reversible with anti-tuberculosis medications if these are given at an early stage of the disease."},{"id":"3535","category":"Diabetes and endocrine medicine","stem":"A 55-year-old woman attends A&E with a 1-week history of sickness, lethargy, and fatigue. She has a 2-year history of metastatic breast carcinoma. On examination, she appears dehydrated and unwell.\n\nHer investigations reveal:\n\nWhich of the following is the most appropriate initial treatment for this patient?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"This patient has marked hypercalcaemia as reflected by the calcium above 3 mmol/L. The most appropriate initial management of this patient with dehydration and hypercalcaemia, which is likely to be malignancy-related, is IV rehydration with normal saline. One would not contemplate IV bisphosphonate until rehydration is completed, as this would compound the nephrotoxicity."},{"id":"3531","category":"Diabetes and endocrine medicine","stem":"A 44-year-old man with a long history of epilepsy and associated learning difficulties was admitted as his carers felt that he was more subdued and unwell. There was little history to obtain directly, although his carers stated that he was normally much brighter and communicative. He was taking omeprazole for gastro-oesophageal reflux disease (GORD), thyroxine, olanzapine, co-codamol on a PRN basis, topiramate, and he had recently been prescribed co-trimoxazole by his GP for assumed UTI.\n\nOn examination, he appeared subdued and uncommunicative with a GCS of 15. His temperature was 37.2 oC, blood pressure 118/72 mmHg, a pulse of 110 beats per minute, oxygen saturations of 98% on air, and a respiratory rate of 30 breaths per minute. No specific signs were noted on examination of the chest, praecordium or abdomen. No focal neurology was noted.\n\nInvestigations revealed the following results:\n\nWhich of the following is the likely diagnosis?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Investigations revealed the following results:","Which of the following is the likely diagnosis?","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"The patient has a hyperchloraemic acidosis with a normal anion gap {sodium – (bicarboinate+chloride) = 11 – NR 8-16}. In this case, the normal anion gap would exclude all the typical causes as found with high anion gap – lactic acidosis, DKA, methanol, etc (A useful mnemonic for high anion gap metabolic acidosis is MUDPILES). Loss of bicarbonate ions is often a cause of normal anion gap acidosis – renal tubular acidosis. In our case, topiramate causes a type 2 RTA and loss of bicarbonate ions. Acetazolamide, fistulas, and hyperparathyroidism are all capable of producing a normal anion gap acidosis."},{"id":"3537","category":"Diabetes and endocrine medicine","stem":"A 31-year-old woman, who is 11 weeks pregnant, presents with tachycardia, tremors, and palpitations. She has a strong family history of autoimmune thyroid disease and goitre. Her thyroid function test results are as shown below:\n\nWhat is the best therapeutic option in her case?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"The patient is likely to have Graves' thyrotoxicosis, as suggested by features of hyperthyroidism and associated strong family history of autoimmune thyroid disease. Because of her pregnant state, treatment with the lowest dose of Propylthiouracil, which renders her euthyroid, should be initiated. The following are a few of the salient points to be remembered as far as pregnancy and thyroid dysfunction are concerned:"},{"id":"11327","category":"Diabetes and endocrine medicine","stem":"A 25-year-old woman is brought to the accident & emergency unit by her boyfriend. They have argued, and she has taken an overdose of an unknown quantity of gliclazide tablets belonging to her grandmother. She had also developed seizures at home and had been attended to by paramedics. She was found to have blood glucose levels of 1.1 mmol/L, and she was started on IV dextrose immediately.\n\nWhich of the following is a potential antidote for sulphonylureas?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","McLaughlin, S.A., Crandall, C.S. and McKinney, P.E., 2000. Octreotide: an antidote for sulfonylurea-induced hypoglycemia. Annals of emergency medicine, 36(2), pp.133-138.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"to this patient every 6 hours","explanation":"Octreotide (Sandostatin) 1 to 1.5 mcg/kg (up to 50 mcg)IV/ SC should be administered to this patient every 6 hours. It blocks pancreatic beta-islet cell insulin release, and thereby inhibits the stimulatory effect of SUs."},{"id":"8096","category":"Diabetes and endocrine medicine","stem":"A 60-year-old man is admitted with a 3-day history of deteriorating lethargy and confusion. The GP had undertaken bloods, of which the sodium was reported as 121 mmol/L (134-144).\n\nWhich of the following parameters would be most supportive of a diagnosis of SIADH?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"the inappropriately high urine osmolality would be in keeping with SIADH","explanation":"In the above, oedema would suggest a hypervolaemic hyponatraemia. SIADH is associated with euvolaemic hyponatraemia with an inappropriate concentration of urine. Therefore, the inappropriately high urine osmolality would be in keeping with SIADH. Low urine sodium, i.e. <20 mmol/L, is suggestive of appropriate sodium retention and argues against a diagnosis of SIADH. Hyperkalaemia would suggest hypoadrenalism."},{"id":"14116","category":"Diabetes and endocrine medicine","stem":"A 50-year-old man has been admitted to the acute ward for treatment of alcohol withdrawal. He has been drinking heavily for the past 3 years after the death of his wife, and he has lost about 20 kg of weight this year. On admission to the hospital 12 hours ago, he was noted to be unkempt, anxious, and tremulous. His blood pressure was 108/70 mmHg, his pulse rate was 114 beats per minute, and his capillary glucose was noted to be 2.5 mmol/L. His body mass index was 19.5 kg/m2. He was treated with an intravenous 10% dextrose infusion, and his capillary glucose had increased to 6 mmol/L.\n\nYou receive a call from the ward doctor who informs you that the patient has become more drowsy and disoriented, and nystagmus is now noted on examination. His current capillary glucose is 5 mmol/L.\n\nWhat would be the most appropriate next step in treating this patient?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","What would be the most appropriate next step in treating this patient?","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"This patient has developed Wernicke’s encephalopathy (WE) due to thiamine deficiency on a background of chronic alcoholism, malnutrition, and self-neglect. The treatment should be urgent administration of intravenous thiamine."},{"id":"3529","category":"Diabetes and endocrine medicine","stem":"A 28-year-old woman who is 30 weeks pregnant presents with profound tiredness and lethargy. She is noted to have a sodium of 130 mmol/L on routine testing, and this sparks further investigation.\n\nHer investigations reveal:\n\nAn MRI of the pituitary reveals an enlarged gland that bulges slightly beyond the sella but shows no obvious tumour.\n\nWhich of the following is the likely diagnosis?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"This pregnant woman presents in the third trimester with hyponatraemia, secondary hypothyroidism, appropriate prolactin and oestradiol concentrations for this stage of pregnancy and an inadequate cortisol response to synacthen. This suggests partial hypopituitarism during the latter stages of pregnancy, which is likely due to lymphocytic hypophysitis (LH). The exact cause of LH is unknown, but it is thought to be autoimmune-related. Some patients will recover either spontaneously or with a short course of steroids, others may have a more protracted course. The condition often presents in late pregnancy or the postpartum period."},{"id":"9425","category":"Diabetes and endocrine medicine","stem":"A 40-year-old man is admitted with a vague headache with a query of possible malignant hypertension after the GP had found the patient's blood pressure was 188/110 mmHg. He has morbid obesity and hyperlipidaemia for which he has been treated with liraglutide and atorvastatin 80 mg daily together with ramipril. He is being considered for bariatric surgery as all therapeutic measures for weight loss have been unsuccessful. He has more recently been diagnosed with diabetes and has also commenced metformin 1g twice daily.\n\nOn examination, he weighs 160 kg and has a BMI of 52 kg/m2. All observations are otherwise fine, and there are no xanthomas/xanthelasmas to inspect. Fundal examination was normal, and the blood pressure with an appropriately sized cuff was 136/90 mmHg.\n\nInvestigations reveal normal full blood count, U&E's and LFTs. Glucose is 10.2 mmol/L. His lipid profile is reported as lipaemia and reveals Cholesterol 10.6 mmol/L (<6), and triglycerides 45.6 mmol/L (0.6 – 1.9). An ECG shows voltage criteria for left ventricular hypertrophy. Amylase was 110 iu/L (30-110).\n\nWhich of the following is the most appropriate approach to the management of this patient?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Ewald, N. and Kloer, H.U., 2012. Treatment options for severe hypertriglyceridemia (SHTG): the role of apheresis. Clinical research in cardiology supplements, 7(1), pp.31-35.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"This patient does not have severe hypertension, and it would seem that the earlier high blood pressure was due to an inadequately sized cuff. However, what has been revealed is severe hypertriglyceridaemia. In this context, he is at risk of developing pancreatitis and acute coronary artery disease. A rapid reduction of hypertriglyceridaemia is required, and this should be achieved through a fixed-rate insulin infusion rather than sliding scale insulin. Insulin is effective in the treatment of severe hypertriglyceridaemia as it promotes the action of lipoprotein lipase."},{"id":"11330","category":"Diabetes and endocrine medicine","stem":"An 80-year-old woman with type 2 diabetes mellitus presents with increasing lethargy, dysuria, and a loss of appetite for the last week. She is drowsy and increasingly confused. She has a history of diabetes for which she takes metformin.\n\nYou have sent routine bloods for analysis and are currently awaiting results, but a nurse in A&E quickly processes venous blood gas for you:\n\nWhich of the following is the most appropriate initial approach to her management?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","The management of the hyperosmolar hyperglycaemic state (HHS) in adults with diabetes Joint British Diabetes Societies Inpatient Care Group August 2012","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"Use intravenous (IV) 0.9% sodium chloride solution as the principal fluid to restore circulating volume and reverse dehydration. Only switch to a 0.45% sodium chloride solution if the osmolality is not declining, despite adequate positive fluid balance. An initial rise in sodium is expected and is not itself an indication for hypotonic fluids. The rate of fall of plasma sodium should not exceed 10 mmol/L in 24 hours."},{"id":"3601","category":"Diabetes and endocrine medicine","stem":"An 18-year-old woman was admitted to HDU for further management of diabetic ketoacidosis. She had two episodes of generalised tonic-clonic seizures and became unresponsive after 3 hours of treatment as per a DKA pathway. On examination, she was thin, and her pupils were equal and reactive to light. She had received 5 mg of diazepam and was postictal. Her current blood glucose is 20 mmol/L (initially, 40 mmol/L), and blood ketones are 3.2 mmol (<1.5).\n\nWhat is the next best step in her management?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"Cerebral oedema is a recognised complication in children, adolescents and adults with low body mass index. It can occur with large-volume fluid resuscitation in DKA. Several mechanisms, including vasogenic oedema (damage to the blood-brain barrier), due to rapid changes in the osmolality with fluid therapy, and interventions like bicarbonate therapy, are thought to be the cause of cerebral oedema."},{"id":"3561","category":"Diabetes and endocrine medicine","stem":"A 71-year-old man is admitted with cramps and twitching, which have deteriorated over the last 2 weeks. The patient denies any change in bowel habits. He has a previous history of type 2 diabetes and hypertension. He was taking metformin and recently started sitagliptin; he also takes bendrofluazide, ramipril, and omeprazole for gastro-oesophageal reflux disease (GORD).\n\nOn examination, trousseau’s sign was positive, his pulse was 88 beats per minute, and his blood pressure was 128/88 mmHg.\n\nHis investigations revealed:\n\nWhich of the following is most likely responsible for this patient’s presentation?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"The patient has severe hypocalcaemia, a lowish phosphate, and a slightly raised PTH (which is inappropriate for this level of hypocalcemia), which suggests secondary hyperparathyroidism most likely due to Vit D Def. It is also important in this scenario to measure the magnesium."},{"id":"11639","category":"Gastroenterology and hepatology","stem":"A 62-year-old woman with a background of autoimmune hepatitis and cirrhosis presents to the A&E department reporting that she has been feeling generally unwell over the last few days. Her liver disease was usually well compensated, but recently, she developed ascites. Awaiting her outpatient review by the liver team, her GP initiated treatment with spironolactone 100 mg twice daily and furosemide 40 mg once daily three days ago, as her ascites were getting rather tense.\n\nOn examination, she has a moderate amount of ascites and her abdomen is mildly tender. There is no flapping tremor. Her chest X-ray is clear, and her urine dip is not indicative of a urinary tract infection.\n\nHer blood test results show:\n\nAn ascites tap shows a neutrophil count of 670 cells/ul.\n\nWhich of the following represents the best treatment?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"antibiotics to treat the infection and IV colloid administration are indicated","explanation":"This is a patient presenting with spontaneous bacterial peritonitis (SBP) and renal impairment. The high lactate indicates that the patient is volume-depleted. Therefore, antibiotics to treat the infection and IV colloid administration are indicated. The diuretics should be at least temporarily stopped and restarted at a lower dose once renal function recovers. Administering terlipressin at this stage would not be appropriate, as the patient is fluid-depleted and, in this context, the use of terlipressin may be complicated by further tissue hypoxia. Ascite drainage in this acute setting is not indicated and is not the priority."},{"id":"9170","category":"Gastroenterology and hepatology","stem":"A 56-year-old man is admitted to the acute medical intake with alcohol withdrawal and associated cirrhosis. On examination, he has clear sarcopaenia. He is treated with IV pabrinex and also put on a CIWA scale.\n\nWhich of the following should be undertaken regarding the management of his condition and associated sarcopaenia?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"such patients should have a meal or snack every 3 hours","explanation":"Patients with sarcopenia and liver cirrhosis have accelerated starvation, where a 10-hour fast equates to a 3-day fast in a healthy individual. This renders the patient susceptible to acute hypoglycaemia and therefore such patients should have a meal or snack every 3 hours. Sarcopenia is a reversible condition that is more prevalent in decompensated cirrhosis. It is appreciated that high ammonia concentrations promote muscle protein breakdown by increasing the utilisation of branched-chain amino acids. Similarly, the evidence now points to a higher protein diet (1.5g/kg) rather than a lower protein diet, with better outcomes being apparent."},{"id":"4212","category":"Gastroenterology and hepatology","stem":"A 40-year-old woman with known alcoholic liver disease presents with jaundice.\n\nHer blood results are as follows:\n\nHer Maddrey’s discriminant functions score is 35.\n\nWhich of the following is the best treatment to improve her 30-day mortality?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Maddrey’s discriminant function score.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"Maddrey’s discriminant function score.","explanation":"The STOPAH study compared prednisolone and pentoxifylline in a double-blinded, randomised controlled trial. Although judged to be underpowered, the study did show an improvement in 28-day mortality with prednisolone, but not with pentoxifylline. The improvements were not seen at 90 days or 1 year. A discriminant function score is useful in predicting short-term prognosis, with a score above 32 suggesting a poorer prognosis and that the patient may benefit from steroid therapy."},{"id":"3946","category":"Gastroenterology and hepatology","stem":"An 18-year-old woman presents to the Medical Assessment Unit (MAU) accompanied by her mother, both visibly distressed. She reports a 5-month history of diarrhoea and has self-presented due to frustration over the perceived lack of progress in her care by her GP. She was diagnosed with irritable bowel syndrome (IBS) by her GP, who previously submitted three separate stool samples for culture, all of which returned negative. She reports no weight loss and denies any other gastrointestinal symptoms.\n\nInvestigations reveal:\n\nWhich of the following is the most appropriate investigation for this patient?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Labtestsonline: Calprotectin.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"Labtestsonline: Calprotectin.","explanation":"The raised platelet count should raise suspicions of ongoing inflammation. A calprotectin level is a good marker for inflammation in the gastrointestinal tract, and a negative result in the presence of symptoms effectively excludes inflammatory bowel disease, thus avoiding the need for an invasive test in a young patient. This patient does not have signs of acute severe inflammatory bowel disease and therefore does not need an immediate colonoscopy, although she is likely to require it in the future. 3 negative stool tests are quite convincing for a lack of infection in the stool, and elastase should be measured in the stool, not the serum, for suspected pancreatic insufficiency."},{"id":"11644","category":"Gastroenterology and hepatology","stem":"A 72-year-old man is admitted with three episodes of haematemesis. He has a history of lone atrial fibrillation for which he is being treated with apixaban and bisoprolol. There is no other history of note.\n\nOn examination, he is oriented, his BMI is 28 kg/m2, his pulse is 102 beats per minute, irregular, and his blood pressure is 90/68 mmHg.\n\nHis haemoglobin is 9.2 g/L, urea 12 mmol/L, and his LFTs are normal. Prothrombin time ratio is 1.1, and APTT is normal.\n\nHe is receiving IV fluids and packed red cells for resuscitation before upper GI endoscopy. He is also treated with IV proton pump inhibitor therapy.\n\nBesides stopping the DOAC, how should his anticoagulation be managed?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"NICE states that in those treated with rivaroxaban and apixaban, andexanet alfa is an appropriate reversal agent in those presenting with a life-threatening bleed (Idarucizumab is used for rapid reversal of dabigatran for emergency procedures, or in life-threatening or uncontrolled bleeding). In this patient who is in shock, the haematemesis appears life-threatening, hence treatment with andexanet would be appropriate."},{"id":"11638","category":"Gastroenterology and hepatology","stem":"A 68-year-old man with hepatitis C-related cirrhosis presents to the Accident & Emergency Department. His wife noticed that over the last 24 hours, he has become increasingly confused and febrile.\n\nOn examination, he has moderate ascites and flapping tremor. His inflammatory markers are raised. His chest X-ray and urine microscopy, culture and sensitivity (MC&S) are negative for infection. An ascites tap shows a neutrophil count of 900/ul. He had similar previous episodes on two occasions over the previous 12 months.\n\nWhich of the following applies when considering his further management?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"There is evidence to suggest that patients who have had previous episodes of SBP have a 70% risk of a further spontaneous bacterial peritonitis (SBP) episode if left without prophylaxis and a 20% risk of recurrent SBP if they receive prophylaxis with norfloxacin 400 mg daily. Therefore, the guidelines of the European Association for the Study of the Liver suggest that norfloxacin is the first choice when considering secondary prophylaxis for SBP. More recently, some evidence for the use of rifaximin for secondary prophylaxis of SBP has emerged."},{"id":"4190","category":"Gastroenterology and hepatology","stem":"A 76-year-old man undergoes an upper GI endoscopy for dyspepsia. The findings are unremarkable, and he is discharged home. However, he attends A&E 3 hours later with a 1-hour history of acute, severe central chest pain associated with feeling hot and sweaty.\n\nOn examination, he appears in pain with a pulse of 98 beats per minute, a blood pressure of 148/88 mmHg, and a temperature of 38.3 oC.\n\nWhich of the following is the most appropriate investigation to confirm this patient's diagnosis?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"as it is water-soluble and will not cause mediastinitis","explanation":"The likely diagnosis here is iatrogenic oesophageal perforation. Although very rare in diagnostic OGD, it can occur, and the fever here suggests that this is unlikely to be cardiac in origin, and as such, the most likely test to confirm the diagnosis is a contrast swallow. Gastrografin should be used as it is water-soluble and will not cause mediastinitis, unlike barium. Ideally, a plain film swallow should be performed before CT as the radiation dose is less."},{"id":"17267","category":"Gastroenterology and hepatology","stem":"A 47-year-old man presented to his doctor and reported having general tiredness for at least 6 months, which he put down to his workload. On further enquiry, he noticed his abdomen was swollen despite not eating much. He does not have a fever and no other symptoms. He has no recent travel history, denies using IV drugs, and he drinks a bottle of wine every night. On examination, he has jaundice, gynecomastia, moderate ascites, and hepatomegaly.\n\nWhat is the most likely diagnosis?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Patel R, Mueller M. Alcoholic Liver Disease. [Updated 2022 Jan 19]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2022 Jan-.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"Alcoholic liver disease occurs most commonly in men between 40-50 years of age and occurs in the setting of heavy alcohol use. The presence of jaundice associated with gynecomastia, hepatomegaly and ascites is common in liver disease. Heart failure is also a common cause of portal hypertension-related ascites, but it is not associated with gynecomastia or jaundice. In fatty liver disease, ascites occurs, and this is more insidious, with no associated gynecomastia, and fatigue is not as pronounced. Concerning nephrotic syndrome, this presents primarily with fatigue and oedema around the eyes, ankles and feet, and with no gynecomastia. Ascites caused by cancer can occur because there is an invasion of the peritoneum or secondary to liver metastasis, causing portal hypertension - alcohol would not play a role in this, and there is no associated gynecomastia."},{"id":"17397","category":"Gastroenterology and hepatology","stem":"A 25-year-old woman presents in the clinic with a 6-month history of frequent loose stools, up to 6 times per day, usually occurring in the morning, and which never wakes her up from sleep. Her weight has increased by 6 kg over the past year, and there has been no rectal bleeding. She has an anxious personality. On examination, she is not tachycardic and appears well with a soft abdomen and active bowel sounds.\n\nWhat is the most likely diagnosis?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","NHS: What is IBS?","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"The correct answer, in this case, is irritable bowel syndrome. The most likely reason is that there is a prolonged history of diarrhoea, which is self-limiting and is not associated with any serious symptoms of weight loss, rather, she has gained weight and secondly, it does not wake her up from sleep and is not associated with any blood in the stool which indicates a benign process."},{"id":"3948","category":"Gastroenterology and hepatology","stem":"Which of the following patients has the most valid indication for urgent assessment for potential liver transplantation?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Which of the following patients has the most valid indication for urgent assessment for potential liver transplantation?","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"Patients with acute, non-paracetamol-related fulminant liver failure with encephalopathy or progressive coagulopathy should be discussed with the liver transplant centre and referred. The guidelines for paracetamol poisoning are more extensive, but the ALT is not a marker of the severity of liver damage or its synthetic functional abilities. A bilirubin over 100 in primary biliary cirrhosis is a criterion for transplantation, but this patient’s age would rule them out of major transplant surgery. Any extrahepatic spread in HCC is an absolute contraindication to liver transplant. Cholangiocarcinoma is not treated with liver transplantation."},{"id":"3973","category":"Gastroenterology and hepatology","stem":"A 24-year-old plumber with ulcerative colitis presents with severe rectal bleeding. He is opening his bowels over 20 times a day, including at least 5 times at night, passing only blood and mucous. He is also complaining of generalised abdominal pain.\n\nOn examination, he looks unwell. His observations are as follows:\n\nHis abdomen is markedly tender in the left iliac fossa but soft.\n\nHis blood tests show:\n\nWhich of the following is the most urgent initial investigation?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"This patient has fulminant/severe ulcerative colitis. The major concern is toxic dilatation of the colon, which can be quickly assessed with an abdominal X-ray. These patients may well need an abdominal CT too, but an X-ray is the most urgent first-line test. Stool microscopy, culture and sensitivity should be sent, but results will take some time. An urgent flexible sigmoidoscopy is unlikely to change the management during the initial assessment phase, as the patient is known to have ulcerative colitis, and the other tests are not useful. Faecal calprotectin is not useful in this scenario."},{"id":"11631","category":"Gastroenterology and hepatology","stem":"A 60-year-old man presented with relentless projectile vomiting and weight loss. He was born in Poland and emigrated to Britain when he was 45 years old. He works with an international insurance company and has no history of exposure to industrial chemicals. He previously smoked when he was young, but quit smoking 35 years ago and has not used cigarettes since.\n\nHis blood gas analysis:\n\nWhat is the likely diagnosis?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","This patient has metabolic alkalosis due to severe vomiting and loss of acid content in the stomach.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"This patient had followed a traditional Polish diet for at least 45 years, which includes smoked and pickled foods. This is a well-recognised cause of gastric cancer. Although the incidence of gastric cancer falls when people migrate to an area where such foods are not eaten, the magnitude of the decline is directly related to the length of abstinence from such foods."},{"id":"11633","category":"Gastroenterology and hepatology","stem":"A 42-year-old woman presents with a 1-week history of profuse watery diarrhoea. There is no history of blood in the stools. She denies any travel, eating outside, or contact with anyone with similar symptoms. There is no history of cough, sore throat or fever. She is currently having ongoing chemotherapy for breast cancer and reports that she had to stop her chemo due to the severity of the diarrhoea. On examination, she has a dry mucous membrane. Her abdomen is soft with some tenderness over the right iliac region.\n\nHer blood results are as follows:\n\nHer abdominal X-ray is normal. A CT scan of the abdomen excluded bowel perforation. Her stool culture and sensitivity are negative, with a negative stool test for Clostridium difficile.\n\nWhat is the likely cause of this patient's diarrhoea?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"Chemotherapy-induced diarrhoea (CID) is a common problem, especially in patients with advanced cancer. CID can occur in 50–80% of patients, depending on the chemotherapy regimen. Findings in such patients include volume depletion, renal failure, and electrolyte disorders such as metabolic acidosis. The treatment of CID includes nonpharmacologic and pharmacologic interventions to control diarrhoea and careful serial evaluation to rule out significant volume depletion. Loperamide, octreotide, and sometimes even budesonide can be considered with specialist involvement."},{"id":"11636","category":"Gastroenterology and hepatology","stem":"A 35-year-old businessman has recently returned from a holiday in India. He presents with a 2-week history of profuse watery diarrhoea, which started soon after he returned to the UK. He was seen by his GP, who treated him for giardiasis confirmed in his stool testing. He felt better for a few days and reported that his symptoms had relapsed. He reports losing a stone in weight in 3 weeks and complains of bloating, flatulence, and abdominal pain. His repeat stool tests are negative.\n\nWhat is the most appropriate next step?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Giardia infection (giardiasis).","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"Giardia lamblia is spread by the faeco-oral route. The cysts are ingested via contaminated water. Excystation occurs after contact with gastric acid, and trophozoites are released. The trophozoites undergo asexual reproduction in the gut and then colonise the upper small bowel using a sucking disc to adhere to the mucosa. This disrupts the small bowel brush border, causing cytokine release and water and electrolyte loss. The trophozoites encyst as they pass the large intestine, and cysts are passed in the faeces. The cysts are infectious and can survive outside the host. Chlorination of water does not eradicate the cysts. The incubation period varies from a few days to months. Treatment is with a short course of metronidazole or a single dose of tinidazole. If symptoms persist, consider treating them with a higher dose of metronidazole and look for immunodeficiency or lactose intolerance."},{"id":"3976","category":"Gastroenterology and hepatology","stem":"A 36-year-old engineer with ulcerative colitis presents with rectal bleeding. He is opening his bowels twice a day, but not at night, passing blood and mucous. He is also complaining of generalised abdominal pain. His only other medical history is of eczema. This is his first flare of colitis since his initial presentation 3 years ago. His usual medications are Mesalazine 2.4g daily and diprobase cream.\n\nOn examination, his abdomen is soft but minimally tender. His blood tests are normal, other than a CRP of 44 mg/dl (normal range <5).\n\nHis chest and abdominal films are normal, with no evidence of perforation or toxic dilatation.\n\nWhat is the most appropriate management for this patient?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Mild to moderate ulcerative colitis flares can often be managed with increased doses of mesalazine in the first instance. This avoids the need for corticosteroids and their subsequent side effects.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"Mild to moderate ulcerative colitis flares can often be managed with increased doses of mesalazine in the first instance. This avoids the need for corticosteroids and their subsequent side effects.","explanation":"Mild to moderate ulcerative colitis flares can often be managed with increased doses of mesalazine in the first instance. This avoids the need for corticosteroids and their subsequent side effects."},{"id":"11640","category":"Gastroenterology and hepatology","stem":"A 55-year-old man presents to the accident and emergency department with vomiting and diarrhoea. The patient drinks 14 units of alcohol per week. He is obese with a BMI of 41. An abdominal examination is done and is unremarkable. Clinically, he appears dehydrated. He is admitted for observation and is rehydrated. Stools are sent for culture and sensitivity.\n\nBloods show the following results:\n\nAn ultrasound of the abdomen shows a fatty liver. A liver screen (viral hepatitis screen, liver autoimmune screen, ferritin, caeruloplasmin, alpha-1-antitrypsin) is sent, which is unremarkable.\n\nWhat is the most appropriate treatment option?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"The patient’s phenotype and the results suggest Non-Alcoholic Fatty Liver Disease as the most likely diagnosis. Initial treatment advice includes lifestyle modification to reduce his weight. There is no evidence to suggest Wilson’s disease or Haemochromatosis. His history does not suggest alcohol or drugs as the cause for the mild rise in the ALT."},{"id":"4208","category":"Gastroenterology and hepatology","stem":"A 42-year-old woman with alcoholic liver disease and cirrhosis presents with acutely decompensated liver disease and ascites.\n\nHer blood results are as follows:\n\nShe undergoes an ultrasound scan of the liver and is found to have a thrombus causing hepatic venous obstruction.\n\nShe has started on diuretic therapy and her ascites responds well. Given her coagulopathy, what is the correct management of her thrombus?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"Although it may seem counterintuitive, the first-line treatment should be anticoagulation, although this can be problematic in patients with liver disease. An alternative can be a TIPs procedure. The safest anticoagulant to use long-term is warfarin, as it can be reversed easily."},{"id":"8405","category":"Gastroenterology and hepatology","stem":"An 81-year-old woman is admitted with increasing confusion and lethargy, and her family has been particularly concerned that she has been unable to look after herself. She has had a recent history of hypertension and diabetes for which she takes metformin, ramipril and amlodipine. On examination, she has a temperature of 35.5 oC, and is confused concerning time and place. Her blood pressure is 128/70 mmHg, and her pulse is 50 bpm regular. An abdominal examination reveals little, but a PR examination reveals that the rectum is loaded with faeces. Examination of the CNS reveals blunted tendon reflexes but no focal neurology.\n\nInitial investigations reveal:\n\nWhich of the following is the most appropriate investigation for this patient?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"This patient presents with a short history of increasing confusion and difficulty coping. The principal features include confusion, constipation, hypothermia and blunted tendon jerks. The investigations reveal an elevated MCV and mild hyponatraemia. These features are in keeping with hypothyroidism, and the most appropriate investigation would be thyroid function tests, which would be expected to reveal a low free T4 and elevated TSH."},{"id":"3975","category":"Gastroenterology and hepatology","stem":"A 68-year-old woman presents with severe diarrhoea, opening her bowels over 10 times per day for the last 2 months. She does not pass any blood and has not travelled, eaten in restaurants or had any other infectious symptoms. She has seen her GP multiple times and is so frustrated that she has presented herself to the MAU. She received a course of radiotherapy for cervical cancer 8 months ago, but was previously fit and well.\n\nExamination is unremarkable, including rectal examination. She is not clinically or biochemically dehydrated. An abdominal X-ray is normal.\n\nHer blood tests are as follows:\n\nWhat is the appropriate management for this patient?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"an urgent referral to a gastroenterologist is the best option","explanation":"This patient most likely has pelvic radiation disease caused by her previous radiotherapy. Pelvic radiotherapy causes a permanent change in bowel habits in over 90% of patients. The pathophysiology is initially inflammatory, but after the first 3 months, the disease process changes to a fibrotic disorder with neovascularisation. This can lead to a wide variety of disorders, including bile acid malabsorption, bacterial overgrowth, carbohydrate intolerance, and recurrence of underlying malignancy. Given the relative longevity of symptoms, the normal blood tests, and the lack of blood in the stool, this patient can be investigated as an outpatient. Her age, coupled with a change in her bowel habit, mandates referral for an urgent colonoscopy, but these patients often need further investigations. Therefore, an urgent referral to a gastroenterologist is the best option. These patients can have severe symptoms that need review by a gastroenterologist and outpatient follow-up."},{"id":"3963","category":"Gastroenterology and hepatology","stem":"A 47-year-old woman presents to the emergency department with a several-hour history of nausea and severe pain in the abdomen. She describes her pain as unrelenting mid-epigastric pain radiating to her back.\n\nOn examination, the patient is in the fetal position and reluctant to move. She is tachycardic and has a low-grade fever. Orthostatic hypotension is noted. Laboratory study results are remarkable except for an amylase level of 1100 iu/L (<100).\n\nWhich of the following tests is most appropriate for assessing the severity of her illness?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"A CT scan is the modality of choice to assess the severity of acute pancreatitis and the presence of associated complications. More specifically, CT with dynamic intravenous contrast injection can determine the presence and extent of pancreatic necrosis, which remains the primary determinant of length of hospitalisation and mortality. Although a KUB can rule out other etiologies for abdominal pain, it does not directly image the pancreas. Imaging by transabdominal US is severely limited by the poor transmission of ultrasound waves through bowel gas that normally surrounds the pancreas. MRI is not superior to CT for imaging in acute pancreatitis and is both less available and more expensive. ERCP is contraindicated in acute pancreatitis unless there is evidence of concurrent cholangitis."},{"id":"4246","category":"Gastroenterology and hepatology","stem":"A 49-year-old man is admitted with an acute severe exacerbation of ulcerative colitis. His condition is settling following treatment with cyclosporine together with IV hydrocortisone 100 mg four times daily. Five days following admission, he presents with a 2-hour history of deteriorating central chest pain, which is worse on swallowing. He has also been receiving low molecular weight prophylaxis during admission.\n\nThere is no other relevant past medical history other than a recent diagnosis of ulcerative colitis. He is a non-smoker and drinks only a little alcohol.\n\nOn examination, he has central chest pain with a pulse of 90 beats per minute, regular, a blood pressure of 132/80 mmHg and oxygen saturations of 99% on air. ECG is normal.\n\nWhat is the likely diagnosis?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","There is no other relevant past medical history other than a recent diagnosis of ulcerative colitis. He is a non-smoker and drinks only a little alcohol.","D-dimer\tPositive\nCRP\t80 mg/L\t< 5\nInitial hsTroponin\t12 < 16","What is the likely diagnosis?","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"D-dimer\tPositive\nCRP\t80 mg/L\t< 5\nInitial hsTroponin\t12 < 16","explanation":"Painful swallowing is a good differentiator between reflux and infective oesophagitis. Proton pump inhibitors and H2-receptor antagonists are thought to increase the risk of Candida oesophagitis, which elevates gastric pH and alters the colonisation of the oesophagus by oral cavity bacteria and yeast. Antibiotics may predispose immunocompetent patients to fungal infection by allowing overgrowth and colonisation of the Candida species. Administering corticosteroids predisposes one to infection by suppressing both lymphocyte and granulocyte function. In this case, the D-dimer will be positive in patients with UC and a high inflammatory marker. Similarly, the normal saturations and pulse rate argue against PE."},{"id":"11632","category":"Gastroenterology and hepatology","stem":"A 48-year-old woman is admitted by the GP with weight loss and watery diarrhoea. He had arranged an ultrasound, which was reported as revealing potentially numerous metastases. She has lost about 1.5 stone in 2 months, even though she has a good appetite. Recently, she has had hot flushes, which she is attributing to approaching the menopause. She is currently taking St John’s Wort to help her symptoms.\n\nWhich of the following is the likely diagnosis in this case?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Neuroendocrine Tumors: Symptoms and Signs","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"This patient has classic symptoms of carcinoid syndrome. She has nothing in her history to suggest acute appendicitis or small bowel ischaemia. Colon cancer can present with obstruction but not with classic features of carcinoid syndrome such as hot flushes. Vipomas are rare and do not present with obstructive symptoms."},{"id":"14150","category":"Gastroenterology and hepatology","stem":"A 67-year-old man with a background of hypertension, diabetes mellitus type-2 and transient ischaemic attack is admitted to the hospital feeling generally unwell and tired. His regular medications include ramipril 2.5 mg once daily, metformin 500 mg twice a day, clopidogrel 75 mg once daily, omeprazole 20 mg once daily, and atorvastatin 20 mg at night.\n\nOn examination, he looks anaemic, but the rest of his systemic examination is unremarkable.\n\nInvestigations reveal the following results:\n\nOn further evaluation, he denies any swallowing issues, weight loss, nausea, or vomiting, but complains of heartburn/indigestion. His bowel motions are regular with dark brown stools, and he does not have any urinary symptoms.\n\nWhat is the most appropriate next step in the management of this patient?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"The patient’s symptoms of feeling generally unwell and having a lack of energy point towards symptomatic anaemia. As the patient is haemodynamically stable and not actively bleeding, he does not qualify for a blood transfusion, and the main aim in this situation is to identify and manage the cause of his anaemia. The blood picture is suggestive of microcytic iron deficiency anaemia, so the first step would be to confirm iron deficiency by checking the levels in his blood and supplementing using intravenous or oral formulations. The findings of iron deficiency anaemia and dyspepsia justify OesophagoGastroDuodenoscopy (OGD), but it can be done as an urgent outpatient procedure. The important thing to consider here would be a history of TIA and the patient being on clopidogrel, which will need to be held a week before the endoscopy, again suggesting that an outpatient investigation is appropriate."},{"id":"3969","category":"Gastroenterology and hepatology","stem":"A 20-year-old otherwise healthy student presents with 3 months of abdominal pain, diarrhoea, a 4kg weight loss, and diffuse arthropathy, but no fevers. He has no travel history, takes no regular medication, is a nonsmoker, and his family history is significant only for an uncle who had “some bowel removed.” His examination is remarkable for normal vital signs and right lower quadrant tenderness with no masses or organomegaly palpable.\n\nWhat is the single next best test to confirm his diagnosis?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"should not generally be used as a first-line diagnostic study","explanation":"This patient has signs and symptoms consistent with ileal and right-sided colonic Crohn’s disease. Although stool studies should be done as part of his evaluation, given the duration of symptoms, he is unlikely to have an infection. His significant weight loss is an indicator that more invasive testing is required. In patients with Crohn’s disease, P-ANCA is associated with a UC-like phenotype, but this is not a diagnostic test. A barium enema may show inflammatory changes in the colon suggestive of Crohn’s disease, but it will not necessarily evaluate the terminal ileum, and biopsy specimens cannot be taken. Capsule enteroscopy is highly sensitive in identifying the lesions of Crohn’s disease, but is not specific and therefore should not generally be used as a first-line diagnostic study. Further, biopsy specimens cannot be taken, and the risk of capsule retention in the setting of stricture can be as high as 25%. Colonoscopy with ileal intubation will not only allow macroscopic visualisation of inflammatory changes in the colon and terminal ileum, but biopsies performed in both inflamed and non-inflamed tissue will permit histologic mapping of Crohn’s disease."},{"id":"3943","category":"Gastroenterology and hepatology","stem":"A 38-year-old woman presents acutely to the medical assessment unit (MAU). A friend found her unconscious at home this morning. She was found with an empty bottle of paracetamol and 2 bottles of vodka. She was started on N acetylcysteine in A&E and has been transferred through to you for medical assessment and management.\n\nArterial blood gas on air\n\nWhat is the most appropriate management at this point?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","The King’s College guidelines are the most widely used published guidelines on when to refer for liver transplantation in paracetamol overdose and acute liver failure.","King’s College Hospital criteria for transplantation in acute liver failure:","Paracetamol","+ pH <7.30 (irrespective of grade of encephalopathy)","+ Prothrombin time >100 seconds and serum creatinine >300 µmol/L if in grade III or IV coma","Non-paracetamol","+ Prothrombin time >100 seconds (irrespective of the grade of encephalopathy) or","+ Any three of the following (irrespective of the grade of encephalopathy):","BSG - Acute liver injury to liver failure – what to do before calling the transplant team.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"The King’s College guidelines are the most widely used published guidelines on when to refer for liver transplantation in paracetamol overdose and acute liver failure.","explanation":"The King’s College guidelines are the most widely used published guidelines on when to refer for liver transplantation in paracetamol overdose and acute liver failure."},{"id":"3944","category":"Gastroenterology and hepatology","stem":"A 64-year-old man with known alcohol abuse presents to A&E. He has had frank haematemesis for the last 4 hours.\n\nOn presentation, his observations include a heart rate of 130 beats per minute, a blood pressure of 89/64 mmHg, a respiratory rate of 28 breaths per minute, and a temperature of 36.9 oC.\n\nYou secure intravenous access and send blood samples for analysis. While you await blood results, you give him intravenous fluids plus 2 mg terlipressin.\n\nHis blood results are as follows:\n\nDespite your initial management, there is no improvement, and he continues to have large volume haematemesis. You contact the gastroenterologist at home, but there is no on-call GI bleeding rota, and he is away from home; therefore, it will be some time before he can perform an endoscopy.\n\nWhat is the next best management option?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"as gastric varices fill from the stomach upwards","explanation":"PPI and terlipressin are unlikely to rescue this patient, and he needs endoscopic therapy. If this is unavailable, a sengstaken tube is an effective way to manage variceal bleeding. Only the gastric balloon should be used as gastric varices fill from the stomach upwards, and the oesophageal balloon can cause significant mucosal necrosis and further bleeding."},{"id":"9067","category":"Gastroenterology and hepatology","stem":"A 56-year-old woman is referred after attending her GP surgery for an insurance medical. Her past medical history is significant for obesity, hypertension and type-2 diabetes. She takes irbesartan, metformin, sitagliptin, amlodipine and atorvastatin. Her HbA1c was 85 mmol/mol (<48 – 9.9%). However, the GP is concerned as she was found to be positive for Hepatitis C on enzyme-linked immunoassay, yet she has no risk factors. Liver function tests, serum creatinine and INR are normal. She does not smoke or drink alcohol.\n\nOn examination, she has a BMI of 38 kg/m2, a pulse of 90 bpm regular, and a blood pressure of 138/86 mmHg.\n\nWhich of the following is the most appropriate approach regarding her management?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Which of the following is the most appropriate approach regarding her management?","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"we cannot be sure if the patient has viral hepatitis","explanation":"This woman has tested positive for HCV on ELISA, suggesting infection. 15-35% of people spontaneously clear the hepatitis C infection, with the majority developing chronic hepatitis C. The viral RNA is useful for making the diagnosis of viral hepatitis C and monitoring the response to treatment. The sensitivity of the ELISA test is excellent, and unless you suspect laboratory error, a repeat test is not needed. Therefore, we cannot be sure if the patient has viral hepatitis, so a confirmatory test is needed."},{"id":"3966","category":"Gastroenterology and hepatology","stem":"A 39-year-old man is noted to have jaundice two days after an uncomplicated appendicectomy. The surgery and postoperative course were uneventful, without documented episodes of haemodynamic instability, and his surgical incision has no signs of infection.\n\nHe is found to have an elevated bilirubin level with a serum ALP level 1.5 times the upper limit of normal. The result of a full blood count is normal.\n\nWhich of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Postoperative cholestasis is characterised by a short-latency elevation in the level of indirect bilirubin, lack of rash or eosinophilia, and ensured recovery.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"Between 25% and 75% of patients undergoing surgery experience postoperative hepatic dysfunction, ranging from mild elevations in serum levels of liver enzymes to hepatic failure. Drugs that may cause hepatotoxicity in this setting include antibiotics and halogenated anaesthetic agents. Most produce injury by causing a hypersensitivity reaction that becomes evident within one to two weeks of administration."},{"id":"4248","category":"Gastroenterology and hepatology","stem":"A 39-year-old man is admitted with a 3-hour history of acute central abdominal pain with radiation into the left side of his back and associated vomiting. Four weeks ago, he was admitted with bloody diarrhoea and diagnosed with acute ulcerative colitis. He was commenced on azathioprine 150 mg once daily, and doses of prednisolone were reduced to 5 mg daily. He has had two doses of infliximab and is awaiting the third infusion this week. His diarrhoea had settled and he had been feeling a lot better.\n\nOn examination, he is in pain with a pulse of 102 beats per minute, regular, a blood pressure of 130/80 mmHg, and oxygen saturations on air of 99%. His abdomen is tender to the touch centrally, but no masses are palpable, and he has normal bowel sounds.\n\nInvestigations reveal:\n\nWhich of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Investigations reveal:","Investigation\tResult\tNormal range\nHb\t12.2 g/dL\t12-16 g/dL\nWhite count\t12.2 x 109/L\t3-10 x 109/L\nU+Es\tNormal\nCalcium\t2.4 mmol/L\t2.2-2.6 mmol/L\nCRP\t110 mg/L\t<5\nAmylase\t730 iu/L\t<140","Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","explanation":"The most likely diagnosis here is azathioprine-induced pancreatitis. An amylase 3x above the normal range with this history suggests the diagnosis. Azathioprine, particularly with steroids, is associated with pancreatitis, and other agents include valproate, mercaptopurine, and oestrogens. The pancreatitis usually resolves with the withdrawal of the offending drug."},{"id":"3955","category":"Gastroenterology and hepatology","stem":"A 64-year-old man presents with gross ascites. He has a background of cirrhosis due to hepatitis C from a previous blood transfusion when he was young. As part of his workup, you perform a diagnostic ascitic tap to rule out spontaneous bacterial peritonitis.\n\nWhich of the following is diagnostic of spontaneous bacterial peritonitis (SBP) on ascitic fluid analysis?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","The other results are not diagnostic of SBP.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"The other results are not diagnostic of SBP.","explanation":"The other results are not diagnostic of SBP."},{"id":"3630","category":"Gastroenterology and hepatology","stem":"A 68-year-old man was admitted with haematemesis. He had gone out the evening before and had drunk too much alcohol at a wedding party. He vomited in the early hours and then, on the last couple of occasions, vomited frank blood. He vomited blood on two occasions, the last of which was 2 hours ago. His wife brought the pillow cloth on which he vomited, which shows dark blood staining. He had nothing of note in his past medical history other than type-2 diabetes and hypertension, for which he takes metformin, ramipril, simvastatin and clopidogrel.\n\nOn examination, he was subdued with a pulse of 68 bpm and a blood pressure of 116/60 mmHg. His haemoglobin concentration was 116 mg/L (120-160). Coagulation and LFTs were normal. His urea is normal at 4 mmol/L, and creatinine is also reported normal. As part of the management plan, clopidogrel was stopped. The admitting doctor calculates his Blatchford score to be 3.\n\nWhich of the following is the most appropriate approach to the management of this patient?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"putting him in a high-risk category","explanation":"In this man’s case, he has had a witnessed haematemesis, and he is over 60 and has diabetes, giving a Rockall score of 3. His Blatchford score is 3, thus putting him in a high-risk category. NICE recommends calculating the Blatchford score for all patients admitted with UGI bleed pre-endoscopy, and early discharge should only be considered for patients with a pre-endoscopy Blatchford score of 0. The most likely diagnosis here is a Mallory-Weiss tear from the description, but even so, the guidelines suggest that this man should be admitted and, where possible, have an endoscopy performed within 24 hours. According to NICE, one should offer endoscopy to unstable patients with severe acute upper gastrointestinal bleeding immediately after resuscitation and within 24 hours of admission to all other patients with upper gastrointestinal bleeding. No evidence commencing a PPI before endoscopy would have any prognostic benefit."},{"id":"11637","category":"Gastroenterology and hepatology","stem":"A 56-year-old man with alcoholic liver disease-related cirrhosis presents to the Accident & Emergency unit. His condition has usually been well compensated, and he has been abstinent from alcohol since his condition was diagnosed 2 years ago. He complains of increasing abdominal distension for the last 2 weeks. On examination, he has a soft, non-tender abdomen with moderate-volume ascites. There is no pedal oedema.\n\nWhich of the following applies when considering his further management?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"An ascites tap should always be undertaken on the first presentation of ascites to establish the cause and exclude SBP. A serum-ascites albumin gradient equal to or higher than 1.1 g/dl is suggestive of ascites due to portal hypertension. The first line of treatment should be spironolactone 100 mg/day and moderate salt restriction. The aim should be a weight loss of 500 g per day in the absence of peripheral oedema and 1000 g per day for oedematous patients."},{"id":"3960","category":"Gastroenterology and hepatology","stem":"A 74-year-old man with a past medical history of coronary artery disease and hypertension presented to emergency care with complaints of fever and abdominal pain 5 hours after a colonoscopic snare polypectomy of a caecal tubulovillous polyp.\n\nHe initially tolerated the procedure well, but he noted the development of intermittent, diffuse abdominal pain after returning home, which was relieved by passing flatus. A few hours later, he developed a 9/10 right lower quadrant abdominal pain aggravated by coughing and movement without significant relieving factors. He denies nausea, vomiting, or changes in bowel habits.\n\nOn examination, the patient had a temperature of 38.1oC but his other observations were normal. On abdominal examination, the patient had normal bowel sounds with diffuse tenderness, most prominent in the right lower quadrant. There was no guarding or rigidity.\n\nLaboratory tests revealed:\n\nAn abdominal radiograph was read as normal.\n\nA CT scan of the abdomen and pelvis with contrast revealed significant inflammatory changes within the mesenteric fat surrounding the cecum and thickening of the wall of the cecum.\n\nWhat is the most likely diagnosis?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"Postpolypectomy electrocoagulation syndrome, also known as post-polypectomy syndrome, transmural burn syndrome, or micro-perforation, is a rare but important complication of polypectomy and is a potential reason for patients to re-present to the hospital following a colonoscopy. Patients with post-polypectomy electrocoagulation syndrome typically present within 12 hours following a colonoscopy with fever, tachycardia, and generalised abdominal pain. However, the onset of symptoms may be delayed by up to 5–7 days after the procedure. They are generally managed conservatively with intravenous fluids, pain control, and gradual advancement of diet as tolerated, with or without antibiotics against Gram-negative and anaerobic pathogens."},{"id":"3971","category":"Gastroenterology and hepatology","stem":"A 57-year-old teacher presents acutely to the medical assessment unit with a 6-hour history of haematemesis and melaena. He has known osteoarthritis for which he takes regular Naproxen, but is otherwise fit and well. He is on no other medication and does not drink alcohol.\n\nOn examination, he is pale and looks unwell. He has marked epigastric tenderness and Maleana on rectal examination. His observations reveal the following: heart rate of 105 beats per minute, blood pressure of 105/78 mmHg, and respiratory rate of 26 breaths per minute.\n\nWhich one of the following risk stratification scores is best to use as part of your initial assessment to assess the urgency and location (inpatient versus outpatient) for endoscopy?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Rockall scoring is based partly on endoscopic appearances, making it less useful during a patient’s acute presentation.","The Forrest Classification is used to grade a bleeding lesion at the time of endoscopy to evaluate the risk of re-bleeding.","The Discriminant function is a scoring system used in alcoholic hepatitis to evaluate both the mortality risk and the requirement for treatment with corticosteroids.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"The Glasgow Blatchford score is a screening tool used to assess the probability that a patient with a suspected upper GI bleed will need to undergo an intervention such as an endoscopy or blood transfusion. It lacks subjective variables (such as the severity of comorbid disease) or the requirement of upper GI endoscopy pre-scoring, making it superior to Rockall scoring in the acute environment. In a controlled study, 16% of patients with suspected upper GI bleeding had a GBS of 0. There were no deaths or adverse interventions required in these patients, and as such, these patients can be managed in an outpatient setting."},{"id":"3964","category":"Gastroenterology and hepatology","stem":"A 36-year-old man presents to the emergency department with several hours’ history of nausea and severe pain in the abdomen. He describes epigastric pain radiating to his back.\n\nOn examination, the patient is in the fetal position and reluctant to move. He is tachycardic and has a low-grade fever.\n\nThe admission laboratory tests included:\n\nIn this patient, which of the following laboratory studies is most indicative of severe disease at admission ?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","In acute pancreatitis, the Ranson criteria have been time-tested indicators of disease severity and prognosis. Ranson criteria include five admission criteria:","And five criteria were determined at 48 hours:","Amylase and lipase levels are not good predictors of disease severity or prognosis.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"In acute pancreatitis, the Ranson criteria have been time-tested indicators of disease severity and prognosis. Ranson criteria include five admission criteria:","explanation":"In acute pancreatitis, the Ranson criteria have been time-tested indicators of disease severity and prognosis. Ranson criteria include five admission criteria:"},{"id":"3949","category":"Gastroenterology and hepatology","stem":"A 29-year-old woman who is 35 weeks pregnant (gravida 3 para 2) presents with nausea, vomiting, and anorexia. She has noticed a change in her eyes, and her GP is concerned that she may be jaundiced. She has previously been fit and well. She takes no medications other than folic acid. The patient has otherwise had an uneventful pregnancy and was looking forward to the birth.\n\nHer observations are as follows: heart rate is 110 beats per minute, blood pressure is 111/76 mmHg, and respiratory rate is 25 breaths per minute. Her temperature is 36.4 oC.\n\nOn examination, she was jaundiced with a gravid uterus. There was no evidence of ascites or stigmata of chronic liver disease.\n\nHer blood results are as follows:\n\nAn ultrasound of the abdomen shows a bright liver.\n\nWhat should be the next stage in her management?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Paracetamol levels form part of the liver screen, but the history is not suggestive of overdose. This patient should be kept as an inpatient and not discharged.","N-acetyl cysteine is used in paracetamol overdose, and ursodeoxycholic acid can be used in obstetric cholestasis.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"This patient has acute fatty liver disease of pregnancy. It is a life-threatening condition, thought to be related to HELLP (haemolysis, elevated liver enzymes and low platelets) syndrome. It can be difficult to diagnose, as patients often have vague symptoms. The management is the prompt delivery of the baby and supportive care to the mother. The Swansea criteria can be used to aid diagnosis and are described below."},{"id":"3945","category":"Gastroenterology and hepatology","stem":"A 56-year-old woman presents to the medical assessment unit (MAU) with jaundice. She has noticed increased jaundice over the last week, and she has recently lost weight. The weight loss has been a deliberate effort as she was previously obese. She feels generally unwell. Her only past medical history is of ulcerative colitis, for which she takes mesalazine.\n\nHer blood results show:\n\nYou arrange an ultrasound scan of her abdomen. The report shows dilatation of the common bile duct and intrahepatic biliary ducts. The pancreas is obscured by bowel gas. The liver appears bright, but the scan is limited due to body habitus.\n\nWhat is the next test you should perform?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"This is a non-invasive test that is excellent for diagnosing the cause of obstructive jaundice. Her history of ulcerative colitis raises the question of possible PSC, which a CT will not rule out effectively. Blood tests should be sent, but the MRCP will give you the diagnosis. ERCP should not ideally be used for diagnosis alone, and it is an invasive procedure with a 1:50 risk of pancreatitis."},{"id":"11634","category":"Gastroenterology and hepatology","stem":"A 38-year-old man from Africa presents with diarrhoea, abdominal pain, and weight loss for the last 6 weeks. He has lost 2 stone in the last 3 months despite having a good appetite. He has noticed some blood occasionally in his stools.\n\nOn clinical examination, there is fullness with a palpable mass in the right lower quadrant. A CT scan shows thickening of the caecum and ascending colon with surrounding lymphadenopathy. A colonoscopy shows superficial ulcers over the right colon. There is no family history of IBD. His biopsy reveals a caseating granuloma with no distortion of the crypt architecture.\n\nWhat is the likely diagnosis?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"The clinical picture is consistent with intestinal TB. Differentiating intestinal TB from Crohn’s disease (CD) is a clinical challenge. The final clinical diagnosis is based on a combination of the clinical history with endoscopic studies, culture and polymerase chain reaction for Mycobacterium tuberculosis, biopsy pathology, radiological investigations, and response to therapy. In a subset of patients, surgery is required, and intraoperative findings with pathological study of the resected bowel provide a definitive diagnosis. Characteristic endoscopic features have been described in intestinal TB and CD. Transversely, placed ulcers, nodularity and hypertrophic lesions resembling masses are characteristic of TB. Aphthoid or longitudinal, deep, fissuring ulcers and a cobblestone appearance are said to be more typical of CD. The histological hallmarks of TB are confluent, caseating granulomas containing acid-fast bacilli, and surrounded by a lymphoid cuff. These are found in all layers of the intestinal wall and regional lymph nodes. Microscopically, common features in CD are aphthous ulcers over lymphoid follicles, fissuring ulcers that extend into the muscularis propria or deeper, distortion of the mucosal architecture, pyloric metaplasia, cryptitis and crypt abscess formation with moderate to severe chronic inflammation. These changes are often segmental or patchy and extend transmurally. Prominent lymphoid follicles in the submucosa and serosa are another characteristic feature of CD."},{"id":"7873","category":"Gastroenterology and hepatology","stem":"A 20-year-old woman presented to the medical assessment unit (MAU) with a 5-day history of deteriorating bloody diarrhoea. She had a 3-year history of ulcerative colitis and was treated with azathioprine. She had 7 episodes of bloody diarrhoea in the preceding 24 hours and had been feeling unwell. Her GP had seen her and referred her to MAU.\n\nOn examination, her pulse was 88 beats per minute, her blood pressure was 100/70 mmHg, and her temperature was 38°C. Examination of the abdomen revealed tenderness in the left iliac fossa.\n\nFlexible sigmoidoscopy revealed continuous inflammation and ulceration extending beyond the limit of the sigmoidoscope.\n\nWhich of the following is the most appropriate approach to the management of this patient?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Mild to moderate disease is treated with topical aminosalicylate, then adding an oral agent if there is no improvement after 4 weeks.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"This patient has an acute severe flare-up of her ulcerative colitis with evidence of inflammation on the sigmoidoscopy. The most appropriate immediate treatment for this acute severe flare would be IV hydrocortisone as per guidance, with a dose of 100 mg IV qds."},{"id":"3972","category":"Gastroenterology and hepatology","stem":"A 48-year-old unemployed woman is referred to the medical assessment unit by her general practitioner with a 2-week history of abdominal swelling. She is known to have a history of alcohol abuse and continues to drink around 80 units of alcohol per week. She has no other medical history and lives alone at home.\n\nOn examination, she is jaundiced and slightly drowsy. She has palmar erythema and multiple spider naevi. She has marked abdominal swelling with shifting dullness, but her abdomen is otherwise soft and non-tender.\n\nHer blood results are as follows:\n\nWhat is the most appropriate test to perform next?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Serum ammonia level can be used to assess the presence of encephalopathy, but it is not an accurate tool and cannot evaluate the severity of encephalopathy.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"This patient clearly has decompensated alcoholic liver disease with ascites. Their initial management should include stabilisation, prevention of acute inpatient alcohol withdrawal, and investigation of potential causes of deterioration. These causes include but are not limited to infections, such as spontaneous bacterial peritonitis (SBP), alcoholic hepatitis, gastrointestinal bleeding, and portal vein thrombosis. In this scenario, an ultrasound is the only listed option that would form part of your management plan (along with other tests)."},{"id":"7992","category":"Gastroenterology and hepatology","stem":"A 75-year-old woman with alcohol dependence was admitted to the hospital with a 3-day history of increasing abdominal pain and nausea. She was taking 50 mg orally of thiamine daily and 20 mg of omeprazole daily. She admitted to usually drinking around one bottle of wine per day, but has not drunk alcohol over the preceding 3 days.\n\nOn examination, she was confused, appeared irritable with tremor of the hands, and had a yellow sclera. Her temperature was 37 OC, her pulse was 100 beats per minute regular, and her blood pressure was 128/88 mmHg. On examination of the abdomen, she had 4 cm tender hepatomegaly with no evidence of ascites.\n\nHer investigations revealed:\n\nWhich of the following is the most appropriate immediate treatment for this patient?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"The most appropriate approach to the management of this patient who appears to have acute on chronic alcoholic hepatitis, possibly encephalopathy and alcohol withdrawal, would be the addition of IV Thiamine/vitamin B complex, such as Pabrinex, to avert Wernicke-Korsakoff syndrome. Whilst the patient is prescribed thiamine, poor compliance is often an issue, and where there is any doubt about thiamine intake in alcoholism, the patient must be treated with IV vitamin B complex. Vitamin B complex should certainly be administered before any glucose."},{"id":"3759","category":"Gastroenterology and hepatology","stem":"A 24-year-old woman is admitted with an 8-hour history of abdominal pain. The pain began at approximately 1 am as an epigastric pain, which was relatively constant, though it had some colicky features to it in that it grew in intensity on occasions and then subsided a little. She felt nauseous with the pain but had not vomited. After enduring the pain for a few hours, she went to the hospital.\n\nIn her previous history, she was diagnosed with Crohn’s disease and had been on infliximab for the last 5 years. She had been in remission since then. Other than infliximab, she took the combined oral contraceptive.\n\nShe had opened her bowels normally the morning beforehand, and was unaware of any diarrhoea or blood in her motion. She denied eating anything that upset her stomach, or so she thought. She is currently having a withdrawal menstrual bleed, having regularly taken the OCP.\n\nOn examination, she was tearful, had a pulse of 82 bpm, a blood pressure of 122/80 mmHg and a temperature of 37.7 oC. Examination of the abdomen revealed some tenderness in the epigastrium with more tenderness and guarding in the right iliac fossa. No abnormality was noted on PR examination.\n\nInvestigations reveal:\n\nWhich of the following is the most appropriate investigation for this patient?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"Reference:"},{"id":"11635","category":"Gastroenterology and hepatology","stem":"A 72-year-old nursing home resident with a background history of cognitive impairment, hypertension, and recurrent urinary tract infections is admitted to the assessment unit with a 1-week history of offensive diarrhoea. She was recently treated with a course of fluoroquinolone for a multidrug-resistant E.coli-associated urinary tract infection. Her medications include donepezil, amlodipine, omeprazole, and aspirin. She had a hospital admission 3 months ago with urosepsis, when she was also treated for Clostridium difficile infection. Stool samples sent by the GP show GDH and toxin positive for Clostridium difficile.\n\nOn examination, her pulse rate is 124 beats per minute, blood pressure is 90/40 mmHg, temperature 38oC, and saturation 95% on air. Clinically, she appears dry with a dry-coated tongue; her abdomen is distended and tender generally. Her bowel sounds are sluggish. Her bloods are as follows:\n\nShe has been started on intravenous fluids. You request an urgent abdominal film, which shows the following findings.\n\nWhat is the most likely next step in management here for this patient?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","She has been started on intravenous fluids. You request an urgent abdominal film, which shows the following findings.","What is the most likely next step in management here for this patient?","Severe CDI is indicated by any of the following:","White cell count WCC >15 x 109 /L","Temperature >38.5oC, or","Evidence of severe colitis (abdominal signs, radiology).","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"What is the most likely next step in management here for this patient?","explanation":"This patient has likely developed Clostridium difficile-related colitis. Risk factors for acquiring CDI include elderly nursing home residents, recent or recurrent antibiotic use, prolonged or recurrent hospitalisation, chemotherapy, and any form of immunosuppression poses a risk for CDI."},{"id":"3788","category":"Gastroenterology and hepatology","stem":"A 72-year-old woman is admitted by her GP with a history of fatigue and weakness, which had deteriorated over the last month. The GP had checked her blood and discovered haemoglobin of 7.7 g/dl (12-16) with an MCV of 59 fl. She had a previous history of type-2 diabetes for which she takes metformin 500 mg bd, and her most recent HbA1c checked 2 weeks ago was 68 mmol/mol (<48). She also has a history of previous DVT and atrial fibrillation with arterial embolism, for which she had required a left below-knee amputation. Consequently, she remains on lifelong warfarin. She takes bisoprolol 2.5 mg/d, ramipril 2.5 mg daily, omeprazole 40 mg daily, ferrous fumarate 210mg bd and simvastatin 40 mg daily.\n\nShe describes feeling weak and lethargic over the last month, which has culminated in her seeing her GP. She denies any abdominal pains and has been unaware of any melaena or PR blood loss. She denies any weight loss. There was some story about iron deficiency a year or so ago for which she had been prescribed iron tablets. There was nothing on the clinical portal about this.\n\nOn examination, she is comfortable but appears pale. Her BMI is 32.2 kg/m2. Her pulse is 70 bpm, irregular, and her blood pressure is 110/70 mmHg. There is nothing to find on examination other than that she had a below-knee amputation, and PR examination is normal.\n\nOther than the above, all other results are normal, including U+Es and LFTs. Ferritin was 10 microg/L (30-100), and INR was 2.5. Chest x-ray is normal.\n\nWhich of the following is the most appropriate management strategy for this patient?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"This patient is haemodynamically uncompromised and has chronic anaemia, has not responded to oral iron, and there is no acute bleeding; therefore, giving IV iron and arranging outpatient upper and lower GI studies is the correct answer. There is no indication here to transfuse this patient."},{"id":"3628","category":"Gastroenterology and hepatology","stem":"A 55-year-old man was admitted with haematemesis and weakness. Over the last 2 days, he had suffered from abdominal discomfort and anorexia. Today, he developed vomiting of dark blood. He had nothing of note in his past medical history. He was fit, having done triathlons in the past, and usually took 75 mg aspirin a day, which was not prescribed, but he took it for his ‘heart’. He took no other medication\n\nOn examination, he was pale with a pulse of 100 beats per minute and a blood pressure of 100/60 mmHg. His haemoglobin concentration was 80 mg/L (120-160). Coagulation and LFTs were normal. The suggested diagnosis was felt to be peptic ulceration due to aspirin use. He was told not to take NSAIDs. He was treated with IV omeprazole and resuscitated with Blood.\n\nHe underwent an urgent endoscopy, and the report indicated that the endoscopist could not see any source of bleeding as the stomach was full of blood.\n\nOver the next 3 days, his clinical condition stabilised and he required 8 units of blood. His haemoglobin on day 3 was 102 g/dl. He had no further melaena or haematemesis. He was switched to oral omeprazole.\n\nWhich of the following is the next step in his management?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"The assumed diagnosis is peptic ulceration due to aspirin use. He has had a life-threatening GI bleed, yet the source of this bleed has not been identified. He requires a repeat endoscopy as soon as possible, as, whilst the bleeding appears to have subsided, often a large clot can overlie a vessel and then this gets digested by stomach enzymes, resulting in a further major bleed. Thus, guidance indicated that this patient requires further endoscopy as an inpatient and should have been performed within 24 hours, where the cause of the bleeding has not been elucidated."},{"id":"3951","category":"Gastroenterology and hepatology","stem":"A 46-year-old man presents to the medical assessment unit (MAU) jaundiced and unwell. He was previously diagnosed with chronic liver disease, but continues to drink alcohol in excess. On examination, he has no evidence of ascites but does have some tenderness in the right upper quadrant. You clinically suspect he has alcoholic hepatitis.\n\nHis blood results show:\n\nWhich of the following scoring systems best determines the longer-term prognosis of his underlying chronic liver disease?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Maddrey's Discriminant Function for Alcoholic Hepatitis.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"Maddrey's Discriminant Function for Alcoholic Hepatitis.","explanation":"Child-Pugh score is the only score system in the list used for assessing chronic liver disease. The Glasgow alcoholic hepatitis score and discriminant function can both be used to assess prognosis and guide treatment of acute alcoholic hepatitis, but have not been validated for chronic liver disease alone. The Blatchford score and Rockall score are used in gastrointestinal bleeding. Maddrey's alcohol discriminant score provides a better approximation of the shorter-term prognosis."},{"id":"11646","category":"Gastroenterology and hepatology","stem":"A 55-year-old woman presented to the assessment unit with a 1-week history of diarrhoea after she had a meal in a restaurant. She was managed with intravenous fluids whilst awaiting her stool results. 24 hours later, she reported weakness in both her legs, which has progressively gotten worse. She reported difficulty in breathing and had to be intubated urgently as she dropped her GCS.\n\nYou receive a call from the microbiologist about the stool results. What is the likely finding in her stool?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"The patient has likely got Campylobacter-related gastroenteritis and is suffering from Guillain-Barré syndrome (GBS). Campylobacter jejuni infection has been associated with Guillain-Barré. Campylobacter is one of the most common bacterial causes of diarrhoea in the UK and also the most common risk factor for Guillain-Barré syndrome. Campylobacter is often found in undercooked meat, especially chicken. Cytomegalovirus, Epstein-Barr virus (EBV), and mycoplasma have also been associated with GBS."},{"id":"4214","category":"Gastroenterology and hepatology","stem":"A 42-year-old woman with chronic liver disease presents unwell to the A&E with diarrhoea and vomiting. You are asked to see her due to her history of liver disease. Her diarrhoeal symptoms are settling, but you are concerned about acute kidney injury. Her blood tests are as follows:\n\nAt what stage is her acute kidney injury?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Modified RIFLE AKIN criteria","Stage\tSerum creatinine (µmol/L)\tUrine output (ml/kg/hr)","<0.5 for >6hrs","<0.5 for >12hrs","<0.3 for 24 hrs or Anuria for 12 hrs","RCPE: Acute Kidney Injury.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"Modified RIFLE AKIN criteria","explanation":"Patients with chronic liver disease often have lower creatinine due to decreased synthetic function of the liver. As such, creatinine and urea levels in patients with chronic liver disease should always be compared to previous results if possible, and as such, ‘normal range’ results may represent a significant kidney injury for these patients. In this case, there has been over a 1.5-fold increase in creatinine; therefore, this fits with a stage 1 AKI. There is no stage 4 AKI according to the modified RIFLE criteria."},{"id":"11641","category":"Gastroenterology and hepatology","stem":"A 42-year-old woman is admitted to the Medical Assessment Unit with nausea, vomiting, abdominal distension, and feeling generally unwell. She gives a history of drinking 1 litre of Vodka every day for many years.\n\nOn examination, she is jaundiced and looks very unwell. Abdominal examination reveals a mildly tender right upper quadrant and moderate ascites.\n\nBlood tests showed the following results:\n\nA diagnosis of alcoholic hepatitis was made based on the presentation.\n\nWhich of the following scores provides the best determinant of prognosis and influences the use of steroids?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"The patient has acute alcoholic hepatitis. One of the best prognostic scoring systems to determine the prognosis for the condition is Maddrey’s discriminant function. The Child-Pugh score is used to determine the prognosis of chronic Liver disease. SAAG is useful to determine the cause of ascites. The FIB4 score is used to determine if there is fibrosis, as is the NAFLD score."},{"id":"9066","category":"Gastroenterology and hepatology","stem":"A 36-year-old woman is admitted to the acute medical unit with a 3-week history of deteriorating abdominal pain, increasing ascites, and confusion. She has a history of cirrhosis associated with autoimmune hepatitis.\n\nOn examination, she is confused with a temperature of 37.5oC, a blood pressure of 124/80 mmHg and a pulse of 100 bpm. There are numerous bruises on the abdomen, arms and legs. She is jaundiced and has a flapping tremor of the outstretched hands. There is mild abdominal tenderness with ascites. Model for End-Stage Liver Disease Score (MELD) was 35.\n\nA paracentesis was performed. The ascitic fluid shows 4,000 WCC (60 per cent neutrophils); Gram Stain of the fluid is negative. Blood cultures are pending. Creatinine is 130 µmol/L (50-100) (baseline 90). There were no recent admissions, and she did not use any antibiotics within the last few months. The patient has been considered for liver transplantation.\n\nWhich of the following is the likely diagnosis?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"This patient is likely to have SBP as suggested by the gradual evolution of symptoms, the low-grade fever, decompensation and importantly, the elevated WCC, which is mostly a neutrophilia on the paracentesis."},{"id":"3958","category":"Gastroenterology and hepatology","stem":"A 50-year-old man presents with an acute onset of ascites. He is known to have hepatitis C and cirrhosis but is normally well-controlled on Spironolactone 50 mg once daily, Lactulose 15 ml twice daily, and Mirtazapine 15 mg once daily. His baseline renal functions were normal a few days earlier.\n\nOn examination, he has mild to moderate ascites.\n\nHis blood results show:\n\nWhat is the most likely cause of his deranged renal function?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"This patient is taking spironolactone, a diuretic, which can adversely affect renal function, which is the most likely cause. The hepatorenal syndrome can only be diagnosed in the absence of shock, after reversal of all other potential causes and with a creatinine of over 130 µmol/L."},{"id":"3959","category":"Gastroenterology and hepatology","stem":"A 71-year-old man presents to the acute medical team with fresh rectal bleeding following a bowel screening colonoscopy earlier that day, where he said the endoscopist “sorted out my polyps on my rectum”. He is still a bit drowsy from his sedation and is passing blood PR.\n\nHis observations include a heart rate of 105 beats per minute, blood pressure of 108/64 mmHg, respiratory rate of 23/min, and temperature of 36.9 oC.\n\nWhat is the most likely cause of his symptoms?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","BSG: Post-polypectomy and post-colorectal cancer resection surveillance guidelines","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"the risk and frequency of bleeding are increased","explanation":"Polypectomy bleeding occurs in 1.0-6.1% of all colonoscopic polypectomies, and patients are warned that bleeding is a risk. Bowel screening colonoscopies have a high adenoma detection rate, and a large number of often large polypectomies are performed; therefore, the risk and frequency of bleeding are increased. The team should liaise with the endoscopist, surgical team and interventional radiology."},{"id":"3965","category":"Gastroenterology and hepatology","stem":"A 17-year-old female, who is otherwise healthy, notes that her urine has become darker than usual and she is having a difficult time concentrating in school. Routine blood tests show the following results.\n\nHepatitis A/B/C serology results are negative.\n\nWhat is the most likely diagnosis?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"Wilson’s disease is most commonly diagnosed in children and young adults and should be suspected in this age group. This disorder results from a defect in the ATP7B gene and results in copper retention in the liver, resulting in hepatocyte injury. Patients can present in various ways, from asymptomatic abnormalities in blood work to fulminant hepatic failure. Patients presenting with severe acute Wilson’s disease are often noted to have haemolysis with elevated hyperbilirubinemia and anaemia resulting in jaundice. AST and ALT levels are often quite elevated compared with the alkaline phosphatase, which is either normal or below normal in acute settings. Patients presenting in this manner need to be diagnosed expeditiously and transferred to a liver transplantation facility, as copper chelators are not beneficial in this setting."},{"id":"4219","category":"Gastroenterology and hepatology","stem":"A 54-year-old man presents with haematemesis. He has a history of diabetes mellitus and hypertension, and was diagnosed with acute coronary syndrome 2 months ago. He smoked twenty cigarettes a day up until his admission with acute coronary syndrome (ACS), but has since stopped.\n\nHe undergoes endoscopy, which confirms the presence of a small duodenal ulcer. He was taking aspirin and clopidogrel, which were stopped, and intravenous omeprazole was commenced. On day 4, he was doing well. He has had no further haematemesis. He had a pulse of 68 beats per minute, regular and a blood pressure of 136/80 mmHg. He was started on oral omeprazole.\n\nWhen should the antiplatelet therapy be restarted?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"In patients with upper gastrointestinal bleeding (UGIB) related to antiplatelet therapy-induced ulceration, it is important to assess the risk-benefit of stopping the drugs and the increased risk of a coronary event. Studies have shown that these patients are at a high risk of ACS, and hence, it is recommended that antiplatelet therapy should be recommenced at the earliest opportunity once the acute GI bleeding has settled and the patient is stable."},{"id":"7818","category":"Gastroenterology and hepatology","stem":"A 56-year-old woman presented to the MAU with vomiting and right upper abdominal pain. Her family had been worried about her as she had a long-standing alcohol problem. She drank excessively, typically consuming at least a bottle of wine per day with spirits.\n\nOn examination, she was noted to be mildly confused and have asterixis and 3-finger breadth hepatomegaly with mild ascites and slight jaundice.\n\nWhat is the most appropriate immediate management for this patient?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"The most appropriate approach to the management of this patient with what appears to be alcohol-related cirrhosis would be to provide IV vitamin B as a prophylactic strategy against the development of Wernicke–Korsakoff syndrome."},{"id":"3947","category":"Gastroenterology and hepatology","stem":"A 62-year-old man with alcoholic liver disease presents acutely unwell to the A&E. He is jaundiced and is behaving strangely. He keeps forgetting who you are as you take the history from him, and his speech is slurred. He has had chronic liver disease secondary to alcohol for many years, according to his notes, and his medications are thiamine 50 mg daily plus lactulose 10 ml twice daily.\n\nOn examination, he is icteric and tremulous, plus has evidence of asterixis. His abdomen is soft and non-tender, with no shifting dullness.\n\nAccording to the West Haven Encephalopathy scale, what grade of encephalopathy does this patient have?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Grade 0 - minimal HE – difficult to diagnose clinically","Grade 1 -Mild HE - Trivial lack of awareness; euphoria or anxiety; shortened attention span; impaired performance of addition or subtraction","Grade 2 - Moderate HE - Lethargy or apathy; minimal disorientation for time or place; subtle personality change; inappropriate behaviour","Grade 3 - Severe HE- Somnolence to semi-stupor, but responsive to verbal stimuli; confusion; gross disorientation","Grade 4 - Coma","Hepatic encephalopathy grades stages.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"Grade 4 - Coma","explanation":"This case correlates with moderate encephalopathy. It is important to recognise encephalopathy and its severity, as it is largely a clinical diagnosis, and prompt treatment is appropriate. The West Haven Encephalopathy grading system (also called Conn score) is the most common tool used to grade the severity of encephalopathy, and it is summarised in the list below:"},{"id":"9171","category":"Gastroenterology and hepatology","stem":"A 61-year-old man is admitted to the acute medical intake with confusion and increased abdominal discomfort. He is known to have alcoholic liver disease, and on this admission, he is diagnosed again with decompensated cirrhosis.\n\nWhich of the following best describes the appropriate protein intake that this patient should receive?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"Protein-calorie malnutrition (PCM) is associated with an increased risk of morbidity and mortality in patients with cirrhosis and occurs in 50-90% of these patients. In decompensated liver cirrhosis, the recommendation is a high-energy, high-protein diet. Previous recommendations that limited protein intake should no longer be practised, as protein requirements of patients with cirrhosis are higher than those of healthy individuals. Targets of 1.5–2.0 g/kg protein are suggested in patients with decompensated cirrhosis, with protein targets for those with compensated cirrhosis lower at 1.2–1.5 g/kg."},{"id":"4218","category":"Gastroenterology and hepatology","stem":"A 36-year-old woman starts a new medication prescribed by her GP. Four weeks later, she presented to the emergency department with severe abdominal pain and was diagnosed with acute pancreatitis. The pancreatitis is thought to be secondary to the new medication; it is duly discontinued, and the pancreatitis resolves. Six months later, the same medication is reinitiated, and pancreatitis develops within 8 hours.\n\nWhat is the mechanism causing this drug-induced pancreatitis?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"The case above displays a classic pattern of a hypersensitivity reaction, which is the most common cause of drug-induced pancreatitis. Drugs that operate through this mechanism include azathioprine, aminosalicylates, metronidazole, and tetracycline. Accumulation of a toxic metabolite and intrinsic toxicity often occur after a longer duration of initial drug use and do not occur as quickly with reinitiation. There is nothing in the history to suggest a drug interaction, and immunomodulatory up-regulation is not a pathogenetic mechanism of drug-induced pancreatitis."},{"id":"3957","category":"Gastroenterology and hepatology","stem":"A 26-year-old woman presents to the MAU with a 4-day history of diarrhoea. She is opening her bowels 8 times a day, passing type 7 stools. There is no blood in the stool. Her symptoms started following a barbecue at a friend’s house. She is clinically dehydrated and is resuscitated with intravenous fluids.\n\nAfter 48 hours, her symptoms have settled, but the stool sample sent on admission has cultured Campylobacter spp.\n\nWhat is the next correct management step?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","GOV.UK/Public Health England: Campylobacteriosis.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"Campylobacter infection is a notifiable disease closely linked to eating undercooked chicken. Antibiotics can be used if diarrhoeal symptoms persist, but are not required if symptoms have settled. There is no need to screen other attendees."},{"id":"3629","category":"Gastroenterology and hepatology","stem":"A 58-year-old man was admitted with haematemesis. Over the last 2 days, he had suffered from abdominal discomfort and anorexia. Today, he developed vomiting of dark blood. He had nothing of note in his past medical history other than type 2 diabetes treated with metformin. He also took simvastatin as prescribed medication and aspirin 75 mg daily. On examination, he was pale with a pulse of 110 beats per minute and a blood pressure of 106/60 mmHg.\n\nWhich of the following is this patient’s initial Rockall score?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Because of his story and the development of melaena, this suggests a large GI bleed, probably a consequence of peptic ulceration related to NSAIDs.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"In acute GI haemorrhage, the Rockall score has predictive significance. A simple way of remembering the Rockall Score is ABCDE. ABC gives you the initial score. A = age (below 60 scores 0, 60-79 = 1 and 80 and above =2); B = blood pressure (tachycardia above 100 =1 or BP below 100 = 2); C = co-morbidity (major co-morbidity such as IHD =2, renal/liver disease or Ca =3. Then, the following criteria would be used after endoscopic evaluation. D = Diagnosis (Mallory Weiss = 0, all other diagnoses=1, malignancy = 2). E = evidence of haemorrhage – blood adherent clot =2)."},{"id":"3978","category":"Gastroenterology and hepatology","stem":"An 18-year-old dancer with a 10-year history of anorexia nervosa presents to the emergency department with confusion, headache, and diffuse weakness one day after a performance. The patient severely restricts her daily intake, keeping to a low-calorie diet for one week before each performance. Immediately after each performance, she quickly liberalises her diet and starts eating a lot more calories in the form of carbohydrates. Her height is 1.56m and she weighs 47kg. The emergency department staff suspect refeeding syndrome.\n\nWhich laboratory result is most commonly seen with refeeding syndrome?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","NHS medicines optimisation: clinical pathways and medication guidelines chapter 9 nutrition and blood refeeding syndrome.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"Patients with anorexia nervosa are at risk of refeeding syndrome, a potentially life-threatening condition characterised by fluid and electrolyte disorders, including hypophosphataemia, hypomagnesemia, and hypokalaemia. This syndrome typically occurs within 4 days of introducing a healthy diet to a patient with anorexia nervosa. As a shift from fat to carbohydrate metabolism occurs, insulin levels increase, leading to increased cellular uptake of phosphate. Associated with intracellular movement of electrolytes is a decrease in the serum electrolytes, particularly phosphate, potassium, magnesium, glucose, and thiamine. Alteration in serum calcium levels is not commonly associated with refeeding syndrome."},{"id":"7816","category":"Gastroenterology and hepatology","stem":"A 51-year-old woman is referred to the medical assessment unit (MAU) from the clinic with increased confusion. She has a background of alcoholic cirrhosis but has remained abstinent from alcohol for 18 months and is on the waiting list for liver transplantation. Reading through her notes, you see that on transplant assessment, she had ascites, which responded to furosemide 80 mg and spironolactone 200 mg per day. She also had hepatic encephalopathy, for which she was controlled on lactulose. In today’s clinic, the ascites had resolved, but she was noted to be confused again with a flapping tremor of the hands.\n\nInvestigations reveal:\n\nWhat is the likely cause of her confusion?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Jalan, R. and Kapoor, D. (2004). Reversal of diuretic-induced hepatic encephalopathy with infusion of albumin but not colloid. Clinical Science, 106(5), pp. 467–474.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"","explanation":"This patient has been over-diuresed with hyponatraemia associated with low sodium, high potassium and a degree of renal impairment, which is now likely to contribute to her hyperammonaemia and hence hepatic encephalopathy. The absence of ascites does not suggest SBP as the cause. Treatment is with judicious fluid replacement."},{"id":"3950","category":"Gastroenterology and hepatology","stem":"A 79-year-old man with a previous cerebrovascular accident (CVA) attends the emergency department. The patient is percutaneous endoscopic gastrostomy (PEG) fed, and his PEG tube had “fallen out” 45 minutes ago after it got caught in his clothing, whilst using the toilet. Unfortunately, the PEG tube fell into the toilet pan, but the patient brought it with him with the belief that it may be sterilised. He is otherwise well.\n\nWhat is the best management plan?","options":["Keyboard shortcuts","Prosser, B. Common issues in PEG tubes—what every fellow should know. The Fellows' Corner| 64;6, pp. 970-972, 2006.","Reflections:\nSave reflection"],"correct":"a new PEG kit would not be an option","explanation":"PEG tubes are fitted endoscopically and cannot be re-inserted (especially after toilet exposure); therefore, a new PEG kit would not be an option. A balloon gastrostomy is a viable alternative, but not listed here. A foley catheter prevents the peg tract from closing (which can happen within 4 hours) and allows the safe re-insertion of a balloon gastrostomy the next day. Using the same tract is desirable as it avoids an invasive procedure and the risks of forming a new tract."}];